<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAR OUT, MAN, I'M STILL A KID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee and
head of the impeachment inquiry into President Clinton's affair
with former intern Monica Lewinsky, has a solemn message for
American males over the age of 40. It is:
</P>
<P>
   PARTY ON, DUDES!
</P>
<P>
   Hyde admitted last week that, while a 41-year-old married father
of four, he began a long affair with a married 29-year-old mother
of two. The story was published in the Internet magazine ``Salon,''
and confirmed by those involved.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde responded to the news curtly, saying, ``The statute of
limitations has long since passed on my youthful indiscretions.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as a professional writer, I'm not sure I could put into
words what Hyde's remark meant to the generation of men who, like
me, were born during the Eisenhower administration.
</P>
<P>
   However, something close might be, ``Henry _ ``you da man''.'' &QL; 
THE QUALIFICATIONS &QL; 
I once drove a '64 Chevy with no power steering, no seat belts and
an 8-track tape deck playing the Average White Band and yet,
according to Rep. Hyde, I'm still capable of ``youthful
indiscretions.''
</P>
<P>
   I saw The Doors in concert, twice, watched first-run episodes of
``MASH'' on television, and saw Roberto Clemente _ dead 26 years _
play right field in Forbes Field.
</P>
<P>
   And qualify nevertheless, according to Hyde, as a juvenile
offender.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde is 74 years old and says he shouldn't be held accountable
for a little skirt-chasing in his 40s.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, it seems he's gone from painting the town red to
looking at it through rose-colored glasses. What he sees,
apparently, is guys like me.
</P>
<P>
   Guys with two kids, a mortgage and a box of Jimi Hendrix, Cream
and Canned Heat albums collecting dust in the attic. Guys who
mistakenly believed, until Hyde corrected us, that the statute of
limitations on ``youthful indiscretions'' expires years before a
man's fourth decade.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, playing Hyde-n-seek with a young woman, while
married, isn't such a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   For some, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The man who happened to be married to Hyde's old girlfriend
disagrees. He sees none of the young Dr. Jekyll in the old Mr.
Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``These politicians were going on about . . . what a
great man (Hyde) is, how we're lucky to have him in Congress in
charge of the impeachment case. And all I can think of is here is
this man, this hypocrite who broke up my family.'' &QL; 
HE WAS JUST A KID &QL; 
I say, give Rep. Hyde a break.
</P>
<P>
   He was a kid, barely 20 years past the legally established age
to drink liquor and engage in partisan politics.
</P>
<P>
   What does a person that young know about love?
</P>
<P>
   About relationships?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe those four kids he'd fathered by then were exerting a bad
influence on young Henry.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, he's much older now and seems to believe those of
us in our 40s should be permitted a brief indiscretion. Or even one
that goes on for several years.
</P>
<P>
   He also seems to believe we shouldn't admit to an affair until
we get caught. And then we should try to divert attention from it
by saying the disclosure was an attempt ``to intimidate me.''
</P>
<P>
   Delay, deny and distract.
</P>
<P>
   Has anyone else been accused of using that strategy recently?
</P>
<P>
   It turns out President Clinton was a man in his 40s when he was
alleged to have made improper advances to Paula Jones. From what
I've read, Rep. Hyde has never described that particular incident
as a ``youthful indiscretion.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, all this talk about personal responsibility and
moral authority and impeachment confuses me. Like many Americans,
I'm having trouble telling the difference between the defendant,
the prosecutor and the jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, what do I know?
</P>
<P>
   I'm just a kid. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
