<HEADLINE>
VENTURA COUNTY DEPUTIES BUST UP 870-PLANT MARIJUANA FARM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SYLVIA L. OLIANDE 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUMMIT, Calif. _ Ventura County Sheriff's Department narcotics
teams dismantled the largest outdoor marijuana farm in Ventura
County found this year, but a man seen cultivating the plants
evaded arrest and is at large.
</P>
<P>
   A narcotics team worked most of Saturday to pull two truckloads
containing 870 marijuana plants out of two sites off Highway 150
between Summit and Ojai.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Bob Garcia of the sheriff's narcotics division said the
area was not conducive to naturally growing the plant, but the
sites were structured well enough to yield an impressive crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area is mountainous with heavy vegetation and very little
water. It's hot,'' Garcia said Saturday. ``The site was very
elaborate. They had their own irrigation system, and it was well
maintained. The plants were some of the better marijuana plants
I've seen in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing sites were originally spotted by a sheriff's
helicopter pilot on a routine fire safety check of the area with
Ventura County Fire Department personnel Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said the pilot, Officer David Nadon, had worked in the
narcotics division before and was able to identify the area from
above.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find cultivations in this area periodically here, and on
the other side of Ojai,'' Garcia said. ``It was a really good job
on the pilot's part. There were certain characteristics you can see
from the sky that led us to believe there was marijuana there.''
</P>
<P>
   The growers had used tarps and trees as screens and had painted
their equipment in camouflage colors to hide the sites.
</P>
<P>
   When narcotics investigators staked out the area Friday night,
they spotted a man harvesting, loading and transporting marijuana
to another area at about 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   They watched him make three trips to unload the plants before he
noticed them. He evaded capture in an all-terrain vehicle and
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Work to dismantle the first site, which contained 520 plants,
began at 6 a.m. Saturday morning, and a second site was found later
in a neighboring canyon. That site had 350 plants.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said there was no doubt the plants were being grown for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a Prop. 215-type deal,'' he said of the
controversial medicinal marijuana initiative approved by voters in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said the plants on the site were 2 to 10 feet tall and
had likely been there since April or May, when the growing season
began.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was probably not the first time the area has been
used by suspects to grow the drug.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the most recent growing sites found in Ventura
County were indoor farms discovered in the spring. The sites raided
Saturday, he said, yielded the largest number of plants this year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
