<SLUG> BC-RISKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GLENN, RISK IS PART OF THE POINT
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fit, trim and tan at age 77, John Glenn just grins
and gives a thumbs up when asked whether he's worried about the
health consequences of being the oldest astronaut ever.
</P>
<P>
   But some scientists and aging experts admit they are ``holding
their breath'' about the Oct. 29 flight's risks, which they say
could include a heart attack or stroke _ even for a superathlete
such as Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Many worry because there are no data on whether anyone Glenn's
age can withstand some of the chal lenges of this ride in space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even his family members aren't thrilled, but they know who he
is _ he lives for that kind of stuff _ he's an old test pilot,''
said Richard Sprott, the former chief biological scientist for the
National Institute on Aging who helped Glenn pull to gether the
scientific data needed to justify the flight.
</P>
<P>
   But the risks don't daunt the Ohio senator, the first American
to orbit Earth, who has maintained a rigor ous workout schedule for
most of his life and scoffs at the idea that old folks should slow
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``For too long, people thought that when you turned 60 or 65,
you would retire and turn into a couch potato,'' Glenn said during
an inter view on Capitol Hill recently. ``But if you live by a
calendar like that, you diminish what you can do. Every day you've
got to do what you can to your limit.''
</P>
<P>
   All the worrying is just another instance of ``back to the
future'' for Glenn. Danger is Glenn's familiar friend. In 1962,
strapped into a Mercury capsule only a little larger than a
refrigerator, he shot into orbit atop an Atlas rocket and into
American mythology as a risk taker and an adventurer.
</P>
<P>
   The three-orbit flight in Friend ship 7 wasn't without drama.
During the tense five-hour flight, signals indicated that his heat
shield had come loose. It was feared that Glenn would die in a
fiery death upon his return to earth.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists said the upcoming ride on the space shuttle Discovery
will be less stressful if all goes as planned, but the G-forces of
takeoff and re-entry have them worried, as does after-effects of
nine days in weightless orbit.
</P>
<P>
   A robust man with bright blue eyes, Glenn is about 5-foot-10 and
fitter than you would expect some one his age.
</P>
<P>
   But then his routine lately hasn't exactly been routine. Ever
since NASA announced nine months ago that the senator would be the
subject of the first geriatric study in space, Glenn has been
shuttling between Capitol Hill and Johnson Space Center in Houston.
He calls it having ``two day-jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's NASA and office press handlers have been trying to keep
reporters away from the senator before the big trip but they aren't
always successful, in part because he is eager to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   In a half-hour walk and talk through halls of several office
buildings, he described to two reporters, from The Arizona Repub
lic and New York's Newsday, the challenging training now behind him
_ rappelling from the shuttle escape hatch was the toughest.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped once to greet a family of tourists and let them
photograph him with their little boy. On a tough day for male hero
figures in Washington _ the Starr report was about to be released
to Congress _ the tourist family had managed to find a good one.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for NASA and for those who hope Glenn's
flight will shatter old stereotypes about aging and pave the way
for more opportunities for elders.
</P>
<P>
   If the flight is successful, ``no one will look at their
grandparents in the same way again,'' said noted gerontologist
Robert Butler of New York City, that night at a dinner in
Georgetown honoring Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   At the dinner sponsored by the Alliance for Aging Research,
Butler described Glenn as one of the 20th century's greatest
explorers.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns over his age make Glenn recall the first flight,
when he was already 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even then I got letters telling me I was too old to go up in
space,'' he said. ``And there were questions like, could you
swallow in space and would the human eyeball change shape in
weightlessness so you wouldn't see clearly.'' No end of things to
worry about, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said there will be more than 80 research projects aboard the
shuttle, making it one of the most scientifically rich flights to
date. As a payload specialist, he'll have chores, but he also is
one of the experiments, and will be sprouting with measuring
instruments and tubes monitoring his heart rate, respiration, body
temperature, blood pressure, blood chemistry and more.
</P>
<P>
   He will wear a catheter in his arm, allowing easy access to a
vein for measurements of immune func tion and protein levels. He is
happy to go back up as a guinea pig, or under any circumstances: He
has never let go of the idea of returning to space.
</P>
<P>
   Though the former astronaut wanted to fly again after his 1962
flight, his request was denied. Some years later, he was told that
Presi dent Kennedy pressured NASA to keep him on the ground.
America didn't want to lose its biggest space hero in an accident.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, a career in the heart of Washington power
politics proved to be Glenn's only way back up. It took only 36
years _ not long in celestial time.
</P>
<P>
   While a member of the Senate Committee on Aging, he heard
testimony and read reports that made him realize the parallels
between physical changes in young astronauts on spaceflights and
older people on Earth. There are more than 50 such changes,
including disrupted body clocks, sleep disor ders, bone
demineralization and repressed immunity to diseases.
</P>
<P>
   On the floor of the Senate two years ago this month, Glenn spoke
on the need for more space-based aging research. He brought about a
meeting the following February of more than 20 respected
scientists, who compiled a list of possible research projects, many
involving older humans.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Huber Warner, a scientist at the National Institute on
Aging, cautions that just because Glenn could do it doesn't mean
other 70-somethings can. Glenn going up is a ``compromised
experiment,'' Warner said. ``It will measure how one very exemplary
77-year-old specimen does in space.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Glenn's mission is a success, it could open the door to
the experiment scientists believe would be more useful _ a whole
shuttle mission designed specifically to address aging issues,
perhaps involving crew members across the whole adult lifespan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will there be other older astro nauts? Sure,'' Glenn said.
``If I bring back good information, there is no doubt that using
older people will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA has its own reasons for studying aging and similar proc
esses that occur in space. Longer spaceflights and extended tours
of duty on space stations will cause problems that must be
understood and solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to go to Mars, we need to work on osteoporosis
(bone loss),'' said Sprott, and to look seriously at osteoporosis
you would need 30 days or more.
</P>
<P>
   Training in Houston, Glenn said, has not left him sore, thanks
to his normal daily exercise routine.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it was always easy, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you train every day to your limit, you don't get sore,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn says that his wife gives him vitamin pills to take each
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annie gives me a whole fistful every morning. She gave NASA a
list of what she gives me, and I expect I'll be taking them up
there each morning, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Mercury he used to jog five miles a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in really great shape,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Seven or eight years ago a doctor told him he could get as good
an aerobic workout, with less stress on his joints, if he did more
fast walking instead of jogging. He does that at least five times a
week, for two miles or more per morning. He has always lifted
weights but more regularly in the past few years to prepare for
going up in space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had done more stretch ing over the past 25 years,''
he said, explaining that he is not as flexible as the other six
crew members.
</P>
<P>
   He's famous in Washington for his determined approach to
fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Determined or not, the roller coaster up, followed by nine days
of floating and the roller coaster down, will put tremendous
pressure on his heart and on the small blood vessels serving his
brain.
</P>
<P>
   Sprott, who now heads his own foundation funding aging research,
is well aware of the risks, some known and others unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has an accident of some kind _ one that is clearly
age-de pendent _ then the second-guess ing will be that we should
never have let him go up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sprott believes that risks are what courage is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Glenn personifies a will ingness to take risks, and that
seems to be rapidly disappearing from our culture. We have become a
risk-averse society. We need people like Glenn if we are to
continue to take on challenges. If you don't take challenges, you
don't make gains,'' Sprott said. &QL; 
 &UR; Maureen West can be reached at 444-8167 or mnwest &LR; aol.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
