<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980920.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4698 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSHA-AZR &LR;      09-20 2418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSHA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE OSHA, THERE IS LITTLE RECOURSE FOR FAMILIES LEFT BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It'snot easy to place a value on human life.
</P>
<P>
   Juries have set its worth in the millions. Philosophers argue
that life is priceless.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, however, a worker's life is worth a little less _
about $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   That's the median fine paid by Arizona companies for safety
violations that contributed to the death of a worker, according to
a computer analysis of Occupational Safety and Health
Administration records by ``The Arizona Republic''.
</P>
<P>
   During a three-month investigation, the paper examined hundreds
of records and interviewed company owners, victims' families and
state officials. The findings:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona companies frequently escape large OSHA fines even when
serious safety violations are found. Fines are low because of legal
limits on penalties and a complex appeal system.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning of 1992 to mid-1997, 79 of the 134 worker
deaths in Arizona investigated by state and federal OSHA officials
led to citations for serious safety violations. Just 12 fines
totaled more than $10,000. The highest during that period was
$103,000, levied against four companies in connection with the 1994
death of a worker at TRW's air-bag manufacturing plant in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Fines are often reduced significantly upon appeal. In the fatal
accidents where safety violations were found, fines were cut by
about 40 percent, saving the companies involved more than $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona ranks last in the United States in workers' compensation
benefits paid to surviving spouses. In the best-paying state, Iowa,
widows and widowers can collect up to $817 a week. In Arizona, the
maximum is $183.75.
</P>
<P>
   You can't sue successfully, even if conditions are unsafe.
Workers' compensation laws prohibit employees and their families
from suing employers over workplace injuries or deaths, except in
cases where an employer intentionally tries to injure a worker.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say laws originally set up to benefit workers now
provide an almost impenetrable shield for employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way our laws work, they're protecting the companies,
they're not protecting the workers,'' said Judy Powell, whose
husband, Cory, was killed in a freak garbage-truck accident in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``There doesn't seem to be a lot of help for the good guy out
there, the small man.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell receives $530 a month from workers' compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty sad the way we handle these types of
situations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that although OSHA found serious safety violations in
her husband's case, his employer paid a fine of $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a human life,'' Powell said. ``He was 35 years old, he
had long time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OSHA's small fines are no deterrent for unsafe practices,
others say.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Catholic nun with a &UR; ruler is more threatening than OSHA,
because they are the consummate slap on the wrist,'' said J.
Tyrrell Taber, a lawyer representing the family of Daniel Weber _ a
worker killed while building Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   In Weber's case, Taber was able to file a negligence lawsuit
because the &UR; project involved several companies other than Weber's
direct employer, a subcontractor on the stadium project. The case
was settled in July for an undisclosed sum.
</P>
<P>
   ``A construction zone is not a war zone,'' Taber said. ``It is
not part of doing business that people have to lose their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   David Vail, a safety director for Perini Building Co., the
general contractor on BOB, said the dollar amount of most OSHA
fines are financially meaningless to companies like Perini, which
posted sales of $1.3 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Vail said safety-related fines can still damage a company's
bottom line, by increasing insurance costs and causing bad
publicity that drives away potential partners. That motivates
companies to strive for clean safety records, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you are cited with a violation, (it becomes) public
record,'' Vail said. ``Anybody has access to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Hughes, a spokesman for a business group, the Arizona
Association of Industries, said OSHA doesn't need higher fines. He
said most companies try to avoid the lost productivity, bad press
and high insurance rates associated with an unsafe workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to be fined by OSHA,'' Hughes said. ``Nobody
wants to have an OSHA inspector come into the workplace. . . . The
fines may not be as large as some people think they should be, but
they send a negative signal about that business, one that companies
want to avoid.''
</P>
<P>
   Vail said OSHA ``just wants people to pay attention,'' and if
companies are willing to work with the agency, fines likely will be
reduced. He said inspectors often impose the maximum sanction
because they know it will be reduced later, after company officials
meet with OSHA.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should be able to walk away with a 30 to 40 percent
reduction in the fine, and probably a good chance of getting the
fine dropped one category,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Etchechury, director of the Arizona Industrial Commission,
which oversees state OSHA, agreed that fines don't have a big
financial impact on large companies, but said OSHA penalties still
carry weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The penalty has the effect of getting someone's attention,''
said Etchechury, who has been with OSHA since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone's attention. The power of OSHA extends only so
far. The agency does not investigate workplace accidents involving
railroads, airlines, motor vehicles or criminal acts. A separate
agency also investigates mining accidents, and the Environmental
Protection Agency deals with air pollution and toxic releases.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, OSHA's authority is divided, but the state OSHA
office handles most accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Federal OSHA inspectors cover Indian reservations, federal
agencies and Fort Huachuca. At other military bases, federal OSHA
investigates accidents involving federal employees. ``The
Republic'' analysis included both state and federal OSHA cases.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by higher fine limits, OSHA has cracked down in recent
years. Fines levied by the commission have risen almost threefold,
to $1.8 million in 1997 from $645,000 in 1995. The average fine per
violation increased to $539 in 1997 from $198 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Commission Chairwoman Gay Kruglick said those numbers reflect a
newfound attitude _ more and more, commissioners are ordering high
fines and stipulating that they not be reduced in the settlement
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad thing is, you just cannot put a price on a life,'' she
said. ``The true value of a life, it's very difficult to come up
with things like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases we would like it to be higher, much higher, but
we're limited as to what we can do in following the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Etchechury said the increase also reflects a change in tactics:
OSHA now targets companies that have high rates of workers'
compensation claims, meaning inspections are more likely to turn up
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I don't think you're ever going to find a
situation where you're looking at penalties that are going to equal
the value of a human life. . . . I just don't think in terms of the
political environment that's out there that you're going to see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   OSHA fines are limited by law. The agency can fine a company up
to $7,000 for each ``serious'' safety violation, and $70,000 for a
``willful'' violation.
</P>
<P>
   Serious violations involve unsafe conditions that could lead
to &UR; injury or death. Willful violations involve dangerous conditions
that are known by the employer but go uncorrected.
</P>
<P>
   If a willful violation is particularly egregious, it can be
referred to the county attorney or the state attorney general. Such
cases are rare; no one has been convicted under the law in recent
memory, Etchechury said.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA also can seek court injunctions to prohibit an employer
from exposing workers to certain hazards. OSHA rarely takes such
extreme action, but when it does, most employers correct the
problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Congress changed the law in 1992, the highest penalty for
a serious violation was $1,000, and $10,000 for a willful
violation.
</P>
<P>
   Although the limits have been raised, the system is set up to
trim them down.
</P>
<P>
   When an Arizona OSHA inspector first calculates a fine, he puts
it through a formula that gives discounts for the company's size,
safety program and record with OSHA. Smaller companies with good
safety programs and no OSHA rap sheets see the highest discounts,
up to 95 percent. And that's not the end of it.
</P>
<P>
   The company can appeal several times before actually paying the
fine. Along the way, the amount is often reduced and citations
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   All the horse-trading is done administratively, without input
from the five commissioners, who are appointed by the governor and
come from backgrounds in medicine, insurance, small business and
labor. Depending on a company's sophistication and the skill of its
lawyers, savings can be substantial.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on July 9, 1996, a maintenance man working for
Doubletree Guest Suites in Phoenix was electrocuted while working
on an air conditioner in a guest room, OSHA records show. The man,
Robert England, apparently forgot to turn off the power while
installing a part.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA cited Doubletree for a willful safety violation for not
providing adequate safety training for employees who work on air
conditioners. The company was also cited for two other serious
violations. Total proposed fine: $61,250.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   After a year of negotiations, state officials agreed to drop the
willful violation against Doubletree, and settle for a fine of
$5,250 _ less than one-tenth of the original sanction. There was a
catch, though: Doubletree agreed to pay $25,000 to England's widow.
</P>
<P>
   In official OSHA records, Doubletree's fine is listed as $5,250.
The $25,000 is not considered to be a fine.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Doubletree's corporate headquarters were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Company owners who can't afford lawyers also have ways of
avoiding fines.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, two men working for Allied Painting in Phoenix were
electrocuted when their aluminium ladder touched a high-voltage
power line. OSHA cited Allied for four willful safety violations,
and fined the company $47,000.
</P>
<P>
   The then-owner, Lorne Williams, appealed, but he didn't hire a
lawyer. In a deposition, he told OSHA officials that he planned on
filing bankruptcy and appealed so he'd have time to hide his
assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought myself five or six months,'' he said in the
deposition. ``And the fine will be _ will go back up to $60,000 or
whatever is, and it doesn't matter. I don't have $47,000 and I
don't have 60 (thousand), so it don't matter which they try to
collect.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams followed his plan, filed personal bankruptcy, and never
paid the fine. Today, he says he was making empty threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to get them to back off,'' Williams said in
an interview. ``They wouldn't. They didn't care. (Bankruptcy) was
the only recourse I had.''
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, even with serious violations, OSHA can't levy
fines.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, Grand Canyon National Park trail-crew member
Randy Thompson was working near Tapeats Creek, a remote area along
the Colorado River, when workers above him dislodged a 200-pound
boulder. It rolled 150 feet before hitting Thompson in the back,
killing him.
</P>
<P>
   Federal OSHA investigated the accident and found three willful
safety violations.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators cited park officials for allowing trail-crew
members to work below an area where boulders were being dislodged.
According to OSHA reports, two workers had been injured previously
under similar conditions.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA also cited park officials for having inadequate emergency
communications for employees working in remote areas and for having
no detailed emergency rescue plan.
</P>
<P>
   The park did not contest the citations; a spokeswoman said
management is committed to improving safety.
</P>
<P>
   The three willful violations _ the toughest sanction OSHA has _
could have resulted in a fine of $210,000.
</P>
<P>
   Total fine paid by the Park Service: $0.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agencies are exempt from OSHA fines.
</P>
<P>
   State agencies, however, are not exempt. And state industrial
commissioners have the option of keeping fines high, in any case.
</P>
<P>
   When levying a fine, commissioners can stipulate that it is not
subject to reduction; then, administrators can't cut a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Etchechury said, the Industrial Commission also wants
to change the workers' compensation law, to provide more benefits
for survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who suffer, essentially, are the widows and
children of widows,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, commissioners wrote a letter to the Legislature,
noting that workers' compensation premiums have dropped 37 percent
since 1995. Benefits, however, have not increased in six years.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum weekly check available through workers' compensation
is $322. The state's average weekly wage is $506.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an agency we see more and more cases of injured workers and
their families losing their homes and personal transportation,''
the commissioners wrote, ``as a result of the dramatic changes in
lifestyle caused by their injuries and the static nature of
Arizona's benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Jones, chairman of the health and insurance committee for
the Arizona Chamber of Commerce, said business and labor have
talked about legislation to raise benefit levels, but there is
little pressure to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the economy is as good as it is, it's not going to
be Number 1 on people's priority list,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Huggins, secretary-treasurer for the Arizona AFL-CIO, said
his organization has been asking legislators to raise benefit
limits for several years, without success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership doesn't see the need,'' Huggins said. ``They
see it as raising the cost of doing business, and they're afraid it
may drive business people out of Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Huggins said he'll continue to press his case and may gather
petitions to put the matter to a public vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good system if business really, in fact, did their
half,'' Huggins said. ``The trade-off was, you don't sue us, and
we'll pony up the money to take care of you and your family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's evolved into, we don't sue them but they don't take care
of the family.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Bill Muller can be reached at 444-8178 or at bill.muller &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
