<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON POINTED TO THERAPIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Mike Tyson's future could be in the hands of a
psychiatrist he has yet to meet.
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada State Athletic Commission voted to postpone for two
weeks its decision on whether to relicense the former champion and
directed him to see an independent therapist to prove he's mentally
fit to fight.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which revoked his license after he bit off a
portion of Evander Holyfield's ear in 1996, will reconvene on Oct.
3.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they say he's normal and can fight again, then we have the
responsibility to maybe, probably, license him to fight again,''
said commission chairman Elias Ghanem, who oversaw the
sometimes-contentious six-hour hearing at a minor-league ballpark
here.
</P>
<P>
   The decision doesn't mean Tyson is guaranteed a license even if
he receives a glowing mental evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners remain concerned about an incident in a
Washington D.C. suburb in which Tyson was accused of punching one
man and kicking another, which might indicate a continued inability
to control his temper. A preliminary hearing is set for Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson has denied any wrongdoing and his attorneys stressed at
the hearing that he's innocent until proven guilty. Commission
members will monitor the case and it will be a factor in their
final decision.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it's a touchy issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still concerned,'' commissioner James Nave said. ``I don't
want to do anything without strongly considering it. We still have
two weeks to see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also don't want to do something that could give anyone an
opportunity to file a lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's advisers and the commissioners verbally sparred on
occasion but, while Tyson was testy at times, he generally kept his
composure.
</P>
<P>
   He again expressed remorse over the biting incident, saying,
``Trust me, this won't happen anymore. I've learned, man. I'm so
sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   And he opened the door to the commission's decision to continue
the hearing when he agreed to waive doctor-patient confidentiality
when he is examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in my life is private,'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   His temper flared only when he was asked how many contracts he's
signed in his long career. He asked how he could possibly know such
a thing and said, ``You are humiliating me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's lead attorney, Dale Kinsella, tried to minimize an
alleged altercation with two women in May and the punch he's
accused of throwing in D.C. by submitting testimony from witnesses
saying they never occurred. However, he failed to mention the
kicking allegation, which irked commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsella tried to illustrate the financial impact of the ban.
</P>
<P>
   He said his client lost $50 million to $60 million since he lost
his license and is having financial difficulties in good part
because of questionable management in the past, which could prompt
him to fight elsewhere if he is rejected.
</P>
<P>
   And, most significant, he had two therapists who have examined
Tyson speak on his behalf. Both said he's stable and mentally fit
to compete.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't good enough for the commissioners, who want to be as
certain as possible that Tyson will not go berserk again in the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   Ghanem suggested that the commission select three therapists and
have Tyson select one. The fighter and his handlers agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsella said he was pleased with the decision, which surprised
many who believed Tyson's application would be rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's still a possibility with the D.C. incident
pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern over the incident will be diminished if a
physician says he's capable of fighting in the ring,'' said Don
Haight, chief deputy attorney general. ``... He's innocent until
proven guilty. You can't take that away from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean his license can't be revoked again if he's
convicted, though.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 0029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980920.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4701 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSHA-POWELL-AZR &LR;      09-20 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSHA-POWELL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWITCH COULD HAVE SAVED LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One button could have saved Cory Powell's life.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, a 35-year-old trash collector from Mesa, was decapitated
in 1994 while working in the bed of a garbage truck. He left behind
a wife and two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA investigators said Powell might have survived to take care
of his family if his employer had bothered to maintain its trucks
or train its workers. The OSHA penalty: $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Powell said the punishment doesn't fit the crime. The
manner of Cory's death _ decapitation _ made it that much harder to
accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was gruesome,'' she said. ``He was really into donating,
like blood and plasma, and he was on a bone marrow list. And the
way he died, he couldn't do it. It was just very tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 16, 1994, Cory Powell was driving a garbage truck on his
usual route in Mesa when he stopped to fix a problem with the
truck's ``ram'' _ a large, bladed device used to compact garbage in
the truck's hopper.
</P>
<P>
   Powell was working with a helper, who was on his first day on
the job. The man watched Powell climb into a pit behind the ram and
fiddle with a switch.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the ram started to move. Powell's tinkering had set it
off.
</P>
<P>
   According to an accident report, the helper ``reached for the
victim to help him out, but the victim turned away from him and
reached for something inside the pit. The victim then became
animated and appeared to be unable to make up his mind which way to
get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell's partner frantically hit all the buttons on the side of
the truck. Nothing helped. The emergency stop button failed. The
ram continued forward.
</P>
<P>
   Powell was killed.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA investigators found mechanical problems with the safety
systems on the garbage truck, and the company that owned it, Apache
Sanitation.
</P>
<P>
   According to OSHA reports, the company kept no maintenance
records, had no formalized training for drivers and did not inspect
its trucks. And the emergency shutdown switch _ which might have
saved Powell's life _ did not work properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The switch would operate only if hit very firmly with the heel
of the hand, and then only after two or three whacks,'' the OSHA
report said. ``Normal finger or hand pressure did nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona workers' compensation laws preclude Judy Powell from
suing Apache Sanitation, which has since been bought out by another
company.
</P>
<P>
   Workers' compensation insurance pays Powell a surviving-spouse
benefit of $530.79 per month. Arizona ranks last in death benefits
paid to surviving spouses, and Powell said the laws need to be
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair the way our laws work,'' she said. ``They're
protecting the companies, not the workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell said her husband's death left her devastated and
financially strapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my house, I had to move into a room,'' she said. ``It
changed my life totally. It made me into somebody that can't
actually have a house by themselves anymore. . . . I can share, but
I can't have my own.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, and I have nobody to talk to.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Bill Muller can be reached at 444-8178 or at bill.muller &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
