<SLUG> BC-OSHA-REDDEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO FINES PAID DESPITE 2 DEATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Painters Robert Redden and Greg Gauthier were probably in a
hurry on that Christmas Eve in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Their foreman was on his way to the bank to get their paychecks,
and they had last-minute shopping to do. Both had big plans.
Redden, 22, was getting married in a week. Gauthier, 19, was
studying to get his general equivalency diploma.
</P>
<P>
   They were finishing up, taking down a 40-foot aluminum ladder.
Suddenly, it began to topple, falling toward a 7,200-volt power
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow that ladder got away from them,'' recalled Lorne
Williams, former owner of Allied Painting. ``They grabbed the
ladder and tried to catch it. It was aluminum, and it hit them
wires and cooked them.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men were killed.
</P>
<P>
   State OSHA inspectors came down hard on Allied Painting and
Williams, who had already been fined $500 in 1991 for not having a
ladder properly secured.
</P>
<P>
   This time, OSHA fined Williams and his company $47,000 for
violations that included allowing the men to work near a live
high-voltage line and allowing them to use an aluminum ladder
around electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fine was hefty, Williams has never paid a dime.
</P>
<P>
   He appealed, and in a deposition conducted by state lawyers,
said he planned to hide his personal assets and declare bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lose all my life savings over something like
this,'' Williams said in July 1993. ``And now it's someplace where
no one will find it. Believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, Williams declared bankruptcy, claiming
liabilities of $47,200 (the amount of the OSHA fine and court
costs) and assets of $2,000. OSHA never collected anything.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Etchechury, director of the Arizona Industrial Commission,
which oversees state OSHA, said it is difficult to collect fines
from a company that declares bankruptcy. The agency must stand in
line with the other creditors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Williams, 66, says he never had any assets to hide, but
was ``just trying to get (OSHA) to back off.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said his son, John, served as his foreman and had
cautioned the painters to stay away from the power lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave them safety classes,'' Williams said in an interview.
``He warned them. They knew to be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said there was no way he could pay the OSHA fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to lose everything I worked for my whole life
over this thing,'' he said. ``I had to declare bankruptcy. . . . At
my age, I'm kind of old to be starting over.''
</P>
<P>
   Redden's fiancee, Jennifer Pruyne, isn't satisfied with
Williams' explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't even supposed to be using those aluminum ladders,''
said Pruyne, who now lives in Rochester, N.Y. ``He was supposed to
be using wood. This guy gets off scot-free . . . and two people
lost their lives as a result of his carelessness.''
</P>
<P>
   Pruyne, the mother of Redden's 6-year-old son, said the workers'
compensation burial benefit didn't even cover the cost of a
headstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert is out there buried with no gravestone at all. . . .
Things like that make me angry,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Redden's death sent Pruyne's life into a tailspin. Because she
wasn't married to Redden, she didn't get workers' compensation. And
Redden had no life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was devastated,'' she said. ``I was only 21 years old. I had
a 6-month-old baby. I didn't have a job, and I had no way to pay
the bills anymore. If it was not for my family . . . I'd probably
be living on the street somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier's death made for some tough family relations. Williams,
who owned Allied, is related to Gauthier by marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst thing that ever happened to me,'' Williams
said. ``That was bad. The whole fam &UR; if
</P>
</TEXT>
