A4703 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CAL-OU-TEX     09-20 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CAL-OU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA EDGES OKLAHOMA, 13-12
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ Opportunity was knocking. Momentum had been
established with two victories, the second an inspiring
final-minute rally to defeat TCU.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma had the chance to start 3-0 for the first time in five
seasons and properly celebrate the school's 1,000th college
football game. Instead, the Sooners went from in sync to down the
drain.
</P>
<P>
   California (2-1), executing a clutch fourth-quarter drive, made
enough plays to record a 13-12 victory last night. The Sooners
(2-1), hampered by an ineffective passing attack for the third
consecutive game, walked away wondering what went wrong _ again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts bad,'' Oklahoma defensive tackle Kelly Gregg said.
``Our offense scored right off the bat. We're supposed to hold them
to nothing. Losing at home by a point ... terrible. Yuck. It makes
you sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Cal's Tim Wolleck kicked his second field goal of the game, a
27-yarder with 5 minutes, 56 seconds remaining, to stomp on the
Sooners' hearts. OU didn't threaten on its final two possessions.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners have lost 12 of their past 16 games at Memorial
Stadium. A sellout crowd (74,235) whooped it up early but started
booing late in the first half _ angered by OU's stuttering offense
and the play of quarterback Brandon Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners entered the game ranked 103rd nationally in passing;
they are likely to drop. Daniels and last-series reliever Jarrod
Reese were a combined 3 for 10 for 77 yards with one interception.
OU's only touchdown was a 58-yard screen pass from Daniels to Matt
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma coach John Blake, who was confident a return to the
option would solve his team's problems, said the lack of a passing
game did not concern him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several times we could have made some long runs,
but we didn't get a key block or the right read,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma had 16 plays resulting in no gain or negative yardage.
With no passing threat to concern them, the Bears crowded the line
of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried to pass early and it didn't work,'' said Cal coach
Tom Holmoe, whose team survived 16 penalties for 130 yards.
``They're committed to the run and they're going to whip some teams
with that offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels was unavailable after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Blake was noncommittal about Daniels' performance. Late in the
third quarter, the fans began chanting ``Fletch-er, Fletch-er.''
They wanted sophomore walk-on Patrick Fletcher, the hero of the
Sooners' first two victories, to replace Daniels. Fletcher did not
play.
</P>
<P>
   In two seasons under Blake, mistakes have been plentiful.
Oklahoma missed two field-goal attempts, lost a fumble that set up
Cal's only touchdown and committed a holding penalty, ruining a
drive at the Bears' 2-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to come away with something, at least a field goal,
when you get that close,'' Blake said. ``It's like throwing punches
and missing.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest mistake came after the Sooners' touchdown. Kicker
Jeff Ferguson, who later became ill and was replaced by Matt
Reeves, missed the extra-point attempt, the difference in the
score.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners hoped a 3-0 nonconference record would boost their
chances for a bowl game. Now, they head into Big 12 Conference play
shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really wanted to go into the conference 3-0,'' Gregg said.
``Losing by one point at home will kill your confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
