<SLUG> BC-OSHA-GARCIA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHT INSTALLATION TURNS DEADLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Macario Garcia feared the one thing that killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after climbing an 8-foot ladder to install
fluorescent lights in a renovated office building, an electric
shock hurled Garcia to the concrete floor. He died 16 hours later
from head injuries. He was 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``He once told my younger brother that it gave him chills to get
up there,'' said Marilyn Chavez, Garcia's sister. ``I wish I had
known that before.''
</P>
<P>
   OSHA inspectors cited Garcia's employer, Keystone Electric,
$6,500 for unsafe working conditions and inadequate training.
Keystone appealed and eventually paid $2,625.
</P>
<P>
   The fine was too small for the Garcia family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' Chavez said. ``That's the value of my
brother's life?''
</P>
<P>
   Keystone owners Jay and Lori Schrock did not return phone calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the state denied Garcia's family survivor benefits
because he was not married and did not have children. But
eventually, it agreed to pay Garcia's mother, Reyna, 15 percent, or
about $300 a month, of her son's salary as required by law.
</P>
<P>
   The money did little to ease the family's grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother's taking it one day at a time,'' Chavez said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's death was felt throughout the 4,000-resident community
of El Mirage where he had served on the City Council and the Dysart
Unified School District board.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia had worked for Keystone Electric periodically for about
five years, but had planned to leave to sell real estate.
</P>
<P>
   As an apprentice, Garcia was not allowed to work on electrical
wiring, according to OSHA. But foreman Brian Drye told
investigators that Garcia may have been trying to tighten some
loose wire nuts on an energized emergency light circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's co-workers heard him yell, ``Whoa!'' and when they
turned, they saw him falling off the fiberglass-framed ladder. His
head and shoulders struck the concrete floor, and he died later,
after his brain swelled.
</P>
<P>
   His sister said the family took the accident hard. She had
already lost her father and her oldest brother. In March, she lost
her 3-year-old nephew to a heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through a lot,'' Chavez said. ``I guess our faith
is the only thing that keeps us going.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
