<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETICS BLAST RANGERS, SELE, 8-4
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Aaron Sele is much more concerned about
helping the Rangers win a division title than he is about becoming
a 20-game winner.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't help either cause last night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead Sele was hammered by the Oakland Athletics in his
shortest outing of the season and the Rangers' four-game winning
streak came to an end in an 8-4 loss before 46,036 at The Ballpark
in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez thrilled the crowd with his 300th home run of his
career. But that and a three-run homer by Mike Simms came after the
Rangers trailed 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just made bad pitches,'' Sele said. ``Every pitch they hit
was well over the plate. You can hang this L on me. I didn't feel
good from the get-go.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss left the Rangers only one game ahead of the Anaheim
Angels in the American League West with eight games to go. The
Angels defeated the Seattle Mariners, 5-3, last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll still be in first place,'' outfielder Rusty Greer said.
``We can't let a loss distract us from what we have to do in our
eight remaining games.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele lasted only 31/3 innings, giving up four runs on eight hits
and two walks. The loss drops his record to 18-11 with one
scheduled start left, on Thursday against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much eliminates the possibility of a 20-victory
season, but Sele said: ``That doesn't mean a thing. We need to win
ballgames; what I do personally takes a back seat to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele's trouble started when he walked Rickey Henderson to lead
off the first. Ryan Christenson followed with a run-scoring double
into the left-field corner, and Jason Giambi slammed a run-scoring
single up the middle, giving Oakland a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Sele got out of that inning but his own fielding led to trouble
in the third after Henderson led off with a single. Christenson
dropped a sacrifice bunt too hard, giving Sele a play at second.
But he first hesitated, then bounced his throw past shortstop Royce
Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He bunted the ball, and I figured if they were (sacrificing)
there, Rickey probably had it made,'' Sele said. ``Pudge
(Rodriguez) yelled two, and I didn't have a good grip on the ball.
But it's still an error. If I had made any kind of a throw, he's
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The play cost Sele. He struck out Jason Giambi and got Matt
Stairs to fly out. But Ben Grieve singled home one run, and Mike
Macfarlane's double made it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great atmosphere for baseball here,'' Macfarlane said.
``This is our playoff so we wanted to play with a little more
intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics kept it up against the Rangers' bullpen with four
runs in the final five innings. The home runs by Gonzalez and Simms
off Oakland starter Jimmy Haynes made it 6-4 in the sixth inning.
But Stairs doubled home a run off Danny Patterson in the eighth and
Eric Chavez had a run-scoring double off Xavier Hernandez in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bullpen just couldn't put zeros up,'' manager Johnny Oates
said. ``I really thought we had a shot after we made it 6-4, but
they added a run right away, and that made it tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson has allowed 12 runs in his past 10 appearances, and
Hernandez has given up 10 runs in his past 12 outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two are not throwing as consistently as they did in the
first half of the season,'' Oates said. ``But they'll be fine. They
brought us this far; they'll carry us the rest of the way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
