<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FRESNO-STATE-TEXAS-TECH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUMBLE RECOVERY SAVES TEXAS TECH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK HERRIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ What Texas Tech linebacker Kyle Shipley saw at
the goal-line was nearly inconceivable.
</P>
<P>
   A free ball. In the air. The game hanging on the line.
</P>
<P>
   And what Shipley, a former Martin High School standout saw, he
took.
</P>
<P>
   The junior grabbed Fresno State tailback Jaime Kimbrough's
fumble with 48 seconds remaining, then stepped over the goal line
from a yard out to complete Tech's frenzied 34-28 victory last
night before 40,035 at Jones Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just trying to keep them down on the goal line,''
Shipley said. ``The ball just popped out in midair and I just
grabbed it and ran it in. It was a candy-hop. Sometimes it's better
to be luckier than good.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech finished nonconference play 3-0 for the first time since
1989 and Fresno State fell to 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   Shipley's defensive play, aided by defensive back Reagan Bounds
who hit Kimbrough, capped a remarkable final five minutes that
included three lead changes and two defensive touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore standout Ricky Williams had another workhorse night,
gaining 250 yards and two touchdowns on a career-high 42 rushes.
Williams, who had a career-high 72-yard burst on his first carry of
the game, now has 665 yards this season.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's 18-point halftime lead completely vanished with 4:04
remaining when senior quarterback Matt Tittle's pass was
intercepted along the sidelines by Justin Johnson and returned for
a 33-yard touchdown. Tittle, a Marcus High School graduate, had an
up-and-down start finishing 8-for-17 with 109 yards and a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the hardest things I've been through,'' said
Tittle, making his second career start. ``I was just pacing up and
down the sidelines ready to get the ball back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders didn't need it.
</P>
<P>
   After Tittle handed Fresno State a 28-27 lead, the Raiders
bounced back. On the ensuing kickoff, Tech sophomore John Norman
burst 86 yards from 3 yards deep in his own end zone. Norman, a
Midland Lee grad, shook tackles and even balanced himself on the
ground with his hands while breaking loose to stay on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was down,'' said Fresno State coach Pat Hill. ``He put the
ball on the ground and spun around. Just look at the film. But you
have to give the kid credit. He made a great play when it
counted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like the odds were turning against us,'' Norman
said. ``I had to make a big play.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman's big play was just a start to this game's craziness in
the waning minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With Williams in the backfield, Tech appeared safe. But the
running back tried for an extra yard at the 1-yard line and was hit
hard by the Bulldogs. He fumbled and Fresno took control at its own
1. But then Shipley's opportunistic play saved the Red Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just made an awful big play when he had to,'' Tech coach
Spike Dykes said of Shipley. ``I admire our guys. They hung in
there when it looked like it was all over with.'' Extra points
All-Big 12 defensive end Montae Reagor became the school's career
sack leader with 19.5 after recording two sacks last night. He
finished with a team-leading 11 tackles. ... The Raiders drew over
40,000 for the second time this season. Its the first time since
1981 the Raiders have drawn 40,000 or more in their first two home
dates. ... Wide receiver Donnie Hart passed Donny Anderson on
Tech's career touchdown reception list with 13 and is seven away
from tying record-holder Lloyd Hill.
</P>
</TEXT>
