<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bean earns a bushel of respect
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- There never seemed to be much to Vaughn Bean. He came
into Saturday night's heavyweight championship bout against Evander
Holyfield as a virtual unknown, although ranked as the No. 1
contender by the IBF.
</P>
<P>
   He displayed a personality that was embraceable, but hardly
captivating. And he wore a red turban and a girth around a waist as
soft as a jellybean.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn left the ring at the Georgia Dome far more impressive and
compelling than when he entered, a winner in defeat. Like the guy
who breaks your lamp at a house party, Bean was looking to spoil
Holyfield's self-promoted championship event.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Holyfield won a 12-round unanimous decision, but
Bean was a heroic contestant.
</P>
<P>
   By the 10th round _ a time when Holyfield expected to be on his
way to a party he threw at the World Congress Center _ a chant of
``Bean, Bean, Bean'' rose from a small but rowdy contingent near
ringside. The challenger took that as a cue to get busier, but it
did not work out too well. After Holyfield slung him into the
ropes, Bean was dropped by a right as he was still trying to gain
his footing _ a transgression that incensed Bean's corner.
</P>
<P>
   He survived the round, but was not nearly as effective the
remaining two rounds, although he did land at least six blows to
Holyfield's surgically repaired ear. When it was over, Holyfield's
hand was raised, but perhaps Bean's stock rose higher.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old Bean, who fights out of Philadelphia, faced
extreme odds, starting with his marginal talent against a noble
champion and ending with the the record-setting crowd
overwhelmingly against him.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bean opened the fight seemingly unfazed about the odds.
He entered the ring to music claiming ``This is it!'' and did not
back down or away from the champion. With promoter Butch Lewis and
former heavyweight champ Michael Spinks, among others, screaming
encouragement, Bean plowed ahead aggressively if not effectively.
</P>
<P>
   He hit Holyfield with a flush right that had to heighten his
esteem. Ditto for an uppercut and a solid body shot. Also, he took
some crisp blows from Holyfield, something that had to concern his
corner.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Bean took the steps in gaining respect. He
received some punishment on the ropes, but he pushed his way out.
Later, he found an effective ally _ a looping overhand right. Bean
used it repeatedly and scored some blows that concerned the crowd,
if not the champion. And those punches and a creditable chin
carried him the distance.
</P>
<P>
   This Bean from nowhere who was supposed to be the prop in a
Holyfield hometown tribute suddenly was in territory few expected.
He had his moments against the champion.
</P>
<P>
   Before the official announcement of his defeat, Bean donned his
red turban and raised his right fist to the crowd. He received an
appreciative ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Bean professed to have learned from defeat in his title fight in
March 1997 against Michael Moorer, saying he would not let the
magnitude of the moment overwhelm him. Bean didn't. He lost, but he
won, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
