<SLUG> BC-FBC-DUKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke can't handle Seminoles' speed
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ The No. 11 Florida State Seminoles separated
themselves from last week's stunning loss at N.C. State the only
way they know how _ running as fast as they can.
</P>
<P>
   Speed has helped them rule the ACC for six years and it was
plenty to shake off a Duke team that was winless in its previous 18
ACC games and had not come within 24 points of the Seminoles in
their six meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils (2-1) have improved and Florida State may have
declined, but that didn't matter in the Seminoles' 62-13 thrashing
Saturday night. That final, combined with N.C. State's 33-30 loss
to Baylor, has last week's Seminole loss looking flukish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duke really caught us at a bad time,'' Florida State coach
Bobby Bowden said. ``You never know how you're going to respond,
but we responded the way I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden simplified his offense early, allowing 26-year-old rookie
quarterback Chris Weinke to recover from his six-interception
embarrassment against the Wolfpack, work his way into the game and
let the skill players around him use their quickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried a lot of things with our quarterback to see if he was
ready,'' Bowden said. ``He looked like a different quarterback than
last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke looked more like the quarterback who played well in the
opener against Texas A&AMP;M, finishing with 241 yards on 11-of-19
passing for three touchdowns and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles (2-1) ended their drought of four scoreless
quarters with 24 points in the second quarter and 28 in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Using two turnovers in the second quarter, Florida State blew
open the game with a pair of touchdown passes, a 97-yard kickoff
return for a touchdown by Laveranues Coles and a 35-yard field goal
by Sebastian Janikowski to take a 24-10 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly it was star receiver Peter Warrick who was the first
to make a play look easy for Florida State. Following a Spencer
Romine interception by Sean Key, Warrick blew past Lamar Grant and
sprinted under a perfectly thrown 30-yard touchdown pass to the
back corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
