<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glavine's 20th is Braves' 100th
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX_ On a stat freak's dream night, Tom Glavine reached 20,
Atlanta reached 100 and the Braves reached a franchise home run
record Saturday night. Unwitting participants to the proceedings
were the Arizona Diamondbacks, riddled for 11 hits in a 5-0 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams, batting .375 this month, hit a two-run homer
two at-bats into the game and Glavine took care of the rest to
become the major leagues' first 20-game winner this season at 20-6.
He retired the first 10 men he faced and 16 of the first 17 to up
his road record to 12-2.
</P>
<P>
   The victory marked the fourth time in his career Glavine has
reached 20 wins, his first since 1993. He is the only active
pitcher in the majors with four 20-win seasons for the same team.
</P>
<P>
   The team also improved to 100-56, the best record in the
National League by two games over NL Central champion Houston. The
Braves have now recorded consecutive 100-win seasons and three in
the last four completed full seasons dating to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise record of 104 wins, set in 1993, is well within
reach with six games remaining to play. Not since the Philadelphia
Phillies of 1976-77 has an NL team recorded back-to-back 100-win
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had accumulated eight hits by the sixth and hit
Arizona starter Brian Anderson hard throughout. The first 18 outs
included eight line-outs, one a suspended-animation leap by
shortstop Tony Batista that took away a single from Andruw Jones in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   After being held to a run in the first two games of this series
(Atlanta's lowest production in consecutive games since May 8-9,
1997), Williams made up for the shortfall with one swing in his
first at-bat. With Ozzie Guillen on first after a leadoff single,
Williams launched an 0-1 fastball over the Diamondbacks' bullpen
down the left field line for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The homer, Williams' ninth overall and his fourth in six starts,
gave the Braves 207 this season, tying the Atlanta record set in
1966, the team's first season at Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium.
Anderson was a likely candidate to help the Braves tie the mark.
The homer was the 38th he has yielded this season, most in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   And the Braves still weren't finished in the first. Andres
Galarraga hit a cue-shot double down the right field line, his
first extra-base hit in seven games, and Andruw Jones followed two
batters later with a double in the right-center alley, driving in
Galarraga for a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
