<HEADER>
A4716 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-EVANDER-MAIN-COX     09-20 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLOSE CALL!
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Promoters billed the evening as, ``The Champ Hits
Home,'' and it goes without saying Evander Holyfield climbed into a
boxing ring at Georgia Dome Saturday night with some distinct
advantages. He owned the heavyweight title. He owned Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, he didn't own Vaughn Bean.
</P>
<P>
   Bean, the obscure and much lampooned heavyweight contender, did
what Mike Tyson couldn't: He gave Holyfield a challenge. Bean took
Holyfield's best punches early and late and survived a
controversial knockdown. Holyfield won a unanimous decision but not
before an overflow crowd of 41,357 at the Georgia Dome wondered
what happened to the guy who so easily dismantled Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very awkward,'' Holyfield said. ``I didn't come in
overconfident. I hit him with good shots. He also hit me with good
shots, so you have to respect that. He's a good fighter and nobody
gave him credit. He fought a smart fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you break a person's rhythm like that, it means (your
opponent) fought a good fight. What I didn't do was put punches
together like I should have.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges' scorecards had a decided tilt: 116-111, 117-110 and
117-110. But knocking Bean off balance wasn't as easy as some
projected. Turns out the opponent, whom Holyfield trainer Don
Turner insisted ``is no joke,'' gave the IBF and WBA champion fits.
Bean's punches didn't carry enough whallop to get Holyfield in
trouble, but he connected enough times and dodged enough to last
the night.
</P>
<P>
   The only knockdown, in fact, was set up by an unfair advantage
for Holyfield. Holyfield dominated the early rounds but could not
deliver a knockdown punch, and Bean seemed to gain confidence with
each passing round. Some ringside fans actually started to chant,
``Bean, Bean, Bean'' in the 10th round when the fight turned ugly
with Bean leaning on Holyfield, the champion sidestepped Bean and
appeared to push him through the ropes. As Bean started to get up,
Holyfield knocked him down with a right to the head before referee
Brian Garry could get between them. Bean got up and lasted the
round, but Bean's corner went crazy, yelling expletives at
Holyfield and Garry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit me when I was down,'' Bean said. ``The ref didn't do
his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean shook off the controversy and the punishment. He hung with
Holyfield in the 11th round and actually landed the stronger blows
in the 12th as the final bell sounded.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bell nobody thought would be run that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I won the fight _ same song,'' said Bean, who lost a
majority decision to Michael Moorer last year. ``I hit him with a
lot of punches.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Don King said later, ``See what I mean about Mr. Bean?
Can't ever tell what's going to happen when you step into the
ring.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not Holyfield's first fight in Atlanta, just his most
significant. All previous ring appearances came either as an
overlooked amateur, not expected to make the U.S. Olympic team, or
as a popular but underappreciated professional. Even as heavyweight
champion in 1991, Holyfield entered the Omni against Bert Cooper
perceived as only second-best in the world to an Indiana inmate
named Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Not Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   When Holyfield strolled down a walkway to ``Spirit of Jesus,''
the crowd rose and recognized him as the probable winner of not
only this fight but the owner of his era. He had destroyed Mike
Tyson twice to claim and defend one title belt and flattened
Michael Moorer to add another, rendering WBC champion Lennox Lewis
into almost an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield wasted little time going after Bean. He pressed the
attack in the first round, landing three consecutive shots to
Bean's belly a minute into the fight and connecting with an
overhand right to the chin in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   Bean, who weighed in at 231 pounds,19 pounds heavier than he
weighed for his last title shot against Michael Moorer 18 months
ago, spent much of the time backing up, trying to catch Holyfield s
he was coming in. But he landed his best shot late in the second
round while standing in the center of the ring, knocking Holyfield
back with a left to the top of the head.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield came out in the third round on his toes, intent on
boxing Holyfield. Bean, however, stayed back and stayed clear of
Holyfield's jab. The two eventually stood flat-footed exchanging
combinations. Holyfield finished with a flurry toward the end of
the round but was unable to land a significant blow.
</P>
<P>
   Bean started to tire in the fourth. As his cornerman yelled,
``Hang on, Vaughn,'' Holyfield connected with a right to the head
and a left to the chin. Bean escaped further damage but was
breathing heavy at the end of the round.
</P>
<P>
   The night was not over any time soon, though. Bean landed a
strong uppercut in the fifth round and seemed to gain momentum in
the sixth, taking the best of Holyfield's punches and firing back.
</P>
<P>
   And he kept it up for six more rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
