<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA STUMBLES TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The UCLA Bruins arrived in this steam bath by
Galveston Bay as four-touchdown favorites, ranked fourth
nationally, feeling wiser and better than their years would
suggest.
</P>
<P>
   They left Saturday evening without big-play receiver Freddie
Mitchell, lost for the season with a broken leg, without talented
defensive lineman Kenyon Coleman, out at least three weeks with a
knee injury, and looking every bit their age.
</P>
<P>
   Don't book those Fiesta Bowl tickets just yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' 42-24 victory over Houston, before 19,540 Saturday
at Robertson Stadium, was delivered in the most atypical wrapping.
From Cade McNown's fumbled snaps to Chris Sailer's missed field
goals, from spotty defense to myriad penalties, this was UCLA's
worst performance since the first half of the Tennessee game 54
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston came to play, and as far as us matching their
intensity, we didn't do a good job,'' Bruins cornerback Marques
Anderson said. ``Even though we're the No. 4 team in the nation, we
still have a lot to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing a winless team they smashed 66-10 last season, the Bruins
started slow, yielded 442 yards and played exactly like a team with
two senior starters on defense. Houston quarterback Jason McKinley
looked like David Klingler at times, as UCLA's blitzers failed to
penetrate the Cougars' line and its cornerbacks failed to slow a
less-than-stellar receiving corps.
</P>
<P>
   Even McNown seemed out of sync, despite his 315 yards.
Mitchell's injury stripped the Bruins of their best big-play threat
and made them look unusually slow.
</P>
<P>
   While tailback Jermaine Lewis tied a school record with four
touchdowns, UCLA's ground game never took charge against Houston's
stingy defense, ranked second in the nation against the run.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars also delivered a series of late hits designed to
rattle the young Bruins and frustrated McNown, who suffered minor
sprains of both ankles and appeared to absorb more blows that
normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little concerned about some of the late hits on
Cade,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``And I wasn't particularly
pleased with how (the officials) controlled the game. I don't think
(Houston coach) Kim Helton was, either.''
</P>
<P>
   To an extent, the 2-0 Bruins are victims of their own success.
They've been so dominant during their school-record 12-game winning
streak that anything less than 50-10 seems a death struggle. This
wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Closer than expected? Perhaps. Sloppier than expected?
Absolutely. The Bruins committed 12 penalties for 90 yards. But
Houston never stood on the brink of an upset, never got closer than
11 points in the second half and never made the Bruins sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Nature took care of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave an excellent effort,'' UCLA guard Andy Meyers said.
``It was probably the best game they'll play all year. But we
showed a lot of poise. It can't get any more adverse than it was,
and we responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have beaten Texas 66-3 last year, but we beat these
guys 66-10, and they were equally vengeful. They wanted our
(butts), and they got the best piece they could get. But good teams
find a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins found it not with meticulous execution, but with a
slew of big plays that turned a 6-0 first-quarter deficit into a
35-14 third-quarter lead.
</P>
<P>
   McNown connected with receiver Brian Poli-Dixon for the first
strike, a 61-yard touchdown pass that gave UCLA a 7-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's ensuing drive stalled after three plays, and Tod
McBride, the third-string safety with two bad knees, charged around
left end and blocked Joey Saavedra's punt. A minute later, Lewis
bulled for his first score and a 14-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was one play I could have back, I wish that we could
take back that blocked punt,'' Helton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins took command early in the third quarter with two
touchdowns in less than a minute. Linebacker Santi Hall intercepted
McKinley's pass at the Houston 26, and with 9:55 remaining, Lewis
plunged for another scored.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays later, Ryan Roques intercepted McKinley's pass in
the left flat and charged 17 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
