<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ALL HIS TALENTS, IT'S EASY TO FORGET RODRIGUEZ'S YOUTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Somewhere between his .320 batting average
and the wild swings he sometimes takes at the plate sits the real
Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between his cannon of a throwing arm and the pitches
he sometimes takes ``off,'' you'll find the real ``Pudge.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, in so many ways, the most valuable of all the first-place
Rangers. But he is also the hardest to understand.
</P>
<P>
   On a team of even-keel personalities, he is easily the most
volatile. He brandishes his emotions like a forearm tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   But as a leader in the clubhouse, Rodriguez falls somewhere
behind Will Clark, Mark McLemore and Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez, you have to remind yourself, is just 26 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   At age 26, he has already risen to the top of his profession. He
has been in seven All-Star Games. He has more than 1,100 hits.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, he is roundly taken for granted by fans and media who
have come to expect ... well, more. The defense of a Charles
Johnson, maybe. The hitting prowess of a Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone on this playing field takes him for
granted,'' manager Johnny Oates argued before last night's 8-4 loss
to the Oakland Athletics. ``Our pitchers certainly don't. In his
arm, we realize we have a weapon that no one else has.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, his youth betrays him. Rodriguez is 26, but looks even
younger. He is Pudge, having a helmet-slamming temper tantrum in
the dugout, and yet he is Pugsley _ the oh-so-cute Beanie Baby
bulldog that honored him in a Ballpark giveaway last month.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez plays with uncommon emotion. But his teammates have
suggested that his occasional self-directed tantrums could be
better spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotten much better,'' a teammate said. ``You have to
remember _ he's still a young guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez plays hard. But when a slider in the dirt slips past
him, the critics wince.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let those critics come out here and squat behind the plate as
much as he has this year,'' said Oates, the former catcher. ``Don't
be a critic if you haven't done it, because you don't know how
tough it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out there in the heat, humidity and all the pressure, and
Tim Crabtree is skipping one to him at 92 miles an hour. Believe
me, he's moving as fast as those stocky little legs can move.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates presents an eloquent argument. For 131 games this year, he
has penciled in Rodriguez's name behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pudge is as good a five-tool player as there is in the major
leagues _ hitting, hitting for power, defense, running and
throwing,'' Oates summed up. ``He can do it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The asterisk that always seems to attach itself to Rodriguez's
numbers is named Charles Johnson, now catching for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``C.J. is a lot more defense-oriented,'' said the Rangers' Rick
Helling, who got to pitch to Johnson when both were with the
Florida Marlins. ``He leaves everything he's got defensively on the
field, and whatever he does offensively, it's a plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Pudge takes his offense more seriously. If he's struggling
offensively, it bothers him.''
</P>
<P>
   All the same, Helling said he has absolutely no problem with an
All-Star like Rodriguez behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, lest we forget, is just 26.
</P>
<P>
   If he is selfish, as the temper episodes used to suggest, his
generosity over the past year suggests otherwise. His charitable
work included donating $50,000 to construct a badly-needed youth
ballpark in North Fort Worth. In the off-season, Pudge plans to
personally deliver stuffed Pugsleys to kids in area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers honored Rodriguez on Friday with the Roberto
Clemente Man of the Year Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was special,'' Rodriguez said. ``Because not only was
Roberto Clemente my favorite player, but the award is for not only
for baseball but for things you do in the community. I want to do
this for kids, to keep them happy and, hopefully, so they'll stay
out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez saw enough of the temptations of trouble when he was
growing up on the streets of Vega Baja in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   For Pudge, the way out was baseball. He signed with the Rangers
at the age of 16.
</P>
<P>
   He is 26 now. Young and precocious. Still a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Shame on us. Sometimes we take him for granted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
