<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA STATE PREVAILS OVER AROUSED UNT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Less than two minutes had passed, 117 seconds to
be exact, and Arizona State already had a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   A Sun Devils squad favored by 36 1/2 points appeared ready to
swallow frustration from an unexpected 0-2 start along with a
struggling North Texas team in a single gulp.
</P>
<P>
   Instead UNT engaged them in an impressive game of keepaway, and
Arizona State had to settle for a less gaudy 34-15 victory.
</P>
<P>
   A big reason UNT remained within spitting distance of Arizona
State was a also a big reason UNT had looked hapless in Weeks 1 and
2.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, an offense that ranked 112th among Division I-A programs
coming into last night's game finally showed up.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles finished with 368 yards in total offense against
Arizona State. They had a two-game total of 264 coming in. The
Eagles finished with 25 first downs. They had a two-game total of
13 coming in.
</P>
<P>
   And when sophomore quarterback LaDarrin McLane tossed a 9-yard
touchdown pass to a wide-open Ron Sterling, it ended a streak of 31
consecutive possessions without scoring a touchdown. The last
touchdown? It came on the Eagles' first drive against Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   UNT then followed it up with a touchdown on its next drive, a
4-yard run by tailback Tubby Coleman. He finished with 26 rushes
for 74 yards and his first-career touchdown. His previous numbers
were 104 yards on 29 carries _ in his career.
</P>
<P>
   UNT coach Darrell Dickey had promised a better attack coming in,
and he delivered with an I-formation that featured two tight ends
in an effort to jump-start a running game that had looked lethargic
at best this season.
</P>
<P>
   So the problem was?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is UNT's defense.
</P>
<P>
   A strength in Weeks 1 and 2, UNT's defense proved to be a
problem against Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   They had allowed 433 yards by game's end, and began by allowing
Arizona State a yard every 2.1 seconds on that opening drive.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils went 57 yards in six plays capped by a 13-yard
touchdown jog by tailback J.R. Redmond. He finished with 15 rushes
for 122 yards with a career-high three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State scored quickly and on big plays, a 60-yard
touchdown pass from Ryan Kealy to Kenny Mitchell, a 24-yard run by
Redmond, a 9-yard pass from Kealy to Lenzie Jackson and another
13-yard run by Redmond. Extra points UNT safety Ramone Archie
suffered a separated right shoulder in the third quarter, and
didn't return. He had been UNT's leading tackler coming into this
game with 26 tackles. ... UNT earned a $400,000 paycheck for last
night's game, according to Eagles athletic director Craig Helwig.
... UNT's defense snagged a pair of interceptions, by Archie and
Phillip Littlejohn. UNT's two interceptions lands them with five on
the season, tying last season's 11-game mark. ... Littlejohn
returned to action after missing last Saturday's game against Texas
Tech with a pulled hamstring. ... Eagles place-kicker Garrett
Courtney's 42-yard field goal marks his ninth straight of 40 yards
or better. ... Courtney had a 35-yard field-goal attempt blocked
earlier. UNT has allowed a pair of field goals and an extra point
blocked so far this season. ... UNT hadn't started a season 0-3
since 1982.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
