<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GONZALEZ-300-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' GONZALEZ HITS 300TH HOME RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JEFF SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ In this, the year of the home run, Rangers
right fielder Juan Gonzalez quietly found his way into the history
books last night at The Ballpark in Arlington by becoming the 81st
player in major-league history to hit 300 career home runs.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the opposing pitcher was the Oakland Athletics'
Jimmy Haynes, the inning was the sixth, the count was 1-0 and the
distance of the home run was 390 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, less than one shy of his 29th birthday, became the
sixth youngest player in major-league history to accomplish the
feat, joining four Hall of Famers and Ken Griffey Jr. Only four
players _ three Hall of Famers and Mark McGwire _ have hit their
300th home run in fewer at-bats than the 4,239 it took Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's, all right, but we lost a very important game, and I'm
more concerned with losing than home runs,'' Gonzalez said. ``I'll
have more chances for home runs, but losing a game is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The home run was Gonzalez's 44th of the season, which is the
third-highest single-season total in club history, behind his own
marks of 47 and 46 in 1996 and '93, respectively. On the Rangers'
career home-run list, Gonzalez is 144 ahead of Dean Palmer, who
ranks second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to see him hit number 300, and I wish him well
in getting 300 more,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The home run also gave Gonzalez his 154th run batted in of the
season, tying him for the major-league lead with Sammy Sosa. The
former minor-league teammates are the first players since Boston's
Vern Stephens and Ted Williams, who each had 159 RBI, in 1949 to
drive in more than 153 runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers vice president-public relations John Blake said that the
ball was returned to Gonzalez after the game in exchange for an
autographed bat.
</P>
<P>
   And while the ball was a nice present to leave the ballpark with
last night, Gonzalez easily would have exchanged it for a victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 0118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
