A4723 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-BEAN-BO     09-20 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-BEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD LOOKS SLUGGISH IN BEATING BEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Evander Holyfield looked like a 35-year-old boxer
Saturday night, and a rusty 35-year-old fighter at that.
</P>
<P>
   In what was supposed to be a joyously easy homecoming for
Atlanta's favorite son, some 42,000 fans at the Georgia Dome
watched in near disbelief as Holyfield struggled mightily before
finally defeating the unknown Vaughn Bean in a unanimous 12-round
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could have knocked him out in the first round, I would
have,'' said Holyfield, who opened the fight with a flurry. ``But I
couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield did knock Bean down once _ with 45 seconds left in the
10th round _ but even that was controversial. Holyfield had pushed
Bean into the ropes and, as the challenger had one arm draped on
the ropes, referee Brian Garry stepped in to separate the fighters,
while Holyfield uncorked a short and powerful right that sent Bean
to the canvas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit me when I was down,'' said Bean. Butch Lewis, Bean's
promoter, was so incensed at the move that he jumped onto the ring
apron and screamed at Garry, but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of the boxing game,'' said Holyfield of the
knockdown. ``You've got to take advantage of any chance you get.
You've always got to take advantage of any chance you see.''
</P>
<P>
   Garry saw it this way: ``Bean was pushed into the ropes and I
stepped in to separate them, but Evander was already in the process
of delivering his right hand. It was a knockdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Garry counted to eight and Holyfield, in his neutral corner,
seemed stupified that Bean could get up. ``I wasn't through,'' said
the challenger.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe the question that should be asked is, `Is Holyfield on
the downward slope after this performance?' If anything, this bout
may have showed how much Mike Tyson has slid, because Holyfield
looked far from the fighter he was in his two easy wins over Tyson.
When he doesn't fight Tyson, Holyfield often struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, there was no way Bean could win a decision over
Atlanta's favorite son in Atlanta. So it was no surprise that two
judges scored the bout 117-110 for Holyfield, and the third had it
at 116-111. The Globe scored the fighter closer, giving Holyfield
the decision by 115-112.
</P>
<P>
   Bean kept Holyfield off balance by pushing him away, something
Tyson could never do against Holyfield. ``My corner was shouting at
me, `Why aren't you jabbing?''' said Holyfield. ``But he slipped
some jabs ... he's a fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield delivered a solid uppercut that stunned Bean in the
first round and all in the Georgia Dome were confident it was only
a matter of time before Bean was done for the night. But the
challenger held his own, and then took the fifth round, which he
punctuated with a solid overhand right.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps it was Holyfield's experience that carried this day
because the champ took the seventh, eighth, and ninth rounds, even
though he did next to nothing in the first two minutes of each
round. But Holyfield knew enough to attack in the final 30 seconds
of each round, and he took all three with late flurries.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 12th round, when the Georgia fans were screaming for
a knockout, Holyfield was spent. So much so that Bean took the
round, leaving Holyfield to answer the obvious question.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the champ said, ``I wasn't overconfident.''
</P>
<P>
   Just old.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
