<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-MUTINY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING NOT ENOUGH FOR REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The Revolution have discovered a winning touch too
late to salvage their playoff hopes.
</P>
<P>
   They took a 3-0 victory over Tampa Bay Saturday night to become
the first Major League Soccer team to record three successive
shutouts this season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution were eliminated from playoff contention by
Miami's win over D.C. United, and must defeat Chicago Wednesday and
the New York/New Jersey Met-roStars Saturday to avoid having the
worst season in their three-year history.
</P>
<P>
   With Walter Zenga in charge, almost anything seems possible.
Since Zenga was named coach late last month, the Revolution have
played seven impressive halves, including 280 consecutive scoreless
minutes, a radical turnaround in a season that included a nine-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``These last two games are games for the future,'' Zenga said.
``They are for the players to show they are not the worst team in
the league. You will read in the newspaper that we are in the fifth
or sixth position in the standings, but this is not right. We are
not the worst team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a good team here with professional players. I feel good
about this team, and we will work to make this a big team next
year. The last games are not to finish the 1998 season; I invite
everyone to the New York game because that is our first game of the
1999 season.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga has quickly stamped his mark on this team, organizing the
defense, injecting confidence into the players, and reinvigorating
the offense. The Revolution lost to Miami, 3-2, in his debut Aug.
30 but have outscored the MetroStars, Columbus, and Tampa Bay, 7-0,
in their last three games.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any doubt over who is the overwhelming symbol of the
Revolution's recent success, it was provided by the vocal greeting
from fans as Zenga arrived for the post-match press conference.
Zenga answered questions, then signed dozens of autographs outside
the Stadium Club.
</P>
<P>
   In the Revolution's three years, they have won only 29
regular-season matches, 14 with Zenga playing goalkeeper last year
and coaching this year.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, the Mutiny provided little resistance,
practicing self-destruction by leaving goalkeeper Thomas Ravelli on
the bench because of a contract problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution tested Ravelli's replacement, Doug Petras, with
some long drives. Edwin Gorter drilled a shot over Petras and off
the crossbar from 40 yards in the 12th minute, and 12 minutes later
Joe-Max Moore sent a 30-yarder that Petras tipped over the bar.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th minute, New England capitalized on a defensive error
by Jan Eriksson to take the lead, as Raul Diaz Arce headed a Mike
Burns cross to Imad Baba, who scored into an open net.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay attack seldom appeared threatening, though the
Revolution seemed prepared to stop Liberian striker Musa Shannon,
who had scored three goals at Foxboro Stadium May 10.
</P>
<P>
   And the Revolution presented an aggressive, confident offense
that expected to be in scoring positions.
</P>
<P>
   The match was played at a frantic pace, and the Revolution
should have controlled the tempo better in the second half. But
they capitalized on their momentum, and after a 35-yard Gorter
drive was easily blocked, he regained possession and set up Moore,
who one-timed a shot off the far post for a 2-0 lead in the 59th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's final goal was also somewhat accidental, as
Petras punched a Paul Keegan cross off defender Chad McCarty's head
for an own goal in the 65th minute.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution deserved most of their good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team has to continue playing with this mentality,'' Zenga
said. ``I don't know if we can continue playing this way, but I
would hope to and I would like to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 0201EDT &QL; 
