<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS GAIN GROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Angels insist they don't watch the scoreboard to
see how Texas is doing.
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, when the Texas Rangers game was on TV late Saturday
afternoon, most of the Angels preferred to watch a tape of Seattle
Mariners pitcher Mac Suzuki, who started Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it couldn't hurt to see the scoreboard and know
that Oakland beat Texas, the Rangers' first loss in five games.
With a chance to gain ground on the AL West-leading Rangers, the
Angels responded with a 5-3 victory over the Mariners before a
sellout crowd of 42,833 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are now one game behind Texas with eight to play,
including three against the Rangers in Anaheim on Monday through
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got clutch performances from all over Saturday, which
is exactly what got them here. Jack McDowell, pitching with a sore
elbow that will probably force him to retire at season's end, went
61/3 innings to get the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Mike Holtz entered with the game on the line in the
seventh inning. With two on and one out, Holtz was called on to
face Ken Griffey and Edgar Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz got Griffey to hit into a force play, then struck out
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fetters, who had an ERA of 18.00 on the last road trip,
retired the Mariners 1-2-3 in the eighth. And Troy Percival set
down the Mariners in order in the ninth for his 41st save.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also got a couple timely hits _ missing in Friday
night's loss _ from two unlikely sources. No.7 hitter Matt Walbeck,
hitting .251 entering Saturday's game, and No.8 hitter Troy Glaus,
hitting .220, came up with back-to-back RBI singles in the sixth
inning off Mariners reliever Paul Spoljaric, breaking a 3-3 tie and
giving the Angels a 5-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners took a first-inning lead on Alex Rodriguez's solo
homer, his 40th of the season. With 40 homers and 43 stolen bases,
Rodriguez became the third player in major-league history to join
the 40-40 club. The others are Jose Canseco (1988) and Barry Bonds
(1996).
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners increased their lead to 3-0 in the third on Ken
Griffey's two-run double. Griffey went to third on the play on
center fielder Jim Edmonds' error, but was thrown out in a rundown
between third and home when Raul Ibanez grounded to first.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got two runs back in the bottom of the third on Randy
Velarde's two-run double, then tied it in the fourth after Tim
Salmon doubled and scored on a single by Garret Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Saturday's victory, the Angels have slumped in
September _ they are 6-10 this month. But Angels manager Terry
Collins will not use Darin Erstad's hamstring injury or any other
injury as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too easy to say I don't have enough bullets,'' Collins
said before the game. ``I have enough. We've got 36 or 37 guys
here. What we've got to do is maximize our chances, and we're not
doing that. I'm well-aware of what we've got going, we've got a lot
of guys hurt. My point being we've still got to do the little
things and we're not doing it. We're trying.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only Angel who has been hitting is Edmonds, who is
hitting .371 (23 for 62) with four homers and 16 RBI this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without him, in the last week we might've been shut out three
times,'' Collins said. ``But I don't think at this time of year one
guy can carry you. Baltimore's too good, Texas is too good,
Seattle's too good for one guy to carry you. You have to spread it
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
