</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON BID HINGES ON PSYCHOLOGICAL EXAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Evander Holyfield is still haunting Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   The specter of Holyfield's willingness to undergo a battery of
medical examinations at the Mayo Clinic a few years ago to prove
his fitness to fight in Nevada following what was misdiagnosed as
heart problems in his odd loss to Michael Moorer came back to haunt
Tyson Saturday at his relicensing hearing.
</P>
<P>
   After more than six hours of questioning and legal wrangling,
the Nevada State Athletic Commission elected to continue its
deliberations into Tyson's relicensing hearing until an independent
psychological evaluation is done on the former heavyweight
champion.
</P>
<P>
   For the evaluation, the commission will pick three psychiatrists
by Monday and Tyson will choose one of them and be examined no
later than Sept. 28. The hearing will then reopen Oct. 3, at which
time a vote will be taken on whether to lift the revocation of
Tyson's license that went into effect after he twice bit Holyfeld's
ears on June 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A private polling of the five commissioners indicated that four
would have voted against Tyson's application had a vote been taken
Saturday, with commissioner Luther Mack abstaining.
</P>
<P>
   Mack was particularly concerned about an incident three weeks
ago in Maryland in which Tyson is accused of hitting one man in the
face and kicking a second in the groin after a fender-bender
freeway accident in stop-and-go traffic.
</P>
<P>
   A car was struck from behind, lurched forward, and rear-ended
the car of Tyson's wife, after which Tyson is alleged to have
atttacked 50- and 62-year-old men from the other cars. Tyson is
charged with misdemeanor battery and also had a civil proceeding
filed against him.
</P>
<P>
   When Tyson's lead attorney, Dale Kinsella, tried to argue that a
Maryland police officer had issued a statement exonerating his
client of one of the charges, an angry Mack asked if there was not
a second person involved, and Kinsella conceded there was.
</P>
<P>
   Mack then asked where the police report said that person was
upon the arrival of the police. Kinsella sheepishly said, ``I
believe the report said that person was on the ground ... but ...
for ... for this panel to presume he got on the ground because of
anything Mike Tyson did would be unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack went on to ask Kinsella if it was true the police report
also said the person was ``teary eyed,'' ``bruised,'' and alleged
he'd been kicked in the groin by Tyson. Kinsella conceded that was
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, what happened in Maryland three weeks out (from
Saturday's hearing) is the key to this whole thing,'' Mack said.
``It was insulting to my intelligence to leave out that they found
one man with his eyes watering and kicked in the groin. That's why
I wanted to make sure that was on the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Maryland is a major condition. When the 3d comes, I'll
ask the same questions. It would have been nice to hear in addition
to the psychological tests they're going to take care of the
Maryland questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack did not get those assurances, just as Tyson was given none
that he would be relicensed if he gets psychological clearance,
although that seemed to be assumed by his squadron of 19 advisers,
friends, and protectors.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsella spent much of the time sparring with Mack and
commissioner James Nave, a Las Vegas veterinarian who was openly
skeptical of many of the arguments made by Kinsella and Shelly
Finkel, Tyson's de facto manager.
</P>
<P>
   Nave several times caught Finkel lying about specific issues,
such as whether Finkel had ever been sued by a fighter or had filed
with the commission every contract he'd had with a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Once again Holyfield haunted Tyson, as Finkel at first said he
had, then had to admit that as Holyfield's manager for many years
he never filed any of their contracts with the commission.
</P>
<P>
   But the ultimate stumbling block turned out to be the
psychotherapists who appeared on Tyson's behalf. After Norton
Roitman and Larry Curry claimed Tyson was ``psychologically fit to
fight'' and had undergone treatment for anger management, Nave
asked how much time they had spent with him.
</P>
<P>
   Between them and two other psychiatrists, the total was 19
hours, much of it coming only weeks before the hearing. That was
not nearly enough to satisfy the commission's concerns that Tyson
might repeat the fouls his advisers claim have cost him $50 million
to $68 million in lost purses and fines.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason I feel like Norman Bates up here with all
these doctors,'' Tyson remarked at one point. ``I've learned I am
sorry. Sooo sorry. Phew.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry or not, Tyson ultimately was forced to wave his
doctor-patient privilege to privacy, despite Kinsella's protests.
The commission demanded it be provided all medical and treatment
records resulting from the psychological study despite the fact
they could become public.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson turned the tide by saying, ``Nothing about my life is
private. What do you want to know?''
</P>
<P>
   He soon waived his privacy, and with that the motion to continue
was passed and Tyson was rushed out of the meeting room at Cashman
Field in silence to await another chance to resume his boxing life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
