<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUTHRIE RIPPED IN RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mark Guthrie has had worse days at 3Com Park.
Last season he allowed a 12th-inning, game-winning home run to
Brian Johnson on Sept. 18. The victory moved the Giants into a
first-place tie with the Dodgers with nine games to play.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday's anniversary of that homer, the Dodgers were
eliminated from the National League wild-card race. Saturday,
Guthrie made his return after missing 20 games with a sprained
ligament in his left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The results were disastrous. Guthrie came on to pitch the
seventh inning of the Dodgers' 18-4 loss to the Giants and allowed
four runs.
</P>
<P>
   The big hit was Doug Mirabelli's first major-league home run and
a throwing error by rookie shortstop Alex Cora led to another run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shape to pitch, but not to compete,'' said Guthrie,
who has not missed this much playing time since 1993 when, as a
member of the Minnesota Twins, he underwent surgery to remove a
blood clot from his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But as the inning continue to unravel, Guthrie became
frustrated. After Joe Carter, the ninth batter in the inning,
singled to left, Guthrie threw up his hands in disgust. Later, he
refused to rip the decision by manager Glenn Hoffman to leave him
in, but he clearly had been embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was I supposed to do, walk off the mound?'' he said. ``I
probably would never have gotten another batter out ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman knew that Guthrie hadn't pitched in more than three
weeks. That was the reason Hoffman left him in.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the minor-league season is over and there are
no rehab assignments,'' Hoffman said. ``You have to put the score
out of your mind and make your pitches. That's what we were
watching. We weren't going to leave him out there to hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie is in the final week of a multi-year contract that paid
him $1.6 million this season. He is eligible for free agency and is
not expected back. Although he did not mention Guthrie by name, new
GM Kevin Malone said revamping middle and setup relief roles will
be a priority this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Quick Hits: The day wasn't a washout for everyone. Damon
Hollins, acquired Sept. 9 from Atlanta in a minor-league deal, had
his first major-league hit, a two-run single in the seventh. Jeff
Kubenka, a rookie left-hander, struck out the side in the ninth....
Mark Grudzielanek left the game after six innings. He has been
suffering from tendinitis in both Achilles' tendons since joining
the Dodgers on July 31. Mirabelli, a 27-year old rookie, who hit
his first major-league homer Saturday, played parts of the past two
seasons with the Giants.... The last time the Giants scored this
many runs in a game was June 8, 1990 when they defeated the Atlanta
Braves 23-8.... The stolen base by Barry Bonds with the Giants
leading 7-0 in the third was his 26th. He is four short of reaching
the 30-30 mark for home runs and stolen bases for a record sixth
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 0206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
