<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-WHITESOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ, WILLIAMS BLAST UMPIRE AFTER RED SOX LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Before his interrogation began, Jim Evans, the man who
ejected Red Sox manager Jimy Williams Saturday and whose competence
later was ridiculed by pitcher Pedro Martinez, had a question for
reporters following the Red Sox' 5-2 loss to the Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this going to be subpoenaed by Starr?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   There is no room for an independent prosecutor in a playoff
chase, but both Williams and Martinez made their case that there's
no place for an umpire and his crew to have an apparent vendetta
against the Red Sox, either, an accusation a lot less funny than
Evans's one-liner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I've done something to that umpire,'' said
Williams, tossed during a heated exchange following the third
inning, after Martinez came off the mound barking at Evans and the
umpire took a couple of steps his way. ``I really don't know. I
don't know if this goes back to the '80s, but we've had our
confrontations all year long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does the American League president choose to have that
group be with us? I don't know. It would probably be wise and be a
benefit for him and for us if we didn't have that crew the rest of
the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that Evans, a 27-year veteran, has been assigned to work
the American League Championship Series, Martinez responded with
comments that could lead to his wallet being lightened in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a huge mistake by the league _ huge,'' said Martinez,
who 11 days ago tipped his cap in mocking fashion to plate umpire
Mark Johnson, a member of Evans's crew. ``I don't care how much
experience he has. If he's going to call the games like he called
this game for me, he doesn't deserve to call those games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing about it is, nobody seems to be doing anything
about it. There should be a supervisor to check on these guys.
Sometimes it seems like they're in the middle of nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Having lost for the second straight time to a White Sox rookie
pitcher in less than 24 hours, the Red Sox aren't going anywhere
fast, either. They had 10 hits Saturday, but left 11 men on base
and didn't score until Darren Lewis's two-run home run in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   With nine games left, their magic number to clinch the wild-card
spot in the AL playoffs was reduced to four when both Toronto and
Texas lost Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who gave up a three-run home run to light-hitting
(.211) Mike Cameron in the second inning, then issued two straight
walks and a wild pitch that led to two more runs in the third, has
now lost three straight decisions for the first time in three
years. He lost Saturday to rookie John Snyder, who has beaten the
Red Sox twice this season, first as vanquisher of Korean rookie Jin
Ho Cho, now of Martinez, whose hopes for a second straight Cy Young
Award may have evaporated along with his composure.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Cameron hit that home run, that was really a deflating
thing for Pedro,'' said White Sox manager Jerry Manuel, who was a
coach with the Expos for three of Martinez's years in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost a little bit of his edge. He lost his swagger. Then
came those questionable calls, and the frustration set in.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustration boiled over after Martinez walked Ray Durham and
Mike Caruso, which brought a visit from Williams, who normally
doesn't venture to the mound unless he's making a pitching change.
On his way back to the dugout, Williams made a detour toward the
plate, but Evans said he was unaware whether the manager had
something to say at that point.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's first pitch after Williams's visit, to Frank Thomas,
was wild, advancing both runners, who scored in succession on
Thomas's infield out and Albert Belle's deep drive to left field,
which stayed in the ballpark only because Troy O'Leary made a
terrific leaping catch at the wall.
</P>
<P>
   When Robin Ventura struck out swinging to end the inning,
Martinez walked toward the first-base dugout, talking to Evans the
entire time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to him, `Is that what I have to do to get a
strikeout?''' said Martinez, upset that Evans was ``consistently
missing pitches the whole game. It's OK to miss one pitch or two,
but it's not OK to miss the whole game consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is convinced that Evans was planning to eject him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to throw me out,'' Martinez said. ``No doubt. He
told Hattie (catcher Scott Hatteberg) not to get involved. Why
doesn't he want him to get involved? Do we have something going?
</P>
<P>
   ``He moved his arms like, `Say it, so I can throw you out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Evans was asked why he stepped toward Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he walked off the mound, he was saying something to me,
and I had no idea what he was saying,'' said the umpire. ``I took a
step or two to ask him what he was saying, and by that point,
(third base coach) Wendell Kim was there. He did a good job
(pulling away Martinez).''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was there, too, but not for long. He was ejected for
the fourth time this season, and it was the second time in 13 days
that he has kicked dirt onto the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like getting thrown out of games,'' he said. ``It's
not smart. It was kind of dumb on my part.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's probably better me than the pitcher. I can't play. I
couldn't play when I did play. It's better me than him.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans dismissed the suggestion that he carries a grudge against
either Williams or Martinez. And while the manager hopes he doesn't
see this crew again this season after Sunday, he had a different
response when he heard that Evans would be at the ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn, I hope I see him again,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
