<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHINING SON WARMS CLOUDS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Parents weekend, Boston College, 1998. The Pops played
Conte Forum Friday night, Saturday there was a luncheon for 2,000
in the athletic complex, and this morning there'll be an outdoor
Mass for the masses on the upper middle campus.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and in the middle of it all there was a football game at
Alumni (a k a Tom Coughlin Memorial) Stadium and BC thrashed
Temple, 31-7, in front of 40,496 _ many of them parents.
</P>
<P>
   A good number of the parents at the Heights this weekend are
forking over $30,000 per year to pay for young Patrick or Mary
Ellen's college education, but 85 lucky families have sons getting
a free ride; they are the parents of the scholarship football
players, and their ranks include Ethel and Charles Cloud of
Portsmouth, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Ethel didn't make it to the game Saturday, but proud papa
Charles was there to see his youngest son, Mike Cloud, run for a
cumulus 196 yards and three touchdowns. The third score was a true
beauty, as Cloud ran a draw up the gut for 85 yards, breaking
through the line, then touching nothing but cool, crisp air and
artificial turf.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't get much better than this at BC. The Eagles are 3-0
for the first time in seven years, and though they may not yet have
designs on the Fiesta Bowl, there is a renewal of football spirit
on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tom O'Brien said, ``It seems like there's a bonding going
on, the way the students are supporting the team. It hasn't been
here in a while, it certainly wasn't here last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloud, a fifth-year senior with all the psychological scars of
any BC player who experienced the depths at the Heights in '96,
said, ``I think the last couple of years the football players shied
away from students. But now we see them on campus and in the dining
hall and it feels great to hear from them.''
</P>
<P>
   When the students abandoned the team, BC players still had their
parents' backing. Charles Cloud sits in Section T and never misses
a game. An Army sergeant who served 18 months in Vietnam, Cloud
retired from the service 13 years ago and today works in the
commissary at the NETC Newport Naval Base. Mike is the third of
three Cloud sons, and the family does not take Mike's scholarship
for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a big savings for us,'' said the tailback's dad.
``It was something that we never thought would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been huge for my family,'' added Mike. ``We didn't have
the money to send me to a school like this. I know all the players
here appreciate getting a great education and the opportunity to
play Division 1 football.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of a Division 1 program is staggering. Take 85
scholarships at $30,000 per year for four years and you've got a
tab of more than $10 million before staff, equipment, food, and
travel costs. But when 40,000 fans pour through the gates and go
home happy, there is great return on the investment.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be many days better than Saturday. Boston enjoyed
perfect San Diego weather, and the Eagles toyed with the visitors
from Philadelphia. Nobody had it better than Cloud.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old tailback has run for 552 yards and seven
touchdowns in three games. He's averaging 184 yards and 29 carries
per game. Before the season, he announced that he planned to go for
2,000 yards, and now the comment doesn't sound preposterous. In the
words of his coach, ``He's a heck of a back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really amazing to be a parent and watch your son please
everyone,'' said the dad. ``The first three years he played, it was
exciting but not overwhelming. This year, I couldn't wait. I knew
good things were going to happen for him. And today I saw him bust
through that line and get the one he'd been waiting for.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Cloud's chest was practically busting through his BC
shirt as he talked about his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him we're waiting outside, please,'' said the dad. ``His
dad and his brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Mike Cloud was talking with reporters and BC athletic
director Gene DeFilippo was leaving for home so he could listen to
the James Madison-Villanova game on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   DeFilippo's son, John, is quarterback at James Madison. For 50
cents a minute, the BC AD can enlist a service that provides
play-by-play. It's pricey, but who could resist? Especially on
parents weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
