<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4732 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-TEM     09-20 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-TEMPLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC LEAVES TEMPLE WITH RUN-DOWN FEELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two minutes remained in Boston College's 31-7 victory
over Temple Saturday when the sum total of Mike Cloud's day _ 27
carries, 196 yards, three touchdowns _ flashed across the jumbo
screens at both ends of Alumni Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   At the sight of those numbers, the members of BC's starting
offensive line rose from the bench to exhort the coaches to put
Cloud back into the game. They wanted to see their teammate break
the 200-yard mark for the second time this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was to rush for 2,000 yards,'' Cloud said afterward,
referring to the objective he set at the beginning of the year.
``The offensive line knows that, and they're rooting for me. When
they looked up at the scoreboard and saw that I had 196 yards, they
were kind of teed off.''
</P>
<P>
   The line wanted more for Cloud _ 4 more yards, to be exact. But
was Cloud capable of supplying the demand? Well, not exactly. Cloud
acknowledged afterward that he had emptied his tank on a dazzling
85-yard sprint on a draw play that made it 31-7 with 7:06 to go. It
was the longest TD run of Cloud's career and the third-longest in
BC history.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud, who has carried 88 times for 552 yards and scored seven
touchdowns, is off to the best three-game start in Big East
history, surpassing the 442 yards (on 77 carries) that West
Virginia's Amos Zereoue had last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were encouraging me,'' Cloud said, ``but the coaches
wanted to give the other guys a chance to play, which was a great
call by the coaches. Like I said, right after that (85-yard) play I
was kind of done for the day.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, were the Owls.
</P>
<P>
   For the second week in a row, BC spotted its opponent a 7-0
lead. Temple (0-3 overall, 0-1 Big East) capitalized on Jermaine
Walker's fumble on the opening kick, scoring two plays after taking
over on the 19. After a 16-yard gain on an option, the Owls took
the lead on Stacey Mack's 3-yard burst.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, however, bounced back behind a withering offensive
attack that amassed 443 yards, 206 rushing and 237 passing. BC's
defense, meanwhile, succeeded in holding Temple, which boasted the
nation's No. 4 rushing attack (298.5 yards), to 297 yards of total
offense, just 151 rushing.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, BC improved to 3-0 overall and 2-0 in the Big East.
BC will travel to Louisville next weekend for a nonconference
matchup against the Cardinals, 35-9 winners over Illinois Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 3-0, that's the good news,'' said BC coach Tom O'Brien.
``As I said coming in, I thought that this would be a great
challenge for this football team. You look at the athletes of
Temple and the size of some of those guys _ this was the most
athletic team that we've played yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm glad that we played them at this point of the season.
I'd hate to play them later in the year if they ever get this thing
going. That's a tough offense to defend. Our defense did a great
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Once BC's defense ``caught up to the speed of this game,''
O'Brien said, the Eagles put the clamps on slippery Owls
quarterback Kevin Harvey, holding him to 12 carries for 58 yards
and 3-of-8 passing for 25 yards before knocking him out of the game
in the third quarter with an injured left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, who entered the game as the No. 2 rusher in the Big East
(108 yards per game), was held to 27 yards on eight carries.
</P>
<P>
   On its last three possessions of the first half, the Owls ran 32
plays and gained 125 yards, but came away empty-handed. They missed
a field goal, threw an interception, and had time expire.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to punt after driving to the Temple 23 on their first
possession, the Eagles rebounded to score on their next four
red-zone opportunities. Cloud tied it, 7-7, when he capped a
10-play, 80-yard drive with a 2-yard run with 52 seconds left in
the first quarter. Then quarterback Scott Mutryn, who completed 17
of 22 for 237 yards, capped a blitzkrieg three-play, 72-yard drive
by hitting Anthony DiCosmo with a 10-yard strike that gave BC a
14-7 lead with 10:50 to go before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud extended BC's lead to 21-7 with a 1-yard plunge in the
third, before John Matich made it 24-7 with a 35-yard field goal.
Cloud then capped his day with the 85-yard score.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Mike Cloud _ and I've been around a lot of
great backs: Mike Cloud is a determined runner,'' said Temple's
first-year coach, Bobby Wallace. ``He's got speed and strength. He
is a hard runner, meaning he is going to break a lot of tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace wasn't the first coach this season to lavish Cloud with
such praise. And, after Cloud's effort Saturday, he likely won't be
the last.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
