<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S MITCHELL OUT FOR YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Freddie Mitchell knew the gruesome truth quicker than
anyone else. And why not? It was his thigh that collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I BROKE MY LEG,'' Mitchell yelled after landing awkwardly on
his left leg at the end of a 47-yard kickoff return in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later, Mitchell was carted off Robertson Field
and whisked to Methodist Hospital, where he underwent successful
surgery Saturday evening. Doctors placed a stabilization rod
alongside Mitchell's fractured femur (thigh).
</P>
<P>
   He will miss the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The operation went very well,'' said Dr. Gerald Finerman,
UCLA's team physician. ``It was a pretty clean break.''
</P>
<P>
   A redshirt freshman receiver, Mitchell will remain in Houston
for several days. Finerman was with him Saturday night; his
parents, Freddie and Joyce, are flying in from Lakeland, Fla., for
the rest of Mitchell's stay.
</P>
<P>
   Finerman expects the recovery to take 4-5 months. But when asked
if Mitchell will be ready for spring practice, he declined to give
an exact return date.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very good chance he'll recover and be as good as he
was,'' Finerman said after UCLA's 42-24 victory over Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was eerily reminiscent of former linebacker Anselmo
Zamano's injury two years ago at Michigan. While Mitchell's doesn't
appear as severe _ Zamano almost lost his leg and might never play
again _ it will have a greater impact on UCLA's fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell was UCLA's best big-play threat and its top punt and
kickoff returner. In his college debut last week against Texas, he
gained 233 total yards and threw a 34-yard touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have receivers who can pick up the slack, but I don't know
if they have Freddie's big-play dimension,'' offensive coordinator
Al Borges said. ``Freddie gave us more confidence that we could
strike any minute, and that's a nice feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's injury leaves UCLA with only three proven receivers:
Danny Farmer, Brad Melsby and Brian Poli-Dixon. That means Jon
Dubravac, a true freshman, and Saugus' Cody Joyce, a redshirt
freshman, must increase production.
</P>
<P>
   Borges and Toledo will decide this week if strategic or
personnel changes are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might do things a little different,'' Borges said. ``We'll
have to be more cognizant of getting the ball to players who can
score touchdowns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
