<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S SUPPORTING CAST EARNS RAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A few minutes before kickoff, UCLA freshman linebacker
Santi Hall visualized the first start of his career. He saw
alignments, he saw assignments, he saw tackles and blitzes and even
a sack.
</P>
<P>
   But an interception?
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through all the plays, but it never crossed my mind
that I'd get a pick,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his third-quarter interception, which set up UCLA's fourth
touchdown, was one of several big plays from supporting players in
the Bruins' 42-24 victory Saturday at Houston.
</P>
<P>
   With only two senior starters on defense _ and four listed on
the two-deep chart _ UCLA's season may hinge on continuing
contributions from unlikely sources. Effective as they are, as many
plays as they make, seniors Larry Atkins and Brendan Ayanbadejo
can't do it all every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to rely on those (younger) guys,'' Bruins coach Bob
Toledo said. ``They've got to continue to get better. They'll grow
and mature each week. But we've got to continue to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Ryan Roques, who climbed the depth chart when Damian
Allen quit last week, typified the inconsistency that comes with
inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the second quarter, he allowed a 34-yard touchdown.
Early in the third, he returned an interception 17 yards for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was gratifying for me to make the play,'' said Roques, a
junior who converted from tailback last season. ``I'm just glad I
was able to do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who started for the injured Michael Wiley, had three
tackles and an interception.
</P>
<P>
   End Travor Turner, a pass-rush specialist, had three
tackles-for-loss and deflected the pass that eventually landed in
Hall's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Inside linebacker Ryan Nece, who switched from safety in the
spring, had four tackles and a sack.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom-used outside linebacker Billy Pieper _ No. 43, in case
you couldn't put a name with the number _ had a sack.
</P>
<P>
   End Steve Sua, linebacker Ali Abdul-Azziz, nose guard Micah
Webb, linebacker Cheyane Caldwell, safety Jason Stephens _ the list
of unexpected playmakers went on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Even senior Tod McBride, a third-string safety, chipped in. His
blocked punt in the second quarter helped turn the game after
Houston had dashed to a surprising 6-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough out there,'' McBride said. ``Houston came to
play. They weren't going to hand it to us. But emotionally, we got
it together and made some big plays. Without them, the game would
have been a lot closer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
