<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA IS ONE FIGHTER WHO CAN TAKE HIS LUMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The Golden Boy showed the president how to handle a
crisis of confidence last week.
</P>
<P>
   Like President Clinton, Oscar De La Hoya was recently outed for
a sexual escapade that hardly fit his squeaky-clean image. Above a
story on De La Hoya in the Aug. 28 Los Angeles Times, a headline
read ``He's No Angel.'' The article outlined an incident last
spring in Cabo San Lucas, a Mexican resort town, in which De La
Hoya was publicly drunk and found dancing on tables with nearly
naked women. He was spotted by the son of the story's author,
boxing writer Steve Springer.
</P>
<P>
   The story went on to report on De La Hoya's previously
well-documented gambling and the existence of a 6-month-old son
born out of wedlock to a woman he does not date.
</P>
<P>
   That none of this seemed to fit the image that promoter Bob Arum
has been creating for the 1992 Olympic gold medalist was a
potential headache both for De La Hoya and the many businesses that
have rushed to hire him as a spokesman. But De La Hoya made all the
right moves in response to the article, acknowledging its accuracy
and thanking the Times for giving him a ``reality check.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It opened my eyes,'' De La Hoya said during a lengthy
interview in his suite with sportswriters last week. ``It's really
been a reality check. It made me think. If I want to become the
best fighter out there and make history and keep being a role model
for kids and stay positive, then I have to cut this out and focus
on boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like the article when I first read it, but after I
read it a few times it helped me. I think it was positive. I was
kind of glad it came out, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure of carrying his sport at a time when so many
denigrate it has mounted on De La Hoya as his celebrity has grown
to vast proportions. He is not just a fighter anymore but a
cultural phenomenon who has been embraced by an expanding
Hispanic-American community.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with a clear example of bad judgment, De La Hoya made
no attempt to split hairs, use either of the two languages he
speaks to create a semantic escape route, or deny the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he conceded that he likes to gamble a bit too much and
so he went along with Arum's decision to ask Las Vegas casinos to
keep him at a $25,000 limit after he made and then lost more than
$300,000 one evening playing baccarat. He conceded that he likes
the young women who seem to follow him everywhere and at times has
treated them with something less than chivalry. Most of all, he
conceded that his behavior had to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm human,'' he said. ``I'm a 25-year-old guy. Who at 25 could
handle all this? I'm not just a fighter, I'm an enterprise that
supports a lot of people. It's impossible to handle all this
pressure and not blow up sometimes, but it showed me I need to stay
focused on my boxing because I was doing something wrong. If you're
doing something wrong, stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, no, I can't just be a regular 25-year-old guy.
That's obvious. But I don't want to be. My job is to fight, stay
focused, and be a role model. I feel I draw a different fan to
boxing, a female fan, which is why my (pay-per-view) numbers are
climbing the charts.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Times article, that climb continued when his fight
with Chavez became the first to sell out the 14,000-seat Thomas and
Mack Center and threatened to break De La Hoya's non-heavyweight
record for pay-per-view sales.
</P>
<P>
   He is arguably the most popular fighter in the world today, and
he knows it. When he fought in El Paso this year, for example, a
young Hispanic woman was overheard at a pay phone telling a friend
how thrilled she was to have been standing under De La Hoya's hotel
window to catch a T-shirt that he signed and threw to her.
</P>
<P>
   That is rock-star idolatry, and it is in evidence whenever he
appears in public. His fan club, which is operated through his
personal website at OscarDeLaHoya.com, has hundreds of thousands of
members and has grown so large that he had to hire a company to
handle the volume of requests. Everywhere he goes he is surrounded
by an army of security guards with small wires in their ears and no
smiles on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   His is a life of celebrity gone wild and with it, he knows,
comes intense scrutiny. You cannot have the one without the other,
so he sees no unfairness in it, only an obligation to live up to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 32 years I've been promoting, Oscar De La Hoya is the
most disciplined athlete that I've been associated with and the
nicest young man to be around,'' Arum said during a recent phone
conversation. ``He's a young man and he has to be able to conduct
himself like a young man but he knows, in the words of his sponsor
(Budweiser), when to say when.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stops and goes back to being the disciplined athlete that
he is. Oscar's not some cardboard figure who marches like a robot.
That's why this was a terrific article.''
</P>
<P>
   On some levels it humanized De La Hoya, who had been criticized
by some in the Mexican-American community for seeming ``too white''
because of his obsession with golf and the suburban life. Now found
to have boxing shoes at least partially made of clay, his
popularity has grown, not lessened, because of his handling of his
life in and out of the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what Oscar's ceiling is,'' Arum said. ``He's the
most popular guy in the sport. He just keeps expanding his base.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya did that again last week not by denying the
undeniable but by embracing it. People in high places could learn
something about crisis management from that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It pays to be on a jury that acquits  &UR; Don King &LR; . This weekend in
Atlanta, King hosted members of the jury that in July found him not
guilty of insurance fraud in a New York federal court. King took
the jurors to the  &UR; Evander Holyfield-Vaughn Bean  &LR; fight, after
first flying them to the Bahamas last weekend for a vacation. ``We
had a great barbecue,'' King boasted. ``It was in a beautiful
flower garden. Then we had dinner. I'm doing this as a gesture of
those who lived the process. You've got to show the people
appreciation for the process. I enjoyed doing it like the Second
Coming. I told my bookkeepers, `Don't even tell me the cost.''' The
guests also included the jurors' families and the staff of the two
law firms that defended King. King's largesse is not without
precedent. He did the same thing when he was found not guilty of
tax evasion several years ago, taking that jury to London for the
 &UR; Frank Bruno &LR; - &UR; Tim Witherspoon  &LR; fight ... What had been rumored for
weeks finally came true last week when heavyweight prospect  &UR; Hasim
Rahman  &LR; pulled out of Saturday's fight with  &UR; David Tua  &LR; on the
undercard of  &UR; Lennox Lewis's  &LR; defense of the World Boxing Council
heavyweight title. Efforts to replace Rahman with  &UR; Razor Ruddock
 &LR; and former cruiserweight champion  &UR; Orlin Norris  &LR; failed, as both
claimed they were not prepared. Word is that Tua's handlers, the
Duvas, turned down a chance to avenge Tua's only loss by fighting a
rematch with comebacking  &UR; Ike Ibeabuchi &LR; , &UR;  &LR; although they claim it
was Ibeabuchi's demand for a $500,000 payday that killed the fight.
Rahman signed a deal with King in May despite still being under
contract to South African promoter  &UR; Cedric Kushner  &LR; until Oct. 31.
Kushner now claims Rahman also signed an extension with him and
took a $200,000 signing bonus after he'd surreptitiously signed
with King, then pulled out of the Tua fight after King told him
that if Tua was still standing at the end of the fight he'd get the
decision. Kushner plans to sue Rahman for breach of contract, and
Tua may be out of a date. Meanwhile, HBO has downgraded the show to
a one-fight extravaganza, Lewis- &UR; Zeljko Mavrovic &LR; , &UR;  &LR; although Tua
will still appear on the card at the Mohegan Sun Casino ...  &UR; Erik
Morales  &LR; looked sharp and  &UR; Junior Jones  &LR; looked shot last weekend
in Tijuana when Morales TKO'd the two-time world champion in four
rounds to retain the WBC junior featherweight title. Word is Jones
may retire to train fighters or possibly move to the radio booth,
working HBO shows in a job once held by trainer  &UR; Teddy Atlas &LR; . That
opening came about because Atlas has been selected as the ringside
commentator for ESPN2's new weekly boxing series. Atlas replaces
 &UR; Al Bernstein &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was dumped by ESPN after 18 solid years ...
 &UR; Gerry Penalosa's  &LR; loss of the WBC superflyweight title on a split
decision in Seoul to  &UR; Joo Cho  &LR; Aug. 29 becomes odder the more we
hear about it. Word now is that judge  &UR; Dalby Shirley  &LR; claimed after
the fight that he had voted for Penalosa mistakenly thinking he was
Cho and wanted his score reversed. How can you be a world-class
judge and not know the Filipino fighter from the Korean? The WBC
refused the request but has already ordered Cho to defend his title
vs. No. 1 contender  &UR; Joel Luna Zarate &LR; , &UR;  &LR; with the winner giving
Penalosa a rematch ... Holyfield grossed more than $6 million
Saturday night for an inconsequential title defense vs. Bean fought
in the champion's hometown. More than 20,000 tickets were sold for
the bout at the Georgia Dome. Meanwhile, De La Hoya became the
first fighter to sell out the Thomas and Mack Center at UNLV for
his rematch with Chavez. Those sales are good signs that boxing is
not as dead as its critics would like you to believe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former world champion  &UR; Pernell Whitaker  &LR; quietly had his
suspension for failing two drug tests lifted last week. He has been
training lightly in his native Norfolk, Va., and told his promoter,
 &UR; Dino Duva &LR; , that he does not want a tuneup fight before a proposed
December bout with International Boxing Federation welterweight
champion  &UR; Felix Trinidad &LR;  ... In an unusual bit of advertising,
King was promoting  &UR; Christy Martin's  &LR; fight Saturday night as the
women's pound-for-pound championship. Her opponent? TBA! To Be
Announced is a busy opponent these days but unlikely to be ready
for a pound-for-pound title ... The IBF may have created headaches
for itself by bowing to pressure from King to let  &UR; Robert Allen
 &LR; fight  &UR; Abdula Ramadan  &LR; Saturday night for the interim
mid-dleweight title held by injured  &UR; Bernard Hopkins &LR; . On the
surface it might seem fair enough since Allen's fight with Hopkins
ended in a no-contest when Hopkins slipped and fell out of the
ring, injuring his ankle. But rather than wait for Hopkins to heal
for a rematch, the IBF rushed Allen into an interim title fight.
These things always lead to problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
