<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4738 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-LADN     09-20 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC STRUGGLES PAST OREGON STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Every time USC schedules a night game, there's the
complaint that East Coast viewers (and poll voters) never get a
chance to watch the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it turns out to be a blessing. Like Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans struggled mightily with usual patsy Oregon State at
the Coliseum, before defeating the Beavers 40-20 before 45,629.
</P>
<P>
   After defeating Oregon State 24 straight times since 1967, the
Trojans were in real danger of ending their Pacific-10 Conference
record streak for consecutive victories over an opponent. Worse,
the Beavers had not actually defeated USC at the Coliseum since
1960.
</P>
<P>
   No matter the end result, it was clear that this was no normal
Oregon State team that former USC assistant Mike Riley brought to
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   That especially became apparent when ex-quarterback Tim
Alexander returned the second-half opening kickoff 100 yards to tie
the game, 17-17.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most USC-Oregon State encounters, this one had a
competitive feel the entire way.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans had to take advantage of a fumble by Oregon State's
Ken Simonton on a punt return just to forge ahead 20-17 with 11:03
remaining in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Kicker Adam Abrams added another field goal, this one from 33
yards, at the start of the fourth quarter to give USC a 23-17 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Other than tailback Chad Morton, who rushed for more than 100
yards for the second time in his career against Oregon State, USC's
offense was inconsistent. The special teams were forced to provide
a lift for the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Locked in a 7-7 tie early in the second quarter, walk-on Danny
Bravo broke through the line and blocked Mike Fessler's punt. The
ball rolled into the end zone and was recovered by Rashard Cook to
give the Trojans a 14-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second straight game the Trojans blocked a punt.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' special teams also rebounded in the kicking game,
as Adam Abrams converted a 33-yard field goal in the second quarter
to stretch USC's lead to 17-7.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams, who was 2 for 2, had gone 0 for 3 on field goals last
week after making 12 straight.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State answered by driving 63 yards before stalling at the
USC 11-yard line. Jose Cortez kicked a 28-yard field goal with 47
seconds left in the half to cut the lead to 17-10.
</P>
<P>
   USC (3-0) appeared to have ended that drive when Cook
intercepted a pass in the end zone, but the Trojans were penalized
for roughing the passer.
</P>
<P>
   As promised, USC head coach Paul Hackett inserted freshman
quarterback Carson Palmer with just under seven minutes left in the
first half, but Palmer got little protection in his opening series
and failed to complete a pass.
</P>
<P>
   There was no electrifying start for USC wide receiver R. Jay
Soward, either, after he thrilled fans last week in his 256-yard
debut against San Diego State. Soward fumbled a punt return in the
first quarter and Oregon State's Darnell Robinson recovered at the
Trojans' 27-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Nine plays later, Oregon State quarterback Terrance Bryant found
James Battle in the end zone on a 5-yard touchdown pass to tie the
game, 7-7. Cook actually tipped the ball in the end zone before
Battle caught it.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Soward's turnover, the Trojans had been off to a
flawless start.
</P>
<P>
   USC needed less than two minutes to start the scoring. After
Hackett said the Trojans needed to throw deep more often, they did,
as Mike Van Raaphorst hit Larry Parker on a 47-yard scoring pass.
</P>
<P>
   It was Parker's first career touchdown in four seasons, and gave
USC a 7-0 lead just 1:42 into the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
