<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS OFF TO RUNNING START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ The Super Bowl will be played in Miami's Pro Player
Stadium on Jan. 31. The Dolphins would love to be there. Home-field
advantage for a Super Bowl? Sounds like enough motivation for Jimmy
Johnson. And Dan Marino.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Sunday's third game of the season, against
Pittsburgh, the Dolphins (2-0) are certainly on the right track,
though in three of the last four years the Dolphins started 3-0 and
it meant little. Yet this year there's a new-found hope that
Johnson is close to establishing the running game that he wants. He
won two championships in Dallas because he had the best offensive
linemen in the world, and at that time, Emmitt Smith was the best
running back on Earth. The ground attack took the heat off
quarterback Troy Aikman, who became exceptionally accurate as a
passer.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also had a defense that could shut down the opposition
and leave the offense in good field position.
</P>
<P>
   But in four years in Miami, he's had none of this. Miami fans
expected miracles when Johnson took over from the legendary Don
Shula, but they are still waiting for a team that could even be
thought of as a Super Bowl contender. The coach has taken more than
a few hits for this.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's start has begun to change some of that. In their
first two games, the Dolphins were a running team. Marino, who
traditionally has had to put the ball in the air most of the time,
suddenly finds himself in an offense that really is thinking about
running first and throwing second.
</P>
<P>
   Question is, how long will this last? After all, the wins came
against the Indianapolis Colts and Buffalo Bills, not exactly the
brawn of the AFC. The offense also sputtered at times. But there
are good trends, and if they continue Sunday against the Steelers,
it will be time to consider whether Johnson has finally pulled it
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured it would be at least one month into the season
before we were in sync,'' said Johnson in his weekly
teleconference. ``I don't know that our running game is going to
scare anybody. Hopefully there'll be a day here that people are
concerned about it. I am happy we've run the ball better.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week against Buffalo, the Dolphins were able to keep the
ball for seven minutes late in the game to salt away a 13-7 win.
They had only 12 yards rushing at the half but managed to finish
with 116 as Karim Abdul-Jabbar found a good rhythm with an
offensive line that has become far more conscious of run-blocking.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dolphins keep this up, it could lengthen Ma-rino's
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' said Marino, 38, during his teleconference. ``I
look at it this way: I'll take it one year at a time. Maybe if we
run more I won't take as many hits. It comes down to the health
factor. I think if any quarterback my age had a major injury it
would be tough to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the advent of Terrell Davis and a run-oriented
offensive line has helped rejuvenate John Elway in Denver. It's not
that Marino doesn't like to drop and fire; he's done that better
than any quarterback in history, and he says that aspect of his
game is still alive and well _ if the Dolphins need it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still capable if we want to throw it more,'' said Marino,
who has two touchdown passes and no interceptions this season.
``It's what Jimmy is trying to get accomplished _ to be more of a
physical team.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as throwing the football, I feel fine. My legs give me
problems during the week but that's because of the operations I've
had in the past few years. As for my ability, I feel I can still
play at a high level in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with passing is that Marino is running out of
receivers. The team's No. 1 pick two years ago, Yatil Green, was
supposed to emerge as a big-play guy, but he is out with injuries
for the second straight season.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, a Dolphin coach criticized Marino for not being
able to get the ball to his receivers and said he might be looking
for veteran O.J. McDuffie a little too often.
</P>
<P>
   If Marino can deal with that kind of occasional motivational jab
and the running game continues to develop, he could play to 40 and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a possibility,'' said Marino. ``I'm looking at this
week right now.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would definitely not be the next Steve DeBerg, who is
playing at 44, but he seemed confident that the Dolphins are a team
that is going to the playoffs ``and we're going to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino said boldly, ``I'm going to be one of the reasons for
that. There's no reason for me to give up because I'm not playing
at the level I did 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he's standing when many younger quarterbacks in
the league have already gone down with injuries is significant. He
seems to be part of a trend around the league that sees older
quarterbacks getting the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have guys who can still play and have been successful for
a long time,'' he said. ``It comes down to ability and the types of
schemes they're in and the people around them.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems the people around Marino are doing a good job
protecting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we're playing now, we're running the ball better and
protecting Dan very well,'' said Johnson. ``Dan is still an
outstanding quarterback in this league, and if we can do the things
to protect an outstanding quarterback, we'll be on the right
track.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also likes the fact that his defense is much more
aggressive and that he keeps finding big-time players such as
defensive end Jason Taylor, who has ``great quickness,
intelligence, and a knack for the big play.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all of these good feelings could end Sunday. The
Steelers have blitzed Marino to death in the past. If they can stop
the run, they'll begin their assault on the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   But for now the Dolphins have their eye on staying home in
January.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The $17 million and change the Patriots will receive as their
share of the Cleveland Browns expansion fee will go toward signing
bonuses for some of the players whose contracts are about up. The
Patriots are trying to finish off  &UR; Troy Brown's  &LR; four-year deal,
and then they'll look to  &UR; Dave Wohlabaugh &LR; , &UR; Ty Law &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Lawyer
Milloy &LR; . &UR;  &LR; Law is expected to command big money, given his rising
stature and the shortage of All-Pro caliber cornerbacks in the
league ... If you're a sports fan and your vote for governor was
based on which stadium plan the candidates backed (the House/ &UR; Tom
Finneran  &LR; plan or the Sen-ate/ &UR; Thomas Birmingham &LR; / &UR; Robert Kraft
 &LR; plan), you'd have a problem because neither  &UR; Paul Cellucci  &LR; nor
 &UR; Scott Harshbarger  &LR; will speak specifically on the issue. All that
their spokespeople would say was that each candidate wants to keep
the Patriots in Massachusetts. The difference between the two
plans, basically, is that in the Senate version, the state would
purchase the land from Kraft, then lease it back to him. Last
September, Cellucci filed legislation to provide $50 million in
infrastructure on a renovated Foxboro Stadium that would include
the purchase of 316 acres of land around the stadium. That
indicates that he isn't opposed to the Senate version, though the
plan has gone from a renovation to a new stadium since then ... In
major league baseball, coaches and managers share licensing money
with players and receive medical and retirement benefits. In
football, coaches have been on their own. But former Patriots
offensive coordinator  &UR; Larry Kennan  &LR; is now executive director of
the NFL Coaches Association and has made strides toward taking care
of retired coaches. ``There have been some legendary coaches who
have incurred so many medical bills they're practically broke,''
said Kennan, who last week struck a deal with the NFL Players
Association for the use of office space and support systems.
``We've been able to increase health care for coaches, who can now
get with a plan in which they pay some with their former team.''
Things still aren't perfect, though. Kennan says coaches can't
receive their pensions until age 65, but few work until that age;
only 7 percent of the coaches in the league are over the age of 55,
and most of them are with  &UR; Dick Vermeil  &LR; in St. Louis. Kennan said
there were nine coaches who were forced to retire last season
because none of them (eight of them were over 54) were rehired.
Kennan, who is being paid by the Patriots this year after he was
replaced as the offensive coordinator and refused to take a paycut
for a lesser position, expects he won't be one of the statistics.
``I think I have a good enough reputation where I'll be able to
hook on next year. Either that or I'd be very interested in a head
coaching position for a major college team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Northeastern quarterback  &UR; Jim Murphy &LR; , who spent training
camp and preseason with the Patriots, is calling offensive plays
for Bentley coach  &UR; Pete Yetten  &LR; (who pounded this reporter into
shape during his days at Whitman-Hanson High), as former Waltham
High and Northeastern legend  &UR; Bob Connors &LR; , Yetten's offensive
coordinator, has taken ill. Murphy is still attempting to hook on
with an NFL team and hopes to play in NFL Europe. In the meantime,
in exchange for a little coaching, he gets to work out and use the
facilities at Bentley to stay in shape. Murphy made a lot of
friends during his time with the Patriots; offensive coordinator
 &UR; Ernie Zampese  &LR; and quarterbacks coach  &UR; Jack Reilly  &LR; called to tell
him he was let go only because the Patriots needed spots for other
positions ...  &UR; Jimmy Hitchcock  &LR; will tell you that leaving the
Patriots can be painful. Hitchcock, a starting right cornerback for
Minnesota, had a tough first game but picked off a key pass the
next week in a victory over the Rams. That was after he'd severed
part of his little finger in an accident earlier in the game.
Hitchcock underwent surgery to save the finger. An update on other
ex-Patriots:  &UR; Sam Gash  &LR; hasn't played much for the 0-2 Bills
because they've gone to so many three-receiver sets; Jets
cornerback  &UR; Otis Smith  &LR; has often been seen chasing receivers after
getting beat; Jets special teams captain  &UR; Corwin Brown  &LR; is still
fairly productive;  &UR; Keith Byars  &LR; looks like an aging fullback and
 &UR; Curtis Martin  &LR; has had two stinkers for the Jets;  &UR; Brian Stablein
 &LR; is in a backup role in Detroit; and  &UR; Dave Meggett  &LR; is a student at
Towson State again ... Kennan said Martin seems to be lacking a
little explosion on his first step, but he was unsure whether that
is a result of the abdominal injury.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the Jets are having quarterback problems,  &UR; Neil O'Donnell
 &LR; leads the NFL in completion percentage (72.1) for the 2-0 Bengals
... Why do players say stuff like this? `` &UR; Bill Parcells  &LR; is going
to line up and play smash-mouth football. That's been him over the
years.'' Those were the words of Colts linebacker  &UR; Jeff
Herrod &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and they would have been true about 10 years ago.
Parcells's Patriots threw the ball more than any team in history.
Jets QB  &UR; Glenn Foley  &LR; leads the AFC in passing yardage, and the
Jets are 29th in rushing. Parcells was a smash-mouth guy with the
Giants. He has been Air Parcells ever since ... Some teams have bad
luck at certain positions. The Jaguars' albatross is defensive
linemen. When  &UR; Jabbar Threats  &LR; went down this past week with a knee
injury, it left the Jaguars with seven healthy linemen. ``I don't
know why this team is so snake-bit on the defensive line,'' said
tackle  &UR; John Jurkovic &LR; . The Jaguars already have lost  &UR; Don Davey
 &LR; (knee),  &UR; Jeff Lageman  &LR; (biceps),  &UR; Tony Brackens  &LR; (high ankle
sprain), and  &UR; Seth Payne  &LR; (dislocated shoulder) ... Remember,
 &UR; Charlie Batch &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the rookie quarterback starting  &UR; today &LR;  for
Detroit, was a player draft guru  &UR; Mel Kiper Jr. &LR;  said was taken too
high (second round) by the Lions out of Eastern Michigan ... From
