<HEADLINE>
CAN YOU SAY CY? GLAVINE WINS HIS 20TH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Say what you will about Greg Maddux and his four
straight National League Cy Young Awards from 1992-96, but the
pitcher who might mean more to the Atlanta Braves is Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   By defeating the Diamondbacks, 5-0, on Saturday night at Bank
One Ballpark, the left-hander became the first pitcher in the
majors this season to win 20 games (20-6) and allowed the Braves to
reach 100 victories for the second straight season (100-56).
</P>
<P>
   He also enhanced his chances to win the second NL Cy Young Award
of his career (his first was in 1991) by scattering six hits,
walking one and striking out five.
</P>
<P>
   The only serious threat by Arizona (62-94) came in the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   With the roof of Bank One Ballpark open for the first time since
June 27 against Seattle, Kelly Stinnett led off with a single and
Karim Garcia sent a double over the head of Andruw Jones in center
field. After pinch-hitter Andy Stankiewicz popped out to second,
Glavine walked Andy Fox but struck out Jay Bell looking and retired
Devon White on a grounder to second for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no secret in what he (Glavine) does,'' Diamondbacks
Manager Buck Showalter said. ``He locates his fastballs in places
where the umpires call strikes. That's the name of the game. He's
been doing it for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   After being shut out by Arizona right-hander Andy Benes and two
relievers on Friday night, the Braves took an aggressive approach
against left-hander Brian Anderson (12-13).
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie Guillen led off with a single to left-center, and Gerald
Williams followed by launching an 0-1 pitch over the fence in left
for a home run. It was the 38th home run allowed by Anderson this
season, tops in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ball was off the plate and in at his (Williams')
shoulders. How he hit it, I don't know. Give him credit. I thought
it was a pretty good pitch,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson got Chipper Jones to foul out to Travis Lee at first
base, but Andres Galarraga connected for a double to right field,
the first of his four hits on the night.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Lopez hit a line drive to Bell at second base, and it
appeared Bell stepped on the second base bag just before Galarraga,
which would have ended the inning, but umpire Eric Gregg ruled
otherwise. Andruw Jones followed with an RBI double to right to
make the score 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I pitched tonight the way I have the last five games
(four wins and a no-decision),'' Anderson said. ``The balls fell
for them, and they didn't fall for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, of course, had a lot to do with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the guy who set the standard (for left-handers),''
Anderson said. ``I think he and I pitch in a similar manner. We're
not overpowering, but we use our location to get guys out. You
can't argue with what he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was any doubt about the game's outcome, the Braves made
sure of it with a couple of insurance runs in the eighth inning off
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Williams singled to left with one out, his third hit of the
night, Chipper Jones singled and Galarraga singled. Showalter
brought in right-hander Felix Rodriguez, who gave up a single to
Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Williams once played for Showalter with the New York Yankees.
Showalter wants him to have success, but not at his expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got him, he was right out of Grambling
(University),'' Showalter said. ``He was raw, but aggressive. He's
come a long way. He's a solid player and a solid guy. He plays hard
and he can play all three outfield positions.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
