<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-LEE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEE FOCUSES ON PROGRESS, NOT AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Due in part to a two-week stay on the disabled list in
late July and early August, the odds are casting a long shadow on
Travis Lee's chances to win the National League Rookie of the Year
award.
</P>
<P>
   While he would be thrilled if enough votes carry his name, the
Diamondbacks first baseman won't consider it a sour season if it
doesn't happen. He seems to be focused more on long-term success
than short-term gratification.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said his first season in the major leagues, which ends a
week from today, ``has been a dream come true and a learning
experience at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter the level, he said, ``baseball is a game of
confidence, but at the major league level, it gets tested a lot
more. The physical part of it is about the same. When you're on,
you can hit anybody. When you're not, you can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said his confidence was a bit shaken after returning from
the disabled list (strained groin). He had only 17 hits in his
first 107 at-bats (.159) and saw his average drop from .288 into
the low .260s.
</P>
<P>
   He has shown signs of coming around of late. He got an infield
hit off Atlanta left-hander Tom Glavine on Saturday night to extend
his hitting streak to seven games and 10 of his last 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed in my numbers,'' he said. ``I never
really got back on track. That's the mental part you have to deal
with. You think you can come back pretty much the same, and I
hadn't seen live pitching in a while. It was 0 for 10, 0 for 12 or
something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starting to doubt myself. I thought my swing was no
good. I called home (to his parents in Olympia, Wash.) quite a few
times. But things are gradually starting to come around.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said that Lee may not agree
with him, ``but I think a little bit of adversity has been good for
him. It's good for him to be exposed to as much of this game as he
can, so he'll know how to handle himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody in the organization could be more
pleased with the way he's handled himself this year, in both good
times and bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe that the numbers he has this year (.267, 20
home runs and 69 RBIs) will be the lowest he'll have in his career.
He has a lot of strikeouts (122), but I doubt he'll have 100
again.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been occasions when Lee has received help on his
strikeouts from the umpires, who have tested him just like opposing
pitchers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
