<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS WIN EXHIBITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The Kings are using the early games of the nine-game
exhibition schedule to evaluate their young players, and two in
particular stood out Saturday night in the exhibition opener, a 3-2
shootout victory over the Colorado Avalanche before a crowd of
6,721 at the MGM Grand Garden Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Rosa scored at even strength and Olli Jokinen assisted on
veteran Glen Murray's goal with a two-man advantage. The Kings also
got a strong effort in goal by reserve Manny Legace, who has a shot
at a spot on the roster at least as long as Jamie Storr remains
unsigned. Legace stopped 25 of 27 Colorado shots. Sandy Moger
scored the winning goal in the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche goals were scored by Chris Drury and Milan Hejduk.
The teams meet again at 5 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   The game was more notable for who was out of the lineup than for
who played. Among those Kings not in the lineup were defensemen
Steve Duchesne, Rob Blake and Garry Galley, and forwards Luc
Robitaille and Jozef Stumpel (who has a twisted ankle).
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche lineup was a bit more representative. Patrick Roy
played the entire game in goal, and star center Joe Sakic also
played, though Peter Forsberg sat out.
</P>
<P>
   Berg signs in Finland: The agent for restricted free agent Aki
Berg said that the 21-year-old defenseman has signed a one-year
contract with TPS, his former team in his native Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kelly of Ottawa said Berg scored a power-play goal for TPS
on Saturday, and added that the chances are ``slim'' that his
client will return to the Kings this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be surprised,'' Kelly said. ``He certainly went back
intending to play in Finland for one year, and probably two.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kelly said a clause exists in Berg's contract that would
allow him out of the Finnish deal if he signs with the Kings by
Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said he does not plan to initiate further discussions with
Kings general manager Dave Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to call, he knows where to reach me,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he is planning to speak with Kelly again about Berg,
who was the third player chosen in the 1995 NHL draft. He also said
there has been no new progress in efforts to reach contract terms
with the Kings' other unsigned player, goalie Jamie Storr.
</P>
<P>
   Against all odds: The odds on the Kings winning the 1999 Stanley
Cup are 30-1 at the MGM Grand sports book, the same as the Mighty
Ducks and Wayne Gretzky's New York Rangers. The Avalanche is 10-1.
The two-time defending Stanley Cup champion Detroit Red Wings are
the favorites, at 7-2. The expansion Nashville Predators are 350-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
