<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ONLY A START FOR SUN DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The Great Mercenary Bowl is over. The check has
changed hands. And now we can resume a college football season
already in progress.
</P>
<P>
   So this is what $370,000 will get you these days? For that much,
you should be able to buy back your Top 10 ranking. Or purchase a
new ending against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   All it got Arizona State was a hollow victory, a padded box
score and a chance to break a sweat. Nothing less, nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Forget a 34-15 victory over North Texas, a football program that
will lick your wounds and feed your ego if the price is right. Need
a sparring partner? Give 'em a call. Except they're already booked
for this season, busy earning a cool $1.28 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they Mean Green. And apologize for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   So, of course, there was a cheap feel to this victory. Sort of
like paying for something you can't get on your own. Which would go
a long way in explaining the half-empty stadium, a reminder that
turnstile apathy isn't always confined to Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   You can look at the bright side. But this is a football team
that teased you with talk of a national championship, and, yes, we
all inhaled. A football team that lost its first two games, killing
off the euphoria in a matter of eight days. A team still looking
for its first meaningful victory.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, redemption isn't always the next game on the schedule.
In the case of the unranked Sun Devils, nothing will matter until
they beat someone worthy.
</P>
<P>
   They will have their chance in the next four weeks. A pretty
good outfit from Oregon State pays a visit. Then it's off to Troy
for a road game with O.J.U. Armageddon at home against Notre Dame,
the biggest mercenary of all. A home game with Stanford, which
upset North Carolina on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In four weeks, the season might look a whole lot better. The
defense could grow up, a leader might appear, and the offense could
very well mature into the juggernaut you expected. And in the year
of the upset, no telling what the Bowl Championship Series will
look like come November.
</P>
<P>
   Hope is not lost. Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is how we play the game of football, what we
do, how we do it,'' ASU Coach Bruce Snyder said. ``That's what the
deal is. Not whether we play Washington or BYU or North Texas. We
have to play up to our standards. We have to take care of ASU.''
</P>
<P>
   Impossible to tell whether that occurred on Saturday. North
Texas outgained the Sun Devils, 118-101, in the first quarter. Ryan
Kealy, one of the main culprits in the stink bomb against Brigham
Young, threw two interceptions. Chad Elliot, a cocky, redshirt
freshman who has a faction of supporters on the team, was looking
more and more like a viable option. And on two consecutive series,
the offense walked to the sideline under a chorus of boos.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the grief was temporary. Kealy caught fire. J.R.
Redmond buzzed along like the one indestructible piece in a game of
electronic football. The receiving corps was splendid, hauling down
everything in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the defense is still suspect. North Texas moved the ball
surprisingly well, and who knows how many points it would've scored
if not for a rash of second-quarter mistakes? All of which
illustrates the inexperience and growing pangs, neither of which
are likely to disappear anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the parade of flags. In three games, ASU has 32
penalties for 309 yards. More than a football field per game in
free yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Against North Texas, it was a formality, not a liability.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, this would've been the ideal opponent to start
the season, the perfect springboard for an team still unsure of
itself. In a sport that doesn't have an exhibition season, the
early stages of the schedule can be a risky proposition. In a
conference without a balanced schedule, the margin for error is
slim. Both have hurt the Sun Devils this season.
</P>
<P>
   At least they have a victory. Now they can work on regaining a
bit of respect. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
