<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4745 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-NORTHTEXAS-AZ     09-20 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-NORTHTEXAS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU FINDS ITS PULSE IN 1ST WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - ``Thump. Thump. Thump''.
</P>
<P>
   That's not just what Arizona State did to North Texas Saturday
night. It's also the sound of a team finding its pulse after
flat-lining for two straight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Whew. There. Behind J.R. Redmond's three touchdowns, the Sun
Devils finally felt what it's like to win again with a 34-15
victory in front of an announced crowd of 61,158 at Sun Devil
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the heart to win nine more games,'' ASU cornerback
Courtney Jackson said. ``You can't win nine until you get the
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. This was not a great effort by ASU. The defense
yielded 373 yards after the Mean Green managed just 264 in two
games. North Texas rolled up 192 rushing yards after posting just
44 against Texas Tech last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned,'' Sun Devils Coach Bruce Snyder said. ``I don't
believe North Texas should have gotten 15 (points).''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was a confidence builder. ASU's offense was much
sharper and the dropped passes that plagued this team a week ago
were practically non-existent.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond had 15 carries for 122 yards and 191 all-purpose yards.
Quarterback Ryan Kealy was 16 of 24 for 207 yards, two touchdowns
and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   North Texas shouldn't be embarrassed by the effort. It
capitalized on ASU's shaky defense after scoring just nine points
combined in its first two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``ASU has a lot of firepower,'' Mean Green Coach Darrell Dickey
said. ``We didn't have that much power.''
</P>
<P>
   How appropriate that ASU's revival was led by one of its
spiritual leaders, wide receiver Kenny Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   The senior is one of ASU's best athletes and most charismatic
personalities. But there has been a lingering sense that he's never
quite lived up to his potential.
</P>
<P>
   If this proves to be his breakthrough game, then his timing, a
key element for his position, was perfect. Mitchell had five
catches for 88 yards, including a 60-yard touchdown reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awesome to watch,'' Kealy said. ``To see him break the
first tackle, then second . . . then score. It's great.
</P>
<P>
   The game had plenty of subplots:
</P>
<P>
   _Gerald Green, the 5-foot-9 tailback with the compelling life
story, played much of the second half and had nine carries for 35
yards. With the loss of Marlon Farlow to academics, the Sun Devils
needed a third back behind Redmond and Davaren Hightower. They
found him.
</P>
<P>
   Redshirt freshman Hightower sprained his knee in the game and
will be examined today.
</P>
<P>
   _The coaching staff had an opportunity to look at a variety of
players. Junior college transfers Junior Ioane and Erik Flowers
started and saw significant minutes on the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils still have issues to address, and most have to do
with their defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it's apparent that we have a ton of things to work
on,'' Snyder said. ``But in saying that, I want to really emphasize
that this week of practice, the amount of work that went into this
week, was really, really important.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU sent a message on its opening drive. It went 57 yards in
under two minutes behind the legs of Redmond and arm of Kealy, who
was 3 for 3 during the drive. Redmond scored on a 13-yard run to
put ASU ahead, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   North Texas' offense didn't appear intimidated during its first
possession. It drove to the Sun Devils' 18-yard line, but Garrett's
Courtney's field-goal try was blocked by Steve Campbell. That's
right, the ``quarterback,'' who has found new life on special
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney's next attempt was successful, a 42-yard effort with
10:53 remaining in the second quarter that closed the Mean Green to
within 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils executed their next drive flawlessly. Redmond and
Hightower combined for 20 yards on four plays and Kealy and
Mitchell capped the possession with a 60-yard scoring play. The 6-3
Mitchell shed several tacklers after the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond increased ASU's lead to 21-3 with 4:54 remaining on a
24-yard run that made Mean Green players look as if they were
wearing lead boots.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who has catches in 28 straight games, gave the Sun
Devils another touchdown on a 9-yard reception. Green carried seven
times for 31 yards during the series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
