<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-IOWA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA RINGS UP IOWA, STAYS UNBEATEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ On its surface, Arizona's 35-11 victory over Iowa on
Saturday night in front of 52,634 at Arizona Stadium would leave
the impression that the Wildcats went unchallenged in their home
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkeyes were one play, one vicious hit, from making things
interesting Saturday. The Iowa faithful no doubt will be asking two
questions of Coach Hayden Fry today: Why did you go for a touchdown
on fourth and goal at the Arizona 2? And what's a 69-year-old man
doing wearing white pants on the sideline?
</P>
<P>
   Iowa (1-2) had its chances to upset the 16th-ranked Wildcats
(3-0). In the first half, Iowa had a touchdown called back because
of a penalty and were intercepted deep in Wildcats territory. But
the most deadly failure came in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 14-3, the Hawkeyes had a first and goal at the Arizona
5 but didn't score.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona linebacker Marcus Bell made the play of the game on the
goal-line stand. After two running plays and an incomplete pass
gained just three yards, Fry elected to go for the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kyle McCann drifted back to pass and was dancing
around when Bell sprinted in and dropped McCann on his can for a
7-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   The hit seemed to sap Iowa's resolve. On Arizona's next series,
quarterback Ortege Jenkins found receiver Jeremy McDaniel for a
76-yard gain down to the Iowa 2.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Kelvin Eafon, following a pancake block by guard
Yusuf Scott, scored on the next play to give Arizona a 21-3 lead.
Eafon also scored on a one-yard run in the fourth quarter to finish
the Wildcats' scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were inconsistent for much of the game, with their
occasional flashes of excellence well-separated by stretches of
floundering.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona looked sharp to open the game. With Keith Smith starting
his second straight game at quarterback, the Wildcats used a
no-huddle offense on their first possession and drove to the Iowa
25.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith then had a pass tipped at the line of scrimmage and
intercepted by linebacker Raj Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa also was occasionally exciting on offense. Behind McCann
and running back Ladell Betts, both freshman, the Hawkeyes proved
difficult at times for Arizona to defend.
</P>
<P>
   Betts, 5-11, 204, rushed for 49 yards on 11 carries in the first
half. But Iowa was usually done in by penalties (four for 36 yards
in the first half) or turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona scored first when running back Trung Canidate capped a
69-yard drive with a 1-yard run, giving the Wildcats a 7-0 lead
with 4:21 left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkeyes answered immediately behind McCann's arm and Betts'
legs, driving to the Arizona 18. But a run that lost 3 yards and
two incomplete passes ended their hopes for a touchdown, and they
settled for a 40-yard field goal as the first quarter ended.
</P>
<P>
   On its next possession, Iowa had a 29-yard touchdown pass from
McCann to Bashir Yamini called back because of holding.
</P>
<P>
   It proved to be a fatal mistake. The Arizona offense woke out of
its slumber, and with Jenkins at quarterback, drove 40 yards to the
Iowa 39. Jenkins was a huge factor in the drive. With the Wildcats
facing third and 14, Jenkins threw a perfect pass to Dennis
Northcutt for a 25-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   Canidate, who missed all of preseason camp with a stress
fracture in his right foot, then showed that he is completely
healthy. On a second down at the Iowa 39 he took a handoff up the
middle, took a jab step left to fake out a Hawkeyes defender and
sprinted for the touchdown, giving Arizona a 14-3 lead with 8:23
left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Northcutt, too, proved to be a deadly weapon, catching four
passes for 113 yards in the first half alone. He wasn't perfect,
however. Northcutt should have scored in the first quarter on a
screen but inexplicably cut into the path of an Iowa defender. And
he fumbled a punt in the second quarter, giving Iowa possession at
the Arizona 42. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
