<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREY'S SAYS GOAL IS ATTAINABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The Bruins began their exhibition season Saturday
night against the Canadiens, and Jim Carey saw action in goal.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought it?
</P>
<P>
   Carey came into the game with 10:09 left in the second period,
the Bruins trailing, 3-0, and allowed two goals and made 11 saves
in Boston's 5-3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Just a season ago, after posting a 2.90 goals against average
and throwing back-to-back shutouts at Anaheim and Vancouver, Carey
fell into disfavor and was demoted to Providence.
</P>
<P>
   It was an embarrassment for the 1996 Vezina Trophy winner.
</P>
<P>
   He initially balked, but when he finally decided to head down
Route 95, he took his problems with him. In 10 games, he was
anything but spectacular, compiling a 2-7-1 record and a 3.97 GAA.
</P>
<P>
   A shoulder injury and the ensuing surgery ended his season in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Ill will between Carey and Bruins management surfaced and there
was speculation that the club would buy out his contract in June.
</P>
<P>
   It never happened and Carey, eager to make a fresh start,
reported to training camp on time and healthy, intent on proving
that he again can be a top-notch goalie.
</P>
<P>
   So he's getting a close look from management. But with Byron
Dafoe and Rob Tallas generally considered the top two goalies in
camp, Carey knows he's in for a fight.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Carey said, ``I don't know of any coach that doesn't
want a good player,'' and it appears coach Pat Burns will give him
a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Carey acknowledged that he's surprised he's still a Bruin but he
also knows that his fate is out of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working hard, playing the best that I can, and just hope I
can make this club,'' said the Weymouth native and former Catholic
Memorial star. ``Either that or maybe someone else sees that you're
healthy and gives you a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about what might happen. Will I be here, will I be
traded, will I go to Providence? All the options are out there and
out of my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey was expected to be the Bruins netminder for many years
when he was obtained from the Washington Capitals in March 1997,
but things didn't pan out as he, or the Bruins, thought.
</P>
<P>
   In 19 games, he had a 5-13 record with a 3.82 goals against
average. He acknowledged that the pressure of playing before the
hometown fans was perhaps greater than he had anticipated. For one,
he wasn't prepared for the chorus of boos he received after a poor
performance.
</P>
<P>
   A return to his 1996 form would change the jeers to cheers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 0241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
