<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NAU-CSUN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAU TAKES BIG TUMBLE IN 1ST LOSS  
 NORTHRIDGE HAS EASY TIME IN BIG SKY OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. - A summer of discontent in 1997 convinced
Marcus Brady that the Naval Academy was not the place for him. It
only took a few months of the structured life to make the
quarterback homesick for California.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the redshirt freshman is loving the free-wheeling life at
Cal State-Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   Brady stunned and frustrated Northern Arizona on Saturday night
as he led the Matadors to a 41-10 victory in a Big Sky Conference
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Brady, who said his academy experience ``is a moment in my life
I want to forget,'' had a night to remember. He threw for three
touchdowns, completing 20 of 26 passes for 236 yards. He also wound
up with 49 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt comfortable out there,'' Brady said. ``I could see
my receivers, and I was able to read the defense because we saw a
lot of film.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady said the bye week for the Matadors (1-1) helped him get a
little healthier after taking a pounding in a 26-13 loss to Boise
State two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   NAU (2-1, 0-1), ranked No. 13 in Division I-AA, played without a
quarterback who might have given Brady a fight. Travis Brown, who
injured his elbow a week ago, remains week to week. Clay Brown did
a fair job filling in, but he was overmatched and perhaps was
trying too hard to carry the team. He ran for a team-high 91 yards
but was only 9 for 26 passing for 78 yards and one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Even a momentary bright spot for the Lumberjacks _ a sizzling
65-yard run by Tavon Cooper to set up a touchdown in the third
quarter _ was negated when Brady came right back to lead his team
to another score. The key play in that drive was his 50-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Brady completed 14 consecutive passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That quarterback is extremely elusive,'' Lumberjacks Coach
Jerome Souers said. ``We couldn't contain him.''
</P>
<P>
   NAU's defense managed to corral Brady four times, but it was
neither enough nor at the right times.
</P>
<P>
   Brady's game rubbed off on his teammates, who seemed to do
little wrong, as evidenced by a 93-yard touchdown run on a
recovered fumble late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the first in the head coaching career of Ron
Ponciano, and he's the first to admit that inheriting Brady was a
stroke of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like the blind squirrel finding the nut,'' he said.
``He's a talented guy, a tough rascal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws back across the field, he places the ball in just
the right place. There isn't a coach in America who coaches that
kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cooper, it was a nice return. He injured his shoulder in the
season opener and has played sparingly. Cooper, a former star at
Peoria High School, seems to be in a good spot to give the
Lumberjacks a solid running back for the remainder of the year.
</P>
<P>
   NAU was the highest-ranked team that Cal State-Northridge has
ever beaten. It was also the Matadors' first win in Flagstaff since
1968. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
