<HEADLINE>
STORMY SEAS SURROUND ISLANDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There's plenty of strife and uncertainty on Long Island
these days. The Islanders have a $10 million lawsuit pending
against Spectacor Management Group, the company that manages the
26-year-old Nassau County Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   New York Sports Ventures, which purchased the club in February
for $195 million, claims that the hoists that hold the scoreboard
in place are unsafe and it wants to nullify the lease with SMG,
which runs through 2015.
</P>
<P>
   However, the real reason for the power struggle appears to be
the owners' desire to terminate their relationship with SMG so that
when a new arena is finally built, SMG would not run the
advertising, concessions, parking, and skyboxes.
</P>
<P>
   It's uncertain whether the club will play home games at the
Coliseum this season, but a restraining order has been issued,
preventing them from playing anywhere else pending a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   This dispute is the latest crisis for a team that has missed the
playoffs the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   There was the John Spano disaster in which the former owner
fooled all of the people most of the time until he ultimately was
revealed to be a financial fraud. And there have been contract
disputes, most notably with star forward Zigmund Palffy.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Dennis Vaske, who had spent his entire career in the
Islanders organization before signing as a free agent with Boston,
said he has seen it all on the Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do I start?'' he said. ``Spano was supposed to be the
knight in shining armor. He had everyone believing that was going
to happen. What's happening now is rather surprising, but I think
they're doing things from a business perspective. They have to do
what they have to do to make ends meet. The fans have had enough
negative things in the area there. I think it was time for a big
positive and this definitely isn't going to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaske said the Coliseum is outdated by new rink standards but
what made it a tough place to play in were the small crowds,
between 6,000-10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough market,'' said Vaske. ``In the same respect, I
think, as a fan, you have to kind of look at what you're spending
and what you're getting, too. We had some lulls in there. We had
some really bad starts and some awful years. There are fickle fans
everywhere and I don't blame them. Everyone loves a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruins captain  &UR; Ray Bourque  &LR; is among those mesmerized and
excited by the home run race between  &UR; Mark McGwire  &LR; and  &UR; Sammy
Sosa &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game was on TV from 58 on and I was watching every one
of them when (McGwire) hit 58, 59, 60, 61, and 62 with (son)
 &UR; Christopher &LR; ,'' said Bourque. ``It was quite an event. We'd all
sit down and watch it together. It was quite a feeling watching him
accomplish that. Just having those two guys going head to head like
that. I hope they finish tied. I'd hate to see one guy win it
because who knows when one of these guys is going to have this type
of year again? If McGwire or Sosa hits 67 and the other one hits
66, it's no fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, a classy ambassador for his sport for 20 years, is
impressed by the way McGwire and Sosa have handled the pressure and
the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had fun with it, Sosa a little bit more than
McGwire,'' said Bourque. ``It seems like the last month and a half,
McGwire has had a blast with it. Really, you could see a change in
how he approached the media and everything like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be tough. McGwire has been hearing it from the
opening day of camp. You're going out there and trying to win games
and play for your team and all they're talking about is your
home-run streak. It's quite an accomplishment with the pressure of
going through that. It's phenomenal. Both these guys are really
humble and love the game. That's why it's been so much fun to
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though Bourque has been enjoying baseball, Flames forward  &UR; Marty
McInnis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a former Boston College standout, has been biting his
nails as the Red Sox go down to the wire in the wild-card race.
``It's tough being a Sox fan,'' said McInnis. ``I've got to say
that '86 was really hard to take.  &UR; Billy Buckner  &LR; took the heat for
letting the ball go through his legs but there was a passed ball
just before that. There were a lot of goats. Right now, though,
it's looking pretty good for the playoffs. I think we're going to
get there.'' ...  &UR; Alexandre Daigle  &LR; didn't do himself any favors
with his sad time in the Flyers' 10-kilometer run, which was part
of the team fitness testing. He ran the route in 53 minutes 50
seconds, among the worst of the 55 players. Daigle has been under a
microscope since signing a four-year, $12.25 million deal the day
he was drafted by Ottawa with the first overall pick in 1993, and
has been widely viewed as a chronic underachiever. ``We need more
consistent play out of Alexandre,'' said Philly GM  &UR; Bob Clarke &LR; .
``He can give you five or six games where he shows you his
greatness and then he gives you games where you couldn't find him
with a program. When players are inconsistent in their performance,
it's hard for coaches to trust them.'' Daigle, who aspires to be an
actor, made news off the ice this summer when he was reported to be
dating former ``Baywatch'' star  &UR; Pamela Anderson Lee  &LR; ... Last
Monday, Senators star  &UR; Daniel Alfredsson  &LR; said his major objective
was to stay healthy. On Wednesday, Alfredsson tore the medial
collateral ligament in his left knee during a scrimmage and could
be out as long as eight weeks. It isn't the first key injury for
the Senators. Defenseman  &UR; Janne Laukkanen  &LR; is recovering from a
groin surgery that will likely sideline him three months ... Nice
decision to hold the 2000 All-Star Game, the NHL's 50th, in
Toronto. It's scheduled to take place at the new Air Canada Centre,
now under construction and due to open Feb. 20. It will be the
first time since 1968 that Toronto has hosted the festivities ...
The weather in Feldkirch, Austria, hasn't exactly been what the
Lightning are used to. The Lightning, along with the Buffalo Sabres
(who view the weather in Austria as relatively tropical), are
staying in the mountain village as part of an exhibition trip. It
has been a raw 45 degrees, accompanied by a steady rain. ``I'm
never going to complain about the weather in Florida again,'' said
Lightning GM  &UR; Phil Esposito &LR; . ``I used to complain every time it
rained and about how hot it was. No more. This place is beautiful,
but it's sooooo cold.'' Food also has been a challenge. The players
haven't been able to get away from Wiener schnitzel. ``If I eat one
more Wiener schnitzel,'' said forward  &UR; Sandy McCarthy &LR; , &UR;  &LR; ``I'm
going to puke.'' ...  &UR; Todd Bertuzzi &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was considered a big
bust with the Islanders, has been a force early in Vancouver's
training camp. The 23-year-old forward, who was taken with the
Isles' first choice in 1993 (No. 23 overall), is finally using his
6-foot-3-inch, 230-pound frame. ``The whole point of having size is
you have to use it,'' said Bertuzzi, who was dealt to the Canucks
Feb. 6. ``I'm going to drive the net. I'm not going to go out there
and kill people or anything, but I am going to finish my checks
whenever I can. This is a fresh start. This is a new team.'' ... As
expected, the Canucks suspended disgruntled forward  &UR; Pavel Bure
 &LR; for his failure to show up to camp. Bure has demanded a trade and
GM  &UR; Brian Burke  &LR; said he won't ship off Bure until the right deal
comes along. If Bure sits the whole year, he stands to lose about
$8 million in Canadian funds ... A youngster who has caught the eye
of Bourque is 23-year-old forward  &UR; Andre Savage &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who also is a
client of Bourque's close friend  &UR; Steve Kasper &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the former Bruin
coach. ``I'm very impressed how he takes the puck to the net and
always gets there,'' he said. ``He's kind of like a
( &UR; Steve &LR; ) &UR; Heinze  &LR; but he doesn't clean up the ice as much as
Heinzey. (Kasper) told me he really goes to the net good. He's got
nice, quick hands. He's finished some nice plays and has made some
nice passes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blackhawks captain  &UR; Chris Chelios &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who turns 37 in January, is
hoping that after such a miserable season last year _ Chicago
missed the playoffs for the first time in 29 years _ the additions
of  &UR; Doug Gilmour &LR; , &UR; Paul Coffey &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Eddie Olczyk  &LR; as well as
tough guys  &UR; Mark Janssens  &LR; and  &UR; Doug Zmolek  &LR; will ease some of the
burden. Despite rumors to the contrary, Chelios said he didn't have
a big problem with coach  &UR; Craig Hartsburg &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was fired in favor
of  &UR; Dirk Graham  &LR; in the offseason. ``I have argued with every coach
at every level,'' said Chelios. ``Just because I looked at him
funny sometimes doesn't mean I didn't respect him.'' The Hawks are
still without Group 2 free agent  &UR; Eric Daze &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is haggling with
management over a contract ... Ducks defenseman  &UR; Fredrik
Olausson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who turns 32 next month, is undergoing tests because of
an enlarged spleen, which was diagnosed during a physical last
weekend. This isn't Olausson's first health problem. He also has
had an irregular heartbeat and inflammation of the colon. He
suffers from Crohn's disease, an inflammation of the digestive
tract ... Defenseman  &UR; Tommy Albelin &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 34, was deemed the fittest
athlete in Calgary's camp. He attributed it to an unfavorable
climate in his native Sweden, where he spent the offseason. ``You
couldn't go outside so you would have to do something inside,''
said Albelin. ``I went to the gym.'' ... Kings defenseman  &UR; Aki
Berg &LR; , &UR;  &LR; LA's first pick in the 1995 draft, is planning to fly home
to Finland this weekend to join a club team rather than accept the
Kings' latest contract proposal. Berg had eight assists and no
goals in 72 games last year. A much bigger problem was solved when
captain  &UR; Rob Blake &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a Group 2 free agent, came to terms Friday.
After winning the Norris Trophy in June, Blake got three years and
$15.8 million ... Former Bruin forward  &UR; Sergei Zholtok  &LR; is
currently listed as the No. 2 center behind  &UR; Vincent Damphousse  &LR; in
Montreal's camp. Zholtok, who was released by Ottawa, had three
goals during a scrimmage last week ... Wings enforcer  &UR; Joey Kocur
 &LR; is a best bet to be among those exposed for the waiver draft.
Reportedly, Kocur would retire rather than go to another city ...
The locals are making a big splash in Edmonton's training camp.
Massachusetts natives  &UR; Tom Poti &LR; , &UR; Brad Norton &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Dan LaCouture
 &LR; all are making impressive runs at jobs on the big team, which
already has Bay Staters  &UR; Bill Guerin &LR; , &UR; Joe Hulbig &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Mike
Grier  &LR; ... Forward  &UR; Trent McCleary &LR; , &UR;  &LR; released by the Bruins, made
an early impression during his tryout with the Canadiens, getting
into a scrap with veteran defenseman  &UR; Igor Ulanov &LR; . McCleary, who
couldn't come to terms with the Bruins last year and wound up
playing for Las Vegas in the IHL, could find a home in Montreal
since the Habs had three unsigned forwards going into the weekend
and  &UR; Shayne Corson  &LR; is holding out ... 20 days to opening night.
</P>
