<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC SHOWS ITS CHARACTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You're not supposed to get excited about handing a
team its 13th consecutive Pac-10 loss. In the hierarchy of bragging
rights, that's right there with knocking down a Julio Cesar Chavez
who's way past his prime or embarrassing the defending World Series
champion Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, there's definitely momentum in the mundane.
</P>
<P>
   Truth to tell, more than the headline-grabbing upset victory
it's ho-hum wins such as the one the USC football team gutted out
against upstart Oregon State Saturday that augur promise.
</P>
<P>
   Because any team can work itself into an inspired frenzy against
an opponent that it isn't supposed to defeat; the motivation then
is as easy to muster as one's next breath. The teams that are
talked about past November are the ones that don't allow themselves
to get tripped up by opponents they're expected to beat, summoning
the motivation to succeed from deep within themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans faced a couple of critical gut checks in the second
half of their Pac-10 opener. That they came back to overpower the
Beavers 40-20 in front of a Coliseum crowd of 45,629 says something
of their collective character.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, USC is in a position to elevate themselves in the
national rankings with a headline-grabbing win this week against
favored Florida State in its first road game, at Tallahassee,
because it weathered a 54-minute first quarter that could have
lulled them to sleep, then stubbornly refused to let a
much-improved OSU team derail them in the pivotal third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   If there was an individual player who personified the team
effort it was senior running back Chad Morton, who finished with
123 yards rushing on 23 carries despite missing most of the week of
practice because of a sore back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed me so much tonight,'' said first-year Trojans coach
Paul Hackett. ``He's as tough as nails.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Alexander tested the Trojans' mettle when he returned the
second-half kickoff yards for the score that tied the game at 17.
It took Alexander, the Beavers' one-time quarterback, only 16
seconds to go _ untouched _ where neither Purdue nor San Diego
State had gone before him in the second halves of their games
against the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's sprint was a kick in the stomach to a Trojans team
that had taken no small pride in the fact it had outscored the
Boilermakers and Aztecs 31-0 over the final 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased with the play of our football team after they
ran back that kickoff,'' Hackett said. ``That was a very tough pill
for us to swallow. We did an outstanding job of not letting us
affect us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (3-0) recovered their collective breath, though it
took a huge play from junior Pat Swanson to enable everybody to
exhale. After the Trojans answered Alexander's score with an
indifferent drive, OSU Ken Simonton promptly fumbled the ensuing
punt.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson swooped in to recover the ball, setting up a 26-yard
drive that culminated in a 28-yard field goal by Adam Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   It was a chip shot for the senior placekicker but by no means a
given; before he could make it, Abrams had to dig deep down, past
the memories of his three missed field goals against the Aztecs.
You could say he put his sad Saturday behind him; his four field
goals were a career high.
</P>
<P>
   The USC defense took up where Abrams' foot left off. On the
Beavers' next possession, they worked the ball into Trojans
territory. But on a third-and-7 play at the USC 35, the
cardinal-and-gold covered quarterback Terrance Bryant like a tidal
wave. He had no choice but to hurry his throw and it fell
incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers had the temerity to tread into Trojans' territory on
their next series but, again, a USC player rose to the challenge.
This time it was David Gibson, who recovered a fumble by Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers fell apart after that, the final score hardly
indicative of the scare they gave a USC team that was supposed to
win if only because no Trojans squad has lost to OSU since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Under the second-year tutelage of former USC assistant coach
Mike Riley, Oregon State looks much better than the squad that was
shut out by the Trojans 23-0 last year on its way to a 3-8
conference record.
</P>
<P>
   But then, so, too, does USC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
