<HEADLINE>
SOSA, CUBS STRIKE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Cubs fans are expected to pack Wrigley Field Sunday
for the Sammy Sosa Celebration. It would be nice if his Chicago
teammates chip in a much-needed victory as their contribution.
</P>
<P>
   While Sosa has been doing all he can to remain in the home run
chase with Mark McGwire (he's still one behind the St. Louis
slugger, who went 0 for 4 against Milwaukee Saturday night),
Chicago has been losing ground to the New York Mets in the National
League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's 7-2 loss to the Reds, coupled with the Mets'
4-3 victory over the Marlins, Chicago and New York are even in
their quest for the postseason with identical 87-69 records.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's final regular-season game at Wrigley against
Cincinnati, the Cubs go on the road for five games, two in
Milwaukee and three in Houston. After Sunday's game against
Florida, New York has two more at home against Montreal, and closes
on the road against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight day, Sosa went 0 for 4, and Saturday
struck out three times.
</P>
<P>
   Of his 63 home runs, 35 have come at Wrigley Field. With his
mother and 40 friends and family members on hand Sunday for the
celebration, Sosa might wind up pressing even more in the finale
than he has in the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows I'm a human being,'' he said. ``Not every day
will be a good day. For the last couple of days they have been
pitching me real great. I want to do something every day to help my
team win. But I can't do it alone. I think people understand.
Tomorrow will be much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Bere, using an assortment of pitches, had Sosa's number
three times, and in the ninth inning, righthander Danny Graves
induced the Dominican star to hit into a game-ending double play.
In all four at-bats, Sosa showed a lack of patience. He went down
swinging in the first and seventh innings, and was caught looking
in the fourth. This was not the Sammy Sosa who has carried the Cubs
on his shoulders since last June. The Cubs don't need home runs;
they need Sosa to be himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I swung at so many pitches,'' said Sosa. ``I never feel
pressure. But I understand that not every day you're going to feel
great. If I was a superman, I'd hit a home run every day. If I
don't do it today, perhaps tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Nunnally homered twice and had four RBIs for the Reds and
that was more than enough for Bere, who gave up just two hits in
eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa said the ceremony won't be a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to enjoy whatever happens. I think I deserve to be
happy. When the game starts, everybody knows I will be there and
will be ready. This is my job. Whatever happens to me and to Mark
happens. We are chasing history. We both know that 60 home runs
don't happen every year.''
</P>
<P>
   The race to stay ahead of the Mets doesn't happen every year,
either. Sosa said he does not do any scoreboard watching. But he's
perhaps the only one at Wrigley Field who hasn't been looking
skyward.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our situation, we cannot afford to think about what happens
in New York,'' he said. ``We have to think about what's happening
in Chicago. We have to come here to play our game. We don't want to
lose. We talked to each other about what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Reds manager Jack McKeon said his pitchers have no secret
formula to stopping Sosa. Good pitching stops good hitters. The key
is to keep them off balance, working both sides of the plate and
changing speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a good job against him,'' said McKeon. ``Sure, he's
gotten to us for a few home runs, but not in our park. We throw him
fastballs and breaking balls. The thing we don't want to do is hang
one of them. I'm pulling for both of them. They put on a great
show. I hope they end up tied ... at 66.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa says he has no idea what his final total will be. But he's
pretty sure he won't be seeing many strikes the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark is right when he said they're not going to give us
anything over the plate to hit,'' said Sosa. ``There is nothing you
can do about it but try to be patient. I love Mark McGwire. We have
a lot of respect for each other. If he's going to win, he's going
to win. I feel satisfied with what I've accomplished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
