<HEADLINE>
SKIP AWAY RUNS AWAY IN WOODWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is no longer a question of greatness; Skip Away
demonstrated again Saturday that he is great. The quest now is to
see whether he is among the best of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with four top foes in the most talented field assembled
this year, Skip Away simply ran them all into the ground as he
powered his way to a convincing victory in the $500,000 Woodward
Stakes at Belmont Park on a beautiful fall Saturday, designed to
showcase a super racehorse. The victory was Skip Away's ninth in a
row, his seventh straight this year, and the $300,000 winner's
share moved him to $9,596,552 in earnings in his relentless pursuit
of Cigar's all-time mark of $9,999,815.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's some horse, the best there is,'' said Sonny Hine, who
trains Skip Away for his wife, Carolyn. ``He's one of the best I
have ever seen. He is so brilliant. The horse makes the trainer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridden by Jerry Bailey, who won his fourth Woodward and third in
four years (Sultry Song in 1992 followed by Cigar in '95 and '96),
Skip Away broke third as the even-money choice ($4.20 to win), but
quickly went up after front-runner Coronado's Quest, the only
3-year-old in the field, and Pat Day. Skip Away took over through a
quarter in :223/5, then sizzled through a half in :452/5, and three
quarters in 1:09, rendering Coronado's Quest, who finished fifth
and last, rubber-legged.
</P>
<P>
   Free House, the 3-2 second choice, made a run under Chris
McCarron, but was done turning for home and faded to fourth.
Gentlemen and Corey Nakatani chased Skip Away home after a mile in
1:341/5, but last year's handicap champion had plenty left and
prevailed by a 1 3/4 lengths in 1:474/5 for the 1 1/8 miles.
Running Stag, a 48-1 shot from Europe, came up the rail with Ray
Cochrane to pick up the pieces and get third, 6 lengths farther
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coronado's Quest always breaks so well that it might have made
it look like we were off a little slow,'' said Bailey. ``But I just
tapped him once and he did his thing and got back in the race. He
does what he has to do. If they try to stay with him, it costs them
a little bit off their finish. If they let him go, he just runs
away. As long as he keeps running like this, I can't see a chink in
his armor.''
</P>
<P>
   This field was considered so strong that Gentlemen, who had not
been higher than 9-5 in his previous 10 races, was 7-1. The veteran
campaigner, now age 6, beat Skip Away in the Pimlico Special last
year but he was no match Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My horse ran his heart out,'' said Nakatani. ``He ran great.
He made a nice move at the top of the stretch but Skip Away was
just much the best out there. I thought Coronado's Quest would
press Skip Away on the lead but it didn't happen. We just got
outrun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Woodward, witnessed by a crowd of 20,237 that gave Skip Away
a rousing ovation upon his return to the winner's circle, was a
major disappointment for Free House, who had won both his races
this year, and Coronado's Quest, who had captured five in a row
against horses his own age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was real happy with my position and then Free House just
stopped trying,'' said McCarron. ``There was something amiss with
him, not in the soundness sense, but something was definitely wrong
with him. I can't put my finger on it. The bottom line is it just
wasn't his day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coronado's Quest took me right out there,'' said Day. ``He was
comfortable on the backside, although we were moving quickly.
Approaching the three-eighths pole, I got no response from my colt.
I asked him to kick on and he faltered. It just wasn't meant to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Next for Skip Away will be the $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup
at Belmont Oct. 10, run at 1 1/4 miles, which he has won the last
two years, defeating Cigar in '96 _ when Skip Away was a 3-year-old
_ and scoring an easy tally last year, which began his winning
streak. The $600,000 victor's purse of the Jockey Club would give
Skip Away the earnings record but it is still expected he will try
to take his second straight Breeders' Cup Classic, a $4 million
race run this year at Churchill Downs Nov. 7, to go out in a blaze
of glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going for three in a row in the Jockey Club, we've been
planning on that all along,'' said Hine. ``We'll retire him after
the Breeders' Cup. He's given us four years. It's time. God forbid
we should see him out on the racetrack someday broken down or being
beaten by inferior horses. Why not quit when you're on top?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
