<SLUG> BC-USC-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAVERS ARE UNWANTED GUESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This wasn't your father's Oregon State football
team.
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers showed up at the Coliseum on Saturday night carrying
a 24-game losing streak to their hosts and a 35-year string without
a bowl appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers went home to Corvallis with a 25th consecutive loss
to USC, the look of a team which could bring the bowl game back to
the program and plenty of respect from USC.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the comfortable 40-20 final margin, don't think for a
minute that No. 25 was easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Oregon State was better than they had been,'' USC coach
Paul Hackett said. ``I said that all week and it proved to be true.
Oregon State gave us a real push. Until the game ended, I didn't
relax one moment.''
</P>
<P>
   USC entered Saturday night with a No.16 or No.18 national
ranking, depending on your poll of choice, and are a week away from
jetting to Tallahassee in an attempt to put its name into the
national picture.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State, which lost for the first time in three games,
nearly ruined all the Trojans fun of taking a 3-0 record into that
matchup with No.11 Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Beavers performed their role as willing victim early
during this Pac-10 opener for both teams. It took the Trojans only
four plays to move 63 yards after accepting the opening kickoff
with Larry Parker gathering in a perfectly thrown 47-yard strike
from Mike Van Raaphorst for the score.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Beavers spent a good portion of the evening
acting as pesky guests. USC didn't always help itself _ amassing
102 yards on 11 penalties, fumbling away a punt and roughing
quarterback Terrance Bryant to nullify what appeared to be a
drive-ending interception by Rashard Cook in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The fumbled punt by R. Jay Soward led to a 27-yard Oregon State
scoring drive, culminating with a 5-yard scoring toss from Bryant
to James Battle. Oregon State's Tim Alexander then ran back the
second-half kickoff 100 yards for a game-tying touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased with the play of our football team after they
ran the kickoff back,'' Hackett said. ``It was a very tough pill to
swallow, particularly right at the start of the second half. I
thought our defense got stronger as the second half went on. Once
again, we played our best football in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   USC's offense never really got comfortable in the second half
thanks to a swarming Oregon State defense. But USC's defense, which
allowed only a field goal in the second half, made sure the Trojans
went home happy.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans now they can set their sights on Florida State,
which beat the Trojans 14-7 in last year's season opener. And USC
can move on with the knowledge that 3-0 starts tend to mean bowl
game appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The last USC team to begin the season 3-0 was the 1995 Rose Bowl
championship team and that happens to be the last Trojans bowl
squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a rule around here we get to enjoy this one for 24
hours,'' Hackett said. ``I think we're ready to take a look against
a team which is clearly one of the top in the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 0300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
