<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEMPLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-STRIKE CAPABILITY NOT ENOUGH FOR OWLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It took Temple 22 seconds to silence the Boston College
faithful Saturday at Alumni Stadium. The visitors capitalized on a
BC fumble on the opening kickoff to take a surprising 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls struck quickly by showcasing the nation's
fourth-leading rushing attack. Their first play was an option run
that went for 16 yards. The second went for 3 yards and a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The quick strike was just what Temple wanted _ to unsettle the
unbeaten Eagles with its option attack and take advantage. The Owls
hoped to then further surprise BC with speed and quickness and ride
that momentum to their first win of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Great plan. But the execution soon began to falter. Before long,
it was the Owls who appeared to be unsettled, bothered by the fact
they couldn't finish a drive. After the early touchdown, BC took
back the momentum and never relinquished it in a 31-7 rout.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought pressure and we really didn't handle the pressure
well,'' said Temple coach Bobby Wallace, whose team entered the
game averaging 298.5 rushing yards but amassed just 151, including
only 20 after halftime. ``We didn't protect very well and execute
very well under the pressure. Really, that is the first time we
have seen that kind of pressure live and not on the practice
field.''
</P>
<P>
   After scoring, Temple managed to move the ball inside the BC 35
five times. Three of the five drives ended with turnovers, another
with a missed field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started shifting their defense to the strength of our
offense,'' said Temple tailback Stacey Mack, who had only 27
rushing yards after eclipsing 100 yards in each of his first two
games. ``There were a lot of mental breakdowns in our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first drive, the only time Temple's quickness caught
the Eagles off guard was in the second quarter, when quarterback
Kevin Harvey shook the grasp of a tackler on third and 8 and
scampered 23 yards to the BC 42.
</P>
<P>
   The play was the seventh on a 15-play, 55-yard drive that ended
with Harvey being intercepted by DuJuan Daniels in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Said Wallace, ``I thought when Kevin broke the tackle and made a
great individual effort _ because they brought the pressure one
time and hit him in the backfield _ and he ended up running it, I
was hoping that would scare them out of bringing it some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a plan that should stop (defensive pressure), but we
just didn't do very well with it today.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said that after Temple's touchdown BC shifted its
defensive front and backs, moving the strong safety over a few
times to Temple's left side, which is where the 16-yard rush on its
first drive was run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we would catch them by surprise with our
quickness,'' Wallace added. ``When they put their strong safety
over there, we went back trying to execute the quick passing game
where the strong safety used to be, and we overthrew it badly. It
was a matter of a little execution here and there, and that's
probably what made that first drive look so easy.''
</P>
<P>
   BC defenders, however, said they did not change a thing after
Temple's first scoring drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there to make the play at the time and I just didn't,''
said free safety Pedro Cirino. ``That's something I take full
responsibility for. We just made up for it the rest of the game.
Everyone stepped up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
