<SLUG> BC-FBC-HARVARD-COLUMBIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD BASHED BY LIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ They decided to designate Saturday's opening game
as their Homecoming bash at Wein Stadium at Baker Field here at the
uppermost tip of Manhattan, and Columbia marked the occasion by
ambushing favored Harvard to give the alums and undergrads
something to celebrate. The Crimson had won their last seven games
a year ago, and completed their first unbeaten and untied Ivy
League season with a victory in Yale Bowl to go 9-1.
</P>
<P>
   This one was no contest as the Lions ran through the Crimson
defense, passed into their zones, and completely shut down their
offense, which was led by returning quarterback Rich Linden and
running back Chris Menick. One needed only to look at the halftime
statistics. The Crimson had just three first downs, a net 12 yards
in rushing, and Linden had been intercepted. The Lions had 112
yards rushing, 10 first downs, and had the ball for 19:43. The
Crimson crossed midfield just once, on an interception.
</P>
<P>
   Things got worse as the Lions roared to a 24-0 triumph, the
first time the Crimson had been shut out since the Penn game of
1994. Just consider this sequence in the fourth quarter of the
Crimson's longest day in a few years. The Crimson fielded a punt at
their 45. Linden was caught for a loss of 1 on the first play from
scrimmage. Linden threw an incompletion but the Crimson were called
for holding. First and 40. By the time the Crimson's John Patton
punted it was fourth and 25.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions, who finished 4-6 overall last season and were
hammered, 45-7, by the Crimson in Harvard Stadium, ended up with a
15-8 edge in first downs, ran off 70 plays to 55 for the Crimson,
and enjoyed a 298-169 edge in total offense before a joyous crowd
of 11,175 on a warm, sunny afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked it a lot,'' said Columbia coach Ray Tellier. ``We
played a full four quarters. I felt we dominated the game. I can't
remember the last time we controlled things physically up front
like that. Five years ago maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We got outplayed every step of the way today,'' said Linden,
who never was able to direct the Crimson offense over midfield. The
only time they made it was on Kane Waller's interception of a Paris
Childress pass and a Clint Killar fumble recovery on the last
sequence of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't get together,'' Linden added. ``We didn't
have 11 guys on the same page today. Their defense played very
well. Their secondary played very well, but obviously turnovers
(one fumble, one interception) hurt us. They won the game. They
stopped us.''
</P>
<P>
   Childress, a senior out of New Orleans, completed 11 of 22
passes for 102 yards, and exciting freshman Jonathan Reese of St.
Louis carried 11 times for 72 yards. The Lions wasted little time
setting the tempo of the game, moving 53 yards in 11 plays on their
second possession and finishing it when wishbone quarterback Jason
Bivens rolled left on a fourth-down call, cut back, and took it in
from the 1 at 4:58 of the first. Before the half, the Lions had
forged a 10-0 lead when Neal Kravitz kicked a 36-yard field goal.
The drive consumed eight minutes and two seconds.
</P>
<P>
   After the Crimson were bottled up on their first possession of
the second half, the Lions went to work on their second possession
when Reese broke over right tackle and raced 30 yards for a first
down on the 31. After a penalty, Childress saw Mark Cannan wide
open in the left corner of the field and hit him with a pass on the
1. Cannan simply stepped into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions had opened a 17-0 lead, and when Paul Roland
intercepted Linden's first pass on the next sequence and returned
it 35 yards to the 1 it set up a 1-yard plunge by Norman Hayes to
make it 24-0. Twelve points in 27 seconds, and it summed up the
Crimson's day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
