<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PENN-DARTMOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN, FINN SLIP BY DARTMOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; HANOVER, N.H. _ Dartmouth was slipped a Finn Saturday. Not a
take-you-down Mickey Finn, but a put-you-down Jim Finn, the
University of Pennsylvania senior running back. Finn and Co.
claimed a nail-biting 17-14 verdict over the Big Green, in weather
that was more like July's than September's.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 10-0 at halftime, Dartmouth almost came back. It scored
twice within a four-minute span in the third period for a 14-10
lead. But it was done in by Finn, a first-team All-Ivy League
selection last season, when he scored from a yard out in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Finn, who wears lucky No. 7 very well, was a force as the
Quakers snapped Dartmouth's modest two-game win streak over them.
The 6-foot-1-inch, 215-pounder from Bergen Catholic in Fair Lawn,
N.J., sent a message to league foes as he carried 41 times for 151
yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Finn started at strong safety against Dartmouth last year and on
offense carried once for 2 yards. He was switched to running back
full time in October, and ran for 797 yards, second best in the
league to Harvard's Chris Menick.
</P>
<P>
   Finn didn't do it alone. Other contributors were senior
quarterback Matt Rader and a swarming defense. Last year Rader
threw for 206 yards against Dartmouth. Saturday he threw for 161.
</P>
<P>
   Penn scored on its first possession when Finn bulled over from
the 6-yard line with 9:29 left in the first. That capped a
seven-play, 68-yard drive, and Jason Feinberg kicked the point
after. Rader tossed 15- and 27-yard passes to Doug McNeill and
David Rogers, respectively, and Finn had 20 yards on three carries.
</P>
<P>
   Penn's second possession ended 1:38 into the second quarter when
Feinberg kicked a 24-yard field goal. A key play was a 15-yard pass
from Rader to Rogers. In the first quarter Dartmouth had minus-4
yards on offense, while Penn had 97 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second Penn drove from its 28 to the
Dartmouth 27 when a Rader pass was picked off by Green safety Brad
Eissler. But Dartmouth had to punt again and Penn's Joe Piela
returned it 41 yards to the Dartmouth 28. Feinberg's 40-yard field
goal attempt was a shade short.
</P>
<P>
   Penn put together a late 41-yard drive to the Dartmouth 18, but
a 35-yard Feinberg attempt was wide left.
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth had 4 yards of total offense in the first half, while
Penn had 194.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my kids at the half that we couldn't let up and that
Dartmouth wasn't going to quit,'' said Penn coach Al Bagnoli.
``Dartmouth just doesn't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I also saw the first half as a good news-bad news thing,'' he
said. ``We played very well and were up only 10-0. I feel we should
have been up 21-0.''
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth got on the board eight minutes into the second half
when Mike Coffey rolled right and hit Damon Ferrara with a
26-yarder in the end zone. Alex Csizinszky kicked the point-after.
That score was set up by a 71-yard Wayne Schlobohm punt to the Penn
1, and a fierce defense that forced a poor Penn punt.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd went wild at 12:14 of the third when Coffey capped a
seven-play, 42-yard drive with an up-the-middle keeper from the 13.
The kick made it 14-10. A key play was a 17-yard pass from Coffey
to Ferrara.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our opportunities and played a great third quarter,''
said Darmouth coach John Lyons. ``It was a great effort by our
offense to come back like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Quakers took the lead again, 17-14, at 3:31 of the
fourth when Finn capped a 14-play, 61-yard drive from the 1, or
more accurately fourth and 6 inches. He carried five times for 18
yards on the drive and caught a pass for 7 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't tired at all in the first half (17 carries),'' said
Finn. ``I was a bit tired in the second half on that long drive.''
</P>
<P>
   On scoring the winner, which took two tries, Finn said, ``I
wasn't sure where the line of scrimmage was on the first carry. The
offensive line was great on the second. The line was great all
day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
