A4759 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NELSON-BOS &LR;      09-20 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NELSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM HELPED BY NELSON'S BACKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILTON, Mass. _ The speech wasn't in the ``Win one for the
Gipper'' category, but it wasn't bad. And more importantly, they
were buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You own them,'' Steve Nelson was telling his Curry College
team just before the second half of Saturday's game against Maine
Maritime. ``You're going to win the game. And you're going to do it
because you're a better team. But you've got to play smart. No
mistakes. No penalties. I want you to go and knock them on their
butts. Every time.''
</P>
<P>
   For Nelson, with a resume that includes a career as an All-Pro
linebacker for the Patriots as well as a second career as a media
personality on WEEI and on Patriots pre- and postgame reports, it
was as much hope as it was hunch.
</P>
<P>
   For so long, Curry football had a negative taint to it. But now,
a game and a half into his career as the Colonels coach, it was
time to take a step in a different direction.
</P>
<P>
   The Colonels could have been forgiven if they raised their
eyebrows just a little. After all, winning was something that had
not happened to a Curry football team for the past 17 games, dating
back two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The streak _ matching the longest in school history and the
fourth longest in Division 3 _ was one of the reasons Nelson had
soft-pedaled his desire to win for most of the early part of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't push them too hard,'' he told his assistants in their
pregame conference. ``We don't want to ruin their confidence if
something bad happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But in this home opener, with a party-like atmosphere
surrounding D. Forbes Will Field, not much bad was happening. Even
when they found themselves trailing at halftime, 8-6, Nelson and
his staff could sense a growing confidence in the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me 30 more minutes,'' Nelson told them. ``Thirty minutes
of football the way I know you can play and they're going to be
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it came to pass. Final Score: Curry 19, Maine Maritime 8.
</P>
<P>
   On the Richter Scale of college football results, it probably
wasn't even a blip on the chart. Division 3 football is a different
world from most games played on Saturday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   But in the world of Curry and Steve Nelson it was one of those
moments that you savor, from the opening minutes to the obligatory
water container shower Nelson received from his players with 33
seconds left, when the victory finally was secure.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson had spent most of the early part of his day being Nellie,
which is less fire and brimstone and more easygoing nice guy, which
characterized his career with the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the morning joking with his assistants, all part-time
employees doing this more for fun than for fame or fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different,'' said Nelson, sitting around an equipment
room/coaches office just off the Curry locker room earlier in the
morning. ``There are so many little things that you just don't
factor in. Like one day in practice, one of my players comes up to
me and says, `Coach, someone stole my spikes.' I was kind of
surprised that something like that could happen and I asked him why
would anyone want to steal his shoes and he said it wasn't the
shoes. Someone had actually taken the spikes off the shoes and
stolen them.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour before kickoff, Nelson was on the phone,
trying to find a rental car agency that could provide
transportation after the game for Maine Maritime coach Mike
Hodgson.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson came to Curry on a whim. After his Patriot playing days,
he had spent a year as an assistant with New England in the
pre-Bill Parcells/Pete Carroll era, but then had gone off into
other areas, primarily radio and television duties.
</P>
<P>
   But he still wanted to get into coaching. He asked around and
through some friends had an interview set up with Curry president
Ken Quigley. ``It was supposed to be a short introductory
conversation,'' said Quigley with a smile. ``And it turned into a
three-hour luncheon. Steve is perfect for this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson brought in other ``volunteers,'' such as former Patriot
teammate Ronnie Lippett to coach the defensive backs and former NFL
offensive lineman Jim Rourke. Other friends and acquaintances soon
joined ranks, including former Curry coach John Doherty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a long way to come,'' said Nelson, who lost his opener
at Norwich two weeks ago. ``But you can see the attitude starting
to change. They're starting to believe in the things we want to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the belief was given a big-time booster shot. The
defense, urged on by the vocal support of defensive coordinator
Mark Pizziferri, came up with three turnovers in the second half,
and Curry first had the lead and then a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys played like men today,'' said Nelson, gripping a game
ball presented to him by his team. ``You overcame a lot of
adversity to get here. Today was the first of many (wins).''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was over _ for the moment. Nelson shook hands, posed for
pictures, signed autographs, and made his way back to the locker
room, stopping for a postgame hamburger provided by the father of a
Maine Maritime player.
</P>
<P>
   In the coaches room, sitting around over a bucket of chicken and
some cold beverages, Nelson looked around with a smile of
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' he said quietly. ``Tomorrow at 4:30. We'll look at tape
of Framingham State.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
