<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4809 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     09-20 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Sept. 27.)  
 (HLW)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; TOWARD THE END OF TIME &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By John Updike. Fawcett Columbine, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Walden'' gone haywire is the spiritual journal of a
ruthlessly intelligent narrator, 66-year-old Ben Turnbull, who
lives in a bourgeois country mansionette and is given to making
flinty observations about nature and philosophy. The novel,
selected by the editors of the Book Review as one of the best books
of 1997, dwells on both the world of the next century and the
wandering of Ben's wits. ``As memento mori and its obverse, carpe
diem, `Toward the End of Time' could scarcely be bettered,''
Margaret Atwood said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOYHOOD: SCENES FROM PROVINCIAL LIFE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By J.M. Coetzee. Penguin, $11.95.
</P>
<P>
   The South African novelist, growing up in a middle-class
Afrikaner household near Cape Town in the 1940s and '50s, was
racked by guilt and fear, and developed an intense sensitivity to
the brutal transactions of power in his tormented country. Last
year our reviewer, Rand Richards Cooper, called this a ``terse,
gritty memoir'' by an author with ``a special gift for dread.'' The
same publisher has reissued a characteristically disturbing novel
by Coetzee,  &UR; AGE OF IRON &LR;  ($12.95), which focuses on a terminally
ill professor who awakens to her complicity with the crumbling
apartheid regime and the rage of a new generation of black youth.
The story ``emerges from its smoky, apocalyptic images as a finely
wrought prophecy ... whose truths cut to the bone,'' Lawrence
Thornton wrote here in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ABUSE OF POWER: THE NEW NIXON TAPES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Stanley I. Kutler. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $17.
</P>
<P>
   In these transcripts of 201 hours of Oval Office tapes released
in 1996, it becomes perfectly clear that Watergate indeed emerged
from Nixon's vindictiveness and that he and his advisers were
strictly amateurs as crooks. ``It makes for spellbinding reading,
and plunges us back into that sordid, astonishing world like
nothing else,'' Joseph Finder said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PEACEABLE KINGDOM: STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Francine Prose. Owl/Holt, $12.
</P>
<P>
   There is little peace on display in these 11 mordant forays into
the weird jungle of modern life, but several uneasy truces between
characters who are eager to feel something even if they're not sure
what it should be. In 1993 in the Book Review, Ron Carlson called
this ``a smartly observed, deftly written book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA: PEOPLE AND EMPIRE, 1552-1917 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Geoffrey Hosking. Harvard University, $16.95.
</P>
<P>
   A historian argues that the building of the Russian Empire
impeded the growth of a strong national identity. In other words,
Russians have difficulty feeling Russian unless they rule others.
``The problem Mr. Hosking raises is not new, but he is the first to
explore it in depth,'' Richard Pipes said here last year.  &UR; RUSSIA'S
WAR &LR; , by Richard Overy (Penguin, $14.95), maintains that the
crucial Soviet victory over Nazi Germany was due to the tough
Russian spirit, forged by a bitter climate, harsh working
conditions and Stalin's purges. Earlier this year our reviewer,
Chris Patsilelis, called this a ``penetrating and compassionate
book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GROOMING, GOSSIP, AND THE EVOLUTION OF LANGUAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Robin Dunbar. Harvard University, $14.
</P>
<P>
   We are a species of chatterers and snoops, a psychology
professor asserts, and gossip is the human version of primate
grooming -- in fact, without it we might never have bothered to
become social creatures. This is a ``fresh and witty book,''
Natalie Angier wrote here last year. ``Dunbar is a clear thinker
and a polymath.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MAGICIAN'S TALE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By David Hunt. Berkley, $7.50.
</P>
<P>
   In this eerie thriller, written pseudonymously by William Bayer,
a color-blind art photographer combs San Francisco by night to find
the killer of a street hustler who was her only friend. The
heroine's surreal perspective ``shows us light and dark, truth and
deception, reality and illusion ... in ways we never imagined,''
Marilyn Stasio wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BODY PROJECT: AN INTIMATE HISTORY OF AMERICAN GIRLS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Joan Jacobs Brumberg. Vintage, $13.
</P>
<P>
   In presenting 100 years of adolescent true confessions and media
images, the author shows how the concerns of American girls and
their response to their bodies reflect larger cultural changes.
``This is the kind of glorious inside dope that your history
teacher never told you,'' Peggy Orenstein said here last year.
``Women and girls should read this fine book together.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOMEWHERE OFF THE COAST OF MAINE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ann Hood. Picador USA, $12.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne, Elizabeth and Claudia are three ex-hippies whose
impulsive behavior in the 1980s is shaped by their experiences in
the late '60s. The Vietnam War era is ``vividly captured ... in
this accomplished'' first novel, Mary-Ann Tirone Smith wrote here
in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OCEAN OF WORDS: STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ha Jin. Vintage International, $12.
</P>
<P>
   These tales by a Chinese poet and veteran of the Chinese army
are set along China's border with Russia in the 1970s and feature
soldiers struggling to keep their humanity within the confines of
Maoist ideology. In 1996 our reviewer, Andy Solomon, called the
stories ``powerful in their unity of theme and rich in their
diversity of styles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
