   CLINTON PACKAGE:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RDP (Washington) _ Lede-all. Developments and talk
shows; mostly congressional comments in advance of videotape
release. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCENE (Washington) _ Nothing is quite the same for
Clinton and his senior aides, advisers and friends these days. They
make little pretense that the White House is other than a shaken,
static place, groping for a way to survive. By Todd S. Purdum. 1300
words.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BLACKCAUCUS (Washington) _ As his troubles mount in
advance of Monday's videotape release, Clinton makes his only major
public appearance this weekend with the Congressional Black Caucus,
whose members stand unwavering beside him. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HILLARY (Washington) _ Her friends put out the word that
she's not yet ready to forgive her husband. But that doesn't mean
she's not ready to combat the political mess he left in his wake.
By Elaine Sciolino. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLICY (Washington) _ U.S. foreign policy during
the Monica scandal. By Philip Shenon. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TV-TAPE (Undated) _ A look at how television plans to
present the videotape. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JEWS-REACT (Undated) _ Reaction among Jewish community
to release of videotape on Rosh Hashana.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   MEDSCHOOL-ELDERLY (Baltimore) _ A new approach to geriatrics at
Johns Hopkins Medical School has students making house calls and
taking the time to get to know patients. It is far from the high
technology approach to patients usually emphasized in modern
medical training; yet it is a part of what is regarded as the
cutting edge training in geriatrics that is required of all
residents in internal medicine at Hopkins. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   AMERINDIAN-TOURISM (Umatilla Reservation, Ore.) _ American
Indian reservations, long considered economic deserts amidst a
landscape of general prosperity, are finding that they have a lot
more to offer the world than casinos and art galleries _ they have
their homes, their backyards, their stories. Visitors, especially a
growing number of Europeans, are traveling to some of the country's
most remote places, like this Indian reservation in central Oregon,
in search of life many Americans overlook on their vacations. By
Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
