A4894 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-LIBRARY-ART-5     09-20 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-LIBRARY-ART-510(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BRITISH LIBRARY WINS OVER CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SARAH LYALL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ ``As far as history, there is no history here,'' said
Doris Fletcher, speaking of the new British Library, the sparkling,
soaring building that recently opened near King's Cross to replace
the old library, which oozed tradition in the heart of Bloomsbury.
``We are starting from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   What Miss Fletcher and others who hold the sought-after reader's
passes to the new library's reading rooms have been pondering since
their surprisingly emotional move across town is this: How do you
weigh history against efficiency? What is better, fading glamour
(and the ghosts of Karl Marx and Virginia Woolf) or modernistic
beauty and a fighting chance of getting the book you need in an
hour, instead of three days?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tradition and history might be helpful,'' said Andrew Wyllie,
who uses the library to study gender in postwar British theater.
``But to have the space to work and easy access to the papers and
books you need is infinitely better.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyllie (pronounced WHY-lee) was full of trepidation about the
move, which has been taking place in stages since last fall. He
loved the atmosphere at the old library, which occupied a number of
rooms in the British Museum. He loved the majestic dome in the
Round Reading Room, where he did most of his research and where
Dickens, Thackeray and George Bernard Shaw did much of their
research, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a great shame to abandon a purpose-built
library like the one in Bloomsbury,'' he said the other day as he
left the Humanities Reading Room, the replacement for the old Round
Reading Room, in the new library. ``This could have turned into a
disaster. But it's infinitely better. It's light. It's comfortable.
It's cool. And most importantly, it takes an average of an hour
between ordering and getting a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyllie and the library's thousands of other readers were
understandably worried about the new building, which during the 36
years and $843 million from conception to completion often seemed
on its way to becoming one of the biggest white elephants London
had ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   The library had been buffeted over the years by changing public
tastes, cost overruns, horrendous delays and a cacophony of
complaints, including Prince Charles' sneering dismissal several
years ago when he asked: ``How can you tell it is a library? It has
no character to suggest it is a great public building.''
</P>
<P>
   But the project has undergone an almost complete reversal of
fortune in the last couple of years, and it opened to glorious
reviews. (Parts of the library opened last fall, others in the
spring; the official opening was in the summer.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The library is, quite simply, awesome; a great public building
that graces its surroundings, provides us with a unique resource
and even offers a new rendezvous for lovers in London,'' wrote the
usually skeptical author Will Self in The Times of London in May.
He said it made him feel young again. ``Trust me _ say to her/him:
`Meet me at the British Library in King's Cross.' And everything
will go swimmingly.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mostly Praise, for the Interior
</P>
<P>
   Visitors have embraced the much-maligned architecture, although
the consensus still seems to be that the red-brick exterior fails
to do justice to the building's glorious interior. ``There's no
real denying that the outside of the building looks like a Tesco,''
said the writer Alain de Botton, referring to one of Britain's
largest supermarket chains.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the architect, Colin St. John Wilson, feels more than
vindicated by the positive response. Prince Charles took a private
tour of the library and was very encouraging (although he failed to
publicly air his compliments, an omission that most likely
irritated Wilson, who attributed his decision last year to close
his design company to the public criticism he had endured over the
library).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the building is beginning to speak for itself,'' said
Wilson, caught by chance the other day as he took some friends on a
tour of his building. ``I never had a doubt, but all the same, it
was a bit like someone coming and spitting in your face. What has
been most gratifying is the way people come up to me and say they
loved the old library and dreaded coming here, and now this is
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense of history tells me that the British always do this
to architects,'' he said. ``Wren was put on half pay and sacked
before he finished St. Paul's,'' he said, speaking of Sir
Christopher Wren. ``And that also took 36 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone has been impressed by the imagination and
attention to detail within the building. ``It's a wonderful space,
devoted entirely to a library,'' said the author Lady Antonia
Fraser. ``I think if a library works as a library, that's the
important thing. You don't necessarily have to sit there thinking,
`I'm part of a great tradition.' You would do better to think about
your own work.''
</P>
<P>
   Enormous Spaces, Online Service
</P>
<P>
   One quality that the new library has in spades is space. The
public spaces are enormous, rising up over several levels with
surprising turns and features on each one. Of the four reading
rooms (divided into 11 discrete ``reading areas''), the most
spectacular is the Humanities Reading Room, built on three levels
and lighted, as much of the rest of the building is, by daylight
filtered through the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   The artificial lights inside adjust automatically to the amount
of daylight coming in. And, as befits a building devoted to the
written word, there are modern, well-run exhibition galleries to
replace the rather haphazard rooms that used to make up the library
in the British Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can see one of the four original Magna Cartas, a
Gutenberg Bible and the Diamond Sutra, which dates to A.D. 868 and
is said to be the oldest surviving printed book. They can hear,
using headphones set up around the room, thrilling audio snippets,
including James Joyce reading a passage from ``Finnegans Wake'' and
the earliest known tape of a bird call, from 1889.
</P>
<P>
   And in the exhibition ``Turning the Pages,'' they can
electronically read, for instance, a complete Leonardo da Vinci
notebook, putting their hands on a special computer screen that
flips from one page to another, magnifies and explains key
passages, and even shows what the passages would look like if they
were written the right way around rather than in Leonardo's
trademark mirror writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the old viewing rooms were gloriously jumbled and musty,
the new setting is as sleek and efficient as the inside of an IBM
mainframe,'' wrote Stephen Amidon in The Sunday Times of London
recently. ``The average viewer will find it lends ready access to
items so canonical as to be otherwise unapproachable.''
</P>
<P>
   In the reading rooms, new technology has arrived with a
vengeance. Instead of using the old card catalogs _ thousands of
entries printed out and pasted, quite quaintly, into thick books _
readers order their books from a computer that can tell them if,
for instance, the book they want is already checked out.
</P>
<P>
   When books arrive, delivered by a mechanized system that sends
them from deep within the library on a conveyor belt, readers are
alerted by lights flashing at their desks. The whole thing seems a
great deal easier, even to traditionalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is online and the service is much more efficient,''
said Patricia Demers, a Canadian who has worked in the library for
nearly 20 years, researching English writing in the 16th and 17th
centuries. ``I still yearn for the old creaks, though, and the old
leather-bound printed catalogs. It's just nostalgia, really.''
</P>
<P>
   A Place to Work, Not Gossip
</P>
<P>
   The hardest change to get used to, it seems, is in ambiance. The
new reading rooms seem colder to some, as if intimacy and
weightiness had been lost along with tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Some people don't like the fact that the desks seem smaller and
that there are no partitions separating readers. Others grumble
that readers are now allowed to use personal computers (there are
no-computer areas reserved for people who object particularly
strongly). And every reader is worried that the library, running at
a deficit, might have to start charging for reader's passes.
</P>
<P>
   The writer David Lodge misses the old ways. ``I've been
convinced that the new facilities in the library and the ability to
store books safely are a huge improvement over what the old library
could offer,'' he said. ``But I have great nostalgic affection for
the old reading room and fond associations and memories of it. It
was a superb space, and there was something sort of majestic and
appropriate about that great dome, which the more utilitarian
design of the modern building _ though it's elegant and
high-quality _ doesn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miss Fletcher said its aura sometimes worked against the old
library, particularly in the reading room devoted to rare books,
where she does her research. The old one, she said, was a
``genteel, exclusive place'' that was used by some people as little
more than a private club.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to come in, not to work, but to gossip and
complain,'' she said. ``In the new library, I don't know why, but
they have disappeared, thank goodness. Now I can sit and put my
nose in my book and study.'' (The old reading room and other spaces
will be absorbed by the British Museum.)
</P>
<P>
   In the end, efficiency has won over sentiment. ``I never
understood the mythology of the old library,'' de Botton said. ``It
was extremely inconvenient in terms of getting a book, with all the
endless bits of paper shuffling around. The old room was fantastic,
but it wasn't efficient. When you do research, at the end of the
day, what makes something beautiful is whether or not it works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
