<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4899 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEEPTHROAT-MEDIA-840&AMP;     09-20 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEEPTHROAT-MEDIA-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR QUESTIONS THE EXISTENCE OF `DEEP THROAT' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man known as Deep Throat is a singular figure in American
culture, credited with being the source of explosive articles
written by the reporters Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein as they
unraveled the Nixon administration's abuses of power. Named for a
pornographic movie, this furtive truth-teller may be the first
pseudonymous American hero not conceived in a comic book.
</P>
<P>
   Unmasking the man who met Bob Woodward in underground garages in
the book and the film version of ``All the President's Men'' has
been an intermittent journalistic quest.
</P>
<P>
   Now David Obst, the former literary agent for Woodward and
Bernstein, writes in a new book that Deep Throat was a composite, a
plot device to fit the narrative needs of the book and the film.
Deep Throat's information was often bad, Obst said, and his
melodramatic warnings that Woodward and Bernstein's lives were in
danger were fantastical.
</P>
<P>
   What a way to get people talking. Obst, who has been a Hollywood
screenwriter, writes in his book ``Too Good to Be Forgotten,'' that
Deep Throat ``has still not come forward to be hailed as a great
American hero. He can't, because he does not exist.'' Deep Throat,
he writes, was not mentioned in the original book proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The thinly defended claim is a minor part of ``Too Good to Be
Forgotten.'' In an interview, Obst said, ``I am not a Watergate
scholar.'' But renewing questions about Deep Throat, in a year of
another wrenching presidential crisis and of numerous journalistic
missteps, is likely to get more buzz than the author's adventures
as a protester at the 1968 Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   Obst's claim is less important than his real contributions, such
as supporting the journalist Seymour Hersh's efforts to bring the
My Lai massacre to light when Obst was head of the Dispatch News
Service. But it is a better sound bite.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward, asked about Obst's claims, said, ``Everybody should
have their say.'' He added, ``We are in a culture where everyone
who was at some event becomes an insider with a theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Obst was in a hotel across town. He never saw the drafts
of the book. He was never consulted.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward added that Obst ``was using his standing as our former
agent to say this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately you would think, `He's an insider, close to
everything, involved in everything.' He wasn't,'' Woodward said.
</P>
<P>
   Obst is now a visiting scholar in religious studies at the
University of California at Santa Barbara. He said he wanted his
say, 24 years after the book came out, because ``if there wasn't a
Deep Throat, a great disservice has been done to a generation of
kids who got into journalism for the wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got angry,'' he added in an interview, ``because I went back
and watched ``All the President's Men.'' And I said to myself,
``Here's a whole generation of kids who believes that the United
States government went after Carl and Bob. I think it's just wrong
to make a group of kids think that the government does things like
that. We have so much cynicism in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being cynical about the government, he is cynical
about journalists. Obst, when asked about his evidence for saying
the two reporters engaged in manipulative deception, said: ``I do
not have a smoking gun. But I have a lot of hot pistols.''
</P>
<P>
   These include the difficulty of seeing from the street the
apartment balcony where Woodward kept the flowerpot used to signal
his need for a meeting with his source. He also said that another
of his clients, John Dean, flatly denied Deep Throat's report that
President Nixon personally threatened Dean.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the dramatic contours of the book and the film have
been called distorted by those with front-row seats on the early
coverage of the Watergate scandal. Barry Sussman, the former city
editor of The Washington Post who wrote ``The Great Coverup'' said
in an interview: ``The importance of The Washington Post in the
Nixon demise was exaggerated. It served a clear and important role,
just not as much of a role as was given it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe the myth that Deep Throat was so important,''
he added, ``there was not much to what we did except being
stenographers.'' Still, Sussman does believe that this ``bit
player'' was real.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's irritation at his old friend Obst is clear.
``Probably David was at his best when he was on acid,'' he said
acidly. (In the book, Obst writes that he had been fed a
hallucinogenic drug just before he persuaded the former Simon &AMP;
Schuster editor Richard Snyder to buy ``All the President's Men.'')
</P>
<P>
   Woodward added that Obst ``only raised one good point: Why don't
we know now, so many years later, who it is?''
</P>
<P>
   At a separate moment, he said: ``I would love to tell you who
the source is. But the arrangement is no. I can't and I'm not going
to'' until the source releases Woodward from his pledge of
confidentiality, or dies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Given the hunger of news outlets for audiences, the controversy
attendant on Obst's debunking of Deep Throat may be irresistible.
Like a spaceship using a large planet's gravity as a slingshot,
accelerating it to speeds it could not achieve on its own, Obst
gets a boost from the sheer heft of the history he sets out to
amend. That he makes only a glancing effort to prove his case will
probably matter little.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the short chapter containing these claims, Obst
said, ``The basic concern regarding Deep Throat, however, is best
stated by Friedrich Nietzsche, who warned us that those who fight
monsters should see to it that in the process they do not become
monsters themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   As less profound minds have said, ``Right backatcha.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
