<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING OF REEKING: LOUD MUSIC STINKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are a lot of things you can get at Seattle's Bumbershoot
Festival besides an acute hearing disorder.
</P>
<P>
   You can learn about art, poetry, nutrition and history. And that
is true despite the fact I was not able to purchase a 40-clove
garlic chicken sandwich from The Stinking Rose on Labor Day
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there were other food vendors shoveling out garlic by the
bushel. And with each bite, garlic lovers learned a bit more about
art, literature, nutrition and history. Culture was oozing out our
pores.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when I purchased my garlic chicken sandwich from
The Stinking Rose booth, I also received a garlic fact sheet from
the San Francisco eatery of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   I learned that the prophet Mohammed recommended garlic as a cure
for snake and scorpion bites. Laborers who built the pyramids were
fueled by radishes, onions and garlic. And garlic was entombed with
King Tut, along with a jillion dollars worth of jewels.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient Greeks believed garlic promoted supernatural powers.
The residents of Transylvania swear that garlic wards off vampires.
Our colonial ancestors put garlic in the shoes of whooping cough
sufferers. Other adherents insist garlic improves the voice, the
intellect, the complexion and the union of fractured bones and
kills intestinal worms.
</P>
<P>
   What I really wanted to know during Bumbershoot weekend is
whether garlic does anything for the kind of temporary deafness
caused by electric guitars amplified by speakers the size of cargo
containers.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, recipes like these might help.
</P>
<P>
   King Tut's Chicken
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 pounds chicken pieces, skinned
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 grinding of black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 cups plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   One-and-one-half teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   One-and-one-half teaspoons turmeric
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   Rub the chicken pieces with garlic, oregano and pepper. Combine
remaining ingredients in a large bowl. Add chicken and moosh around
until all the pieces are covered with some of the marinade. Cover
and refrigerate for a day.
</P>
<P>
   After 24 hours, if the hungry customers are still standing in
line, heat the oven to 350 degrees. Remove chicken pieces from
marinade and place in single layer of a large oven dish or pan.
Cover with foil and bake 30 minutes. Remove foil, turn pieces and
bake 30 minutes more, basting occasionally, until lightly browned.
Serves four to six.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic-chicken Fried Rice
</P>
<P>
   One-half pound fillet of chicken breast
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup low-fat ham, cut into thin sticks
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cooked white rice, cooled
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, cut into thin sticks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup frozen peas
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced ginger root
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 green onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   Combine the broth, soy sauce and vinegar in a small bowl and
will somebody please turn down that infernal hi-fi? You can't
properly eat or cook Chinese food within five city blocks of an
electric guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a pot of water to a boil. Put the carrot sticks in a sieve
and immerse in the hot water for 30 seconds. Remove and drain. Put
the peas in the same sieve and dunk into the boiling water for 10
seconds. Remove and drain. Add some salt to the boiling water and
drop in the chicken breast. Reduce heat and poach the chicken until
the meat is no longer pink inside when sliced in half. Remove and
cut into cubes.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a large skillet or wok over medium-high heat. Add the oil,
then toss in the ham sticks and stir-fry for a minute or so. Add
the garlic and ginger and cook 15 seconds. Add the rice, green
onions and carrot. Cook 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pour in the beaten egg in a thin stream and stir. Add the
soy-vinegar sauce. When the rice has absorbed most of the liquid,
stir in the chicken and peas. Stir-cook another 30 seconds until
hot. Serves four.
</P>
<P>
   As they say around the Stinking Rose: ``It's chic to reek!''
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the
Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
