<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FALLSEASON-MEDIA-9     09-20 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALLSEASON-MEDIA-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NETWORKS UNDER MORE PRESSURE AS SEASON BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BILL CARTER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For network programming executives, the start of a new
television season is always intense because the stakes are so high.
But to hear them tell it, the debuts of 36 new series this season
have become something akin to the landing on Omaha Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like the opening scene of `Private Ryan,''' said
Warren Littlefield, the president of NBC Entertainment. ``You have
to keep your head down and move carefully and with consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving forward is what the season, which officially begins
Monday night, is all about for the six networks now squeezing shows
onto the already densely crowded landing area of prime time.
Crunched by escalating costs for programming and the drift of
viewers to cable channels and other entertainment choices, the
executives in charge of programming recognize the urgent need to
show some sign of momentum.
</P>
<P>
   That may be all that determines the condition of their networks
when the ultimate tally of the success or failure of this season is
made next June by advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Last June they committed about $6.5 billion to the network
prime-time schedules being introduced this month, but that was
little or no increase over the previous year. It was, however,
considered a good showing in light of the widespread expectations
that the networks, with their ever-declining audience shares, would
finally start to see some fall-off in their annual take from
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   As the new season begins, concerns about where the business is
heading are everywhere. One senior network executive, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said: ``I've told people at the network
that the next 18 months will be the ugliest in the history of this
business. What there is in the air is desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   The desperation, the executive said, is reflected in deals like
the $13 million an episode Time Warner's Warner Bros. was able to
get NBC to pay for more episodes of ``E.R.,'' television's biggest
hit _ as well as by the fact that of the six networks spending
millions on programs to catch the increasingly diverted attention
of viewers, only one, NBC, a unit of General Electric, has been
taking in significant profits.
</P>
<P>
   But even NBC announced cost-cutting measures last week,
including 200 to 300 layoffs because of an anticipated drop in the
$500 million the network made in profit last year.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the enormous price increase for ``E.R.'' (NBC had only
been paying about $2 million an episode for the series) NBC faces
its first season in almost a decade without ``Seinfeld.'' It also
will not have the World Series or Super Bowl this season as it did
last. All of which is reason for Littlefield to assert that if NBC
holds its own this season, it will be ``a remarkable achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC had an enormous margin over any other network in terms of
both the total viewers and the 18-to-49-year-old group that
dominates most television advertising budgets, so even finishing
flat for the year would mean the network had a successful year.
</P>
<P>
   For every other network, however, a flat year will not be good
enough. ``Improvement'' is the word most used by the executives
responsible for the prime-time schedule this season. Publicly they
are trying to bury that erosion story. Three network program
executives _ Stu Bloomberg at ABC, Leslie Moonves at CBS and Peter
Roth at Fox _ said, more or less, that there is no way they won't
be better this season.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg predicted flatly that Walt Disney's ABC, which has
slid sharply the last three seasons, will end the season up from
last season, citing the earlier start of ``Monday Night Football,''
which gives it three hours of prime time; the reconstruction of
Sunday night around two shows, ``20/20'' and ``The Practice,''
instead of a movie, and enhanced programs on Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly Moonves went out on a limb, saying CBS will
``definitely do better'' among the younger viewer categories
important to advertisers _ an area where that network has suffered
in recent years. He cited the network's acquisition of professional
football, a new Monday lineup of shows, and ``Martial Law,'' about
a Chinese police officer who is a martial arts expert, which he
hopes will be a cult hit on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Roth noted that Fox, a subsidiary of News Corp., will have the
World Series and Super Bowl this season. His plan for improvement
also includes establishing some new comedies, especially ``That
'70s Show'' on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no network is more confident of improving fortunes than
WB, which made major strides last season by introducing ``Dawson's
Creek,'' a hit with teen-agers. Jamie Kellner, that network's chief
executive, said, ``We've had a three-year record of growth, 63
percent in audience over that time and we think we'll easily keep
that up this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons: ``Felicity,'' the season's most highly
publicized new series, which is expected to score another bulls-eye
with that network's youthful target audience.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the other would-be new network, UPN, whose
president, Dean Valentine, said, ``The goal is to change the trend
line and get it pointing upward.'' He is counting on dramas like
``Legacy'' and ``Seven Days'' to change the image of the struggling
UPN _ a joint venture of Viacom and Chris-Craft, which he said,
``has gotten a reputation for being synonymous with bad programming
_ not a brand I'd like to develop.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the hope for hits springs eternal. The executives also know
that the business has to change in some fundamental ways. ``There
is a very serious quest to find a new economic model,'' said Jamie
Tarses, the president of ABC Entertainment. Mainly, she said, the
networks have to find programs that cost less.
</P>
<P>
   Finding ways to add new programs in summer has become a crusade
of sorts for Roth of Fox, who noted that the way networks introduce
shows, with a big glut in the fall, is a self-defeating
anachronism.
</P>
<P>
   Fox tried introducing more of its shows before this week with
mixed results. UPN has pushed most of its premieres off into
October. Some shows like ``The X-Files'' won't be back with new
episodes until November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
