<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-CONGRESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGED TO CONFRONT IMPEACHMENT PANEL
</HEADLINE>
 BC-  By ANDREW J. GLASS 
 c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A key Democratic senator called on President
Clinton Sunday to respond to the airing of his videotaped grand
jury testimony on Monday by going before Congress and directly
facing the question of whether he should be impeached for having
lied to the nation about his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' Sen. John Kerry of
Massachusetts, who is weighing his own run for the White House in
2000, said Clinton should ``rapidly'' explain to the House
Judiciary Committee ``exactly what he did and exactly what he was
thinking'' in triggering the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's vote and let's move on one way or the other,'' Kerry
added, ``but the nation is being ill served by this political water
torture that's taking place in a highly calculated, highly partisan
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry's call to lance the White House crisis by an early
confrontation Capitol Hill came as four cable news channels
prepared to run the full unfiltered footage of Clinton's Aug. 17
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN, CNN, the Fox News Channel and MSNBC each announced they
would show a complete tape of the testimony, which runs more than
four hours, simultaneously with its release, at about 9 a.m. (EDT).
</P>
<P>
   Along with the grand jury tape _ whose release marks a historic
turning point in the annals of politics and television _ the
Republican-led House panel voted to make public seven volumes of
supporting documentation.
</P>
<P>
   It will be uploaded to Internet sites, which already feature the
initial 445-page impeachment report to Congress by Kenneth Starr,
the independent counsel, and several rebuttals by Clinton's
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The new material becomes available even as 69 percent of
respondents to a CBS News poll released on Sunday said it was
unnecessary to make the videotape public and with 59 percent
feeling the House panel weighing impeachment acted to embarrass the
president.
</P>
<P>
   According to the CBS survey, 56 percent of Americans believe
Clinton should be censured by Congress, while 37 percent favor his
resignation _ a slight rise from last week's numbers. The poll had
an error margin of plus or minus four percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The new documents are expected to include:
</P>
<P>
   _ More evidence on Paula Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit
against Clinton, which led to the current presidential crisis.
</P>
<P>
   _ Transcripts of Lewinsky's appearances before the grand jury
and her roughly 20 interviews with the FBI, as well as a record of
her visits to the White House, the gifts she and the president
exchanged and the phone calls they made to one another.
</P>
<P>
   _ Excerpts from Lewinsky's personal diary and a detailed lab
analysis of the tests that identified the president's semen on
Lewinsky's navy blue dress.
</P>
<P>
   One of the president's chief defenders, White House deputy chief
of staff John Podesta, predicted on ``Meet the Press'' that this
fresh outpouring of evidence would disgust most Americans and spawn
a political backlash against the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They decided that rather than just doing a document dump, they
would do a garbage dump on Monday, and I think people are going to
wonder about that,'' Podesta said.
</P>
<P>
   As Starr noted in his original report, Clinton in his testimony
repeatedly falls back on a prepared statement that White House
lawyers have given to several news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Starr maintains was an overt act of perjury, Clinton told the
prosecutors and grand jurors:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was alone with Ms. Lewinsky on certain occasions in
early 1996 and once in early 1997, I engaged in conduct that was
wrong. These encounters did not consist of sexual intercourse, they
did not constitute sexual relations as I understood that term to be
defined at my January 17, 1998 [Jones'] deposition. But they did
involve inappropriate intimate contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``These inappropriate encounters ended at my insistence, in
early 1997. I also had occasional telephone conversations with Ms.
Lewinsky that included inappropriate sexual banter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that what began as friendship came to include this
conduct and I take full responsibility for my actions. While I will
provide the grand jury whatever other information I can, because of
privacy considerations affecting my family, myself and others and
in an effort to preserve the dignity of the office I hold, this is
all I will say about the specifics of these particular matters.''
 &UR; For use by clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
