<SLUG> BC-TECH-COLUMN-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET GYRATIONS CAUSE ANXIETY IN SILICON ALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JANET STITES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In contrast to politics, in the world of
entrepreneurs, going public has fabulously positive connotations.
Many founders of start-ups set their sights on taking their
companies public before even filing their incorporation papers.
</P>
<P>
   Going public is how their investors make back their money _ and,
hopefully, then some. It is how entrepreneurs achieve real wealth,
if only on paper. It is how they will be judged for years to come.
It is the consummate measure of business success or failure.
</P>
<P>
   So consider the anxiety of Silicon Alley entrepreneurs like Jack
Hidary, Todd Krizelman, Stephan Paternot and Alan Andreini. All
four run high-profile Internet companies that filed papers in the
summer with the Securities and Exchange Commission to go public.
All have, to this point, capitalized on the innovation and
excitement of the Internet and helped to define the amorphous New
York new-media industry that has come to be known as Silicon Alley.
</P>
<P>
   But as the stock market continues to vacillate, all these men
face a quandary: to go or not to go. They have arrived at the ball
only to discover that the orchestra is taking a break.
</P>
<P>
   In all, six new-media companies in the New York area have filed
for public offerings, including Hidary's Earthweb, Krizelman's and
Paternot's theglobe.com and Andreini's Interworld, plus two New
York companies, Multex and Net Grocer, and All-Tech Investment
Group of Montvale, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Under the SEC's quiet-period rules, the executives of those
companies are prohibited from discussing their situations, but
speculation in the Alley has been rampant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those that are in registration now will wait if they can do
so,'' predicted John Siracuse, vice president and head of East
Coast Internet banking for Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities.
``They don't want to be the first to test the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the go/no-go question, Siracuse observes,
is that the window of opportunity is diminishing as the holiday
season approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult for small-cap companies to get the investors'
attention between Thanksgiving and Christmas,'' he said. If
companies wait until the new year to go public, he continued, they
will have logistical issues, like having to update their
prospectuses, but more important, they will have to wrangle with
the perception that they were not ready to go public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perception is reality,'' he said. ``And there will be the
perception they couldn't get the deal done.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Cohen, head of Internet research at Merrill Lynch,
believes many companies will turn to mergers and acquisitions. He
notes that mergers and acquisitions have been increasing in the
last six to 12 months anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And while there have been virtually no technology offerings in
the last few weeks, Cohen said, ``The landscape for Internet IPOs
has shifted, but the window is still open for high-quality
companies with compelling business models _ models such as
community and e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors want to see properties with components of high
functionality and high intellectual property,'' he said, saying
that theglobe.com is an example of a community site where users
create a wealth of intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists see the recent correction in technology
stocks as a much-needed dose of reality.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hirschfeld, a principal at Patricof &AMP; Co. Ventures Inc.,
which has interests in Alley-based Medscape Inc. and New
Jersey-based Audible Inc., says that the current market has not
diminished his firm's interest in the Internet and new-media
start-ups. But, he added, ``It does have an impact on price
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The drop in the market, Hirschfeld says, brings a sense of
sanity to private market valuation.
</P>
<P>
   But it also leaves pre-public Silicon Alley companies in a
precarious position. If they are hard-pressed for cash, they may
have to turn to their original investors or go for a private
placement. They may have to pull their public offerings altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Siracuse adds that delayed initial public offerings can cause
problems back at the office. ``Employees who have other
opportunities may decide to leave the company,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A big issue for Silicon Alley is the fact that it is still being
judged by the number of successful public offerings. Each one is
tallied as younger companies continue to try to lure venture
capital from the West Coast, and to garner the respect of Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Siracuse agrees with Cohen that while the outlook may not be
peaches and cream, neither is it liver and onions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still an appetite for Internet stocks,'' he said.
``What the market needs is a high-profile Internet stock to go out
and do well.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock needs to sell out at its offering, Siracuse said, and
then continue to sell well in the after market.
</P>
<P>
   As for those companies that had already gone public, many
star-struck entrepreneurs and their option-holding employees found
out what their investors already knew: What goes up must come down.
Double Click Inc., an Internet advertising network and an Alley
favorite, watched its stock drop from more than $50 a share in July
to $23 last week. It closed Friday at $19.69.
</P>
<P>
   Double Click's chief competitor, 24/7 Media Inc., TFSM went
public in mid-August, opening at $18.50 and closing at $20.25. Last
week, its stock was selling below $12. It closed Friday at $11.56.
</P>
<P>
   Among other Alley stocks that saw their share prices drop into
single digits were N2K Inc., the owner of Music Boulevard, and
Cyber Shop Inc., an online mall.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Cohen, who has been following Silicon Alley companies
for the last three years, first as an analyst at Salomon Smith
Barney, then at the Union Bank of Switzerland, remains optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silicon Alley has come to be populated with good companies and
intelligent people and will continue to be a source of investment
ideas going forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Music to the ears of New York's high-technology entrepreneurs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
