</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA TALK: `E.R.' GAMBLE PAYS OFF; BARNICLE'S NEW DEFENSE;
MARRYING RICH  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After agreeing to pay $13 million an episode for ``E.R.,'' which
returns for a new season Thursday night, NBC may be feeling like
one of the patients on a gurney in the series. But it shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   From the very beginning, NBC was able to cash in on ``E.R.'' in
spectacular fashion, taking immediate advantage of a rare
opportunity to make advertisers pay for their own inability to
recognize a big hit when they see one.
</P>
<P>
   This is how it happened.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the year ``E.R.'' arrived to anchor NBC's Thursday
night lineup, CBS thought it had found the answer to breaching the
fortress of success NBC had built on Thursdays. ``L.A. Law,'' which
had faded badly, was coming off the air as NBC's 10 p.m. entry. CBS
had a new hospital drama called ``Chicago Hope,'' created by a new
television drama wunderkind, David Kelley, and decided to use it to
go after NBC on Thursday at 10.
</P>
<P>
   That June, during the so-called up-front season, when
advertisers decide how much money they will commit to the new
network prime-time schedules, based on how they estimate shows will
perform, advertising agency executives looked at the pilots for
``E.R.'' and ``Chicago Hope'' and could not decide which of them
had greater potential to emerge as a hit. Mainly they expected the
two doctor shows to cancel each other out, so they estimated that
neither would get more than 21 percent of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   NBC wanted to be paid for at least a 25 share _ 25 percent of
viewers watching in its time slot _ and when it could not get that
price, Don Ohlmeyer, the head of NBC's West Coast entertainment
division, made a daring decision. He refused to sell more than 40
percent of the commercial time in the show before the season began
_ an unheard-of figure in a business in which shows routinely sell
at least 80 percent of their time during the up-front season.
Ohlmeyer was betting that the time would be more valuable later if
``E.R.'' did hit that 25 share.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of that season, ``E.R.'' had eclipsed a 40 share.
Because NBC had retained more than half the commercial time left to
sell, it was able to charge prices commensurate with that level of
success. If advertisers had been willing to assign the show even a
25 share at the start, they would have enjoyed an enormous free
bonus audience.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, everyone knows what a hit ``E.R.'' is, and the
show is in huge demand with advertisers, so NBC sells almost all
the time in the show during the up-front season.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is also able to package sales in ``E.R.'' with sales in many
other shows, squeezing as much leverage as it can out of the status
of ``E.R.'' as the highest-rated show on television _ though $286
million a year (the cost for 22 episodes of ``E.R.'') represents an
awful lot of squeezing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Globe's Ex-Columnist Defends His Work
</P>
<P>
   Mike Barnicle, the former Boston Globe columnist, said Friday he
hoped to buy a full-page ad in the Globe to defend the
authenticity, if not the accuracy, of the 1995 column that led to
his forced resignation last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe has refused to run Barnicle's defense on its op-ed
page. ``It didn't bring anything new to the table,'' said Richard
Gulla, a spokesman for the newspaper, which is owned by New York
Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle's disputed 1995 column told the story of two boys _ one
white, one black, both with cancer _ who bonded at Children's
Hospital in Boston in 1994. He wrote that after the black child
died, the parents of the white boy sent his family a check for
$10,000. He quoted from a letter that accompanied the check. In
August, he said that a nurse had passed along the story and he had
never been in touch with the families.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Saturday, Gulla said: ``If you make up quotes
from people you've never met, that's fabrication. We do not allow
anyone to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle recently went to Springvale, Maine, to interview Pat
Shairs, whose son Joshua died of heart disease. At the Children's
Hospital's cardiology unit in 1987, Joshua befriended Lacey
Ringwelski, a girl from Wisconsin. Both were white. After Joshua's
death, Lacey's grandmother sent Joshua's parents a check for
$5,000, which they gave to a scholarship fund for nurses, according
to both families.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal Tribune in Biddeford, Maine, published an article
about Pat Shairs on Aug. 25; The Globe followed suit. In his new
defense, Barnicle avoids saying his 1995 column was about the
Shairses. But he quotes Pat Shairs saying, ``This is our story.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Felicity Barringer &QR;
</P>
<P>
   A Forbes List Maker Makes the List
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at Forbes ASAP's annual listing of the 100
wealthiest people in technology, which will be published Monday,
and you will learn some of the secrets of getting rich quick these
days. They include selling technology for the Internet and selling
things on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is marrying into Internet wealth. One of the 28
Internet executives on this year's list happens to be the husband
of the list maker.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Rutter, a senior editor at Forbes ASAP, who was in charge
of this year's list and the accompanying articles, is married to
Jim Clark, the 54-year-old co-founder of Netscape Communications
Corp. He is No. 28 on the list, with total assets of $412.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rutter, 44, an information-technology journalist, met Clark
in 1989 while he was still running Silicon Graphics Inc. and she
was editor of Upside Magazine. They married in 1990. She is now a
part-time staffer for ASAP, a bimonthly supplement to Forbes
magazine, working from the couple's homes in Silicon Valley and
Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rutter, whose job includes editing most of the magazine's
``list'' stories, says she no longer writes the kinds of in-depth
industry articles she used to because of the potential for
conflicts of interest. And she said the magazine is careful not to
involve her in stories even remotely related to any of her
husband's businesses. The ``Technology's Wealthiest'' list is an
exception, she said, because the facts speak for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy to be married to No. 28 on the list,'' Ms.
Rutter said in an interview from her California home. ``It's not a
bad position for a reporter to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list that Ms. Rutter compiled are the industry's old
guard, led once again by Bill Gates of Microsoft Corp., with a net
worth of nearly $59 billion, and his co-founder, Paul Allen, with
$16.98 billion. Among executives of Internet companies, Jeffrey
Bezos, of Amazon.com Inc., joined the billionaires' club at No. 9
with $2.14 billion, along with David Filo of Yahoo, No. 15 with a
little over $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While the Internet may be hot, it should be noted that the
Forbes ASAP list was calculated on Aug. 3, well before the market's
huge slide. As of last week, the net worth of the group of 28
Internet executives was down $1.8 billion since the calculations
were made. And, yes, that means Ms. Rutter's net worth is down,
too.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laurie J. Flynn &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
