<HEADLINE>
STAR TREK FANS TAKE NOTE: THE FUTURE MAY BE HERE 
PERSONALIZING A BOOK WITH A GIVER'S PHOTO
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Fans of the television show ``Star Trek'' know that one of the
wonders of the science-fiction future is the starship sensor. With
it, crew members can detect the exact location of living bodies on
a planet they are orbiting. If mankind does someday develop those
fantastic sensors, they might have their roots in inventions of
today.
 &HT;    A German inventor has patented a device that uses
electromagnetic signals to detect the presence of living bodies.
The invention is intended to help find people buried by rubble in
earthquakes or other disasters, like the many who were trapped in
the recent bombings of American embassies in Africa.
 &HT;    Gerd Jurgen Schmidt, from Frankfurt, intends for his invention
to replace both search-and-rescue dogs, which cannot distinguish
between survivors and the dead, and listening devices, which cannot
pinpoint unconscious victims.
 &HT;    In his patent, Schmidt says, ``Living bodies generally
surprisingly influence high-frequency electromagnetic signals, even
over relatively long distances, by virtue of their heartbeat and
respiratory activity.'' For human beings, the influences fall in a
characteristic frequency range.
 &HT;    Schmidt designed a diode direct receiver to pick up and
demodulate, or convert, the electromagnetic signals emanating from
human bodies. The system works like the method used to send and
receive television signals, transmitting signals through the air
and recapturing them. At the end of the process a monitor displays
heart and lung activity.
 &HT;    Schmidt says his device can detect up to four people buried in
one spot and can pick up heart and lung signals up to three yards
away. He received patent 5,790,032.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Books are a popular gift, and many gift givers personalize a
book by writing an inscription or dedication inside the cover. Marc
Salzberger, an inventor in Middle Village, N.Y., thinks givers and
receivers would enjoy the gift even more if givers could add their
pictures or favorite photos to the book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Salzberger has patented a process that lets a book buyer add a
portrait and an inscription to the jacket when buying a book.
</P>
<P>
   A bookstore would install a camera, a computer and a printer.
Publishers would supply the store with software to use in creating
the jacket covers of books. The jacket designs would include blank
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   After selecting a book, a customer would pose for a video or
still camera, and the picture would then be scanned into the
computer. Or a buyer could bring in existing pictures, like old
family photos or school portraits, or substitute a drawing made on
an electronic pad.
</P>
<P>
   The customer could also type a caption to accompany the photo.
Then the book-jacket data would be entered into the computer and
the buyer's chosen artwork would be added to the book jacket. The
jacket would be printed and wrapped around the book.
</P>
<P>
   Salzberger received patent 5,782,598.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
