<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: CYBILL SINGS; OZAWA'S 25TH; KIDMAN IN LONDON;
HONORING CASANOVA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Great Britain, Italy)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She used to be ``Cybill.'' Now she's Cybill again.
Leaving behind the sitcom and the little screen, Cybill Shepherd
will appear in the flesh in a singing, storytelling cabaret
engagement beginning Tuesday night and continuing through Oct. 4
high over Manhattan at Rainbow and Stars. In her first such New
York appearance since 1994, Ms. Shepherd will reminisce in a light
vein about her 30-year career as model and movie and television
star, offering up standards like ``Tennessee Waltz,'' ``Walkin' the
Dog,'' ``But Not for Me'' and ``St. Louis Blues.'' Information:
(212) 632-5000.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Servings
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years have passed since Seiji Ozawa became music
director of the Boston Symphony Orchestra. In anticipation of his
silver anniversary and the orchestra's 118th season, which is to
begin on Wednesday, subscribers were asked what music they would
most like the maestro to conduct again. The answer: Beethoven's
Ninth. Not only will the symphony open the season, it will also be
performed by Ozawa and the orchestra again on Sunday in a free
concert at 4 p.m. on the Boston Common.
</P>
<P>
   Romance
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Kidman makes her London stage debut Tuesday night at the
Donmar Warehouse, playing not one but five roles. If the movie
star's presence was not enough to focus attention on the 250-seat
theater, the vehicle happens to be a piece written by David Hare
and directed by Sam Mendes, fresh off his New York triumph with
``Cabaret.'' The play, ``The Blue Room,'' is Hare's modern take on
``La Ronde,'' by Arthur Schnitzler. The co-star with Ms. Kidman in
the two-actor play is Iain Glen. Information: 011-44-171-369-1732.
</P>
<P>
   Venetian Roue
</P>
<P>
   As everybody knows, love's magic spell is everywhere, and these
days it is notably potent in Venice, where the 200th anniversary of
the death of that immortal libertine, aristocrat and adventurer
Giovanni Giacomo Casanova de Seingalt has inspired an exhibition at
Ca' Rezzonico, the Museum of the Venetian 18th century. Running
through Jan. 10, the show, ``The World of Giacomo Casanova: A
Venetian in Europe, 1725-1798,'' attempts to evoke the spirit and
style of his time.
</P>
<P>
   It is divided into themes suggested by Casanova's life: Europe
and its great cities, 18th-century Venice, European courts, science
and alchemy, theater, gambling and, of course, seduction. Paintings
by artists of the day, including Watteau, Boucher, Fragonard and
the Venetian masters Canaletto, Longhi and Guardi illustrate these
themes. In addition, jewelry, furnishings and documents illuminate
the era. Information: 011-39-041-520-4036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
