<P>
   THE CLINTON CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-UN _ NEW YORK _ As the nation gets ready to judge more
Starr evidence, President Clinton prepares to tell UN General
Assembly how nations must work together to combat global terrorism.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ All Americans will have a chance
to judge whether President Clinton committed perjury in his Aug. 17
testimony to grand jurors on the Monica Lewinski affiar. As a White
House aide calls the new release a ``garbage dump,'' a prominent
senator calls for Clinton to go before the House Judiciary
Committee to tell his story. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MORALS _ ATLANTA _ It's not just the President. All
Americans have slipped morally, or so we believe, according to some
recent polls and statistics. That's why we're not as upset about
Clinton as we might be, say ethicists. ``Jesus said it best, let
him without sin cast the first stone,'' says Atlanta area retiree
Larry Travis. But are our standards really lower? We talk about the
perception of a moral dis-ease in the United States, and how it
influences our feelings about the events in Washington. (And we
offer a quick test, to see if your own diet is high in moral
fiber.) (Emerson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
