<HEADER>
A4930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-RODCHENKO-MOMA-NYT     09-20 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RODCHENKO-MOMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISIONS: RODCHENKO AND HIS ARTISTIC BROTHERS IN AMERICAN JAZZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARGO JEFFERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I went to the Museum of Modern Art to see the work of the
Russian artist Aleksandr Rodchenko for two reasons. I certainly
wanted to see first-rate art. But I also wanted to see what a
first-rate artist committed to being an honorable citizen did when
faced not with second-rate political scandals but with
life-and-death upheavals: a revolution that was changing
everything, from the way people worked to the way they thought.
</P>
<P>
   Rodchenko took his stand as an avant-garde abstract painter in
the years just before the Russian Revolution of 1917. As part of a
group whose members called themselves the Constructivists (they
included Vladimir Tatlin, El Lissitzy and Rodchenko's wife, Varvara
Stepanova), he committed himself to the highest ideals of that new
society. And he did his best work in the decade or so just after
the revolution, when experimentation was still the norm, with
extraordinary artists marrying art, craft and technology, and
testing how expressivity could be joined to collectivity.
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy hangs over the show, of course. We know Stalin is moving
in, ready to lunge as the 1920s end, and he is all the more potent
here because his image is nowhere to be found. The year 1928
brought the denunciation of Rodchenko's work as bourgeois
formalism; 1932 brought the dissolution of the independent artists'
groups he had been such a force in, working with poets, filmmakers
and stage directors like Mayakovsky, Eisenstein and Meyerhold.
Rodchenko was not a trusted Socialist Realist, so his work
opportunities dwindled and he found himself isolated and ignored,
the artist's equivalent of solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   The work is wonderful. You see the paintings, photographs and
graphic design the way you hear a piece of perfectly constructed
music. The colors are harmonics, and the lines are uncannily pure
melodies. He uses space the way a musician uses silence.
</P>
<P>
   But what struck closest to home was the way Rodchenko plunged
into the everyday, the practical and the commercial. He designed
factory uniforms, teapots and a workers' club. He produced gorgeous
book and magazine covers and advertisements for stores and airline
companies. He never felt any of this was beneath him and there was
no slacking off between the early high art and the later mass art.
(At least, not until the 1930s, when he was pushed aside.)
Rodchenko and his peers wanted to reach as many people as possible
with the best work they could do, remaking art in and for a society
trying to remake itself.
</P>
<P>
   It was this reaching inward and outward simultaneously, this
eagerness to test the resources of his art and his audience that
was so moving. There was so much beauty here and such idealism, and
simplicity too. (Art like this can be thoroughly and rewardingly
analyzed. But it can just be enjoyed, too). In his rigorous and
manifesto-laden way, Rodchenko was striving to make and help define
a truly modernist popular art.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to think of an American visual artist with this
reach. The Constructivists sometimes compared themselves to
architects. But given their work with people like Meyerhold and
Eisenstein, their ties to the performing arts are quite clear.
Which is no doubt why I began thinking of American popular music
and of those two composers who are celebrating their centennials
this year and next, George Gershwin (1898-1937) and Duke Ellington
(1899-1974).
</P>
<P>
   They weren't considered avant-gardists because the music they
wrote wasn't considered high art. But it was new and unsettling for
plenty of people. Rodchenko and his peers learned that high art
could be inseparable from everyday life and commerce. Gershwin,
Ellington and their peers learned that mass art could be converted
into high art without losing its character or its place in the
culture.
</P>
<P>
   You could write a jazz concerto or a folk opera. Of course a
two-and-a-half minute instrumental piece could be as texturally
rich as a piece two or three times as long, while a popular song
could have all the pleasures of an art song. Between them,
Ellington and Gershwin wrote short and long pieces, a host of
symphonic works, operas and liturgical music, all of it available
to all of us. They seized on the tensions between jazz, theatrical
and classical styles, between writing for an audience willing to
sit in a concert hall and one eager to leave a theater humming
tunes and enter a nightclub to dance to them.
</P>
<P>
   Rodchenko and his peers were high artists who remade themselves
as mass artists. Ellington, Gershwin and their peers were mass
artists who remade themselves as high artists.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ellington nor Gershwin came of age artistically during a
full-scale revolution. But they did come of age amid the economic,
political and social shocks of the Depression and the New Deal, and
in a country obsessed by race, ethnicity and Anglo-Saxon dominance.
Neither risked artistic death through political censorship. But as
commercial artists, they did risk the obliteration that can come
from failing to please the producers, bookers and reviewers who
controlled their access to their audience.
</P>
<P>
   And for every experiment they made, they risked disappointing
and losing some portion of that audience. In the United States, it
is commercial failure that lands an artist in solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin had Broadway and Hollywood and all those recordings of
his songs to offset experimental failures like ``Blue Monday'' and
``Porgy and Bess.'' Ellington, denied more than occasional access
to Broadway or Hollywood, had his band, and between unceasing tours
and recordings he was able to underwrite his more experimental
work.
</P>
<P>
   We make a big point today about post-modernists who blur the
distinctions of high, low and mass art. Modernists like Rodchenko,
Ellington and Gershwin did little else. Maybe ``blur'' is the wrong
word. You can't use a form or technique effectively if you don't
know what distinguishes it from other forms and techniques.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to their work and their audience, these artists
refused to respect what these distinctions were supposed to
signify. This meant not only that they were brilliant. It meant
they honored their audience, as they were and as they could be.
</P>
<P>
   We may find it small comfort during tawdry or brutal political
times, but Shelley was right when he said that artists (his word
was poets, but surely he wouldn't object) are the unacknowledged
legislators of the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
