<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MULTICULTURAL MARKETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A giant agency company is stepping up its efforts in
multicultural marketing, forming a unit devoted to encouraging
advertisers to keep pace with the changing face of consumers by
increasing sales pitches aimed at ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   The unit, New America Strategies Group, is being introduced by
True North Communications in Chicago, the world's sixth-largest
agency company, with estimated billings of $10.8 billion handled by
units like Bozell Worldwide and Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding. The start-up
is timed to coincide with a three-day conference, beginning Tuesday
in Chicago, that describes ethnic marketing as a ``gateway to
America's trillion-dollar growth markets,'' which include black,
Hispanic and Asian-American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the conference, sponsored by True North and the
Strategic Research Institute in New York, New America Strategies
Group will share results of a study analyzing household shopping
and spending propensities of multicultural and white families.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing initial finding of the study is that
household spending of multicultural families, on purchases deemed
essential and discretionary, is growing faster than for white
families in 10 of 13 categories in a New America Market Basket
Index, which include vehicle purchases, clothing and utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multicultural Americans are in many ways the growth engine of
the economy,'' said Alfred Schreiber, who becomes managing partner
of New America Strategies Group, based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``CEOs who can manage change will be the winners,'' he added.
``And one of the biggest coming changes is the rise of what we call
the New America, which probably offers the best opportunity for
companies for organic growth.''
</P>
<P>
   True North is joining a lengthening list of mainstream agency
companies that are devoting additional resources to multiethnic
marketing. For instance, Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. in New York, which
already owns shops specializing in advertising aimed at Hispanic
and Asian-American consumers, is acquiring operations of One World
Communications, a unit of Leap Group in Chicago dedicated to
multicultural marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Those intensifying activities have stirred irritation and
anxiety among the smaller, independent agencies _ many of which are
owned by members of minorities _ that have long focused on the
ethnic market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of outstanding ethnic agencies and I
applaud them,'' said Charles Peebler Jr., president of True North
and chairman and chief executive of True North Diversified Cos.,
the division under which New America Strategies Group will operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are looking at the broader, total multicultural
picture,'' he added, ``which marketers have yet to give the
substantial time and attention they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   The new unit is offering clients a planning tool called the
Multicultural Marketing Opportunity Model, intended to analyze the
return on investment of initiatives aimed at ethnic consumers.
</P>
<P>
   New America Strategies Group will consist of three agencies and
a marketing consulting company. These are the agencies:
</P>
<P>
   _ Siboney USA in New York, which specializes in advertising,
direct marketing, promotion and public relations directed at
Spanish-speaking consumers. Siboney, which also has offices in
Dallas, Los Angeles and Miami, has billings estimated at $50
million from clients like Colgate-Palmolive Co. and Mastercard
International.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stedman Graham &AMP; Partners in Chicago and New York, which
specializes in marketing communications campaigns aimed primarily
at African-Americans. The agency, founded in 1996 as Graham Gregory
Bozell, works for such advertisers as Johnson &AMP; Johnson and Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   _ Admerasia in New York, an affiliate of True North that creates
campaigns in languages including Chinese, Indian, Japanese, Korean,
Russian and Vietnamese for marketers like American Express Co. and
the Citibank unit of Citicorp.
</P>
<P>
   The consulting-company component of the new unit is Skunkworks
Marketing Lab in New York, whose clients include AT&AMP;T Corp. and
Coca-Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   New America Strategies Group will be overseen by a partners
board. The members are: Peebler, 62; Schreiber, 52, who is also
executive vice president and general manager at Graham; Stedman
Graham, 47, chairman and chief executive at Graham; Jose Cubas, 68,
chairman at Siboney; Richard Mascolo, 43, president at Skunkworks,
and Val Zammit, 51, president and chief operating officer at True
North Diversified Cos.
</P>
<P>
   The market basket study, developed in alliance with Demograph
Corp., a management consulting company in Miami, concluded that
spending by multicultural households has grown 17.8 percent from
1995 to 1998, compared with an increase of 13.1 percent for white
households in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The categories in which the growth rate in spending in
multicultural households most exceeded the growth rate in spending
in white households were entertainment, vehicle purchases and
health care. As a sign of upward mobility among ethnic consumers,
the study showed, spending has been shifting from public
transportation to purchasing vehicles and from rental housing to
homeowning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
