<SLUG> BC-TV-FARMER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FARMER'S WIFE': DOUBLE BIND IN NEBRASKA: FARMING AND A MARRIAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a delicate matter. Juanita and Darrel Buschkoetter are not
made-for-television characters whom a reviewer can kick around
without getting personal. They are a young Nebraska farm couple,
parents of three, whose ordeal of dry weather with its crop of
economic and emotional troubles is the subject of ``The Farmer's
Wife.''
</P>
<P>
   David Sutherland, the conscientious filmmaker who culled six and
a half hours of television from 200 hours of shooting over three
years, trains an intimate yet generally unsentimental lens on the
Buschkoetters and their children, parents, creditors and others
involved in their battle for a way of life and for a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   None of them are noticeably put off by the prying cameras or
sound equipment, but their collaboration, which invites comparison
with the 1973 television portrait of the Loud family, seems to go
on forever. Sutherland demonstrates that given enough time, a
likable, hard-working couple on the edge of disaster can make
pretty wearing company. Their story will be told over three nights
beginning Monday on PBS' ``Frontline.''
</P>
<P>
   As the title suggests, Juanita Buschkoetter is at the heart of
this chronicle of tough going on the Nebraska range. It begins in
the spring of 1995, when the couple are battling to hold onto their
small farm. ``Am I going to be farming this fall or am I going to
be forced to sell out?'' Darrel asks and keeps asking. ``How can it
get any worse?''
</P>
<P>
   Wait and see. If you had any doubt about how hard farm families
still work, it should be laid to rest as Darrel takes a job in a
factory and Juanita hires out as a housekeeper. Darrel says,
``Trying to farm at night and work all day for somebody else, it's
worse than a living hell.'' The pressures, which threaten to reduce
the pair from independent farmers to a beaten-down peasantry,
buffet their marriage. ``The Darrel that's on the surface right
now,'' Juanita says, ``it's really hard to deal with him.''
Fortunately, self-esteem counseling is available even in rural
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   You have to sympathize with the couple's grit and perseverance,
but six and a half hours of worries about getting a government loan
(Sen. Bob Kerrey helps) and accepting handouts and enduring family
nagging is demanding on the audience, too.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue can be relentlessly real.
</P>
<P>
   Juanita: Do something. You're sitting here in my way.
</P>
<P>
   Darrel: Like what?
</P>
<P>
   Juanita: Take a bath or. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Darrel: How can I take a bath? Can't take a bath yet.
</P>
<P>
   Juanita: Why?
</P>
<P>
   Darrel: Well, the kids running all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of sensitivity on show during these three long
nights _ Sutherland catches all the nuances of pillow talk _ and no
resort to the sensationalism that gave the Louds of Santa Barbara
their soap-opera appeal. Missing, however, is a compelling
narrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Farmer's Wife,'' with its unsparing theme, just doesn't
produce enough drama to repay watching unless you have a soft spot
for in-law spats and domestic bickerings. By the end, when the
weather finally improves, the series slips into a feminist fable,
with Juanita going to school and finding a fulfilling job and a
newly respectful Darrel taking over the housework.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is a criticism of the Buschkoetters. Few lives are
made for television, and their troubles deserve attention.
Sutherland has delivered a respectable sociological document. But
for six and a half hours, it would be helpful to have a more
eventful story to tell or more variety in the telling.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FRONTLINE: THE FARMER'S WIFE'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday at 9 p.m. ET
</P>
<P>
   Written, produced, directed and edited by David Sutherland;
Nancy Sutherland, co-producer; Lisa Olivieri, associate producer;
original music written and performed by Reeves Gabrels. For ITVS:
James Yee, executive producer. For Frontline: Michael Sullivan,
executive producer; David Fanning, senior executive producer. A
co-production of David Sutherland Productions Inc. and Frontline in
association with the Independent Television Service (ITVS).
</P>
</TEXT>
