<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Sept. 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A final day of sultry weather is expected along the East Coast
from New England to the Carolinas as high pressure over the
southwest Atlantic circulates tropical air northward along the
seaboard. The day will begin with widespread haze and fog east of
the Appalachians, but balmy breezes will stir the lower atmosphere
enough to bring intervals of sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Remnant moisture from tropical storm Hermine will flow northeast
into the southern Appalachians, eastern Tennessee Valley and
western Carolinas. Dense clouds will accompany heavy showers and
thunderstorms with flooding rain likely in some spots. The cloud
shield will be drawn up the Appalachians along with a few
thundershowers. Very moist and warm air from Maryland to
Massachusetts will become buoyant when heated by sunny intervals.
An approaching cold front will trigger a few clusters of strong to
severe thunderstorms in the northern Appalachians Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The leading edge of much cooler, drier air will press southeast
from the Great Lakes and Plains. A few thunderstorms will mark the
advance of cooler air into the Ohio Valley. A jet stream
disturbance exiting the Rockies will further lift chilly, moist air
in its ascent into the western Dakotas and Wyoming. A cold rain
will soak South Dakota and showers will spread east into southern
Minnesota and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few thunderstorms in the central Rockies, the West
will be brighter with a steady warming trend. Coastal clouds will
obscure sections of the Los Angeles Basin.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: A Plains Cold Front
</P>
<P>
   The mercury rose to a record maximum of 92 degrees at the Twin
Cities airport in Minneapolis on Saturday and readings reached 95
degrees at Redwood Falls, southwest of the capital. The hot air
preceded a strong cold front which swept through the northern
Plains on Saturday night. In fact, cold fronts mark both the
leading edge of advancing cooler air and the apex of a warm air
mass being displaced. As winter approaches, it will become more
evident that the mildest air precedes cold fronts. By Monday
afternoon, readings were 20 degrees lower in Minneapolis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
