<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODMORNING-MEDIA-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOOD MORNING AMERICA' DRIFTS INTO SERIOUS TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of ``Today'' and ``Good Morning America'' ratings
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In early morning television, Katie and Matt don't
need surnames. As co-hosts of the enormously popular ``Today'' show
on NBC, Katie Couric and Matt Lauer are not only familiar
companions in more than 5 million American homes each morning; they
are also well known to movers and shakers from Washington to New
York to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to ``Good Morning America'' on ABC, many
people think of the co-hosts primarily as that smiling blond woman
and that nice young man who wears glasses.
</P>
<P>
   True, Lisa McRee has been in the job for just one year, and
Kevin Newman took over from Charles Gibson only this May. But their
valiant, visibly difficult struggles to stay smiling and
sharp-witted in the competitive arena of morning television are the
surface signs of turbulence at a show in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of a decade, from 1985-95, ``Good Morning
America'' was the most-watched show in the 7-9 a.m. weekday slot.
But in the last two years, it has seen its Nielsen ratings plummet,
losing more than 25 percent of its viewers. In May 1996, the
average number of households watching the show each day was 4.17
million, just a bit behind the ``Today'' show's 4.43 million. By
May 1998, ``Today'' had an average of 5.26 million homes tuned in,
while second-place ``Good Morning America'' had slipped to 3.12
million.
</P>
<P>
   That drop hurts the prestige of ABC, a subsidiary of Walt Disney
Co., but the financial pain is far worse. Not only are the
breakfast shows the most profitable news programs on NBC and ABC,
but those networks split the advertising time 50-50 with their
owned and affiliated local stations _ for whom it is almost pure
profit since they contribute little to the shows' costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Morning America'' had been run by ABC Entertainment since
its debut in 1975. But because all the morning shows were becoming
newsier and more sophisticated in keeping with changing American
habits and tastes, and because the show's ratings had begun to
stagnate, ABC in 1995 moved the program to the news division.
Oddly, that is when the downturn began.
</P>
<P>
   And it has been costly. For the first half of this year,
``Today'' earned about $117 million for NBC, a unit of General
Electric Co., more than the other two morning shows combined,
according to estimates reported by the networks themselves and by
advertising agencies, and compiled by Nielsen. Those estimates show
``Good Morning America'' earned about $77 million.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, ``Today'' and ``Good Morning America'' were
``dead even'' in revenue, said a network executive with direct
knowledge of the revenue picture, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``CBS This Morning,'' usually a distant third but
improving recently, earned about $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   The news division takeover is widely blamed for the ``Good
Morning America'' decline, but even die-hard devotees of the old
show admit that changes were needed. Its audience was growing
older, and ``Today'' was growing stronger and more competitive in
snapping up the important first interview with the news maker of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the changes backfired, either because they were too
precipitous, were not well thought out, or were poorly communicated
to the staff producing the show, according to interviews with two
dozen people, including some who work on the show now, some who
have left it and executives at all three networks. Many, especially
those still employed at ABC, insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Since Phil Beuth, the president of ``Good Morning America''
under the entertainment division, and Jack Reilly, its executive
producer for seven years, departed in early 1994, the program has
had four executive producers in four years.
</P>
<P>
   That has helped foster high turnover at other levels, especially
among producers and bookers, who are the people who get guests to
commit themselves to appear on the show.
</P>
<P>
   For viewers, the change is most visible in the co-anchors.
Newman, a well-regarded reporter, and Ms. McRee, a former anchor of
ABC's overnight news, of magazine shows and of local news at KABC
in Los Angeles, may be competent, but they were almost unknown when
they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The tension seen on the set began when the news division took
over in 1995, and even some news staffers acknowledge that change
may have been too blunt and too fast, according to accounts from
people on both sides. Many longtime staff members of the show use
the same word _ ``disdain'' _ to describe the attitude they sensed
from the news division.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense when news took over that anyone who worked
there before that was an idiot,'' said Kevin Magee, a former senior
producer who now works at CNBC, the cable business-news channel.
``It was very sad, very hurtful, especially when people were
killing themselves with the work level they gave to that show.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Originally created to be an alternative to ``Today,''
deliberately less newsy and more folksy, ``Good Morning America''
grew popular with little help from the news division. It built its
own news gathering team and its own slate of experts, like doctors,
lawyers and consumer advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to find Tim Johnson, Geraldo Rivera, Joel Siegel,''
said Bob Reichblum, the executive producer through all of 1995 and
now the vice president for prime time at CNBC, ``but that became
the signature of the show, its own family of contributors. That
concept started with `GMA' out of necessity, because the show had
no support from ABC News.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Today'' show even copied that ``family'' concept in the
early 1990s, trying to mend its own rifts of 1989 and 1990 after
Jane Pauley quit, Bryant Gumbel criticized colleagues in a memo
leaked to the press and Deborah Norville proved a disastrous
replacement for Ms. Pauley.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, ``Today'' got viewers' attention by moving to a new
studio on Rockefeller Center's plaza, where a live audience could
participate, and by 1995, ``Today'' had pulled even in the Nielsen
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   It was at that point that ABC News took over, but there was a
history of scant mutual respect between the news division and the
program. By contrast, ``Today'' had the advantage of having always
been an integral part of NBC News, going back to its debut on Jan.
14, 1952, with Dave Garroway as host.
</P>
<P>
   Many longtime ``Good Morning America'' producers and
correspondents were pushed aside, and the number and quality of
their assignments diminished. With producers' roles frequently
changing and the program's top executives tending to rule by
committee, according to most accounts, the show began to appear
chaotic on the air, too.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors circulated that Joan Lunden and Gibson would be replaced,
yet the ABC News executives never chose regular substitute anchors
to groom them to fit comfortably into the morning's mix, as
``Today'' had done with Ms. Couric and Lauer. (Lauer co-anchored
almost one-third of the ``Today'' shows in the year before he took
over permanently from Gumbel, according to NBC News.)
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to attract younger viewers, young contributors were
hired, but they often did not stay long. Cindy Adams, the brassy
New York Post gossip columnist, was added. Many loyal viewers of
the show began to feel they scarcely recognized it.
</P>
<P>
   When Elizabeth Vargas replaced Morton Dean as the show's news
reader, in May 1996, audience research showed that many viewers
were upset, said one ABC executive, who insisted on anonymity. It
was yet another goodbye to a familiar face, and Ms. Vargas was
perceived as openly seeking to replace Joan Lunden as the show's
co-anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Executives did not stick with her either, however; she left a
year later to become a correspondent for the news magazines
``20/20'' and ``Prime Time Live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I reported to had no vision whatsoever,'' Reichblum
said. ``It's one thing to say, `You're stale, you have dead wood,
you're not coming up with new ideas.' Nothing's wrong with that, if
you have a plan for how to fix things.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one at `GMA' was opposed to change,'' he said. ``They
recognized that, like any television show, it needed to evolve. But
it did not need a revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those responsible for making the changes say complaints
about ``revolution'' are naive. They say the ``family'' so
cherished by longtime ``Good Morning America'' staff members
blocked the integration of new talent into that clan, and did
little to recruit a new generation of viewers. And the ``Today''
ratings were getting stronger, especially in the 18-49 age group
that advertisers covet.
</P>
<P>
   But even these people acknowledge there may have been too much
change, too fast. ``It has lurched back and forth,'' one said.
``For six months this year it tended toward fluffier, lighter
segments, more spontaneity, and then for the last two, three months
it has been trying to get newsy again.''
</P>
<P>
   Indecision like that causes bookers to be less certain about
what sort of guests to pursue, and if they wait to get approval
from a high-level producer, the guest will often already be booked
by ``Today.'' Or, a booker will snare a guest, only to have to call
back and undo the commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Indecision can also give the anchors less time to prepare for
interview segments, or make them appear uncomfortable and jittery
shifting between segments.
</P>
<P>
   A nadir mentioned with chagrin by a number of people connected
with the show was the coverage of the crash of TWA Flight 800 into
the sea off Long Island in 1996. ``Good Morning America''
executives decided not to risk sending Gibson to the scene because
technical problems made it questionable whether he could get on the
air. NBC flew Gumbel back from the Atlanta Olympics to anchor the
coverage from the beach.
</P>
<P>
   That will not happen again, said Shelley Lewis, the show's
current executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mantra now is substance,'' she said. ``We're trying to be
the most substantive news and information program on television.
The show just has to get a lot better, and then the ratings will
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   But the climb back toward No. 1 is much steeper now than it has
ever been for either show, since there is more competition in the
morning than ever _ from local morning shows, like Fox's ``Good Day
New York,'' to cable networks, like ESPN for the sports fan or CNBC
for the business person.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took over `Today,' they told me I had two years to fix
that show,'' said Steve Friedman, a former executive producer of
``Today'' who is now vice president and station manager of
WCBS/Channel 2 in New York. ``I did it a lot differently knowing I
had two years than if I'd had to worry about every week, every
month, every quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   How long does he think it will take to revitalize ``Good Morning
America''?
</P>
<P>
   ``At least two years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewis said bravely, ``Nobody has given me a deadline or a
time frame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
