<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVSURFER21-COX     09-20 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Married . . . with TV: `King' a blue-collar kid
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doug has been married for three years, works hard as a parcel
deliveryman and is a lovable, little kid.
</P>
<P>
   When wife Carrie tells him he's going to dinner at his in-laws',
Doug _ a 2-ton baby in an adult's body _ whines, ``C'mon, Carrie,
please. Don't make me go to that bad place.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug is ``The King of Queens'' (8:30 tonight on CBS), the lord
of his New York row house and the latest in a long line of
adorable, know-nothing males who populate TV's adorable blue-collar
sitcoms. Like Tim Allen in ``Home Improvement'' and Ray Romano in
``Everybody Loves Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to like Doug (nicely played by stand-up comic
Kevin James). He's honest, caring and overjoyed by the warm glow of
a new 70-inch TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   That bigger than big TV is the heart of tonight's ``King''
debut, and it's a promising start. Doug's pals pile in like Little
Rascals to watch sports. His too-understanding wife (admirably
played by Leah Remini, an escapee from last season's dreadful
``Fired Up'') towers above their juvenile ways. And adding depth to
the wacko mix are Jerry Stiller, reprising his Frank Costanza
antics from ``Seinfeld'' as Carrie's dad Arthur, and Lisa Rieffel,
playing her ditsy sister, wannabe actress Sara.
</P>
<P>
   Getting all these family members under one roof (it wouldn't be
TV if it didn't happen) is pretty much a stitch _ far funnier than
``Home Improvement'' these days and a nice warm-up to the superior
``Everybody Loves Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   The rough road starts next week. That's when Episode 2 of
``King'' drops back and punts, trying to generate laughs by having
rotund Doug worry incessantly over whether a slender Carrie is
gaining weight and will eventually blimp out.
</P>
<P>
   Can a husky king love a husky queen?
</P>
<P>
   That's when female viewers might decide that ``King's'' humor is
a
</P>
<P>
   little thin.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Raymond hates termites
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' moves to a new time slot tonight (at
9 on CBS ), forcing those who once used it as a running start into
Fox's ``Ally McBeal'' to make a choice between the two.
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad, because ``Raymond'' was TV's best pre-9 p.m.
show, a family sitcom for adults. Tonight's season opener features
some coarser language than usual, as if that'll make it sound older
for those not already tucked into bed. But the rest is pure, if not
classic, ``Raymond'': Ray (Ray Romano) and Debra (Patricia Heaton)
find termites in their house and are forced to move the family in
with Ray's parents.
</P>
<P>
   Parents as beloved enemies is at the root of this show's
success, and tonight Doris Roberts, as Ray's mother, Marie, shows
again why she's as good a supporting sitcom actress as there is on
TV.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Drew Jubera, TV critic, Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   A dark, dreary `Bay'
</P>
<P>
   No one's happy on ``Hyperion Bay'' (9 tonight on WB ). Not
Dennis Sweeny (Mark-Paul Gosselaar), a high school nerd now all
grown up and ready to show off his white-collar success with
computers to his tired hometown. Not his older blue-collar brother,
Nick (Dylan Neal), whose marriage is crumbling. And certainly not
his pop, Frank (Raymond J. Barry), who's caught between feuding
sons angling for attention.
</P>
<P>
   This hour bummer bristles with the darkest, dreariest strains of
``thirtysomething'' _ as you imagine it would since it comes from
Joseph Dougherty, a writer, director and producer for that dark,
dreary show.
</P>
<P>
   ``thirtysomething'' took time to develop. Since it airs opposite
``Ally McBeal'' and ``Monday Night Football,'' time is the one
thing ``Hyperion'' hasn't got.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Longino, TV critic, Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Caroline's reject
</P>
<P>
   Might as well call ``Conrad Bloom'' (8:30 tonight on NBC )
``Conrad in the City,'' since this new sitcom was created by
``Caroline's'' producer Marco Pennette and stars Mark Feuerstein,
who played her boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's a nice young mensch surrounded by difficult women _ his
stereotypically Jewish mother (Linda Lavin), needy best friend,
nutty sister, neurotic co-worker. Taxing him further is Steve
Landesberg (``Barney Miller''), the best thing in the show as a
burned-out ex-whiz now partnered with Conrad at their ad agency.
Just another by-the-numbers NBC comedy that doesn't distinguish
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _ Phil Kloer, TV critic, Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   `Benben'? Dream on
</P>
<P>
   A sendup on the shallowness of local news anchors. Can't we just
watch the real thing?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brian Benben Show,'' which debuts at 9:30 tonight on CBS
and stars that guy with the redundant name, tries to milk laughs
from one very dry cow. It wants to be the light sex farce that the
likable Benben fit perfectly into in ``Dream On,'' but it comes up
far short.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting two new reporters, a Barbie and a Ken, the
soon-to-be-replaced Benben remarks ``So young and clean and shiny.
They're about to smile!'' They then cover their eyes, as if
shielding them from a solar eclipse. Hey, it's a gag. If that
doesn't hurt you enough, they bomb away with double entendres.
``I'd pour coffee in your lap if I thought I'd hit anything.''
Guess the bomb dropped on them.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _ Drew Jubera
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
