<HEADER>
A4949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYFASHION21-COX     09-20 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYFASHION21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Klein skirts and dresses survive stumbles, uncoordinated colors
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When a model tripped and fell to one knee during
Calvin Klein's spring/summer 1999 runway preview Friday night, it
signaled a turning point in an otherwise flawlessly executed show.
The incident, which came 57 outfits into Klein's 79-outfit show,
also symbolized the stumbling block that derailed many of the
collections shown throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   The model, identified only as Angela, was wearing a fire-red,
sheer and strapless stretch evening gown with a zippered slit
running up one side. Her pratfall gave those in the
standing-room-only crowd reason to reconsider the desirability of
the only shoe Klein showed for next season: leather mules in black,
beige or brown, with heels that looked like roofing nails.
</P>
<P>
   What followed the incident, which sparked a chorus of gasps, was
a calvacade of Klein's ``surprise'' styles for next season's
soirees: layered sheer slip dresses in such color-over-color
combinations as pink and green, green and blue, pink and gold. The
look carried all the ``drama'' Klein intended it to as the
side-slit, bias-cut layers of jersey danced around the models'
scant contours. But the odd mix of colors also injected the
collection with an element of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Would a woman really feel elegant wearing such uncoordinated
colors? And how willling will she be to pay for two separate
dresses _ underwear not included _ in order to achieve this look?
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of Klein's message, however, couldn't have been
clearer. From his standpoint, women should wear (knee-length)
skirts and dresses much more often than pants. The former
outnumbered the latter by a 6-to-1 ratio. And, predictably, most of
Klein's collection came in a subtle mix of neutrals; i.e., a cream
silk/canvas jacket with a sheer white tank top and a beige cotton
stretch skirt, or a metallic grey suit with a steel-blue,
suede-textured tank.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes were cut to look curvy and comfortable.
Distinguishing features included the zippered skirt slits;
needle-thin streaks of red, green or metallic embroidery; wrap
skirts with Napoleonic pockets; concealed closures on jackets;
raw-edged linen waistbands; muted plaids and a revolutionary new
``crushed'' wool fabrication that's weightless and intentionally
wrinkled.
</P>
<P>
   Weightless, wrinkled fabrications were also central to the
spring/summer '99 collection by Vivienne Tam, whose runway show
closed the first of a full five weeks of previews in the fashion
capitals of New York, London, Milan, Paris and New York again.
</P>
<P>
   Tam took a waxed-paper fabric and cut it into: cheeky short
shorts; collarless zip-front blouses and jackets; skirts and
dresses that ranged from mini- to maxi-length; and swingy trench
coats. Another innovative fabric Tam employed was one of rubberized
mesh that she calls ``Airtex.''
</P>
<P>
   Fashion editors agreed that the most attractive outfit shown was
the purple paper skirt and matching sheer cotton sweater that Tam
herself wore when she appeared from backstage to accept rousing
applause.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, the show was further testament to Tam's mastery of
intricate embroidery and beading, her creative fearlessness and her
flair for melding modernity with femininity. At its worst _
specifically, a grouping of palm-leaf-print separates in rust and
wine shades _ Tam's collection was too busy to suit the tastes of
women who're becoming increasingly enamored of simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
