<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONIMORRISON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern impact on works key topic
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In Toni Morrison's novel ``Jazz,'' Joe and Violet
Trace board ``the colored section of the Southern Sky'' in 1906 and
leave Virginia for a Northern city. As the train nears their new
home, they are ``nervous at having gotten there at last, but
terrified of what was on the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe and Violet represent the nearly 4 million African-Americans
who took part in the ``great migration'' from the largely agrarian
South to the urban North from Reconstruction through the world
wars.
</P>
<P>
   Though Nobel laureate Morrison was born in Lorain, Ohio, her
parents had been among those who moved north, and the background of
her novels offer rich readings of the meaning of the South in the
lives of her urban characters.
</P>
<P>
   That richness is the context for ``Toni Morrison and the
American South,'' a five-day conference beginning Wednesday at
Georgia State University. As many as 200 scholars and readers will
attend the events, sponsored by the Toni Morrison Society.
</P>
<P>
   In a public session benefiting the society, Morrison will read
from ``Paradise'' and answer questions at 8 p.m. Saturday at the
Rialto Center for the Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to make Toni Morrison into a Southern
writer,'' says Carolyn Denard, the GSU associate professor of
English who has spent two years organizing the conference. But ``if
we talk about blacks in the North from 1865 to the 1930s and try to
understand their psyche, their sense of self, we've got to
understand their relationship to the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Denard is among those interested in how Morrison portrays the
ways migrants dealt with their Southern pasts and constructed
modern urban selves in the North. ``You have to travel to see your
culture,'' she says. ``That's when its distinctiveness becomes
apparent.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison's father was about 14 when he left Cartersville, Ga. at
the turn of the century, and her mother was about 6 when she moved
north from Alabama. In an interview with Denard, to be published in
November in the GSU journal Studies in the Literary Imagination,
Morrison discusses the sense of the South she gained from her
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had diametrically opposed positions,'' Morrison says in
the interview. Her father remembered Georgia racism, while her
mother had fonder memories and was nostalgic. Even so, her father
returned for yearly visits while her mother never went back. ``I
grew up with a complicated notion of the South, neither sentimental
nor wholly frightening,'' the author says.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Morrison discusses what the South means for
African-Americans. While ``for us, it's home, I guess, in the sense
that it was the first stop when you left the ancient home,'' she
struggles to keep the South from ``being just the old place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What black people did in this country was brand new,'' she
tells Denard. The people were inventive, she says, creating, among
other things, ``a music that is the world's music, a style, a
matter of speaking, a relationship with each other. . . . And no
one gives us credit for the intelligence it takes to be forced into
another culture, be oppressed, and make a third thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison's literature and the multidisciplinary conference
reflect that creativity. Events include a Dwight Andrews Jazz
Quintet performance of an original tribute to Morrison's works, the
Spelman College Readers' Theater ``Talking Drum,'' an exhibit and
lecture by artist Michele Wood and a visit to Cartersville, the
birthplace of Morrison's father. Conference fees are $150 ($75 for
students).
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold is a book critic for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
