<HEADER>
A4954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT &LR;      09-20 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS IS OFTEN THE MEASURE OF THE GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the modern era of the National Football League, no team has
helped define the success or failure of any Giants season quite
like the Dallas Cowboys. Year after year, how the Giants have fared
against the Cowboys has tended to mark the team's season _
positively or negatively.
</P>
<P>
   Only twice since 1960 _ when the Cowboys and the Giants first
met _ have the Giants had a winning season without defeating the
Cowboys at least once. The series between the teams is strewn with
landmark games.
</P>
<P>
   The first Giants game at Giants Stadium 22 years ago was against
the Cowboys _ the Giants lost. The first National Football
Conference East game in 1970 was a Giants-Cowboys game _ the Giants
lost. After losing 12 consecutive games to the Cowboys in the late
1970s, the first Giants playoff season in 18 years wasn't clinched
until the Giants had defeated the high-flying Cowboys in overtime
in the regular-season finale.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' rivalry with the Washington Redskins may be longer,
their rivalry with San Francisco more bitter, and their rivalry
with the Jets more regionally significant, but for two decades or
more, it's the Cowboys by which the Giants have often measured
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And it could be so again this year.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to know if the Cowboys will be the Giants'
principal competition in the division this season. The preseason
consensus was that their chief rival would be Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But for Monday night's game at Giants Stadium, once again it is
the Cowboys who arrive at a pivotal juncture in the Giants' season.
</P>
<P>
   Just as they did a year ago. Just as they did 17 years ago, and
any number of years in between.
</P>
<P>
   Last season when the Cowboys came to town, the Giants were a
team in search of itself after a staggering 2-3 start.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to remember the 1997 Cowboys now as a team in
disarray that won just six games. On Oct. 5 last year, the Cowboys
arrived as the defending NFC East champions with a 3-1 record in
1997. They knocked the Giants' starting quarterback, Dave Brown,
out of the game with a chest strain, and his backup, Danny Kanell,
took over with the team trailing by 3-0 as the game wound into the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell did not turn the ball over, playing just well enough to
rally the Giants to a 20-17 victory, the second of five successive
victories that sparked them to an undefeated division record and
the division title.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Giants, then the youngest team in the National
Football League, took confidence from their defeat of the Cowboys.
It was the first time in five years that the first meeting of the
season between the Giants and the Cowboys had not been a lopsided
Dallas victory, and it had the Giants believing not only in Kanell,
but also in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that Giants-Cowboys game with the one three years ago _
the last time the Giants played on ``Monday Night Football.''
Emmitt Smith burst up the field for 60 yards and a touchdown on his
first carry of the night.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who had been 9-7 in 1994, contended that they were
ready to challenge the Cowboys for supremacy in the division. The
Cowboys won that 1995 season-opening game, 35-0, on their way to a
Super Bowl championship. The Giants lost 11 games and finished
fourth in the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other notable Giants-Cowboys games, including
some eventful struggles in the late 1960s and in 1970, when the
Giants were trying to wrest a division championship from the
ascendant Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   But two other games stand out among the rest in a series the
Cowboys lead, 44-25-2.
</P>
<P>
   On the final day of the 1993 regular season (it was actually
Jan. 2, 1994), the 11-4 Cowboys came to Giants Stadium to face the
Giants, who had the same record. The division title, and more
important, home field throughout the playoffs would go to the
winning team.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 13-0 at the half, the Giants rallied to send the
game to overtime. A controversial penalty against Giants center
Brian Williams cost them an overtime scoring opportunity. Shortly
thereafter, in a game played under dark skies, things got truly
gloomy for the Giants as Eddie Murray of Dallas kicked a 41-yard
field goal to win the game, 16-13.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants won their opening-round playoff game, but were blown
out in San Francisco in the conference semifinal game. Another
Dallas Super Bowl championship followed.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's field goal wasn't the only one in overtime between
these teams to set a historic playoff course. In 1981, on a
Saturday during the final weekend of the regular season, the Giants
needed to defeat the Cowboys to qualify for the playoffs for the
first time since 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Kicker Joe Danelo, who had missed two short field goals in the
first half, made a 40-yard field goal into a strong wind to tie the
score with 30 seconds left in the fourth quarter. In overtime,
Danelo missed another field goal. Then, he converted from 35 yards
for the Giants' 13-10 victory.
</P>
<P>
   For a generation of Giants fans who had never seen their team in
the NFL postseason, Danelo's last act on the Giants Stadium field
that long, tense day 17 years ago is still the kick that liberated
a storied franchise from a dismal, doleful period. It's the baby
step on the path to the Giants' first Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That it came against the Cowboys no doubt makes it all the more
memorable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
