</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-BEAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD WINS BUT DOESN'T IMPRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield absorbed several big blows late in his fight
against Vaughn Bean on Saturday night, going 12 rounds against an
opponent who many observers thought might last three. The champion
was not awful, but he was not awesome, either.
</P>
<P>
   Bean, the International Boxing Federation's No. 1 contender,
could not do enough to take Holyfield's two belts away, but he may
have raised some concern about Holyfield's ability to unify the
heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Styles make fights, and he had a very awkward one,'' Holyfield
said after winning a unanimous decision against Bean at the Georgia
Dome in Atlanta before 41,357, the largest boxing crowd in 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox Lewis would not have been moving,'' Holyfield said of
the World Boxing Council champion.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield-Lewis is no closer to being made than Ali-Foreman II.
There are mandatory defenses to take care of, purses to divide and
bidding from different sites.
</P>
<P>
   And there is Holyfield's age. He turns 36 in October, and given
how he looked before his hometown fans, it is reasonable to wonder
how much longer he can hold the IBF and World Boxing Association
titles. His next fight, probably against the No. 1 WBA contender,
Henry Akinwande, will be Holyfield's 40th.
</P>
<P>
   As he said his goal was to unify the title and then ``hang up
the _ '' the promoter Don King quickly interrupted his new meal
ticket. (King's former meal ticket, Mike Tyson, is suing him.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's close the books on that right now,'' King said. ``No one
asked Rockefeller when he was going to stop pumping the oil. So no
one should ask us when we're going to stop making the money. This
is Evander Holyfield's time. He set the record tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield promoted himself to his fellow Atlantans in the weeks
leading to the bout, and he was rewarded with the largest crowd to
see a fight since 63,350 piled into the Superdome in New Orleans to
see Muhammad Ali against Leon Spinks in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The people who paid from $25 to $500 a ticket got to see
Holyfield (36-3) force the action and drop Bean in the 10th round
with a vicious right uppercut. He appeared to have pushed Bean into
the ropes before the punch, but the ring referee ruled it a legal
knockdown.
</P>
<P>
   Using his forearms and elbows to bull his shorter and less
athletic opponent around the ring (the pudgy Bean stands 5 feet 11
inches and weighed 231 pounds, while the 6-2 Holyfield weighed
217), the champion won 117-110 on two scorecards and 116-111 on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   But his penchant for trading shots inside instead of boxing from
the perimeter got him in trouble at times. Bean (31-2) did not have
the size or the power of Riddick Bowe, who knocked Holyfield out in
their last fight. But the punches he did land _ clubbing overhand
rights that Holyfield said he could not see coming because of the
angle _ caught Holyfield flush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
