<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980920.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4959 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MORALS-COX     09-20 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MORALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is all lost? As nation airs the president's sins, some aren't
rushing to judgment
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's not just the president.
</P>
<P>
   The whole country has slipped morally. Or so we believe.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the past through a rosy rearview mirror, we see a
time when our leaders were noble and our word was our bond. Today,
we're awash in gross-out movies, nasty talk radio, rude drivers,
ill-behaved children and mendacious politicians.
</P>
<P>
   These conditions have convinced many people that we're headed
for Hades in a handbasket. Three out of every four respondents to a
recent Washington Post poll said the country is in a serious moral
decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not even shocked any more,'' says Julie Rogers-Martin,
director of Christian education at Columbia Presbyterian Church in
Decatur. ``Nobody's going to call(President Clinton) on the carpet
in Washington, because they're all doing the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Or so it would seem. Revelations in recent weeks that several
leading Republicans, including Henry Hyde, chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee, have indulged in adulterous affairs add to the
impression that our elected leaders are perennially auditioning for
``Oh, Calcutta!''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Josephson, a California millionaire who sold his company
to start a nonprofit foundation devoted to teaching ethics, is
another who's worried. The latest Josephson Institute survey of
10,000 high school students, to be released in two weeks, indicates
that kids are lying, cheating and stealing more often.
</P>
<P>
   Though Josephson won't reveal the figures until the biennial
report is published, he said this year's survey register a sharp
rise from 1996, when ``39 percent admitted they stole from a store
in the last year, 63 percent said they had cheated on an exam in
the last year and 25 percent said they lied to get or keep a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Josephson, ``There's a hole in the moral ozone, and it's
getting bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Are we tolerant of Clinton's behavior because of our own sagging
standards? The Post survey, also conducted by Harvard University
and the Kaiser Foundation, found that even among those seven out of
10 who said adultery ``should not be tolerated,'' fewer than half
said the president's dalliance was an important matter. While we
look to the Internet for the details of his Oval Office trysts with
Monica Lewinsky and Americans wait to view their chief executive
explaining himself on videotape (to be released this morning), his
job ratings remain high. Polls conducted after the Starr report was
released show Clinton's job approval rating unchanged at more than
60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book ``The Death of Outrage,'' former Bush Cabinet
member William Bennett contends that the ``moral exhaustion'' of
many Americans makes them reluctant to judge Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The men of Congregation Etz Chaim aren't convinced. In the
Jewish calendar, the season of Rosh Hashana, which began Sunday, is
a time for confession and repentance. The consensus of this group
of men meeting for breakfast after morning prayers (or ``morning
minyon'') at the east Cobb County synagogue, is that all of us have
plenty to confess.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's acts were abhorrent, but the rest of us aren't so hot
either, said Larry Travis, 67, a former police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jesus said it best,'' Steve Dix, 47, a Sandy Springs
lawyer, said as he munched a bagel with cream cheese with the group
at the Bagelicious deli on Johnson Ferry Road. ``Let he who is
without sin cast the first stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that we are any more sinful than past generations. ``I don't
think morals in this socioeconomic class are any different than
they were 50 years ago,'' Dix said.
</P>
<P>
   But times are more complicated, said Harold Sarles, 75, a
retired podiatrist. Much is made of the fact that the younger
generations are spoiled, that they've never had to suffer an
economic depression or a world war. But Sarles, who participated in
the invasion of Normandy (``D-Day, H-Hour plus 28 minutes''), said
the current generation has problems he never encountered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I don't have young children now, and I'm glad I'm not
16 or 17 myself because I know I'd end up trying drugs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Young people are threatened by new and different troubles, such
as AIDS and economic uncertainty, says Emory theologian Elizabeth
M. Bounds. They are pressured to succeed by parents who themselves
work long hours. ``Our social structures are leading us to
anxiety,'' says Bounds, associate professor of Christian ethics at
the Candler School of Theology.
</P>
<P>
   Pop moralists such as radio talk show host Laura Schlessinger
tell us ``if we just get our moral values straight then it will all
work out,'' Bounds said. But it's not that simple. ``We should
still be doing that, but we will do that against a background of
complex lives,' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bounds said she's reluctant to believe in a moral decline or any
mythical golden age. ``Fifty years ago, to say blacks were inferior
was morally acceptable for many people in this country,'' she
points out. ``It is no longer acceptable to make assumptions of
black inferiority and female inferiority. In certain ways our
public discourse has improved.''
</P>
<P>
   The widespread feeling of a slide in standards and behavior may
be due to a particularly tumultuous summer, said Gerald Celente,
director of the Trend Research Institute in Rhinebeck, N.Y. ``Look
what has happened just since August,'' says Celente, counting off
disasters: an unraveling stock market, missiles launched against
Sudan and Afghanistan, the collapse of Russia and the president
caught with his pants down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course people are concerned,'' Celente said. ``There's a
sense of chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Josephson, whose survey gives evidence that young people are
straying, said his findings also indicate that youngsters still
know right from wrong. The failing, he says, is more ``a question
of moral will power not moral sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   And, says Josephson, our tolerance of Clinton may be a pragmatic
decision rather than a moral choice. ``I don't think for a minute
Clinton could be re-elected again, nor would he be nominated,'' he
says. ``But would we throw him out of office? That's different.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite worries about what a moral example our tolerance might
be setting for our children, this scandal may serve as a salutary
lesson, Josephson says.
</P>
<P>
   Sarles agrees. The World War II veteran says the story of
Clinton may become a warning: ``You can be the greatest man in the
world, you can be the president, but look at what will happen if
you lie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
