<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION LEADER IN MALAYSIA IS JAILED IN SEX CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ After a day of lurid headlines and
protests by thousands, the rising star of Malaysian politics, Anwar
Ibrahim, was jailed Sunday night, following a long, bitter struggle
against his one-time mentor, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours before his arrest, apparently on charges of sexual
indecency, Anwar led a mass rally calling for Mahathir's
resignation, and the police fired tear gas at demonstrators who
were marching on the prime minister's house.
</P>
<P>
   The tumult coincided with a state visit by Queen Elizabeth II
and the competition of athletes from 70 nations in the Commonwealth
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the tear gas drifted past the British flags raised to
honor the queen, the police kicked down the door of Anwar's house,
where he was talking to reporters, and gave him one hour to pack
his clothes, eat dinner and say goodbye to his family. He was
driven away in a white van, surrounded by dozens of red-helmeted
officers, as his supporters ran alongside shouting, ``God is
great!''
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of Anwar, 51, followed his ouster on Sept. 2 as
deputy prime minister and heir apparent to Mahathir, 72, in the
most lurid political battle this conservative Muslim country has
known in years.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir, whose authority is rarely challenged, has had the
upper hand throughout. But the protests and arrest have shaken
Malaysia's reputation for stability, overturned one of Asia's most
solid succession scenarios and removed from public life a leading
standard-bearer of a more liberal generation of leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mahathir has been a vocal advocate of authoritarian
``Asian values,'' Anwar has called for the ``creative destruction''
of old political traditions and has advocated more free expression.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign since his ouster has uncovered what appears to be a
broad and formerly voiceless mood of discontent. As Anwar
barnstormed last week he drew large and enthusiastic crowds that
raised the cry of ``reformasi,'' or reform, that was the slogan of
the demonstrators who helped oust President Suharto of Indonesia in
May.
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts here said Mahathir's leadership was not
threatened, although an official of the governing party, the United
Malays National Organization, warned that Anwar's campaign ``could
create chaos and spark a revolution, which would eventually lead to
anarchy in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir's hold on his party is unchallenged, and his reputation
as a nation builder remains high. His word has been law for
decades, and many Malaysians seem reflexively to credit the
allegations against Anwar.
</P>
<P>
   But as in Indonesia, the economy is the wild card. Even as he
was moving against Anwar, who had promoted tight fiscal policies in
tune with the International Monetary Fund, Mahathir took the ailing
economy on a risky about-face, curbing trading in the currency, the
ringgit, and cutting off the country from the global financial
system.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange rate immediately stabilized, currency flowed back
into the economy, and the stock market rose, with help from
civic-minded institutional buying. But economic analysts said that
those gains might be short-lived and that Malaysia could in a few
months plunge back into a worse decline.
</P>
<P>
   But Anwar, lacking an independent organization and apparently
facing a prison term, seems at the moment to have little chance of
capitalizing on political changes. From the start he said he was
certain he would be arrested. But he had expected Mahathir to wait
until the end of the Commonwealth Games on Monday and the departure
of the queen on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where the press is tightly controlled and even
professional political commentators sometimes ask reporters not to
quote them by name, Anwar and his followers seemed to bask in the
thrill of nothing-to-lose invective.
</P>
<P>
   Shouting words that had hardly been whispered here before, Anwar
roused his listeners with statements like ``Dr. Mahathir has lost
the people's support,'' ``The time has come for him to step down,''
and ``My greatest sin was to challenge Dr. Mahathir _ he's old,
he's senile.''
</P>
<P>
   Anwar reached the point on Saturday of calling his rival
Malaysia's ``chief Tarzan'' and his friends ``apes and elephants.''
</P>
<P>
   The vivid language was far from one-sided. Anwar's dismissal
followed the publication of a Malaysian-style Starr report, ``50
Reasons Anwar Cannot Become Prime Minister,'' filled with detailed
allegations of sexual hijinks with men and women, as well as
sedition, abuse of power and bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's headlines _ including ``We Were Sodomized'' and ``They
Allowed Themselves to Be Sodomized by Anwar'' _ repeated the
allegations. The newspapers reported that two of his close male
associates had confessed to having sex with Anwar and were each
sentenced on Saturday to six months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking the same linguistic taboos as the Starr report in a
Muslim nation where explicit sex is carefully censored, the
newspapers reported on both cases in surprising detail.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar, who is married and has six children and who is known as a
devout and clean-living Muslim, strenuously denied the accusations
as having ``not an iota of truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a political conspiracy of the highest level to
destroy my political career by means of character assassination,''
he said on Saturday. ``I once again clearly and specifically deny
that I have been involved in these despicable activities.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his friends had been tortured, on Mahathir's orders,
into making false confessions and accused security forces of using
Gestapo and Israeli secret-police methods.
</P>
<P>
   That was too much for the inspector general of police, Abdul
Raheem Noor, who said: ``We can no longer tolerate it when he
accuses us of being similar to Israel. If he had accused us of
being similar to pirates, we could accept that. But not that he
equates us with Israel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
