<SLUG> BC-RUN-BERLIN-MARATHON-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIAN SHATTERS WORLD MARATHON RECORD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Brazilian named Ronaldo accomplished in marathon running
Sunday what his counterpart in soccer could not do at this summer's
World Cup _ prove that he was indisputably the best on the planet
in his sport.
</P>
<P>
   Running only his second marathon, Ronaldo da Costa shattered the
world record for the 26-miles-385-yard race, winning the Berlin
Marathon in 2 hours 6 minutes 5 seconds. Having spun the record on
its head, da Costa felt energized enough to perform a cartwheel in
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny day in Berlin with temperatures rising through the
50s, Da Costa shaved 45 seconds off the record, which had been
2:06:50, set in 1988 in Rotterdam by Belayneh Densimo of Ethiopia.
Last year, in his first marathon, da Costa, 28, finished fifth at
Berlin in 2:09:07.
</P>
<P>
   His victory Sunday challenged the international distance-running
supremacy of Africans, Mexicans, Koreans and Spaniards, and it
contradicted the belief that marathoners need significant altitude
training to increase their oxygen-carrying capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, da Costa trained about a quarter-mile above sea level
in Brazil and employed sprint training that allowed him to run the
final 13.1 miles in a searing 1:01:23 after running the first half
of the race in 1:04.42.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to run under 2:08 this year, but conditions were so
good I just went for it,'' da Costa said.
</P>
<P>
   Believing the pace-setters were too slow at the midpoint, da
Costa ran the next 5 kilometers (3.1 miles) in 14:20 to open a
40-second lead over a group of Kenyans. Josephat Kiprono of Kenya
finished second in 2:07:26, and Samson Kandie of Kenya finished
third in 2:09:11.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the half, he ran the next kilometer in 2:49,'' Luis
Posso, da Costa's Tampa, Fla.-based agent, said by telephone from
Berlin. ``The last seven kilometers are slightly downhill. At 39K,
I told him, `Don't look back, don't look at your watch. This is a
world record. Just run.' He was in shape to run anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The approximately $200,000 in prize and bonus money that da
Costa won will come in handy for a runner who grew up poor and now
is the chief provider for an extended family of about 20 relatives,
Posso said.
</P>
<P>
   Da Costa's family lives north of Rio de Janeiro in two small
towns named Descoberto and San Joao de Nepomuceno. He has a twin
brother, who formerly trained with him, and he pays his nephews
small amounts of money to carry water and pace him on their
bicycles, Posso said.
</P>
<P>
   While his coach, Carlos Alberto Cavalheiro, operates altitude
training camps in Brazil and in Boulder, Colo., da Costa is a
``hometown guy, who'd rather stay at home,'' Posso said.
</P>
<P>
   So Cavalheiro tailored a training regimen that drew from his
experience as a sprint coach. Cavalheiro previously coached Robson
da Silva, who won a bronze medal at 200 meters at the 1988 Summer
Olympics in Seoul, South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Da Costa's training partners include Andre Ramos, who finished
fourth at the 1998 Boston Marathon in 2:08:26, which, until Sunday,
was a South American record.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Da Costa employed an eight-week program to train for Berlin,
Cavalheiro said from Berlin. He did two long runs of 22 miles each
per week in the hills above his hometown, and trained about 120
miles a week at peak, but the most intriguing aspect of his
training was his speed work.
</P>
<P>
   His workouts included 15 repeats of 1,000 meters in 3:00 or
3:01, with 20 to 30 seconds' recovery time, and 25 repeats of 400
meters in 66 to 68 seconds, with a recovery time of 15 to 20
seconds. After his long runs of 22 miles, da Costa completed the
workouts with 10 or 15 100-meter sprints, Cavalheiro said. He also
employs jumping and bounding exercises used by sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   Da Costa began running 10 years ago, and, on the track, has run
13:37 for 5,000 meters and 28:07 for 10,000. He also finished third
in the 1994 world half-marathon championships, and 1:00.54, but
nothing suggested that he was ready to shatter the world record for
26.2 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Now the accomplishments of da Costa and Ramos and Luis dos
Santos, a two-time winner of the Chicago Marathon, suggest that
Brazil is an emerging marathon nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are as good as the Africans, and now they are
using scientific training,'' Posso said. ``They have a coach who
knows how to coach, they are eating properly and they are using
heart-rate monitors to train. It's totally professional. That made
the difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
