<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TESTAVERDE'S ARM, JET SEASON, BOTH REVIVED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Vinny Testaverde had no feeling from his
shoulder to his fingers, but inside his helmet he was fine. He was
not thinking about his own misfortune, but about the two
quarterbacks on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about Ray Lucas not getting any snaps in
practice,'' Testaverde recalled, ``and how Glenn might have to go
in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   His concern for his fellow quarterback was on target. This was
early Sunday, with the Jets ahead by a simple touchdown and the
season hanging in the balance. The Jets had lost their first two
games, and their fans were nearly as numb as Testaverde's throwing
arm.
</P>
<P>
   A regular for almost all of his 11 seasons in the league,
Testaverde has had to adjust to the concept of being a backup
quarterback. In the ever-beefed-up National Football League,
however, there is no such thing as an invisible or dormant backup.
Everybody is on full-stage alert.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde was playing Sunday because Glenn Foley's ribs were
all bunged up, so early in the season. And Lucas, the nominated
backup quarterback for the day, is a dashing role player but not
expected to lead a team for more than three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my shoulder was separated,'' said Testaverde, who
has had it happen before.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde had gone diving on the unforgiving artificial turf
for a teammate's fumble, and a phalanx of 300-pound brutes had
fallen on him.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years ago, a quarterback's getting hit was the
equivalent of being struck by a sedan; in this chemical age the
experience is now the equivalent of being clobbered by a sport
utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Then, slowly, Testaverde felt the tingle in his arm. The injury
was only a stinger. Meanwhile, his mind was still working. The
referee came over and said it would cost the Jets a timeout if
Testaverde stayed on the field after the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the scoreboard and it was third-and-12,'' he said
later, although it had actually been third down and 14 yards to go.
``I thought it was better if I came out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas came in for one play, the Jets punted, and then Testaverde
came back to lead the Jets to a 44-6 victory over the Indianapolis
Colts, the right opponent for a team in trouble. The Jets hardly
needed that extra timeout he had saved by walking off the field
after his injury.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde wound up completing 12-of-21 passes for 203 yards. He
had four touchdown passes, the second time he has thrown that many
in one game in his career. There was little sense that a star was
being born. Basically, the Jets were just running right over the
Colts, offense, defense, special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Testaverde is too old, and too established, for the
theatrics of being discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier for me to come in and play this way than if I was
a backup all my career,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The discerning fan will note that there has been no mention so
far of any so-called quarterback controversy, the very stuff of
football. Bill Parcells, the oft-sarcastic coach of the Jets, was
in such a jolly mood that he merely rolled his eyes at questions of
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the future. The Jets have next weekend off on a schedule
that gives four different teams a bye at a time. The week off let
Parcells be almost expansive in his discussion of his quarterbacks.
He would have used Lucas first Sunday if Testaverde had not
continued. Foley was merely the ``third quarterback,'' in uniform
but available only in case of injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a good job,'' Parcells said of Testaverde. ``When
you're moving the ball around, you can throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there any question about who will play quarterback in two
weeks, when the Jets play host to Miami?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there sure is,'' Parcells said, then, referring to
Foley: ``If you could tell me how he is, then I'd know better. If
he's OK, I'd plan on playing him. He was available for spot duty,
but I'd hate to use him.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Testaverde think he should be starting in two weeks? He
replied: ``Personally, I think I should get $8 million, but you
don't always get what you want. It's the coach's decision if I
play, and if it's Glenn, I'll be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Was it disappointing to know he might be a backup in two weeks?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can disappoint me,'' Testaverde said. ``We had too
good a game.''
</P>
<P>
   He has no complaints, at the moment. And the Jets' fans can feel
life returning to their season, the way the sensation returned to
Testaverde's throwing arm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
