<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TV-TAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS HAVE DIFFERING PLANS FOR HANDLING CLINTON VIDEOTAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-BLACKCAUCUS,
CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLICY, CLINTON-JEWS-REACT.) 
(th) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Videotape of President Clinton's Aug. 17 grand jury testimony
will begin rolling on the major all-news cable television networks
as soon as it is released to them Monday morning, but the three
major broadcast networks plan to use only parts of the video at
first, incorporated into live reports beginning at 9 a.m. or as
soon as the tapes are released.
</P>
<P>
   CNN, MSNBC, Fox News Channel and C-Span all plan to carry the
four hours' worth of testimony in its entirety, spokesmen said.
They will also release the videotaped testimony simultaneously on
their websites.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, CBS and NBC will have their anchormen _ Peter Jennings, Dan
Rather and Tom Brokaw, respectively _ leading coverage of the
videotape's release, but all three were unsure how many excerpts
they would run or how long they will stay on the air in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The length of time depends on the content,'' said Kim Akhtar,
a CBS spokeswoman. ``We won't play this wall-to-wall without any
kind of context, perspective and analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   The three major networks will also cut into their normal
programs during the day if news developments warrant, and all three
plan to expand their evening news broadcasts to a full hour,
instead of the usual half-hour, from 6:30 to 7:30 p.m. Eastern
time.
</P>
<P>
   NBC also plans to devote its Monday-night edition of
``Dateline'' (10 p.m. Eastern time) to the testimony, and ABC plans
a special one-hour edition of ``Nightline,'' to begin 35 minutes
after the end of ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   All three broadcast networks will also carry the entire four
hours of testimony on their websites, in video, as soon as it is
released. That video will carry advisories warning of possible
objectionable content.
</P>
<P>
   The all-news cable networks also will label the testimony with
warnings about the adult nature of the content, and will add spoken
advisories from time to time as well.
</P>
<P>
   CNN Headline News, which is not carrying the testimony
videotape, will break into its normal coverage to televise
President Clinton's speech at the United Nations, at 10 a.m.
Monday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
