<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-780(     09-20 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHROEDER THE INVULNERABLE? LOOK AT HIS RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This story was eliminated earlier and is now reinstated.)  
(js) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, Germany _ He went to the opera in Vienna with the
chairman of Volkswagen. He took a spin on the Boeing yacht in
Seattle last year. He has visited with Bill Gates, the chairman of
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   If Gerhard Schroeder has tried to communicate anything during
his long quest to unseat Chancellor Helmut Kohl, it is that he is
worldly and modern. A Social Democrat who started out as a Marxist
student leader, he now talks easily about working with both
business and labor to tackle Germany's high unemployment and
prepare for the future.
</P>
<P>
   But with elections just one week away, Schroeder's past is
coming back to haunt him. As the premier of Lower Saxony since
1990, he presides over a state with nearly 11 percent unemployment
_ one of the highest rates in western Germany. The state's budget
is a shambles, groaning under a mountain of debt. Job-training,
school budgets and community programs have been cut back, and
bigger cuts are likely next year.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Kohl and his Christian Democratic Union,
steadily gaining in national polls, have begun to hammer at
Schroeder's problems at home. The issue was a major theme in the
Sept. 12 state elections in Bavaria, where the Social Democrats
suffered a major setback by receiving only 28.7 percent of the
vote. Schroeder continues to lead Kohl in national polls by two or
three percentage points, but many voters are still undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents charge that Schroeder is all show and no substance, a
person who thrives on dramatic gestures but whose state
nevertheless lags behind in key respects.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves to be the trouble-shooter, to jump into situations
where he can rescue a factory from being shut down,'' said Fritz
Muller, a senior economic adviser to Christian Democrats in the
state parliament. ``The problem is, he doesn't have any fundamental
economic policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder has shown a knack for bailing out troubled local
factories. Brushing aside objections from environmentalists, his
government has spent hundreds of millions of marks to deepen a
small river so that a family-owned shipbuilder could build luxury
liners and deliver them to the Baltic Sea.
</P>
<P>
   When Preussag AG wanted to sell its steel mill in March to an
Austrian company, Schroeder's government bought the factory for
about $600 million and then quickly listed it on the stock
exchange. It has also propped up Continental Tire, based in Lower
Saxony, and taken over an airplane maintenance center that
Daimler-Benz wanted to shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder and his supporters say such actions show their
resourcefulness as the state's old manufacturing industries
struggle with global competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is not how we compare with other states today,
but whether things look better now than they did when we came into
power,'' said Alfred Tacke, Schroeder's state secretary for
economics. ``We think there has been progress.''
</P>
<P>
   But government statistics show that Lower Saxony has grown more
slowly than most other western German states for the last several
years _ and more slowly than several eastern German ones. While
industrial growth has roared ahead in states like Bavaria,
Germany's wealthiest, it barely limps along here. And while
Schroeder talks about creating 100,000 more job-training positions
and investing in technology, his own state has invested much less
than many others.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's record here provides a vivid insight into his
personality and his style of governing. The picture that emerges is
of a relentlessly pragmatic leader who thrives on protecting jobs
but is bored by economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of sympathy for him,'' said Gernod Preuss,
president of Lower Saxony's association of employers, who has known
Schroeder for two decades. ``He has learned a lot about business,
and he has consistently said that the state can only be successful
if the economy is successful.''
</P>
<P>
   He relishes his role as a member of Volkswagen's supervisory
board, a position he holds because the government of Lower Saxony
owns 20 percent of the company. When Volkswagen was in danger of
bankruptcy in 1993, he strongly supported brutal cost-reduction
measures that raised howls of protest from suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   But Schroeder gets much poorer grades as a thinker. Executives
and many local government officials complain that he was sloppy
about finances when the state was booming in the early 1990s and
was then caught by surprise when the economy slowed to a crawl. And
they were infuriated this year when Schroeder unilaterally vetoed
Preussag's decision to sell its steel mill and had the state take
it over instead.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Today, Schroeder's budget problems are among the most acute of
any state in western Germany, and his lieutenants have been
scrambling to keep them from damaging his campaign for chancellor.
The state's total debt has ballooned from 37 billion marks in 1989
(then about $23 billion) to more than 62 billion marks (about $34
billion) last year. The debt here has grown faster than in any
other state in western Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, the state supreme court ruled for the second time
that Lower Saxony's budget deficit violates legal limits. Local
governments, meanwhile, have sued the state, maintaining that it
has shortchanged them by about $300 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders now contend that Schroeder faces a shortfall
of nearly $3 billion in the two-year state budget for 1999 and
2000, and they are asking a court to force him to reveal his budget
before the elections. Schroeder's lieutenants have said they won't
even show their draft to the parliament until just before
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The financial straits have seriously cut into social programs.
Local school districts have all but stopped hiring new teachers,
and one town on the northern coast went so far as to use its own
money to do so. The University of Hanover has been forced to
increase the size of classes, delay renovations and lay off
clerical workers. At a community counseling program in Hanover for
battered women, workers have gone without pay since the government
cut off money several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lower Saxony's level of joblessness, at 10.7 percent, is
markedly higher than the western German average of 9.1 percent. Its
level of youth unemployment, at 13.9 percent, is the highest of any
western German state.
</P>
<P>
   Yet because the state's budget has been so cramped, Schroeder's
government has spent far less than other states on training
programs and investment in new industries.
</P>
<P>
   Lower Saxony has privatized about $1 billion worth of
state-owned companies, but it has used almost all that money either
to make interest payments on its debt or support entitlement
programs. Defenders of Schroeder say he has had to wrestle with
long-term problems that were evident before he came to power. Lower
Saxony's industry was dominated by old-line manufacturing companies
that have been battered by global competition since the 1980s.
Volkswagen, the state's biggest company and the anchor for an
extensive industry of parts suppliers, came perilously close to
bankruptcy in 1993 before it put itself through brutal cost
reductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame Schroeder for everything,'' said Wilfried
Prewo, president of Hanover's chamber of commerce and industry.
``Unemployment was high before he came to power. He started out
with a pile of debt.''
</P>
<P>
   But Prewo did say that Schroeder had made mistakes. When
Schroeder was elected premier in 1990, Lower Saxony was in the
midst of a boom resulting from the re-unification of Germany.
Because the state lies right on the old eastern border, its
companies sold vast amounts of equipment and services when the Bonn
government pumped hundreds of billions of dollars into rebuilding
the east.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of using the good years to shore up the state's
finances or invest in new industries, it embarked on new
entitlement programs, such as giving free school materials to every
child in the state. When the economy in eastern Germany went into a
deep slump around 1995, Schroeder was left with billions of dollars
in additional debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``His miscalculation was that the growth would go on forever,''
said Prewo. ``He didn't invest his surpluses, but rather consumed
them on long-term commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   But even his critics acknowledge that Schroeder has an
unorthodox cleverness, which he showed after acquiring Preussag's
steel mill in February.
</P>
<P>
   The move outraged free-market purists and many business leaders.
But then Schroeder took advantage of what was still a booming stock
market and listed the company on the stock exchange in June. The
government sold most of its stake for a cash profit of about $25
million, and still owns shares worth several hundred million
dollars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980920.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HILLARY-2TAKE     09-20 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HILLARY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY`S RESPONSE TO SCANDAL: MORE WORK, MORE INTENSITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Colo., Wash., Ore., Calif.)  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-BLACKCAUCUS,
CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLICY, CLINTON-JEWS-REACT, CLINTON-TV-TAPE.) 
(mk) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the dedication of the new Peace Corps
headquarters last week, Hillary Rodham Clinton cut a long red
ribbon with two-foot-long scissors and nearly signed up.
</P>
<P>
   When the Peace Corps director praised the first lady for her
character and said she would be a great volunteer, Mrs. Clinton
deadpanned, ``Maybe I'll just leave this afternoon. Point me in the
right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Mrs. Clinton really wants escape from Washington, or from
the humiliation and betrayal her friends say she feels, she is not
showing it. Nor is she talking about forgiveness, leaving her
husband to do all the atoning and confessing on his own for the sex
scandal that may doom his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she is playing her role as first lady with a
no-time-to-waste-hello-goodbye intensity that is both breathtaking
and unnerving, struggling to change the subject with passionate
talk about health care, education and family, and fighting to win
back disillusioned voters, especially women.
</P>
<P>
   To outsiders, paradoxically, the first lady has never looked
better, sounded stronger or even seemed happier. Her popularity
rating is high. Her loyalists say that no matter what happens to
Bill Clinton, she is a lady with a future. Every day seems to be a
good-hair day.
</P>
<P>
   She is said to feel pressure, not to leave Clinton or to come to
his defense, but to get a lot of things done before her tenure
ends, whenever that may be. There's simply no time to fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gets up in the morning and takes a shower and puts on her
makeup and a nice dress and does her events,'' said Sara Ehrman, a
Middle East expert who has been one of Mrs. Clinton's closest
friends since the 1968 McGovern campaign. ``She went on vacation
and probably ate chocolates and pulled the covers over her head and
pitched her fits. Have you ever said to yourself, I want to have a
nervous breakdown but I don't have the time now? It's enough
already.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Marsha Berry, Mrs. Clinton's press secretary, ``She doesn't
wallow.''
</P>
<P>
   So Mrs. Clinton has made her already full fall schedule even
fuller. On Thursday, for example, she appeared with pop singer
Kenneth ``Babyface'' Edmonds to accept a grant to buy musical
instruments for public schools, and met at the White House with
educators and executives to promote corporate support for the arts
in public schools. Then she gave a speech that evening on the need
for American engagement around the world as she picked up an award
for ``raising consciousness'' globally for family issues.
</P>
<P>
   To raise her own foreign policy consciousness the day before,
she called in senior officials like the national security adviser,
Samuel Berger, and more than a dozen outside experts, including
former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, to brief her on
America's role in the post-Cold War world. She plans to travel to
Chile, Haiti, Uruguay and the Dominican Republic later this month
to promote development and women's issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gets sustenance from her work, sustenance from her friends
and this is the cloth through which she has her support system,''
said Melanne Verveer, her chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's most immediate goal is to stanch the damage of
her husband's errant sex life at the polls this November.
</P>
<P>
   While Democratic candidates are shunning the president, they are
clamoring for her. And this week she is slated to campaign for
Democratic candidates for Congress in New York, Colorado,
Washington, Oregon and California.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, two dozen female lawmakers who came to the White
House for 90 minutes of tea and conversation prevailed on her to do
even more.
</P>
<P>
   They referred to the scandal as ``the clutter,'' telling Mrs.
Clinton that there was an urgent need to cut through it and focus
on issues that mattered to them and their constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told her that as women, we know that women can do more than
one thing at a time in an emergency,'' said Rep. Lynn Woolsey,
D-Calif. ``If there's an emergency, women still make their kids'
lunches, listen to the news, get ready for work, pay the bills. So
we asked her to get on a plane and stop at places where her voice
so desperately needs to be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is so seized with this fall's elections that at a
Democratic fund-raiser in New York last Monday she wasted no time
in gathering intelligence. ``I hadn't been with her two minutes
when she asked me to evaluate what the state-by-state prospects
might be,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J. ``We didn't focus
on the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes the ``problem'' intrudes.
</P>
<P>
   At a National Council of Negro Women black-tie dinner for 2,000
people honoring Dr. Dorothy Height, there was Mrs. Clinton all
dressed up in a black, V-necked, sequined St. John knit.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the Rev. Jesse Jackson, the sometimes White House
confessor, using his invocation time to tell Mrs. Clinton that no
one knows exactly what to say to her during this crisis. The crowd
applauded as he praised her as a woman of ``uncompromising
dignity.'' He then prayed to God to ``forgive us for our sins and
the foolishness of our ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton put on her serenely opaque face. While Jackson may
feel like talking about forgiveness, she is keeping quiet.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1994 news conference, Mrs. Clinton spoke of her desire for
``a zone of privacy'' and has always struggled to keep up a thick
wall that few are allowed to penetrate.
</P>
<P>
   After a Clinton confidante suggested earlier this month that
Mrs. Clinton might make a stand-by-your-man statement of support
for her husband, one of her close allies asked her about it. ``Her
answer was, 'Look, this is a purely private issue and we're working
it through, and if I have anything to say it's going to be if and
when I say it,''' the ally said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Neel Lattimore, who was the first lady's press spokesman for
five years, said that there is a political motive as well. ``If she
went out there and said, `I forgive my husband,' well, what woman
so quickly does forgive and forget? She is very smart politically
and this has political ramifications. She will choose her moment.''
</P>
<P>
   When reporters ask about the first lady's marriage, Ms. Berry
repeats the mantra authorized by her boss: ``She has made it clear
that she supports her husband, she loves him and she forgives
him.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the first lady's aides, she has not shared even
with them her feelings about either the investigation or her
husband. ``She has not talked about her personal situation, and all
of us to a person honors the fact that that is absolutely
private,'' Ms. Verveer said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the aftermath of the Starr report, Mrs. Clinton has
abandoned her verbal war against her husband's enemies. She is no
longer publicly blaming the scandal on a right-wing conspiracy
against him.
</P>
<P>
   That's because she now knows the facts about Monica Lewinsky,
her supporters say. ``She was not privy to the information,'' said
Ms. Berry.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, the Clintons are giving the impression that they have
never been closer.
</P>
<P>
   At the state dinner at the White House for Czech President
Vaclav Havel last week, Mr. and Mrs. Clinton smiled and cooed and
held hands throughout the evening. She waved her arms and he
mouthed the lyrics as they danced to the Marine Band's rendition of
``Mustang Sally.''
</P>
<P>
   In her speeches, she talks frequently about her ``husband'' and
``the president'' in promoting his policies.
</P>
<P>
   And what she is doing is greatly appreciated. ``She has been
very supportive of the president publicly in terms of her events
and that's been great,'' said Douglas Sosnick, the president's
counselor. ``It's not my place to suggest anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Her close associates insist she has not read the Starr report
with its salacious allegations about Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky,
including Ms. Lewinsky's account of a conversation in which the
president told her he had had hundreds of lovers in his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a report in large part that is designed to embarrass and
humiliate,'' said Ms. Verveer. ``Why would she spend her time
reading it?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berry said that Mrs. Clinton is scarcely reading the
newspapers or watching television, except for Chicago Cubs games.
She is said to be exercising every day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
