<HEADER>
A5009 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LASTWEEK-COX     09-20 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LASTWEEK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Final week of season promises answers to questions
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The final week of baseball's regular season should be
just like the first 25 _ breathtaking. There are some many
questions needed to be answered, so little time to do so.
</P>
<P>
   No playoff-bound club, despite that five of the six divisions
have been wrapped up, knows who they will be playing in the
divisional playoffs. There is the home run race between Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa and who will finish with the new standard.
There are wildcard spots to be won, final impressions for all the
awards to be made, close races for both batting titles to end.
</P>
<P>
   What to look for:
</P>
<P>
   _ The home run race: On paper, Sosa should be able to hit a few
homers this week considering he has two games left against the
Brewers and 10 of his 63 homers have come against Milwaukee
pitching. But Sosa doesn't get the benefit of the wind blowing out
at Wrigley Field, spending all week on the road. McGwire has to
face the pitching-tough Astros but he does get to close out the
season against Montreal in St. Louis where he is hitting .307 and
has 33 of his 65 homers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The wild cards: Remember the division race between the Braves
and the Giants in 1993, which came down to the final game and
Atlanta slipped past by winning its 104th game? Well, that's what
happening between the Mets and Cubs for the NL wildcard. For almost
six weeks, the most the has separated the two clubs has been one
game, that margin now being held by the Mets. Neither team really
has an advantage when it comes to their schedule as the Cubs close
out the season in Houston and New York in Atlanta. Braves manager
Bobby Cox, even if his team has wrapped up the league's best
record, will want to beat the Mets considering the club would much
rather play the Cubs in the first round rather than Houston or San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox can't just seem to put away the AL wildcard, having
lost three straight and they are four games up on Toronto. The Red
Sox, known for their late September disasters, is at home all week
with three with Tampa Bay and four with the Orioles. The Blue Jays
are also at home, with three against the Orioles and three against
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   _ The battle in the AL West: For a moment there it appeared as
if the Rangers were going to pull away from the Angels. But Texas
can't stand prosperity and this spot could come down to these next
three nights where the club face each other In Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _ The battle for the NL best record: The Braves lead the spot by
two games over the Astros and head to Florida for two and then back
home against the Mets. The Astros have two in St. Louis and three
with the Cubs while the Padres appear out of the hunt at 4 1/2
games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the season ended today: In the AL, the Yankees would open
up with Anaheim in a best-of-five series and the Indians would host
the Red Sox. In the NL, the Braves would open the first round with
the Padres and Houston would play the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   _ The batting titles: The NL race has come down between
Colorado's Larry Walker (.355) and John Olerud (.354) of the Mets.
Walker may be helped by the fact that he is playing very little
lately while Olerud is caught up in a wildcard chase. On the AL
side, New York's Bernie Williams (.336) has a four-point lead over
Boston's Mo Vaughn. Williams will get some time off this week while
Vaughn must stay in the lineup until the Red Sox clinch the
wildcard.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cy Youngs: Both races are close. In the NL, Braves
lefthander Tom Glavine may be out front after becoming the major's
first 20-game winner with a shutout Saturday while teammate Greg
Maddux, stuck on 17 wins, may be out. Glavine's biggest competition
will come from San Diego where starter Kevin Brown (18-7) has the
league's second best ERA (2.44) and whether voters will go with
closer Trevor Hoffman, who perhaps has been the most dominant of
any pitcher this year.
</P>
<P>
   The AL side is as tough. Boston's Pedro Martinez was the
favorite until he lost three straight and now it appears that
Toronto's Roger Clemens will win his fifth Cy Young and second in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   _ MVPs: Sosa should win the NL version considering how he has
carried his team all year but McGwire will get a lot of votes. The
AL is wide open though it may come down between Seattle teammates
as Ken Griffey Jr. has 53 homers and 137 RBIs while Alex Rodriguez
has 40 homers, 119 RBIs and 43 stolen bases. With 43 homers and a
major league-leading 154 RBIs, Rangers outfielder Juan Gonzalez
could help his chances with a big week that pushes his club to a
division title.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
