</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-INSIDE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside College Football
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ For those Tennessee fans who want to spend
this week celebrating Saturday night's emotional 20-17 overtime win
against Florida, Volunteers coach Phillip Fulmer has two words:
Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame opened the 1998 seaon with an equally emotional
victory over Michigan. The following week the Fighting Irish looked
like a team without a clue when they were embarrassed by 0-2
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   You don't think the same thing can happen to the No. 4
Volunteers Saturday night against Houston? Here are two more words,
said Fulmer: Florida State. The Seminoles were ranked No. 2 on
Sept. 12 and never dreamed they could lose to N.C. State.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we'll be reminding our players of those things this
week but I also think our guys will handle it (beating Florida)
maturely,'' said Fulmer, who got only a few hours sleep before
going back to his desk on Sunday. ''But we've been a pretty
consistent team over the years. We don't usually go up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston (0-3) is certainly not a good team but the Cougars did
make No. 3 UCLA work for a 42-24 win on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it may be hard for the Vols to concentrate on the
Cougars, given the October guantlet awaiting them. They play back
to back road games at Auburn (Oct. 3) and Georgia (Oct. 10). After
a week off, they face improving Alabama at home on Oct. 24.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this team knows that we're going to have to play hard
every week to have a chance,'' said Fulmer. ''They know this is a
blue-collar team. We're going to have to fight for everything we
get.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Tennessee can get past those games and get to November,
it has a great chance to run the table. In the 90s, Tennessee is
30-1 in the month of November.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier: it's not over
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss to Tennessee, Florida coach Steve Spurrier said
Sunday he is not conceding the SEC East to anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got to play eight conference games and I think the SEC
is very tough and very even this year,'' said Spurrier. ''We just
have to wait and see how everything plays out.''
</P>
<P>
   No mystery why Florida is struggling. The Gators have nine
fumbles in three games, one more than they had all of last season.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night Florida had five turnovers, nine penalties, and
had to burn several timeouts because of miscommunication on the
sidelines. Florida fumbled once going into the Tennessee end zone
and then had to settle for a field goal inside the Volunteer
five-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Right now the Gators are playing very un-Gator like.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now we don't have 11 guys who know what to do out
there--at least on offense,'' said Spurrier, whose team hosts
Kentucky on Saturday. ''We've got to sharpen up our assignments on
each play.''
</P>
<P>
   There was more bad news for Florida on Sunday: Cornerback Tony
George suffered a severe knee sprain against Tennessee and will be
out for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Vols No. 4 in both polls
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's win over Florida elevated Tennessee to No. 4 in both
of the major polls that were released on Sunday. It also left the
polls in an unusual state. For the first time in almost eight
years, a team from the state of Florida is not ranked in the top
five.
</P>
<P>
   Florida (2-1) dropped from No. 2 to No. 8 in the Associated
Press poll of sportswriters. Florida State, which trounced Duke,
moved back into the Top 10 at No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a team from the Sunshine State was out of the top
five was Oct. 27, 1990, when Miami was eighth, Florida State 12th,
and Florida 15th.
</P>
<P>
   Just thinking
</P>
<P>
   --Looks like Auburn is rethinking this idea about running the
football. After losing 50 yards to quarterback sacks, Auburn was
heled to just 21 yards on 28 carries in Saturday's 31-19 loss to
LSU.
</P>
<P>
   ''We made our minds up that we weren't going to lose like we did
to Virginia (19-0),'' said Bowden. We were going to do things that
win games.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for Auburn's miracle win over Alabama last season,
Saturday's loss to LSU would have been the fifth straight at home
for the Tigers. They get this week off and host Tennessee on Oct.
3.
</P>
<P>
   --Maybe Kansas State is for real. The Wildcats (3-0) did
anything they wanted in beating Texas 48-7. The coaches who vote in
their poll are convinced, putting Kansas State third. The writers
in the AP poll remain skeptical and have K-State at No. 5. Kansas
State's next test will beat Colorado on Oct. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
