<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIKINGS-COX     09-20 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vikings' patience tames the Lions
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Football is mostly a game about speed, but as the
undefeated Minnesota Vikings demonstrated here on Sunday afternoon
in their 29-6 victory over the Detroit Lions, patience is often as
significant a virtue as quickness.
</P>
<P>
   Victimized by their own aggressiveness and haste during a first
half that ended in a 6-6 tie, the Vikings advanced to 3-0 for the
second time in three years by emphasizing a steadier approach on
both sides of the ball over the last two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like we thought, `Oh, boy, a rookie quarterback' on
those first couple series and we probably were aggressive to a
fault,'' said Vikings defensive coordinator Foge Fazio. ``You see a
guy starting his first NFL game and the reaction is to get after
him. You see Barry Sanders running to the sideline and everybody
wants to sprint after him. But the biggest thing you need is
discipline ... and we had that after halftime.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the Vikings gradually began to control Sanders and
Lions first-time starter Charlie Batch, the first series of the
second half was a microcosm of the turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   On first down from the Detroit 14-yard line, Sanders was buried
for a 2-yard loss off left tackle by defensive end John Randle. On
second-and-12, middle linebacker John McDaniel came through an
inside gap cleanly to stuff Sanders for minus-3 yards. Instead of
blitzing on third-and-long, Fazio called for a ``cover-two'' zone
and Batch was forced to scramble for 4 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Slippery all-purpose threat David Palmer returned the subsequent
punt 44 yards to the Lions' 22-yard line, and three plays later
Minnesota quarterback Randall Cunningham rifled a 5-yard touchdown
pass to Randy Moss. The Vikings went on to score on four straight
possessions, three of which originated in Detroit territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first (defensive) series set the tone for the whole
second half,'' said McDaniel, who had eight tackles, 1 1/2 sacks,
one pass defensed, a forced fumble and a fumble recovery. ``We
really carried the play to them after that.''
</P>
<P>
   With the usually explosive Minnesota offense struggling to take
advantage of ``red zone'' opportunities _ five drives ended in Gary
Anderson field goals as the 17-year veteran became the No. 2 scorer
in NFL history _ the defense had to carry the Vikings as well.
</P>
<P>
   To eliminate the double-team blocking Randle typically commands
when he plays at the ``under'' tackle position, Fazio moved the
All-Pro defender outside to end. After blitzing on 11 of Detroit's
first 23 offensive snaps and being burned at times by Batch runs,
he settled on a five-man rush with zone coverage on the back end
thereafter. And once the Vikings widened the lead, Sanders was no
longer a factor.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Sanders carried 13 times for 12 yards, with
five of the rushes for negative yardage. For the day, he had 22
carries for 69 yards, but 10 rushes went for 1 yard or less as
McDaniel and weakside linebacker Dwayne Rudd hounded him
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Fazio and his charges were abetted by dubious play-calling from
the Detroit offensive staff. Nursing a 6-3 lead midway through the
second quarter, the Lions never gave the ball to Sanders again in
the first half. Instead, they called 12 consecutive pass plays and
Batch, who scrambled for 63 yards on eight carries, slowly came
undone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking nothing away from (Batch), because I thought he showed
a lot of poise,'' Vikings coach Dennis Green said. ``But as long as
he's running the ball, and not Barry Sanders, I can live with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
