<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin wins at Dover
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ Mark Martin gave Jeff Gordon an old fashioned
whipping Sunday at Dover Downs Speedway, leading 380 of the 400
laps for his sixth victory of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, however, hardly could feel the pain. While Martin
dominated, beating Gordon to the MBNA Gold 400 checkered flag by
2.036 seconds, he cut only 10 points into his rival's Winston Cup
championship war chest. He now trails by 194 points with seven
races left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is the glue that holds a championship together,''
Martin said. ``We lost 140 points two weeks ago at Darlington. The
only way we can be a contender is if he loses 140 points or 75
twice. If we hadn't been so hooked up, he would have won again
today.''
</P>
<P>
   That Gordon didn't have anything for Martin can be attributed to
Martin's gile and tenacity in working lap traffic over the final 49
laps laps with a 1.026-second lead. Gordon never could close within
a car length, though he also skirted the same traffic as Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to congratulate Mark and that team,'' Gordon said.
``They did a great job; had the car to beat. they pretty much had
us whipped all day. There, at the end, was about the best my car
had been all day. I was just too tight on those long runs. You go
back and forth, loose-tight, loose-tight. We got the best we could
out of it today.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin got the best he could muster, also. He needed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't been so hooked up, he would have won again. They
threw everything they had at the end,'' Martin said. ``But, we had
a dominant car. This is what it's all about. I'm so happy for the
entire Valvoline team.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon led only once for six laps in the middle of the day.
Whatever momentum he might have mustered went plop on lap 246 when
he was black flagged and ordered into the pits. His pit crew a lap
earlier had pulled the fenders out from the wheels. Gordon came to
the pits in third place and left in ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to have to ask NASCAR about that (black
flag),'' Gordon said. ``I've never heard of anything like that
before.'' ``We didn't do anything to the fenders. I did get hit,
knocked into somebody and caved in the right side,'' Gordon said.
``I don't think it bent anything out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush Grand National Matt Kenseth might have been the
show-stopper. He finished sixth in his first Winston Cup race,
subbing for Bill Elliott, whose father died Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one race, and I appreciate Bill giving me this
opportunity,'' said the 26-year-old Kenseth, who on Saturday won
his third Busch race of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
