A5013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-COACH-COX     09-20 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-COACH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young coaches on the move
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ During her playing career at Georgia Tech , Theresa
Gernatt displayed the characteristics that quickly helped her move
up the ladder of Division I women's basketball assistant coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The walk-on from Marietta, Ga.'s Wheeler High earned a
scholarship and became the team captain because of her leadership
and infectious enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been in my family, it's been in my blood for as long as I
can remember,'' said Gernatt, in her third season as Florida
State's recruiting coordinator. ``I'm doing now what I've always
dreamed of doing, but to be in this position at this point in my
life is truly incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Gernatt, 29, personifies the growing number of young female
assistants who have used momentum from Title IX gender equity
legislation to propel them into full-time jobs in collegiate
sports. She also earned a master's degree at Georgia Tech while
working as an assistant to former athletics director Homer Rice.
</P>
<P>
   But has she paid sufficient dues to fulfill her ambition of soon
becoming a head coach? Are women being pushed along an exceedingly
fast track so university presidents and athletics directors can
tout a progressive hiring record? Gernatt began her networking
while in college, attending the Women's Final Four and confirming
in her own mind that the coaching bug she felt needed to be
parlayed into experience. She has not coached in high school,
unlike many of her older peers _ men and women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess things are different for us now than maybe they were
10 or so years ago,'' Gernatt said. ``I don't know whether I want
to be a head coach or not. But I've had some great mentors, and
it's very important for us to get established that way.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to her current boss at Florida State, Sue Semrau, a
former assistant at Wisconsin, where head coach Jane
Albright-Dieterle served under Tennessee's Pat Summitt for a time.
</P>
<P>
   Those kinds of connections among female coaches have
strengthened in recent years. Ironically, the networking approach
may be keeping more experienced males out of jobs.Vivian Acosta, a
retired Brooklyn College professor and coach who tracks gender
numbers, acknowledged that at the top levels , women basketball
coaches have a statistical advantage, albeit a diminished one, over
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do, and why shouldn't they?'' she said. ``If young women
don't see women in leadership positions, they can never aspire to
do the same thing. Role-modeling is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the gains women have been making on the coaching side,
their presence is nearly invisible at the helm of major athletics
departments _ which oversee men's and women's sports _ and other
administrative posts.
</P>
<P>
   Only two women are overall athletics directors at
football-playing schools in major conferences _ Barbara Hedges at
Washington and Deborah Yow at Maryland. Linda Bruno of the Atlantic
10 is the only female commissioner of a major conference.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno and UNC-Charlotte athletics director Judith Rose have made
attempts at being selected for the men's basketball committee, but
were turned away. The women's committee has had just one male
member in recent years, and former chairwoman Jean Lenti Ponsetto
thinks there's no need to apologize for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of keeping men away,'' she said. ``It's a
chance for women administrators to obtain some leadership
experience that isn't available in other places.''
</P>
<P>
   A good example is former Georgia Tech associate athletics
director Bernadette McGlade, who was a candidate to succeed Rice
when he retired last year. Within months of Dave Braine's
appointment, McGlade was hired as an associate commissioner at the
Atlantic Coast Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
