<HEADER>
A5014 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-OLYMPICS-COX     09-20 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-OLYMPICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A women's place is in the Olympics
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The evolution of women as accepted Olympians did not
take quite as long as the evolution of ape to man. But the starting
points were not too dissimilar.
</P>
<P>
   _ 776 B.C. Inaugural Ancient Olympics are held with no women
competitors. All females caught watching are put to death.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1900 A.D. Women make Olympics debut in two sports _ golf and
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1912 A.D. A record 57 women _ compared with 2,490 men _
compete in Stockholm Games. Baron Pierre de Coubertin, founder of
the Modern Day Games, describes Olympic competition as ``the solemn
and periodic exaltation of male athleticism, with . . . female
applause as reward.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, a woman's place is in the Olympics _ on the field, not in
the stands. Females not only account for greater numbers than ever
_ the 3,685 in Atlanta represented a 33 percent increase over
Barcelona in '92 _ they have shifted the balance of gender power in
U.S. sports. In the last two Summer Games, American women have won
40 percent of the country's medal total, up from 33 percent in the
previous two Games and 23 percent in the five before that.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta '96 has been called the Games of the Woman.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. strides taken in the snow and ice of the Winter Olympics
are even more impressive. In the last three Games, women captured
26 medals to 11 for the males, including 13 of the 17 golds. Two of
the biggest stories in Nagano illustrated the diametric fortunes of
the sexes: The U.S. women's hockey team winning the gold medal,
with the men's team failing to place and some of them acting like
frat boys in vandalizing their dorm rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The women's increasing market share in precious metals has not
gone unnoticed in Colorado Springs, Colo., home of the U.S. Olympic
Committee. Executive director Dick Schultz recently signaled a
shift in the philosophy of slicing the financial pie in even
pieces, announcing a greater emphasis before the next Games in
Sydney (2000) and Salt Lake City (2002) to support sports in which
the U.S. has strong medal hopes. And increasingly more of those
events fall on the women's side.
</P>
<P>
   The apportioning of $26 million in new funds will be decided in
the coming months, with three women's sports _ hockey, soccer and
softball _ already earmarked for a significant increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in putting the most dollars where it can (be)
the most (productive),'' Schultz said. ``You won't necessarily see
a shifting away from a certain sport, but we're thinking about
additional funds that go strictly to performances and potential for
winning medals.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is the success of U.S. women on the rise? Many point to
Title IX, the 1972 legislation that prohibits sexual discrimination
in the sports programs at educational institutions receiving
federal funds. Olympic ``team'' sports are an illustration.
Americans won gold medals in the Olympic debut of softball and
soccer in Atlanta and hockey in Nagano. In basketball, the U.S. has
won three golds and a bronze in the four Games since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   American IOC member Anita DeFrantz said, ``This is the first
generation of girls who grew up in a country that was friendly to
opportunities for women in sports. It's been a cultural change. I
don't know where we would've found a women's soccer team without 20
years of soccer growing in colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known about Evelyn Ashford and Jackie Joyner-Kersee. But
nobody knew about Mia Hamm because she was in a team sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The gold-medal soccer game was played before 76,481 fans at
Georgia's Sanford Stadium, the largest crowd ever to see a women's
sports event. ``Atlanta really opened doors for women's sports,''
Hamm said, ``in terms of allowing people to see our level of play
of soccer. The same with hockey. As a team, we always felt we had
something special. The hardest part was getting people out there to
watch us. People were drawn to the event to be a part of the
Olympic Games. They came away from our final saying it was the best
thing they saw in the whole Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. women also benefited from the fact that many programs
started about the same time as those in most other countries, so
there was little catching up to do.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1900 Games in Paris, women competed in only two sports.
In 2000, they are expected to compete in all but two _ wrestling
and boxing. Weightlifting, modern pentathlon, water polo, taekwondo
and triathlon will welcome women for the first time in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Women's wrestling could be added by 2004. Boxing, while gaining
acceptance in the U.S., remains verboten in many countries and
could be the lone holdout. Arthur Tunstall, an international
amateur boxing association official from Australia, said, ``I am
totally opposed to women's boxing. I think a women is a petite
person, not to be knocked around.''
</P>
<P>
   Perceptions have changed since the Olympics went 32 years
(1928-60) without a women's track race longer than 200 meters. The
abbreviated schedule resulted from the Amsterdam Games in '28, when
five women's track and field women events were introduced. Media
accounts of the women's 800 meters painted a picture of women
collapsing after the race.
</P>
<P>
   One reporter wrote, ``Below us on the cinder path were 11
wretched women, five of whom dropped out before the finish, while
five collapsed after reaching the tape.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFrantz said there were only nine entries, and more recent
accounts say none collapsed. She blames ``the evil men of ink'' for
shaping negative stereotypes, adding, ``It was a basis for women
saying, 'Oh, no, we can't do this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic movement now knows otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
