<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER-NOTES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield thinks Lewis's style a better match
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two years ago, Mike Tyson concluded that if Evander
Holyfield had so much trouble taking out Bobby Czyz, the Atlanta
heavyweight must be too slow, too old and too worn out to inflict
any damage on him.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield bounced back with the peak performance of his
roller-coaster career, introduced Tyson to the canvas and pummeled
him into a daze. After theTKO win, Holyfield reiterated the boxing
adage: ``Styles make fights, and Tyson has a style that's perfect
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to Saturday night, when Holyfield was taken the
distance by little-known contender Vaughn Bean. Could WBC champion
Lennox Lewis be faulted if he suddenly holds Holyfield in less
regard heading into their projected title unification next spring
or summer?
</P>
<P>
   ``It don't matter to me what people think,'' Holyfield said.
``But Lennox Lewis wouldn't be moving as much as Vaughn Bean. I'm
sure Lennox Lewis will try to take my head off and it will put me
in position for me to get his. . . . He has a style that I match up
with well. It'll be an action-packed fight. It probably won't be as
long a fight as (Saturday's).''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield will have to wait a while before testing his
projection. In order to keep two of his three title belts (WBA and
IBF), he likely will face a mandatory opponent next _ the WBA's No.
1 ranked contender, Henry Akinwande.
</P>
<P>
   The two were supposed to meet in June in New York, but the bout
was cancelled when Akinwande tested positive for hepatitis B.
Akinwande has been on medical suspension ever since, but his
manager expects him to pass a blood test soon, then be reinstated
by the New York Athletic Commission. (Even though
Holyfield-Akinwande is likely headed for Las Vegas, states
generally observe each other's suspensions.)
</P>
<P>
   King, Showtime cable network executive Jay Larkin and
Holyfield's attorney, Jim Thomas, will huddle this week to discuss
options. The Akinwande fight would be a pay-per-view event.
</P>
<P>
   Despite going 12 rounds against Bean, Holyfield said he would
have no trouble fighting before the end of the year. ``I'm not
injured, I'm in shape,'' he said. ``I can just take a few weeks off
and be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's trainer, Don Turner, added: ``Bean isn't that big of
a puncher. So going 12 rounds with Vaughn Bean is not like going 12
rounds with a Tyson.''
</P>
<P>
   The imminent fight against Akinwande didn't stop promoter Don
King from starting to pump up a meeting with Lewis, which could
complete Holyfield's goal of claiming all three major title belts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander will fight him anywhere _ in the kitchen, in the
halls, in England,'' King bellowed. ``He's the most wanted man on
the planet. Send out an APB that can lead to the capture of Lennox
Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
