<HEADER>
A5017 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-EVANDER-BISHER21-     09-20 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER-BISHER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An eventful fight night, but not title fight
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This was, indeed, a spectacle of the Sweet Science,
the term that the late A.J. Liebling bestowed on boxing. There is
no fight mob in Atlanta, but one was being created now by an
alumnus of Marion Correctional Institution in Ohio, No. 125734, Don
King. And if you were unsure of the name, all you had to do was
cast your eyes about from the men's room to the forest of banners.
Evander Holyfield, who has cast his seed upon the wind, had set his
own table at home in the Georgia Dome, and this would be his night,
bearing out, as his theme ran, ``what hard work will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the gloss and the garishness hit a crescendo, there were
minor details to be covered, at least 10 preliminaries. The
spear-carriers, though at least five were listed as the
champeenship of some kind of world. These are the sad scenes.
Hopefuls, some scrawny, hungering for their slice of the cake, but
first, something for the till.
</P>
<P>
   Here each one came, preceded by old men, grey and paunchy, and
wizened little men with scrooched-up faces, climbing through the
ropes carrying a bucket with their tiger. He dances about, boxing
the air. They _ busy in the corner, arranging their tools of repair
_ hug him and send him out on his way, prayerfully, to glory.
</P>
<P>
   Most pitiable was a migrant from Uganda, Abdula Ramadan, who
entered the ring with a practiced scowl and left in humiliation.
His enemy was Robert Allen for the ``interim'' middleweight title
of some piece of the world. Allen quickly dispatched the scowl and
Ramadan took refuge, cowering in a corner. Then he made a limp
effort at fighting back and fled to the other corner, hiding his
head under his gloves. He never finished the round, and if that
wasn't enough, he had to stand there watching it over and over
again on the big screen while the gallery jeered and Allen gloated.
</P>
<P>
   Something I'd never seen before was two women fighting. Marquis
of Queensbury rules, I mean. I'm not sure there's a place in my
world for this.
</P>
<P>
   Surely there's a more proper way for two females to settle a
grievance than pummeling each other in public. (Monica Lewinsky and
Hillary Clinton, I'd pay to see.) When one's ``falsie'' came flying
out, that did it. I'm for going back to hair-pulling and clawing.
</P>
<P>
   What I shall say of Evander Holyfield's share of the evening
will have less to do with prizefighting than ancillary matters.
Vaughn Bean turned out to be more than a punching bag for the
night, though he's built like one. A pleasant, pudgy face with the
build of a bullpen catcher, he gave Local Hero a bellyful, and I'm
not certain that if this had been Las Vegas, Holyfield would have
survived the 10th round.
</P>
<P>
   When Bean had become entangled in the ropes, Holyfield whacked
the daylights out of him, helpless to defend himself. There are
rules. You don't hit a man caught in the ropes. It left a smear on
his evening of self-promotion, and though the verdict in his favor
was a foregone conclusion, this did nothing to inflate his sporting
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing, while Bean was down, Holyfield left the neutral
corner, sliding down the ropes to jaw with Butch Lewis, Bean's
manager, who spent his evening lambasting the referee, a Brian
Garry from Tampa. Garry did not distinguish himself as a threat to
Mills Lane. Frequently the fight got out of hand. The Bean corner
was like feeding time at the zoo. Garry never got that bunch in
control.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, it will not go down in the diary of memorable
heavyweight title fights. Holyfield, the event promotor, was more
impressive than Holyfield, the fighter. His punch is losing sting,
but more distressing is that he takes an awful lot of punishment
and that in time takes its toll. Check C. Clay, a.k.a. M. Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is the Sports Editor of The Atlanta Journal,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
