</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER-HUMMER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aging, King ill winds bout blew in
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Beware, Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Beware your 36th birthday that arrives next month. It does not
come gently. It is like a killing frost, and overnight, some night
soon, you will become an old fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Beware the omens of Saturday night. There have been many others,
of course, and you have always been able to beat them back. The
doubt never sticks for long.
</P>
<P>
   This time, in the din of a well-sold Georgia Dome, the puzzle
was Vaughn Bean. And the simple word scramble turned into a Rubik's
Cube. This show got a lot more real than anyone could have
imagined, going the 12-round distance, Bean giving three-quarters
of what he was getting. The one knockdown, in the 10th, was
inconclusive, flawed. We saw you tired; we saw you frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Vaughn is a tougher Bean than advertised. In one way,
he was the winner Saturday night. He made himself known as a
serious fighter with a serious chin. Beneath the gelatinous
midsection, some iron exists.
</P>
<P>
   And granted there is merit to your contention afterwards that
Bean's defensive style did not suit you. ``He may have a style that
confuses me. It's like (Muhammad) Ali and Ken Norton. Norton gave
Ali the blues, but he didn't give nobody else the blues,'' you said
afterwards. Yes, Bean is just made to fight ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there remains this one central warning from the episode: On
what should have been an inspirational night before the home folks,
against a fighter who is not of your pedigree, you lost the final
round on all three judges' cards. The last word was Bean's.
</P>
<P>
   It's nature's way of saying: Cut to the Lennox Lewis denoument
and get the heck out of this play before it turns into a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Above all else, beware the shock-haired promoter. Don King is
the serpent in this garden.
</P>
<P>
   Think he cares for you or your long-term future? Strange how
Sunday morning I just happened to run across a 1991 Esquire column
on King, back when he was solidly with Mike Tyson and in the
business of baiting you. Just keep in mind what he said then:
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander Holyfield's a (n-word). He's going to be a (n-word)
till he dies. If he's rich, he's going to be a rich (n-word), if
he's poor, he's going to be a poor (n-word). ... Big business spits
on the name of Holyfield. ... The people who like him like him
'cause he's docile. Holyfield can be controlled. `Run, Johnny.
Sing, Johnny. Dance, Johnny.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's show, the topic of retirement was inevitably
raised. How much longer can it go when Vaughn Bean is able to push
you around in the 12th round?
</P>
<P>
   King burst in at midanswer before you could complete the thought
of retiring after unifying the heavyweight title. ``When you ask
Rockefeller when he's through pumping oil, then ask when
(Holyfield's) through getting all the money he can out of this,''
he blurted. King sounded very much like the King who brokered
Muhammad Ali's ruinous fight at 38 against Larry Holmes. Fight 'em
until they can only mumble, right?
</P>
<P>
   Another fight, another set of warning signs. None more glaring
then the relationship with King, necessarily forged when it was
time to get at Tyson. Know that King still has bills to pay, many
jurors to reward, and he would meet his expenses with your blood.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
