<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-DRAGILA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pole vaulter overcame stereotypes on, off track
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stacy Dragila, 27, is the American record holder in the women's
pole vault. She talks about breaking into the once all-male sport.
</P>
<P>
   I remember when I was curious about the pole vault back in
junior college. I was going to school with a guy pretty much my
build and he was vaulting. I told him I wanted to try it, and he
kind of laughed at me. He said, ``Oh, women can't do it. They don't
have the upper-body strength. It's not safe for women.''
</P>
<P>
   I listened to him and backed off. It wasn't until I got to Idaho
State a year later that my coach encouraged me and offered me the
chance to try vaulting.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, I was considered a tomboy, anyway. There weren't a
lot of girls where I grew up in Northern California, so I was
always around my brother and the other guys. I played their games.
</P>
<P>
   I used to wear my hair shorter and get those stupid comments,
too. Fortunately, I had really good coaches who told me to have fun
doing sports and that it has nothing to do with your sexuality.
That's how I took it to heart.
</P>
<P>
   I was also fortunate to come along after Title IX, which has
given women more opportunities, more scholarships. That's how I
stayed in sports. My scholarship helped me through. Now I'm a
world-class pole vaulter, and I would never have thought that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
