<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLICY     09-20 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLICY-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TROUBLES CAST SHADOW OVER U.S. FOREIGN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Neb.)  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-BLACKCAUCUS,
CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-JEWS-REACT, CLINTON-TV-TAPE.) 
(lh) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If President Clinton wants a sense of how dangerous
a place the world has become in the midst of a scandal over his
personal conduct, he might want to study the grim faces in the
audience when he rises on Monday at the green marble podium of the
U.N. General Assembly in New York.
</P>
<P>
   There will be the leaders of Asian nations that are being
convulsed by an economic crisis more severe than any since World
War II, and delegates from Russia, which is facing its own economic
and political meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   There will be diplomats from the nations surrounding Kosovo,
where a war is raging in the heart of Europe and where tens of
thousands of refugees are in danger of freezing to death; from
India and Pakistan, which now face off across their common border
with nuclear-tipped missiles, and from Israel and the Palestinian
Authority, which are still far from the peace agreement that the
United States had hoped to broker.
</P>
<P>
   And to the dismay of many in the United Nations, one face will
not be in the crowd of diplomats at the General Assembly, that of a
U.S. ambassador. The nomination of Clinton's choice for the post,
Richard Holbrooke, has been sidetracked until at least early next
year by a Justice Department inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Many on Capitol Hill say that because of the scandal resulting
from his sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky, Clinton lacks the political capital to move Holbrooke's
nomination any faster _ or for that matter, to champion any
significant initiative on foreign policy that requires
congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware, the ranking Democrat on the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said that U.S. foreign policy
was being ``sidetracked'' as a result of the president's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreign leaders who know about the president's difficulties,
who know about the attitude and partisanship of the Congress, are
wondering whether this is a president who can deliver,'' he said in
an interview. ``I think in a sense, foreign policy has been
paralyzed.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a view stated even more forcefully by Republicans. Sen.
Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., who is a fellow member of the Foreign
Relations Committee, returned last month from a trip to the Middle
East, where he met with government leaders in Israel, Egypt, Syria,
Saudi Arabia and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``And every one of those leaders told me that as a result of the
president's problems, his motives when he acts in foreign policy
will be called into question,'' Hagel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coin of the realm in foreign policy is trust, and when you
are not trusted, you cannot lead,'' he said. ``If foreign leaders
don't believe that the American people and the Congress trust our
president, the next question for them is: Why should we?''
</P>
<P>
   No one in Congress has been heard to blame the sex-and-lies
scandal for last week's vote in the House to rebuff the
administration and provide only $3.4 billion in new credits to the
International Monetary Fund, a fraction of what the administration
has said is necessary for the fund to deal with a global financial
crisis. But it certainly did not help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is almost impossible now for President Clinton to pick up
the phone and ask a favor from a member of Congress on a tricky
matter of foreign policy,'' said a senior U.S. diplomat, speaking
on condition of anonymity. ``If there is any lingering good will in
Congress, he'll want to cash that in to prevent his impeachment.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
