<HEADER>
A5025 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-EVANDER-FOLO-COX     09-20 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER-FOLO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield: Tough fight credit to Bean, sport
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Less a slight reddish mark under his left eye, the
heavyweight champion emerged from his latest title defense looking
like he had just gone for a late-night jog. No cuts, no bruises, no
obvious aches _ just a sweaty smile.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for most of the 41,357 who packed the Georgia Dome
late Saturday night was they expected to see Evander Holyfield jog
an easy mile, not labor through a marathon. Ringside judges were
expected to be window dressing, not necessities, in the third pro
hometown bout of his career.
</P>
<P>
   And to think that after six rounds, one judge's scorecard had
Holyfield even with . . . Vaughn Bean?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I love boxing,'' Holyfield said. ``Vaughn Bean
proved that no matter what people say about you, in the end it's up
to you. You're the last word.''
</P>
<P>
   In yet another strange chapter in Holyfield's career, the
champion saw his reputation dip in victory while having his
opponent's climb in defeat. Bean was a 9-to-1 underdog but survived
a furious assault by Holyfield in the first four rounds of their
WBA/IBF title bout, won the middle rounds and came back from a
10th-round knockdown to finish strong in the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield won a unanimous decision by wide margins _ 116-111,
117-110, 117-110. But he managed to score just the one knockdown,
and looked fatigued and frustrated at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like the old Evander who would do great at the
beginning and then get tired,'' said friend and Showtime executive
Jay Larkin, whose cable network carried the bout. ``He was puffing
on his stool after the fourth round. He didn't have that glow we've
been accustomed to seeing lately. I told him afterwards, `Please
don't scare me like that any more.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield deflected all criticism after the fight with praise
for his opponent. Indeed, few expected that Bean would be able to
take so much punishment _ particularly to the body, given that he
weighed a bloated 231 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that (labeled) him a bum are the people who write
stories and who never had a fight,'' said Holyfield's trainer, Don
Turner. ``The guy takes a wicked punch. He's more durable than he
looks. This guy wanted to win. After the eighth round, I told
Evander, `This man can takes a hell of a shot.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Between heavy breaths, Holyfield responded, ``I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield rocked Bean with body shots and uppercuts early, but
the challenger rallied in rounds four through six. (Judge Duane
Ford had the bout even at the midway point, the other two had
Holyfield with a two-point lead.) Holyfield appeared to relax in
those rounds to catch his breath but said later he was struggling
to get a fix on Bean's tendencies. As time went on, Bean's
confidence grew, and Holyfield's jab and combinations became less
frequent.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield finished the eighth round with a flurry and controlled
the ninth. Bean tired in the 10th and often tried to hold Holyfield
after being hit.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the round, Bean lunged forward after being tagged with
consecutive lefts and again tried to clutch onto Holyfield. This
time Holyfield spun out of the way, and his right forearm appeared
to help push Bean into the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   While Bean's cornermen screamed at referee Brian Garry, Bean _
standing but bent over with one arm on the ropes _ was nailed with
a right to his temple and dropped to the canvas. Somehow, he made
it up by the count of seven and survived the round.
</P>
<P>
   Bean later complained that Garry ``didn't do his job'' and that
Holyfield ``could have been more gentlemanly.'' He also said, ``I
thought I won the fight. I'm not satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Garry said he was reaching in to separate Bean and Holyfield
near the ropes but that ``Evander had already started to throw his
punch.'' Bean's promoter, Butch Lewis, criticized pretty much
everything after the fight and argued with Garry in the ring during
a TV interview. Lewis stopped just short of saying he would file a
protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butch is not fighting,'' Holyfield said later. ``People on the
outside always have opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   If nobody else was pleased with Holyfield's performance, it
didn't bother the champion.
</P>
<P>
   Did he take Bean lightly?
</P>
<P>
   ``I take no one lightly. If he couldn't carry himself, I
wouldn't carry him.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he find Bean's defenses difficult to penetrate?
</P>
<P>
   ``He may just have a style that confuses me. It's like
(Muhammad) Ali and Ken Norton. Norton gave Ali the blues, but he
didn't give nobody else the blues.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Holyfield was concerned, there was no reason to be
depressed. He won, he retained his titles and he did so in his
hometown before the largest crowd to see a heavyweight title fight
in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came out, it was a pleasant shock to see all the
people,'' he said. ``I'd like to thank everybody who showed up, and
I'm glad we could give them a good show.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a longer show than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
