<DOCNO> NYT19980920.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLICY     09-20 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLICY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: his impeachment.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senior Clinton administration officials say that the president
remains fully engaged in the conduct of foreign policy. They say
that he may even be more interested in the details of foreign
policy since it provides him with a welcome diversion from his
troubles in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the president directed White House meetings over the
crisis in the Serbian province of Kosovo, where the United States
is threatening to use air strikes to end a Serb onslaught against
the ethnic Albanians who make up a majority of the population
there, and over the standoff with Iraq for its refusal to allow
U.N. weapons inspectors there to do their work.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Secretary of Defense
William Cohen have expressed confidence in the president.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's spokesman, James Rubin, said: ``Secretary Albright
has made clear that she has never had a problem in recent months or
years in getting the president on the phone when she needs him and
doing the work that she needs to do when it needs to be done. She
has expressed her strong confidence in the president's leadership
and his ability to make sound judgments.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, the sole Republican in the Cabinet, said at the Pentagon
last week that Clinton ``continues to be effective in dealing with
national security and foreign policy issues, and as long as he's
able to do that, then he will have the support, I think, of the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the evidence suggests that the president remains fully
engaged in debates within the administration over foreign policy,
his aides say they are dismayed that almost any decisive action
taken by Clinton is now being viewed in Washington and around the
world through the prism of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   That became alarmingly clear, they said, when the president
decided to bomb Afghanistan and the Sudan on Aug. 20 in retaliation
for terrorist attacks on U.S. embassies in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, members of Congress were publicly questioning
whether the air strikes were simply an attempt to divert the
public's attention from the furor over his acknowledgment to a
federal grand jury of his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In an age of satellite television and the Internet, the news of
the president's sexual misadventures _ and the cynicism over his
motives in conducting foreign policy in light of the scandal _
spread to virtually every corner of the globe in a matter of
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sudanese capital of Khartoum, anti-American demonstrators
took to the streets the day after the bombings carrying signs that
bore cartoons depicting Ms. Lewinsky. Other protesters carried
signs with the words ``Wag the Dog,'' a reference to the recent
Hollywood comedy about a president who launches a war in Albania to
divert attention from allegations that he molested a Girl Scout.
</P>
<P>
   Biden said he feared that every critical foreign policy action
taken by the Clinton administration would now be viewed with the
same skepticism, and that it could hinder decision-making as the
White House pondered whether to launch military strikes in Kosovo
and against the Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes time to pull the trigger, the White House will
have to think and expect that every serious observer in the
country, as well as every wacko, is going ask: OK, is this `Wag the
Dog'?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hagel said he did not see how Clinton could ever again reassure
foreign leaders that his decisions were not being influenced by the
scandal. ``The fact is that when you've lost that confidence,
you've lost it forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomats abroad say the scandal has begun to color the way
the United States and its leaders are being perceived abroad,
particularly among nations considered adversaries of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim clerics in Iran, where the name of Ms. Lewinsky is
becoming nearly as well known as that of the president, have cited
the scandal as proof of the decadence of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
that intelligence reports showed that leaders of unfriendly nations
as far-flung as Libya, Cuba and Myanmar were known to have obtained
copies of the full report to Congress by the Whitewater independent
counsel, Kenneth Starr, from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that it is being translated into 100 different
languages for 100 different governments, and every foreign leader
will be reading it with the same idea in mind,'' he said. ``They
see the president as tarnished, probably irretrievably, and they're
wondering how they can capitalize on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
