<DOCNO> NYT19980920.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-RDP-900&AMP;ADD-N     09-20 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RDP-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT IS URGED TO SPEAK TO CONGRESS ABOUT AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Fla., Mass., S.C.)  (See also: CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-BLACKCAUCUS, CLINTON-HILLARY,
CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLICY, CLINTON-JEWS-REACT.) 
(js) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The day before President Clinton's grand jury
testimony beams into television sets across the nation, White House
officials stepped up their accusations Sunday that Republicans are
conducting a smear attack against Clinton, while a leading Democrat
suggested the president should personally visit Congress to answer
its questions.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., a strong ally of the president's,
proposed that Clinton testify and respond to relevant questions
before the House Judiciary Committee as soon as possible. The
testimony, he said, could help the nation sort through its
conflicted feelings about the president's behavior and help it
decide what should be done next.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, supported by Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass and a
Judiciary Committee member, signals the deep dissatisfaction among
many Democrats with Clinton's use of legalisms to try to explain
his affair with Monica Lewinsky, the former White House intern. The
White House has been scrambling to shore up the troops on Capitol
Hill, placing daily phone calls and visits to dozens of Democratic
lawmakers, some of whom have been wavering in their support for the
president.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats, as well as Republicans, have mainly rejected
Clinton's narrow definition of sex and have already concluded that
he lied in saying that the two did not have a sexual relationship.
In many ways, lawmakers have shifted to the next phase of the
Judiciary Committee's mandate, as they try to decide whether the
president's actions amount to impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the question of lying, Frank argued Sunday that Congress
needed to take into account the circumstances of Clinton's conduct.
``Was he lying to cover up some terrible misdeed?'' Frank asked on
the NBC News program ``Meet the Press.'' ``Was he lying to cover up
corruption? Or was it private sex he was embarrassed about?''
</P>
<P>
   In appealing to Clinton to be straightforward with Congress,
Kerry said on ``Meet the Press'' that the panel's inquiry would not
be protracted if the president cooperated fully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the president would be well served to explain
exactly what he did, exactly what he was thinking,'' Kerry said,
adding ``do it to the Judiciary Committee, and let's vote and let's
move on one way or the other, but the nation is being ill served by
this political water torture that's taking place in a highly
calculated, highly partisan way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry skirted questions, however, about whether Clinton should
resign. ``I said that the presidency is diminished, his presidency
is diminished. I think he knows that. Everybody in America
understands that.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman said Sunday that it had not yet
considered Kerry's proposal and had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Gearing up for the Monday morning release of the videotaped
testimony and documents from the report by the independent counsel
Kenneth Starr, White House officials and Democrats took to the
airwaves Sunday and lambasted Republicans for the Judiciary
Committee's decision on Friday to release such sexually explicit
material so quickly and with so few deletions. Among the materials
to be released are Ms. Lewinsky's grand jury testimony, her
immunity agreement and information about materials recovered from
her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that people are going to wonder about the judgment of
people who decided to put a good deal of salacious material that is
completely irrelevant to the charges leveled at the president by
Mr. Starr,'' said John Podesta, the White House deputy chief of
staff. ``They decided that rather than just doing a document dump,
they would do a garbage dump on Monday, and I think people are
going to wonder about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahm Emanuel, a senior White House adviser, echoed those remarks
on the CBS News program ``Face the Nation,'' saying that
Republicans harbored a ``political goal to embarrass the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans on the committee argued that they were following
the full mandate of the House, which voted to make public as much
information as possible, as quickly as possible. They accused
Democrats of trying to score political points by making it appear
as if Republicans are behaving recklessly, instead of openly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important the American people would be able to
evaluate this evidence as we do in Congress so that whatever we
decide, hopefully the American people will confirm and support,''
Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark. and a Judiciary Committee member, said
on the ABC program ``This Week with Sam Donaldson and Cokie
Roberts.''
</P>
<P>
   A CBS poll released Sunday shows that 69 percent of those
surveyed said it was not necessary to release the videotape of
Clinton's testimony, and 59 percent thought the Judiciary Committee
voted to release it to humiliate the president.
</P>
<P>
   Polls also point to a slight erosion of support for Clinton. The
CBS poll, which has an error margin of plus or minus 4 percentage
points, found that 56 percent of its respondents think he should be
censured, while 37 percent favor resignation, a slight increase
from last week.
</P>
<P>
   And the latest Newsweek poll found that 46 percent of those
surveyed said the president should consider resigning, up 7
percentage points from a week ago. Forty-one percent said Congress
should begin impeachment hearings and 64 percent said a censure or
reprimand was in order. The president's approval ratings dipped
slightly and hovered at 58 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his remarks Sunday, Podesta once again emphasized that
Clinton had acknowledged wrongdoing. ``I think we're not attempting
to hide behind legal language,'' Podesta said. ``What he did was
wrong. He misled the public. That's what's important here, and I
think we've admitted that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Podesta said he did not believe that the president's
actions amounted to impeachable offenses, several House Judiciary
Committee members shifted their attention Sunday from the release
of the tape to the sensitive and difficult task at hand: deciding
what constitutes ``high crimes and misdemeanors,'' grounds for
impeachment mentioned in the Constitution that could apply.
</P>
<P>
   Clear battle lines appear to be forming between Democrats and
Republicans over whether perjury, or more specifically lying about
an adulterous sexual affair, warrants an act as serious as
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Does perjury about sex amount to a high crime or misdemeanor?
``I doubt it, not under this circumstance,'' Rep. Robert Wexler,
D-Fla. and a Judiciary Committee member, said on ``Meet the
Press.'' ``It's not foreign policy, it's not domestic policy, it's
not about an Article II of power. It's about an extramarital
affair.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The Constitution doesn't say if the president
doesn't tell the truth, he's out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson insisted that perjury was perjury. ``You can't put it
into compartments and say, `Well, if it's about this subject, it
doesn't matter, if it's about that subject, it does matter.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., said lying before a grand jury was
tantamount to perjury, a ``slam dunk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that a high crime?'' he asked on ``Meet the Press.'' The
founding fathers would say yes, he answered. But Graham added that
``it's got to be a serious crime that would subject anybody at this
table to criminal prosecution, and there's a few things in there
that might meet that standard. There's a lot that won't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
