<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5036 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-COLTS-NYT &LR;      09-20 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-COLTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS HEED COACH'S WARNINGS ANDWALLOP COLTS 44-6 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Before the Jets obliterated the hapless
Indianapolis Colts on Sunday, 44-6, there was a week of practice
that was terrible by all accounts, one that some Jets players say
they will never forget.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Parcells, miserable because of his team's 0-2 start,
was in maybe his worst mood ever. He berated some of his assistant
coaches in meetings. Players, of course, got it just as bad. Any
mistake in practice, no matter how minor, set him off. He told
several players, in particular some defensive linemen, that if they
did not perform against the Colts, they were gone. Period.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he tells guys you're on a one-game notice, you take it to
heart,'' center Kevin Mawae said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like a head coach threatening to end your career to
provide a little motivation. And nothing like a really bad team
coming into your backyard to help salvage your season. The Jets,
who put on one of their best performances in years, would like to
thank the Colts for participating in one of the most lopsided
victories in team history.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 0-2, I told the team this, you don't know if
you're ever going to win another game,'' Parcells said. ``I think
the players responded pretty well today.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even Parcells, who is a tough man to make smile, has to
be pleased with how well the Jets played before the crowd of 79,469
at Giants Stadium. The Jets rushed for a startling 302 yards, only
31 yards behind the team's single-game record, set in 1972 against
New England. Running a lot to the outside, Curtis Martin rushed for
144 yards on 23 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts came into this game with one of the few National
Football League defenses without a sack, and nothing changed. They
rarely pressured Jets quarterback Vinny Testaverde, who threw four
touchdown passes to four different receivers. Terrible tackling by
the Colts, as well as great execution by the Jets' offensive line,
led to 505 yards of total offense for New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a plain, old-fashioned tail-whipping,'' Colts
Coach Jim Mora said. ``That's the thing that happened to us today _
we just got whipped physically. When a team can rush for 300 yards
on you, that is a physical tail-whipping.''
</P>
<P>
   The margin of victory was big, but Jets fans should not make
Super Bowl plans just yet. The Colts (0-3) are not a good team, and
while quarterback Peyton Manning (20 of 44 for 193 yards and 2
interceptions) has superb skills, he is having a rough rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts have scored only two touchdowns this season, and their
defense has given up 97 points in only three games. They failed to
take advantage of Martin's two early fumbles in Jets territory, and
the conservative game plan of Mora, who stuck with two tight ends
for most of the afternoon and stayed with the run even after
falling behind by more than three touchdowns, did not help.
</P>
<P>
   The blowout was the result of a poorly executed Indianapolis
offense, a suddenly fired-up Jets offensive line and great
defensive play by the Jets. Of course, the offensive explosion
could lead to something else: a quarterback controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde started in place of Glenn Foley, who was on the
sideline as the third quarterback because of injured ribs.
Testaverde is sometimes Joe Montana, sometimes Scott Mitchell.
Sunday, he was Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde is known to have good games, then play terrible.
Foley has good games, then gets hurt. Does Parcells go with the
quarterback who Sunday led the Jets to the most points they have
scored since they beat the Patriots _ then coached by Parcells _ by
45-7 in 1993? Or does he go back to the gunslinger Foley?
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said that if Foley is healthy, he will go with him. But
Testaverde's performance will further captivate Parcells, who is
already enamored of his arm. His performance probably only
shortened the rope for Foley.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a concern of ours now, who is going to be the
quarterback,'' said wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson, who had his
third straight game with a touchdown catch. ``We're just happy with
the win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' first four series typified the day. Running back Leon
Johnson, on a beautifully executed screen pass, went 82 yards for a
touchdown behind three key blocks. It was the Jets' longest pass
completion since Nov. 2, 1986, when Ken O'Brien threw 83 yards to
Wesley Walker.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, the Jets faced a first-and-goal at the
1-yard line. Perhaps learning a lesson from last week, when they
were stuffed by Baltimore on four straight runs at the goal line,
Testaverde did a sweet play-action fake to Martin out of a tight
formation, then tossed a touchdown pass to tight end Kyle Brady.
</P>
<P>
   Later, wide receiver Wayne Chrebet, who would leave the game
with a sprained left ankle, caught an 8-yard touchdown pass from
Testaverde for a 21-0 lead. Then, just as the Colts were bracing
for more attacks through the air, Leon Johnson scored on a 16-yard
run behind a brutal pancake block from tackle Jumbo Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult for a team to stop that kind of varies attack,
and the Colts just got sloppier on defense as the muggy afternoon
pressed on.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we take pride in is yards after contact,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps lost in the Jets' explosion is this fact: the Jets are
now 1-0 in the American Football Conference East. They play Miami
two weeks from now, and if the Jets can win, it would be an
entirely new season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could get back to 2-2 with two division wins, we can
start the season over,'' Parcells said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
