 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The streak is finally over.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken's streak of starting in 2,632 games ended Sunday when
the Orioles third baseman pulled himself from the lineup in a game
against the Yankees, telling manager Ray Miller, ``I think the time
is right.''
</P>
<P>
   The streak started back on May 30, 1982 and the Associated Press
reported that a Orioles official said Ripken would not play at
Sunday. Ripken also said through he team that he is not hurt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Ripken broke what was thought once to be an unbreakable
record when he played in his 2,131st straight game, passing Lou
Gehrig.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mark McGwire is going deep again, Sammy Sosa and the
Chicago Cubs are falling apart and the Atlanta Braves are getting
closer to wrapping up the best record in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire pushed his home run lead to two over Sosa with his 65th
of the season, a first-inning blast Sunday in Milwaukee. It
appeared he had hit No. 66 in the fifth when he drove a ball deep
to center which appeared to clear the fence. But a fan reached over
the low railing and interfered with the ball and second base umpire
Bob Davidson called it a ground rule double. McGwire did not argue
the call.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, meanwhile, won their 101st game of the season,
knocking off the Diammondbacks 10-0 as rookie starter Bruce Chen
pushed his record to 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago and their last home game of the season, Sosa went
0-for-4 and the Cubs lost 7-3 to Cincinnati, getting swept in the
three-game series. The Mets beat the Marlins 5-0 and now have a
one-game lead over the Cubs for the NL wildcard.
</P>
<P>
   In the AL wildcard race, the Blue Jays were able to close within
four games of leader Boston. Toronto beat Tampa Bay 7-5 in 12
innings while the Red Sox lost for the third straight time, 6-4 to
the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Houston beat the Pirates 2-0 to remain within two games of the
Braves for the best record in the NL. 1/2
</P>
<P>
   In the AL West, Texas lost to Oakland 6-3 as their lead over the
Angels is now at one-half of a game. Anaheim played later Sunday
against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   I. J. Rosenberg writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
