<HEADER>
A5047 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JEWS-REACT-48     09-20 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JEWS-REACT-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RABBIS ASK FOR DELAY IN RELEASE OF VIDEOTAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-BLACKCAUCUS,
CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLICY, CLINTON-TV-TAPE.) 
(lb) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several rabbis in the Washington area have asked the House
Judiciary Committee to postpone releasing the videotape of
President Clinton's grand jury testimony until after the Jewish
holiday of Rosh Hashana, which began Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of other Jewish leaders said they were not offended
by the timing of the videotape's release. And one Orthodox Jewish
leader even called it ``a blessing in disguise'' that observant
Jews will be forced to refrain from watching television _ and hence
seeing the tape _ during the two days when they are supposed to
devote themselves to prayer and reflection.
</P>
<P>
   Rosh Hashana, which ends on Tuesday at sundown, marks the start
of the Jewish New Year and ushers in the High Holidays, a solemn
10-day period of repentance and introspection.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Joseph Weinberg, the senior rabbi of the Washington Hebrew
Congregation, said that he and a group of other Washington-area
rabbis had tried phoning all the members of the House Judiciary
Committee on Friday to ask them to refrain from releasing the tape
on Monday. He said that no committee members responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Releasing it on Rosh Hashana is such a mean-spirited thing to
do,'' Weinberg said in a telephone interview on Sunday. ``The
officials who are doing this ought to say: `Wait a minute, there's
a whole community within our nation that is celebrating its solemn,
solemn day of the New Year. This is not the time. We'll wait two
days.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we don't expect the government to close up,'' he
added, ``but at the same time, when we are dealing with the
specifics of our nation, and what touches the hearts and souls of
so many people, it's not appropriate. If tomorrow were Christmas,
you certainly wouldn't see this happening.''
</P>
<P>
   But like most other Jewish leaders interviewed Sunday, Rabbi
Arthur Hertzberg, the Bronfman visiting professor of the humanities
at New York University, said he found the request for delay absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are soon going to acquire a country in which it will be
wrong to release something on Kwanzaa, to release something on a
Hindu holiday, on a Buddhist holiday or a Muslim holiday,''
Hertzberg said. ``We are a plural country. There is nothing
compulsory about having our Jewish curiosity satiated on Monday. It
can wait till Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   David Harris, the executive director of the American Jewish
Committee, agreed. ``I would not expect such a tape to be released
in Israel on Rosh Hashana,'' he said, ``but frankly, this is not
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The High Holidays end with Yom Kippur, the Day of Atonement,
when Jews take stock of their lives and repent the previous year's
misdeeds. Many rabbis have said they intend to address the Clinton
situation in their sermons. The Central Conference of American
Rabbis, which represents the United States' Reform Jewish rabbis,
called for all Americans to use the 10-day period as a time of
atonement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mandell Ganchrow, the president of the Orthodox Union, said he
considered the release of Clinton's testimony on the first day of
the High Holidays to be a blessing from God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is good for the soul of the Jews not to be looking
at those tapes for 48 hours,'' said Ganchrow, whose organization
represents approximately 1,000 Orthodox synagogues in the United
States. ``It actually gives us a chance to be concentrating on our
atonement, on our souls, and not looking at salacious material. So
let's not look for anti-Semites behind every videotape. In truth,
it's a blessing in disguise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
