u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMB-SUSPECT-EXTRADIT     09-20 0178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-SUSPECT-EXTRADITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBING SUSPECT FACES EXTRADITION TO U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ German officials said Sunday that they were
preparing to extradite to the United States a Sudanese suspect
arrested last week in connection with the bombing of the U.S.
Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Bavaria's interior minister, Guenther Beckstein, said the police
had identified the suspect as Mamdu Mahmud Salim, a 40-year-old
Sudanese man who U.S. authorities believe is a top lieutenant of
the Saudi exile accused of organizing and financing the bombing,
Osama bin Laden. While Salim is not disputing his identity, German
officials said he continues to deny that he is one of bin Laden's
confidants.
</P>
<P>
   Salim was arrested by the German police on Wednesday near
Munich, not long after he arrived in Germany from Spain. The police
were acting on a request from the FBI and the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   Beckstein said the German government would arrange Salim's
extradition to the United States as quickly as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
