<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-TALK-COX     09-20 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TALK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biggest new show this season? Maybe the presidential testimony
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (w) Washington and (E) Entertainment
categories.)
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today marks the official start of the fall TV season, but no
program is getting as much pre-show hype as the four-hour,
melodrama starring President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the president's videotaped grand jury testimony
is redefining what qualifies as ``must-see TV'' for millions of
Americans expecting to watch Clinton respond to questioning about
his relationship with former intern, Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The major TV networks are planning some form of Clinton
coverage: Cable news outlets will be running unedited versions of
the tape while the commercial broadcasters will be airing censored
excerpts throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   All of them have promised to run content warnings during their
telecasts warning viewers that the tape contains sexually explicit
material.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is keeping the videotape under lock and key until 9
a.m. when a copy of the tape will be made to Fox, which will then
provide a ``pool feed'' to the other networks covering the story.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, only members of the House Judiciary Committee were
supposed to have access to the tape and the 2,000 pages of
supporting documents also released by independent counsel Kenneth
Starr, right?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   TV pundits abhor a vacuum, and the tight security surrounding
the videotape didn't keep the talking heads who populate Sunday
morning news shows from reporting or just guessing what was on it.
</P>
<P>
   CNN and several other networks had obtained copies of a
five-minute opening statement Clinton made in which he describes
his contact with Lewinsky as ``inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't enough for Jonathan Turley, a professor at George
Washington University who appeared on ``Fox News Sunday'' to give
viewers a preview of what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theyre going to watch a president commit a series of criminal
acts,'' said Turley, who repeated his calls for the president to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.) has seen the videotape, and said its
a one-sided performance thats unfair to the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its like watching ``Perry Mason'' re-runs where you only get a
chance to see (TV prosecutor) Hamilton Burger, `` said Frank , also
appearing on the Fox morning show.
</P>
<P>
   Some who hadn't seen it and even swore they wouldnt watch, gave
their their opinions about how the videotape could change life on
earth as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were treating the president as if he's a date and we want to
know all about him,'' said media analyst Ken Auletta on ``CNN
Sunday.'' ``The president has lost all right to privacy. Soon it
will be Congress, and then members of the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Kalb, co-host of CNNs ``Reliable Sources'' was even more
dramatic, sounding as if he was describing some apocolyptic horror
movie. ``There will be a global silence as clickers of the world
tune in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
