<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA INTENSIFIES CRACKDOWN ON APPLICANTS FOR NEW PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chinese authorities have stepped up their crackdown on
dissidents' efforts to form a political party, sending a clear
signal that despite liberalization in many areas of Chinese life
they would not allow such organized dissent.
</P>
<P>
   In three days authorities in four regions have detained
dissidents associated with the fledgling China Democratic Party.
The harsh reaction is a marked change from 10 days ago, when
dissidents who applied to start local branches of the incipient
party received what they interpreted as vaguely positive signals.
Local officials, rather than immediately rejecting the
applications, had listed the conditions for registering social
organizations like providing a list of members and paying a
registration fee.
</P>
<P>
   No parties have been allowed to be formed since the Communists
took power in 1949. And arrests and detentions over the weekend
left little room for hope that a new party would be founded soon.
These are some of the government's actions:
</P>
<P>
   _ In Shandong province one of the two dissidents who had
applied, Liu Lianjun, was detained on Saturday, according to the
Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in
China, which has its headquarters in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Shanghai, Han Lifa, who delivered the application there,
was detained for six hours, and the application was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Beijing, Ren Wanding and Ma Shaohua, who had planned to
submit an application, were detained and warned not to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tang Yuanjuan of Jilin province was arrested on charges of
``contacts with an illegal organization,'' his family was told.
Although Tang is not a member of the fledgling party, he has
friends who had signed the applications. Tang was detained shortly
after having arrived at the house of a longtime dissident in
Beijing, Xu Wenli, and taken back to Jilin.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us this is a very dangerous signal, and the situation is
extremely threatening,'' Xu said Sunday night. ``It shows that they
may destroy the party, and we need to organize fierce protests
against that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many people the China Democratic Party
represents, although the number is clearly small. It does, however,
have bylaws that stress democratic principles like free elections.
</P>
<P>
   In June dissidents in Zhejiang province tried to register a
committee to form the party. Several were jailed. Groups in
Shandong and Hubei provinces tested the waters again this month,
during a visit by Mary Robinson, the U.N. high commissioner for
human rights.
</P>
<P>
   When the two groups encountered neither arrest not outright
rejection, three other groups _ one from the far northeast, one
from Beijing and one from Shanghai _ were emboldened to apply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
