</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEDEN-VOTE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEDISH PARTY PLEDGING EXPANDED WELFARE GAINS SLIM VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden _ The governing Social Democrats rode a pledge
to expand Sweden's huge welfare programs to a thin victory Sunday
night in a national election that signaled a shift to the left.
</P>
<P>
   With all the votes tabulated, the Social Democrats received 36.5
percent of the vote, and the conservative opposition Moderates 22.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Though the result represented a significant drop in support for
the Social Democrats, who got a bit more than 45 percent of votes
in 1994, it appeared sufficient to allow them to form an alliance
with parties farther left. That would keep Prime Minister Goran
Persson in power and frustrate the bid by Carl Bildt, the Moderate
leader, to regain the office he occupied from 1991 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Minority governments are becoming the norm in Sweden, and so is
the leadership of the Social Democrats, who have held power for 57
of the last 66 years. This time, however, they will be even more
dependent on cooperation with the Left Party, the former
Communists, who succeeded in stealing votes from the Social
Democrats and nearly doubling their representation in Parliament.
Another likely partner will be the Greens, with 4.5 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bildt, the former international peace mediator in Bosnia, said
he found the outcome ``disturbing for Sweden,'' and his party
secretary, Gunnar Hokmark, added, ``It puts Sweden in a left lock
that is stronger than any other country in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Persson conceded that ``things will be more difficult now'' but
said his weakened party would not adopt any radical measures or
enter any agreements that could ``undermine confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Persson, 49, is a former finance minister with a reputation for
austere spending habits, but his party won the election Sunday with
an appeal to people upset with cuts made in Sweden's sweeping
welfare state.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Persson pledged more money for health
services, the elderly and day care that he said would not break
spending limits because the country now had a budget surplus from
an economic recovery that he led.
</P>
<P>
   Bildt, by contrast, campaigned for tax cuts, an alluring
political proposition in almost every other country but Sweden,
even though its citizens are among the most heavily taxed on earth.
``Talking about tax cuts in this campaign is like swearing in
church,'' said Toivo Sjoren, the research director of the Sifo
opinion surveying firm.
</P>
<P>
   Bildt also argued that tax cuts would ease Sweden's
unemployment, now at 7.3 percent, by creating private sector jobs,
but Persson predicted that the number would decline in the
traditional Swedish way, a growth of the public sector. Public jobs
already account for 31 percent of Swedish employment.
</P>
<P>
   Swedes, particularly the growing aged population, have been
expressing fears about gaps in their vast social coverage. The most
repeated claim in this election was not the dynamic pledge to bring
about change common to campaigns elsewhere in Europe but a stolid
promise to restore what was.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the enthusiasm for replenishing the welfare state stems
from real anxiety over the treatment of the needy, and part
bespeaks a nostalgia for the time when Sweden and its so-called
``caring capitalism'' were seen as the international model of
politics with a social conscience.
</P>
<P>
   The government already spends 46 percent of Sweden's gross
national product on welfare, more than any other industrialized
country, and its overall public spending is 63 percent of gross
national product.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The income taxes required to support this public outlay take 59
percent of the pay of people earning as little as $30,000 a year
and oblige employers to pay up to 41 percent of employee
remuneration into social security and pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   Broad support for increasing welfare was seen in the strong
showing by the Left Party, which attracted 12 percent of votes,
almost twice its 1994 total of 6.2 percent. Its candidate, Gudrun
Schyman, 50, campaigned to cut the work week to 35 hours, raise
company taxes and leave the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, sensing its growing acceptance by mainstream voters,
the party ordered its district branches to remove photographs of
Lenin from party office walls.
</P>
<P>
   Fulfilling the hopes of voters for broader welfare coverage
could be at cross purposes with Sweden's need to increase its
competitiveness in the world marketplace. The country's largest and
most successful company, the telecommunications giant Ericsson, is
threatening to move its headquarters to Britain, where it finds
business conditions better. In Sweden, industrialists have
complained of high personal income taxes and rigid labor rules.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development has
lowered Sweden's position on its prosperity tables to 15th from
fourth in the world, ranking it behind its Scandinavian neighbors,
Denmark, Finland and Norway, as well as Ireland and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to regain the country's leadership will be a keen
disappointment to Bildt, 49, who in 1997 returned here as the most
popular public figure in Sweden after two years spent trying to end
the war in Bosnia. His ratings in the polls have since steadily
declined.
</P>
<P>
   His accomplishments abroad and his concern for the outside world
did not resonate in a country absorbed with domestic security and
stability. Bildt also failed with his calls on Sweden to become a
more aggressive leader in the Baltic region, to join NATO and to
hold a referendum on entry into the single European currency.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 Sweden decided with only 52.5 percent of the population
in favor to become a member of the European Union. Surveys show
that the country would reverse that decision today, with only 31
percent now in favor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
