<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-ART     09-20 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICO PREPARES FOR HURRICANE GEORGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ With Hurricane Georges, the most
powerful storm of the season, bearing down on them Sunday with
135-mile-per-hour winds, Puerto Rico and a dozen smaller Caribbean
islands south and east of here braced for what authorities warned
could become a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Three damaging hurricanes have struck Puerto Rico over the past
decade, including Hugo in 1989, and residents of the island
reluctantly mobilized again after a hurricane warning was
officially issued Sunday morning for an area extending from
Dominica to the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   With gusts of up to 190 mph, Hurricane Georges was described by
meteorologists as a severe threat to life and property, likely to
cut a wide swath through the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is similar in size and strength to Hurricane Hugo,''
James Lewis Free, a research scientist at the National Hurricane
Center in Miami, said in a telephone interview. ``It is an
extremely dangerous storm.''
</P>
<P>
   In advisories issued throughout the day, the National Hurricane
Center said it was likely that the storm would make landfall in the
northern Leeward Islands late Sunday night before continuing a
west-northwest course that would take its powerful eye directly
across Puerto Rico on Monday. The hurricane s classified as a
category four storm, the second-most powerful type of hurricane,
but could gain strength.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologists said it was too early to tell if Hurricane
Georges could threaten the Southeast in the United States this
week. But with the course of the storm shifting somewhat north and
west during the day, that possibility is ``something that needs to
be watched very carefully,'' Free said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here Sunday afternoon, Gov. Pedro Rossello
of Puerto Rico declared a state of emergency, warning the 3.8
million residents of this American commonwealth that the hurricane
represented ``a moment of crisis.'' Rossello said that although
``our people are better prepared than on previous occasions,'' the
magnitude of the storm required that the population act ``with the
utmost seriousness'' and take extra precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything indicates this hurricane has the characteristics to
be the most powerful that we have confronted in Puerto Rico in
decades,'' he said. ``If everything continues as predicted, there
is going to be extensive damage and destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   All days off and vacations for police here have been canceled
until further notice, as were classes, concerts and other public
events scheduled for Sunday night and Monday. In anticipation of
the storm, the Federal Emergency Management Agency, criticized for
its slow reaction when Hurricane Andrew struck Miami in 1992, sent
early response teams to Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands,
which also lie in the storm's path.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Puerto Rico appeared calm, covering windows with
plywood or metal shutters and flocking to stores to buy emergency
supplies. ``Here comes Georges!'' read the graffiti on the shutters
of a building in the Condado section of San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as ready as I'm ever going to be,'' Sonia Padilla Guerra,
a homemaker, said as she emerged from a grocery store. ``I've got
plenty of water, canned food for three or four days and batteries
for my flashlights. Let's just hope this one will not be as bad as
Hugo was.''
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, some flights between Luis Munoz Marin
International Airport here and other Caribbean destinations had
already been canceled, leaving some passengers stranded and
nervous. American Airlines, which uses San Juan as the hub of its
Caribbean operations, announced that it was canceling all flights
from Puerto Rico Sunday night and moving its planes until the storm
passes.
</P>
<P>
   Islands east and south of Puerto Rico began feeling the first
effects of the hurricane early Sunday, in the form of rough surf,
rain and heightened winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the third time in four years, we are facing a major
hurricane,'' Lester Bird, prime minister of the twin-island nation
of Antigua and Barbuda, warned in a radio address to his country's
65,000 citizens. Antigua was hit by Luis in 1995 and Bertha in
1996, and last summer had to accommodate refugees from a volcanic
eruption that severely damaged the neighboring island of
Montserrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 2120EDT &QL; 
