<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5056 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN21-COX     09-20 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves' Chen impressive in 10-0 shutout against Arizona
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Still squirming in a headlock with 1998, the Braves
paused for a moment Sunday to ponder their future.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Chen worked seven shutout innings in his most impressive
work yet while Atlanta was blowing away the Arizona Diamondbacks
10-0. Ten Braves had RBIs during a 13-hit assault that only got out
of hand late, when the bench scored six times in the last two
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the game was all Chen's, making just his third major
league start. After surviving a two-walk, one-hit first inning, he
allowed the Diamondbacks only two more hits while striking out
five, retiring 14 in a row in at one point. Indeed, this was the
second worst team in the league and the Diamondbacks reaffirmed
that by setting the National League strikeout record when Yamil
Benitez whiffed in the fifth for the 1,204th D-Back strikeout of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a 21-year-old kid still only six weeks removed from
Class AA. If Chen wasn't a candidate to make the 1999 Opening Day
roster before Sunday, he is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game, I was much more comfortable than the other two
games,'' Chen said. ``Even though I was missing, I stuck with my
plan. I wanted to keep the ball down and keep it away. I wasn't
like worried.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Away, away, away, away,'' Benitez said. ``Nothing
over-powering. You just can't see it or something.''
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, Atlanta's ninth in 11 games, the Braves
maintained a two-game lead over Houston for the NL's best record
while slumping San Diego, loser iof five of six, fell five games
off the pace. The shutout, completed by Rudy Seanez and Norm
Charlton, gave the Braves a major-league 21 and two in a row over
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Seanez, making his first appearance in 15 days after sustaining
a micro-tear in a right forearm muscle, walked one and struck out
one in a hitless eighth inning, a positive sign for the postseason.
With 46 strikeouts in 33 innings, Seanez remains a vital cog in the
club's playoff plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``First time out there, I didn't want to go blow 'em out,''
Seanez said.. ``I was just trying to get in the swing of things. It
felt good. I felt comfortable out there but it's been a couple of
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The day contained a number of major-league firsts for Chen _ a
switch-hitter, who recorded his first major-league single in the
third off Arizona starter Amaury Telemaco. Four innings later, Chen
delivered a bunt on a suicide squeeze, scoring Javy Lopez for a 4-0
lead and his first major-league RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was how he worked into trouble and then out of it that
impressed more. The same team beat up Greg Maddux for 10 hits and
five runs in just seven innings two nights before at least had six
hits against Tom Glavine Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''He just locates,'' said Diamondbacks right fielder Andy Fox,
whose sixth-inning double was the hardest hit ball all day. ''It's
almost on a smaller scale like Glavine. Nothing over-powering but
you look up and you've got just two hits off the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He got untangled after the first two innings,'' said Bobby
Cox, who won career game 1,413, tying Miller Huggins for 18th place
on the all-time managers' victory list. ''He was not real sharp.
And then he got real sharp and stayed ahead of the hitters almost
the rest of the way. He threw a ton of pitches in the first two
innings (29 in the first alone). They just missed some balls,
almost hit 'em square. But they didn't. He's got that little extra
giddy-up on his fastball that surprises them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was starter Denny Neagle who joked after Chen's first win
that the Braves were now free to trade him. But with Neagle
fighting a sore shoulder, Chen's ERA (3.31) fell below Neagle's
Sunday (3.59) and while the club has had no time to plot an
offseason course, Neagle's joke may not be quite as funny today.
</P>
<P>
   ''It feels pretty good,'' Chen said. ''I want to be a starter
with the Braves. It's fun to be a young guy, to come and pitch with
five great starters. I have learned a lot from them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, almost by the day, are learning alot from him too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
