<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-NOTES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR NOTES
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Breaking down the MBNA by the 100s:
</P>
<P>
   The First 100
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wallace blew a motor before he could complete a lap. It
failed to faze Mark Martin, however. Martin led the first lap,
Rusty Wallace the next two and from there Martin dominated over the
first 100 laps. Following a short caution for debris on the track,
Martin led a torrid pace to lap 85 before Buckshot Jones' motor
blew, sending him to his pit in a cloud of smoke. Wallace jumped in
to lead two more laps. At that point, only 13 cars were on the lead
lap. Five laps later, the Burtons collided. Ward got into some oil
and spun into Jeff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lap leaders: Martin (92), Rusty Wallace (8)
</P>
<P>
   _ Under caution: (lap 13-15, 86-91) debris and oil on the track.
</P>
<P>
   Second 100
</P>
<P>
   The Burtons returned. By this time, it was even more evident
that it was Martin's show. He led from lap 101 to 169, lapping 13
more cars along the way. On lap 170, Kenny Irwin spun in turn two
and hit the wall. Kyle Petty had a good run going, but broke a
camshaft and was done for the day. There were only 10 cars on the
lead lap at 150.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lap leaders: Mark Martin (93), Bobby Hamilton (1), Jeff Gordon
(6)
</P>
<P>
   _ Under caution: (Lap 172-178) Irwin accident
</P>
<P>
   Third 100
</P>
<P>
   Martin led 95 of the 100 laps and Rusty Wallace the remainder. A
caution came on lap 244 while the speedway transported Irwin to
Kent Hospital for observation. He suffered back and shoulder pain,
and had hit his head against the inside of the car. Jeff Gordon
black-flagged for having right front fender stuck out beyond his
tire..
</P>
<P>
   _ Lap leaders: Martin (95), Rusty Wallace (5)
</P>
<P>
   _ Under caution: 244-251, ambulance leaving infield; 294-298
(Irwin's accident).
</P>
<P>
   Fourth 100
</P>
<P>
   Martin held off Gordon's challenge over the final 50 laps to
coast to a more than two-second victory. Jerry Nadeau, Mike Skinner
and Todd Bodine were in a turn three accident on lap 316.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lap leader: Martin (100).
</P>
<P>
   _ Under caution: 316-326, accident in turn three. 334-340, oil
on the track.
</P>
<P>
   Points update
</P>
<P>
   Although Martin won for the sixth time, he gained only 10 points
on Gordon. Dale Jarrett remained in third, but lost 39 points to
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's impact
</P>
<P>
   It was an in-your-face, take-that race day for Martin. An
enormous amount of effort for a dominating victory, but Martin will
still find it difficult to catch Gordon for the Winston Cup
championship with only seven races remaining. If Gordon finishes
fourth or better in all the remaining races, he cannot be caught.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
