A5062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-STEELERS-DOLPHINS     09-20 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STEELERS-DOLPHINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS SHUT DOWN STEELERS 21-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ This game was billed as a slugfest, two teams that had
barely been able to throw the ball and loved to run it. So on its
first two offensive plays Sunday, Miami hurled bombs. Both fell
incomplete. Pittsburgh, on its first two offensive plays, tossed a
short pass and then a deep one. One gained 2 yards and the other
was incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well.
</P>
<P>
   Back to basics. Back to the rugged running game and to punishing
defense, the way it was supposed to be. And once the nitty-gritty
was under way, Pittsburgh, surprisingly, was not up to the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   It fell behind by 7-0 with 5 minutes 12 seconds left in the
first half after allowing an 11-play, 64-yard drive that consumed a
little more than 7 minutes. With 2:39 left before halftime,
Pittsburgh allowed another score that was set up when the Miami
defense intercepted a pass and returned it to the Steelers' 24. And
then with 8:06 left in the third quarter, Miami returned an
interception 17 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   That was it, 21-0, Miami, in an aggressive, attacking, physical
and dominating game for the Dolphins that was absolute
embarrassment for Pittsburgh before 73,948 fans at Pro Player
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Miami is 3-0; Pittsburgh is 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Humiliating for Pittsburgh? Check out these numbers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Steelers were 3 of 14 on third down (a 21 percent
conversion rate compared with Miami's 37 percent).
</P>
<P>
   _ The Steelers gained only 200 yards, including 78 passing.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Steelers punted 10 times and missed a 47-yard field-goal
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Steelers were intercepted three times.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Steelers possessed the ball for 9 minutes 32 seconds less
than Miami (the tally was 2:11 to 12:49 in the second quarter).
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an extremely poor display of offensive football,''
said Bill Cowher, the Pittsburgh head coach. ``Miami played good
defense and we played poor offensively. Those are two distinctly
different statements. I look out on the field and see too many good
football players for us to have this level of production. We will
get this thing turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   There was simply no Steelers production. It rained for most of
the second half, but well before that the Pittsburgh offense was
all wet.
</P>
<P>
   It started with quarterback Kordell Stewart. He was miserable in
the first half (4 of 15 passing for 3 yards) and finished 11 of 35
for 82 yards with a sack and three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Running Back Jerome Bettis carried 13 times for only 48 yards.
Receiver Charles Johnson caught two passes for 40 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this was not our best day,'' Stewart said. ``Things
did not click.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettis said, ``If you go out there and you are not on all
cylinders and you play a great defense like that, you are going to
get embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   A great defense? Words seldom spoken around here. But maybe
Miami finally has one.
</P>
<P>
   Its defensive front of Kenny Mixon, Tim Bowens, Daryl Gardener
and Jason Taylor won the confrontation at the point of attack. Its
linebackers, Derrick Rodgers, Zach Thomas and Robert Jones, were
adept at pass coverage and at snuffing the run.
</P>
<P>
   They eagerly took on the challenge of tackling Bettis, known as
the Bus, all 250 pounds of him, and often put him down hard. The
secondary features Terrell Buckley and Sam Madison at cornerback
and Calvin Jackson and Brock Marion at safety. Buckley and Madison
often locked in man-to-man coverage with Pittsburgh and won that
showdown.
</P>
<P>
   After Karim Abdul-Jabbar (a career-most 33 carries for 108
yards) scored on a 3-yard run, Madison made one of his two
interceptions of Stewart. The first set up an 8-yard pass from Dan
Marino to Lamar Thomas that made it 14-0. Zach Thomas returned an
interception 17 yards for the game's final points.
</P>
<P>
   This Miami defensive crew earned the Dolphins their first home
shutout in a nonstrike game since Sept. 22, 1985. That was so long
ago, Miami was playing in the Orange Bowl then.
</P>
<P>
   Zach Thomas said: ``We changed up our game plan a lot, showed
Stewart a lot of stuff, and we tried to rattle him as much as we
could and keep him in the pocket. The guy is so quick, but we did a
good job of containing him. We have another quick start, but we
want to go on from here. I know Miami teams are known for quick
starts.''
</P>
<P>
   And wimpy finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Miami is 3-0 for the fourth time in five years, but none of that
led to playoff success. The Dolphins say this team is different.
This team has a running game and defense. It can win the
old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is 1998,'' end Jason Taylor said. ``None of the other
years matter. This team is for real. A shutout against their
offensive personnel? That speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Pittsburgh's first shutout loss in five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's head coach, Jimmy Johnson, said this is the difference
in this bunch of Dolphins: ``More players and a little more
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   More confidence and more attitude. Sunday, the Dolphins put all
of that on display. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
