<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GAFOOT21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Donnan promises hard work in aftermath of Wyoming game
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ After a less-than-impressive showing in Saturday's
16-9 win over Wyoming, the 13th-ranked Georgia football team won't
have much time off during its bye week.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, who don't play again until an Oct. 3 date at No. 6
LSU, will practice four straight days, beginning with a light
workout this afternoon, and probably won't get a day off until
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't work hard, we may practice on Saturday and
Sunday,'' Bulldogs coach Jim Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has two weeks to address several concerns on offense.
The Bulldogs lost four fumbles to Wyoming, matching the team total
all last season, and rushed for only 74 yards. The Bulldogs managed
just 93 yards offense against the Cowboys in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to work on ball security,'' Donnan said. ``I'm not
worrying about the running game, based on one game. We're going to
be a good running team. I knew we were going to have problems
against Wyoming. I said that all last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan didn't expect many mistakes from freshman quarterback
Quincy Carter, who was involved in three turnovers. In the second
quarter, Carter handed off to the wrongback and later dropped a
high shotgun snap from center Miles Luckie. Midway through the
fourth quarter, Carter fumbled after taking a hit on a passing
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Quincy had a good first half,'' Donnan said. ``He
made the right plays, except for dropping that snap that hit him in
the facemask. ... We're concerned about not having more protection,
but we also were without a starting guard (sophomore Jonas
Jennings).''
</P>
<P>
   Though Donnan emphasizes mistake-free football, both were absent
Saturday. Georgia rushed for only 74 yards on 35 carries, an
average of only 2.1 yards per attempt. Senior Olandis Gary led the
Bulldogs with 26 yards on 11 carries; junior Patrick Pass had only
24 on nine attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Highly regarded freshman Jasper Sanks didn't play for the third
straight game. ``We'll certainly continue to look at Sanks and see
if he gives us a chance to be successful,'' Donnan said. ``Some of
the plays (Saturday) _ Jim Brown couldn't have gained a yard. It
doesn't matter who the back was. They just did a good job of
penetrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia may have redshirt freshman quarterback Daniel Cobb of
Kennesaw available against LSU. Cobb, who has been sidelined for
several months with circulation problems in his throwing shoulder,
was taken off blood thinner last week. He'll be tested today and
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan also said two-way player Champ Bailey, who had six
catches for 100 yards in the opening half, but only played
sparingly in the second with cramping in both legs, is being
evaluated by a specialist and was placed on new medication.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
