</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GTFOOT21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LB Uremovich's trademark is intensity
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This clip never showed up on the Matt Uremovich
highlight tape _ the one he and his brother Mike made by hooking up
two VCRs back home in Joliet, Ill., to help drum up some interest
in a young linebacker who is, as Mike Uremovich puts it, ``an inch
too short and 20 pounds too light.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech assistant coach Doug Marrone never saw this
``behind-the-scenes moment'' after watching the tape, showing it to
coach George O'Leary and getting the vigorous nod to go after the
smallish (6-1, 215) and slowish kid who might turn out to be Tech's
next great linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   It was Matt Uremovich's sophomore year at Providence Catholic,
his first year playing on the varsity, and it was the playoffs.
Uremovich had a broken arm and was in a cast, something he had no
intention of letting keep him out of the game. Trouble was, he
needed a note from a doctor to give to the referees so they would
allow him to play in a cast. But the team trainer forgot the note,
and the officials weren't going to let Uremovich play.
</P>
<P>
   As his brother Mike tells it, Uremovich slipped past his
coaches, trainer and any security at the opposing school, broke
into a maintenance closet and came out with a saw. He cut his cast
off and played in the game, helping Providence to the first of
three state championships in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't surprise me,'' Marrone said. ``He's a tough, tough
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Uremovich got that kind of reputation around Tech his scout
team year, so much so that future Atlanta Falcons first-round pick
Keith Brooking said Uremovich reminded him of himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Providence Catholic football team has a copy of Brooking's
quote up in its locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Brooking) is a good player if he plays like my brother,''
said Mike Uremovich, who is two years older than Matt and has taken
time off from his studies at Purdue to be the offensive coordinator
for Providence Catholic. ``You won't find a guy who's more intense,
dedicated or wants to win more.''
</P>
<P>
   As a scout-team linebacker, Uremovich was in fights weekly. As a
second-team linebacker during the preseason, Uremovich watched the
first team practice with his toes on the sideline, eyes on the
action and his calf muscles flexed for the coaches' call to come
in.
</P>
<P>
   He was ready during the Boston College game when he came off the
bench for his first play on defense. He wrapped up running back
Mike Cloud on the play. A week later, he was in the starting lineup
at Brooking's old position of weakside linebacker and giving the
impression he might not come out for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy right now,'' Uremovich said. ``I just don't want to
screw it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Uremovich, who says he'll be lucky if he's half the player
Brooking was, needs to get stronger and is still in the early
stages of learning Tech's defense. But his coaches like the way
he's doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uremovich plays the game the way you like it to be played,''
defensive coordinator Randy Edsall said. ``You can tell football
really means something to him.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said, ``I like his attitude. And the way he's getting to
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The first glimpses Mike Uremovich saw of his brother's intensity
came when he was 11 and Matt was 9 and the two were playing
volleyball at a hotel on vacation. They were going against another
kid and his 30-something father. As Mike tells it, the pair started
cheating on line calls, and Matt and the man started arguing. Next
thing Mike knew, Matt had knocked the man down. Game over.
</P>
<P>
   As teenagers, the Uremoviches went through four Nintendos
because, after Mike or Matt would lose a video football game, he'd
bash the Nintendo. That would inevitably lead to a fight and a trip
out to the backyard to finish off their business.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Matt was a sophomore at Providence and Mike was a
senior, their wrestling coaches had the ``Uremovich rule.'' Mike
and Matt were not allowed to go against each other in practice
because they ended up in fights.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mike, who first broke Matt's nose, the one which he has
rebroken every year since his junior year either wrestling or
playing football. He broke it again during this preseason when his
chinstrap busted and the top of his helmet crashed into his nose.
</P>
<P>
   Uremovich can't breathe out of one side of his nose. He wears a
Band-Aid across the bridge of his nose to hide the cut, which
splits open regularly. Tech has ordered him a special fitted helmet
that it hopes will solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   To Uremovich, the problem isn't the pain, it's the chance that
officials might take him out of a game if he has blood on his
jersey. ``It's more of a hassle.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
