<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-BREWERS-MCGWIRE-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 FAN INTERFERENCE ROBS McGWIRE OF HOME RUN NO. 66 
 (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The greatest home run spectacle in history spawned
an outrageous subplot Sunday when Mark McGwire belted what many are
calling home run No. 65 and a half at County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a two home run day, McGwire had to settle for one
homer and a near-miss after fans interfered with the second of his
drives. The umpire ruled it a ground-rule double, one fan was
ejected from the stadium and fined, and many were left debating
whether McGwire was robbed.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence of events began when McGwire took a mighty swing
that launched what appeared to be his 66th home run of the season
in the fifth inning of the St. Louis Cardinals' 11-6 victory over
the Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   As the ball headed on a line toward the left-center-field
bleachers 392 feet from home plate, dozens of fans pushed and
shoved their way toward the fence in hopes of retrieving a part of
history and perhaps a valuable souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   Two of them, Michael Chapes of Waterford, Wis., and Allan
Riesbeck of Dubuque, Iowa, lunged for the ball and, judging from
videotaped replays, simultaneously caught it near the yellow home
run line above the wall. The ball landed in Chapes' glove, but
Riesbeck had his gray T-shirt in Chapes' mitt.
</P>
<P>
   The second base umpire, Bob Davidson, who was sprinting toward
the fence, thought the fans reached over the yellow line and into
the field of play and called them for fan interference.
</P>
<P>
   In that situation, the league rules call for the umpire to make
a judgment on where the ball would have landed if the fans had not
interfered. Davidson, believing that McGwire's hit would not have
cleared the yellow line, ruled it a ground-rule double.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball got out there in about half a second,'' said
Davidson, who is in his 16th season as a major league umpire. ``I
got out there as fast as I could, and I saw it. When I saw it, the
fan was leaning over and the ball hit him below the yellow line. So
that's why I called it a ground-rule double. I saw the ball good.''
</P>
<P>
   William DeWitt Jr., the Cardinals' owner, telephoned
Commissioner Bud Selig shortly after Davidson's ruling, asking for
an official review of the tape and possible overturn of the call.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who hit his 65th home run off Scott Karl in the first
inning, said he looked at the videotape twice after the game and
believes Davidson made the wrong call.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man who caught the ball never came over the yellow line,''
said McGwire, who is now two homers ahead of Chicago's Sammy Sosa,
who has 63. ``The replay shows that he didn't. But then again, it's
a judgment call.''
</P>
<P>
   Though obviously disappointed, McGwire was satisfied with
hitting No. 65, a 423-foot blast that was one of five St. Louis
homers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty-five had a lot of meaning because that's the number my
son said he wanted me to hit,'' said McGwire, referring to
10-year-old Matthew. ``Before spring training, I asked him how many
homers he wanted me to hit, and he said 65. That's all I thought
about when I ran around the bases. What a prediction.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Dombrowski, a 21-year-old senior at the University of
Wisconsin at Whitewater, caught McGwire's home run and said he will
return it to the slugger. McGwire said he will give the ball to his
son.
</P>
<P>
   The would-be homer in the fifth was the second home run that
McGwire has had reversed in his career, the first coming during his
rookie season in Oakland in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Within seconds of Davidson's fan-interference call, security
guards, following stadium rules, ejected Chapes from the park.
Chapes, a 31-year-old physical education teacher, denied any
wrongdoing, saying that he could not reach over the three-foot moat
that separates the yellow home-run line from the fence in the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only 5-7. My arms aren't that long,'' said Chapes, who was
cited and fined $518.15 for trespassing. ``It was a home run. I had
the ball in my glove and somebody knocked it out. I don't
understand why the guy who ended up with the ball got to stay in
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapes and Riesbeck had the ball for less than a second before
it was knocked out of the glove by rushing fans. The ball fell into
the moat between the two fences, and Johnny Luna, an 18-year-old
from New York City jumped into the moat and grabbed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't over the fence,'' Luna said of Chapes. ``It should
have been a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Luna was one of dozens of fans in the left-field bleachers who
said that Chapes and Riesbeck were not over the yellow line and
that, consequently, McGwire had been robbed of his 66th home run.
But numerous Milwaukee County police and stadium ushers in the
bleachers said the two fans definitely interfered and leaned into
the field of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were at least eight inches over the yellow line,'' said a
security guard who wanted to remain anonymous. ``I see many, many
close home runs, and I know what to watch for. The umpire made the
right call. The ball would have hit the fence.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Luna, a high school senior from the Astoria section of Queens,
rode to Milwaukee in a 1986 Ford van with four other New Yorkers:
40-year-old Gerald DiGilio; his two teen-age sons, Jerry and Joe
DiGilio, and David Schiff, 20. The group shuttled between Chicago
and Milwaukee on Friday and Saturday in hopes of catching a home
run ball by Sosa or McGwire. They will remain in Milwaukee on
Tuesday and Wednesday for the Cubs' two-game series with the
Brewers and then go to St. Louis to see McGwire's final home series
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Admitting that they could not care less about baseball, they
said their interest is strictly monetary. So even if the
controversial ruling is overturned and McGwire is granted his 66th
home run, Luna will not give him the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ain't trading it in for nothing,'' said Gerald DiGilio, a
bridge painter from Astoria. ``We're selling it to the highest
bidder. We didn't come down here to give anything to McGwire. He
didn't come to Astoria to give us anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
