<DOCNO> NYT19980920.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ANDERSON-HOMERUN-     09-20 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDERSON-HOMERUN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: CHICAGO TO SAMMY: YOU THE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Trotting past Wrigley Field's ivy-covered brick
outfield wall after the ceremonies, Sammy Sosa was waving his blue
Cubs cap at the adoring applause from the bleachers when the word
suddenly arrived at Wrigley Field. Some 90 miles to the north in
Milwaukee, Mark McGwire had just hit another homer _ his 65th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upstaged again,'' somebody said.
</P>
<P>
   Not here. Not on his ``Day,'' when a dozen red-white-and-blue
Dominican Republic flags fluttered from the grandstand roof. Not
when a big banner on the wire screen above the left-field bleachers
bragged, ``Sammy, You're the Man.'' Not when the Friendly Confines
were never friendlier. Even if he only partly agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGwire's the man,'' he told the television station WGN before
the game, ``but in Chicago, I am the man.'' Then, with a sly grin,
he said, ``Excuse me, Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, Michael Jordan was at Wrigley Field too, peering down
at the festivities from a private sky box, too smart to risk really
upstaging the Cubs slugger. His children ``wanted to see Sammy,''
Jordan had said during the week, so he was here as a father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for Sammy,'' Jordan, the man in Chicago and
elsewhere for more than a decade, would say later. ``I think he's
going to hit the most homers.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, Sosa needs a big last week. McGwire has six games
remaining, all in St. Louis against the Astros and the Expos. Sosa
has only five, all on the road (two in Milwaukee, three in Houston)
unless there's also a Cubs-Mets wild-card playoff at Shea Stadium.
When told after he was 0 for 5 (and 0 for 17 since his 63rd homer)
in the 7-3 loss to the Reds that McGwire's homer occurred during
Sunday's festivities, Sosa smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why Mark's the man,'' Sosa said. ``I hope he continues
and hits 70.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Cubs' clubhouse before his ``Day'' really began, Sosa was
wearing a sleeveless T-shirt with ``Swing, Hit, Run, Slide, Score''
on the back as he stared at photos showing that both he and
McGwire, in a way, were already in the Hall of Fame at Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our `March On Maris' exhibit with you and Mark,'' the
Hall of Fame president, Don Marr, was saying. ``It's right at the
entrance as you come in.''
</P>
<P>
   One by one, Sosa kept staring at the photos like a little boy
would, in the wonderment of it all. His Cubs shirt and his bat from
his 62nd homer are already part of that exhibit. Finally, he
thanked Marr, shook hands and returned to his locker, where a
cereal box with Roberto Clemente's face on it was perched nearby.
</P>
<P>
   As his Latin American tribute to Clemente, the Puerto Rican
outfielder who wore No. 21 during his Hall of Fame career with the
Pittsburgh Pirates, Sosa wears No. 21 on his Cubs' uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a blare of trumpets on the grass behind home plate,
Sosa accepted a crystal ``Historic Achievement Award'' from
Commissioner Bud Selig, who mentioned how ``you have handled
yourself with class and dignity that has been unparalleled. Thank
you, above all, for being what you've been.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Marichal, the onetime San Francisco Giants ace and the only
Dominican with a bronze plaque in the Hall of Fame, spoke on behalf
of Dominican President Leonel Fernandez Reyna.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I heard about Sammy was about 10 years ago when
the scouts were talking about him,'' Marichal would say later. ``I
saw him play on the Dominican team and you could tell he had the
speed, the arm. He struck out a lot, but the way he hit the ball
hard, you knew he had the potential to be a long-ball hitter. And
the way he composes himself, he's so good for the kids as a role
model.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Lynch, once a Mets right-hander and now the Cubs general
manager, presented Sosa with a Tiffany crystal trophy, a Malcolm
Farley painting and the traditional gift on a ballplayer's ``day''
_ an automobile _ a purple Chrysler Prowler convertible. And then
Sosa walked to the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, God,'' he began, ``for giving so much opportunity
to be who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   He thanked Selig, the league presidents, his family, Roger
Maris' family, ``all the people from my country, the Dominican
Republic, that supported me,'' the Cubs' organization, his manager
(Jim Riggleman), his coaches and teammates, all the Latin-American
people who have supported him, especially in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago, I love you,'' the Cubs right fielder closed, ``and
the right-field bleachers, I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   He turned away, but seeing his wife, Sonia, and his mother,
Lucretia, sitting there, he spun back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me,'' he told the sellout crowd of 40,117. ``I forgot
my family. My wife. My mother. My brothers. My friends. And one
more thing I want to say. Baseball has been very very good to me.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has been very good to baseball. Even with a four-year,
$40 million contract, he's a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   And no matter how many more homers Mark McGwire might hit before
the season ends, Sammy Sosa deserves to be the National League's
most valuable player this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Easily,'' Michael Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   More than anybody else, Michael Jordan ought to know an MVP when
he sees one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
