<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5073 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-A'S-RANGERS-TEX     09-20 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS STUMBLE, FALL TO ATHLETICS, 6-3
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ This is not the way the Rangers wanted to be
playing, especially at The Ballpark in Arlington and going into the
biggest series of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers wanted to use the last of their home-field advantage
to strengthen their hand before heading to the West Coast. Instead,
they were outplayed for the second consecutive day by a last-place
team.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers stumbled through what manager Johnny Oates said was
``the most disappointing loss of the season'' and finished their
1998 home schedule with a 6-3 loss to the Oakland Athletics before
a listless crowd of 37,606 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels played the Seattle Mariners last night, and
could make the loss even worse with a victory, which would pull
them back into a first-place tie with the Rangers in the American
League West. With seven games left in the season, the two teams
open a three-game series tonight at Edison International Field of
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out flat today,'' Rangers second baseman Mark McLemore
said. ``We didn't come out like a team that's in first place. It's
one thing to lose, but the way we lost today wasn't very good. But
we've got to forget about it. We can't let it linger.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates let it linger long enough to fume afterward about bad
defense and poor pitch selection between pitcher Esteban Loaiza and
catcher Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, this should have been a shutout,'' Oates said.
``This was not one of our better cerebral games. There wasn't
anything wrong with the effort, maybe if anything we were trying a
little too hard physically. We just didn't play very smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza said he made just two mistakes. Oates counted more than
that, but both were in agreement about the first-pitch, hanging
curveballs that Jason Giambi and Ben Grieve hit for home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza's strength is his sinking fastball that hits 95 mph on
the radar gun. His curveball is his ``fourth or fifth'' best pitch,
Oates says, and the Rangers' pregame strategy sessions didn't call
for Loaiza to pitch that way to the Athletics' best hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got the big boys up there that can hurt you, you
don't want to mess with them,'' Oates said. ``It's not the pitch
selection, but the thought process ... what's my best chance of
getting this guy out? When in doubt, go to your strength, rather
than his weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza, who has allowed 14 home runs in his past nine games,
declined to dwell on pitch selection, preferring instead to blame
his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four errors probably cost us the game,'' Loaiza said, and he
did have a point. Better defensive could have prevented three more
runs from scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton bounced a throw past first baseman Mike
Simms on a potential double-play ball in the third inning, allowing
Eric Chavez to score. The Rangers then committed three more errors
in the fifth inning, allowing the Athletics to score twice and
break a 3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you lose it's disappointing,'' outfielder Rusty Greer
said. ``The thing we have to remember is we can't throw the towel
in now. We've played hard for 155 games to get where we are. We
just have to keep pressing with the same desire and intensity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980920.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-POLITICS-915(2T     09-20 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-POLITICS-915(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS NEED EIGHT SEATS TO TAKE TEXAS HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moved in ``p'' category) 
(lb) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG SPRING, Texas _ It is a warm, cricket-loud Friday night in
West Texas, which means the parking lot is jammed next to the high
school football field, big enough to hold much of the town, which
it does.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few feet away from the man selling chances on a football
autographed by the whole team and the woman handing out discount
coupons for chicken-fried steak (``Fifty percent from every
purchase goes to the boys,'' she says) is Scott McLaughlin, local
wholesale plumber and Republican candidate for the Texas House.
</P>
<P>
   ``People out here are so conservative,'' McLaughlin said as he
handed out campaign pamphlets to people carrying their seat
cushions through the stadium gates. ``Either side, either party.
The Republicans, of course, are shocked about what's come out about
the president, and the Democrats have been somewhat taken aback by
it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more than a dozen states, including Texas, where the
turnover of a relative handful of seats this November would change
control of the legislature, at a time when an increasing share of
the nation's business is being conducted at the state level.
</P>
<P>
   And candidates and political strategists all across the country
are wondering how, if at all, President Clinton's troubles might
affect state races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think there's a gap between what happens at the
national level, even at the congressional level, and what happens
lower down,'' said Janice May, a professor of government at the
University of Texas in Austin. ``In the South there has been a
tremendous increase in Republican support, but it takes time to get
down to the legislative level. Still, we could very well have a
sweep for Republicans in Texas this year.''
</P>
<P>
   If eight seats change hands in the Texas House in November, the
Republicans, who have controlled the state Senate since 1996, will
have sway over the entire legislature for the first time since
Reconstruction in the 1870s. The party is giving extra money and
support to candidates, like McLaughlin, who are in key races.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts caution that a Republican turnaround is not
guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a study back in June based on primary turnout and other
things in which I was absolutely sure there would be a downturn in
turnout and that would benefit the Republicans, especially in
states like Texas,'' said Curtis Gans, director of the Committee
for the Study of the American Electorate. ``But we've got a couple
of wild cards now that make me want to hedge my bets a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the wild cards are the state of the economy. For instance,
Gans said, if the stock market dips even more, which is entirely
possible, or unemployment rises significantly, which seems much
less likely, it could burst public optimism about the economy which
has buoyed the campaigns of incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   Even more vexing, he said, is whether the president's troubles
will dampen Democratic turnout, or whether perceived Republican
missteps in handling the crisis will rankle the Democratic
rank-and-file sufficiently to get them out to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin, whose great-grandfather began by selling windmills
to farmers and who now sells well equipment, plumbing fixtures and
high-end kitchen appliances from a two-story building off
Interstate 20, says that he intends to include a pitch about
character and integrity in the new television spots he will shoot
next week for the fall campaign. He knows it's a way of talking
about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, he said, is to choose just the right words to raise
the character issue without making it look as if the Republicans
are taking advantage of the president's situation. He's still
working on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can definitely tell you that the issue of virtue and
character will be a part of my message this fall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Texas, sensing an opportunity, are redoubling
their efforts in the wake of the release of special prosecutor
Kenneth Starr's report on the president.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the state party's funding efforts, a separate ``Eight in
'98'' political action committee was formed earlier this year to
feed money into targeted races, like McLaughlin's, that could shift
the balance in the House, which currently has 68 Republicans and 82
Democrats. In the state Senate, the Republicans hold 17 seats to
the Democrats' 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say the president's problems are a factor, but not the
only factor,'' said Robert Black, a spokesman for the state
Republican Party. ``We've also got an extremely popular governor in
George W. Bush at the top of our ticket in November, and a strong
slate for all the statewide offices. We definitely feel we have a
good shot at it.''
</P>
<P>
   No consensus has formed on what the Democratic Party's national
problems might mean in statewide races in battleground states like
Texas. Guesses are all across the map; from no impact to full
impact.
</P>
<P>
   And at least one veteran Texas prognosticator, Robert Stein, a
professor of political science at Rice University, believes that
Republicans eager for a November rout here may well be in for a
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``My money now is on the House staying Democrat and the Senate
possibly going back into Democratic hands,'' he said, ``although
the whole thing is very much up for grabs. A lot depends on how
good these campaigns are in the coming weeks and how much
ticket-splitting there is going to be. Mostly what you hear from
candidates is that no one wants to listen. Voters are
disinterested.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The 70th legislative district sprawls across 12 rural counties
in West Texas, coming up to the edge of, without entering, three of
the region's biggest cities; Lubbock, Midland and Abilene. The
district encompasses mile after mile of cotton farms, ranches and
small towns.
</P>
<P>
   The district has been represented for a decade by David Counts,
D-Knox County, on the far side of the district from McLaughlin's
home in Big Spring. McLaughlin first ran against him two years ago,
losing by a slim margin.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, McLaughlin focused his campaign on neighborhood walks,
knocking on more than 10,000 doors. This year, he said, he will
knock on about the same number. ``I am absolutely convinced that
the way to do it, at this level, is to look as many voters in the
eye as you can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His message is drawn directly from the Ronald Reagan playbook,
by way of Newt Gingrich; smaller government, fewer regulations,
strong family values.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin spent about $140,000 on the 1996 campaign, he said,
and plans to spend roughly the same amount this year in his rematch
against Counts. Some of that money comes from local donors, but
some comes from ``Eight in '98,'' which offers logistical and
strategic advice, as well as money. ``They are a definite factor,''
McLaughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Counts was at a Democratic event earlier this month at church
picnic grounds north of Abilene. ``The Republicans came after me
two years ago and they're doing it again,'' he said. ``They keep
trying to tie me to President Clinton, but it won't work. I
personally think this Clinton thing is going to go away real quick.
The last straw was the lurid detail that Ken Starr put in that
report. Now the people know his heart was black and his cause was
not pure.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin doesn't really know how much national political
obsessions will affect his race, nor how much he will benefit from
Bush's coattails in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to tie ourselves to Bush as much as we can,''
McLaughlin said. ``After all, we're both singing from the same
sheet of music.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor has been in the district a couple of times to
campaign for himself and for local Republicans, and each visit has
meant a boost for McLaughlin.
</P>
<P>
   What would happen, McLaughlin is asked, if Clinton came to the
70th district to campaign for his opponent?
</P>
<P>
   A smile spread across his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election would be over,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980920.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-POLITICS-915(2T     09-20 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-POLITICS-915(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS NEED EIGHT SEATS TO TAKE TEXAS HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moved in ``a'' category) 
(lb) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
