</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin, whose great-grandfather began by selling windmills
to farmers and who now sells well equipment, plumbing fixtures and
high-end kitchen appliances from a two-story building off
Interstate 20, says that he intends to include a pitch about
character and integrity in the new television spots he will shoot
next week for the fall campaign. He knows it's a way of talking
about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, he said, is to choose just the right words to raise
the character issue without making it look as if the Republicans
are taking advantage of the president's situation. He's still
working on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can definitely tell you that the issue of virtue and
character will be a part of my message this fall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Texas, sensing an opportunity, are redoubling
their efforts in the wake of the release of special prosecutor
Kenneth Starr's report on the president.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the state party's funding efforts, a separate ``Eight in
'98'' political action committee was formed earlier this year to
feed money into targeted races, like McLaughlin's, that could shift
the balance in the House, which currently has 68 Republicans and 82
Democrats. In the state Senate, the Republicans hold 17 seats to
the Democrats' 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say the president's problems are a factor, but not the
only factor,'' said Robert Black, a spokesman for the state
Republican Party. ``We've also got an extremely popular governor in
George W. Bush at the top of our ticket in November, and a strong
slate for all the statewide offices. We definitely feel we have a
good shot at it.''
</P>
<P>
   No consensus has formed on what the Democratic Party's national
problems might mean in statewide races in battleground states like
Texas. Guesses are all across the map; from no impact to full
impact.
</P>
<P>
   And at least one veteran Texas prognosticator, Robert Stein, a
professor of political science at Rice University, believes that
Republicans eager for a November rout here may well be in for a
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``My money now is on the House staying Democrat and the Senate
possibly going back into Democratic hands,'' he said, ``although
the whole thing is very much up for grabs. A lot depends on how
good these campaigns are in the coming weeks and how much
ticket-splitting there is going to be. Mostly what you hear from
candidates is that no one wants to listen. Voters are
disinterested.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The 70th legislative district sprawls across 12 rural counties
in West Texas, coming up to the edge of, without entering, three of
the region's biggest cities; Lubbock, Midland and Abilene. The
district encompasses mile after mile of cotton farms, ranches and
small towns.
</P>
<P>
   The district has been represented for a decade by David Counts,
D-Knox County, on the far side of the district from McLaughlin's
home in Big Spring. McLaughlin first ran against him two years ago,
losing by a slim margin.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, McLaughlin focused his campaign on neighborhood walks,
knocking on more than 10,000 doors. This year, he said, he will
knock on about the same number. ``I am absolutely convinced that
the way to do it, at this level, is to look as many voters in the
eye as you can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His message is drawn directly from the Ronald Reagan playbook,
by way of Newt Gingrich; smaller government, fewer regulations,
strong family values.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin spent about $140,000 on the 1996 campaign, he said,
and plans to spend roughly the same amount this year in his rematch
against Counts. Some of that money comes from local donors, but
some comes from ``Eight in '98,'' which offers logistical and
strategic advice, as well as money. ``They are a definite factor,''
McLaughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Counts was at a Democratic event earlier this month at church
picnic grounds north of Abilene. ``The Republicans came after me
two years ago and they're doing it again,'' he said. ``They keep
trying to tie me to President Clinton, but it won't work. I
personally think this Clinton thing is going to go away real quick.
The last straw was the lurid detail that Ken Starr put in that
report. Now the people know his heart was black and his cause was
not pure.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin doesn't really know how much national political
obsessions will affect his race, nor how much he will benefit from
Bush's coattails in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to tie ourselves to Bush as much as we can,''
McLaughlin said. ``After all, we're both singing from the same
sheet of music.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor has been in the district a couple of times to
campaign for himself and for local Republicans, and each visit has
meant a boost for McLaughlin.
</P>
<P>
   What would happen, McLaughlin is asked, if Clinton came to the
70th district to campaign for his opponent?
</P>
<P>
   A smile spread across his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election would be over,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
