<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-COMSAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKHEED TO BUY COMSAT FOR $2.7 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (mk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving away from the military business and toward global
telecommunications, Lockheed Martin Corp. announced Sunday a $2.7
billion acquisition of Comsat Corp., a communications satellite
company created by the government more than three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   The deal represents a strategic shift for Lockheed Martin, which
only three months ago abandoned a planned $8.3 billion takeover of
Northrop Grumman Corp., a move that would have pushed Lockheed
deeper into military products. The Northrop deal collapsed in the
face of Defense Department opposition on antitrust grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Comsat acquisition would build on Lockheed's existing
satellite services business, which primarily focuses on satellite
design and launches. Comsat is a leading provider of voice, data,
video and other satellite communications services between the
United States and other countries, and is the mechanism by which
such companies as AT&AMP;T, MCI Communications and Sprint send their
telephone calls overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The deal must still be approved by the Federal Communications
Commission and the Department of Justice, as well as shareholders.
But John Sponyeo, chief executive of Lockheed's global
telecommunications division, said he did not anticipate antitrust
problems with this acquisition, since Comsat and Lockheed are not
in overlapping businesses. The Defense Department does not have to
review this deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area of growth and telecommunication services is
something our company has been looking at for a long time,''
Sponyeo said. ``We are heavily involved in the manufacture of
satellite launches and this brings us more heavily into global
information technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Lockheed created the new global
telecommunications division, one of six major business lines, in a
move that initially signaled a strategic shift. According to
Sponyeo, the Comsat acquisition had been in the discussion stage
for at least 18 months, and would have gone ahead even had the
Northrop deal been successful. ``They were on two parallel
tracks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Chao, an aerospace industry analyst at Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter, said the Comsat acquisition was a good fit for
Lockheed, adding, ``It's great in terms of providing long-term
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Others agreed. ``In one fell swoop, Lockheed has become a major
player in the global telecommunications industry and, in
particular, in that part of the industry that exploits the use of
space-based technology,'' said Loren Thompson, chief operating
officer at Lexington Institute, a military research group based in
Arlington, Va. ``This signals that telecommunications will become a
major long-term strategic thrust for Lockheed, and it's a decisive
departure from the traditional Cold War definition of the defense
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the first phase of the deal, Lockheed Martin will acquire
up to 49 percent of Comsat's common stock for $45.50 a share in
cash, or about $1.3 billion. That price represents a 33 percent
premium over Comsat's stock price, which closed Friday at $34.125,
down 62.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In the second phase, Lockheed Martin will merge a new
telecommunications subsidiary with Comsat, in a stock swap under
which Comsat shareholders will receive a half-share of Lockheed
Martin for each Comsat share. The companies value this transaction
at $1.4 billion, based on recent market prices. Lockheed Martin's
shares ended trading Friday at $100, down $3.50.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Lockheed Martin will assume Comsat's debt,
which was $700 million as of June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase of the deal is contingent on changes in federal
law to remove restrictions on the ownership of Comsat voting stock.
Charles Manor, a Lockheed spokesman, said he anticipated no
congressional problems with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we propose fits into the desires of Congress,'' Manor
said, adding that Lockheed will ``reach out to Congress'' to
explain the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Alewine, chief executive of Comsat, which, like Lockheed,
is based in Bethesda, Md., said the partnership with Lockheed
``makes strategic and competitive sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our partnership with Lockheed will provide us with the
resources to compete effectively in the years to come,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Comsat owns 18 percent of Intelsat, an international consortium
that is the world's largest communications satellite network. In
the last two years, Comsat has been working to increase profits by
spinning off nontelecommunications businesses. Ms. Alewine said no
reduction in the Comsat work force was anticipated as a result of
the merger. ``There is an exploding market for telecommunications
services and what Lockheed is buying are our major assets, our
people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson of the Lexington Institute said, ``This deal gives
Lockheed the ability to leverage its military technology in this
area to a far broader range of markets and applications.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
