<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA CABBIE TAXIS TO GREAT AMERICAN VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Chalk one up for the good old USA.
</P>
<P>
   Against an international field that included drivers from Ghana,
Thailand, Pakistan and Eritrea, Johnny Carney of Ardmore, Okla.,
defended the honor of America with a victory in the Great American
Taxi Race yesterday at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Carney, who has worked 10 years driving cabs in the Fort
Worth-Dallas area, outdueled India's Baldren Bassra over a course
set up in the frontstretch and pit road that was designed to test
various skills involved in operating a taxi. He won $500 and a
trophy to commemorate his victory in the afternoon preliminary to
the Indy Racing League's Lone Star 500K.
</P>
<P>
   Driving for the team from Big Tex Taxi, Carney brought van No.
820 around the course at tire-screeching speeds, driving with
abandon around the turns and earning cheers from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought I'd be at a disadvantage driving a van
against the cars, but I told them I could take any one of these and
do the same thing,'' said Carney, who led Big Tex to the team title
over Terminal Taxi and Choice Cabs. ``It's the driver. I drive
70,000 miles a year, so I know what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   He took his van to the edge in navigating a course that included
a stop sign, a toll booth, an obstacle course, a required stop to
pick up and deliver ``passengers'' _ dummies placed in the back
seat _ and parallel parking. But Carney pointed out that he doesn't
drive that fast every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the difference,'' he said with a smile. ``When I have
passengers on board, those people are trusting me with their
lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
