<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-STREETCAR-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREVIN'S `STREETCAR' OFF THE TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSHUA KOSMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO &LR;   &LR; _ Amid all the pomp and hullabaloo surrounding
Saturday night's world premiere of ``A Streetcar Named Desire'' _
the operatic version, that is, commissioned by the San Francisco
Opera from composer Andre Previn _ the true focus of attention was
a dead man who had nothing to do with the project.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Tennessee Williams, whose classic play lent a
little reflected light to this adaptation but more often simply
upstaged it.
</P>
<P>
   The premiere of this three-act opera, Previn's first, was
unmistakably a major event. The War Memorial Opera House was
buzzing beforehand with the sort of curious anticipation that
rarely attends opera openings, and it seemed as though every member
of the international music press was on hand to weigh in on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's most succinct criticism, though, came from the man
I overheard on the way out of the Opera House, saying to his wife,
``I didn't think they'd just put the play to music. I thought
there'd be some (set ital)songs.(end ital)''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there are a few _ one gorgeous aria apiece for Stella and
Mitch, and a steady stream of virtuoso lyric showpieces for Blanche
DuBois, the fading Southern belle whose descent into madness is
charted with terrifying clarity in the play.
</P>
<P>
   But what's striking about this opera, which has a libretto by
Philip Littell, is how little it adds to Williams' dramatic
conception. There are long stretches in which the experience of
watching Previn's work is scarcely distinguishable from watching
the original play _ other than the fact that the famous words are
sung rather than spoken.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, of course, the project has a certain canny
appeal. Even when Previn's music is at its most timorous and
faceless, the audience is still watching ``Streetcar,'' and how bad
can that be?
</P>
<P>
   Williams' great melodrama has managed to outlive the definitive
early performances by Marlon Brando, Vivien Leigh, Jessica Tandy
and Kim Hunter. For all its overheated rhetoric, the play's
depiction of the collision between Blanche's fragile, self-deluded
devotion to the ``finer things'' in life and the animal sexuality
embodied by her brother-in-law Stanley Kowalski retains its tragic
power.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about Previn's score, in fact, is the way it
embodies that duality in music, through a stylistic shorthand that
perhaps only this composer _ with his extensive background in jazz,
film music and the classical tradition _ could have pulled off.
</P>
<P>
   The code is a simple but effective one, in which jazz stands for
the harsh pull of sexual desire while the bland melodies of
contemporary opera _ those watery vocal lines, derivative of
Strauss and Puccini, that make up today's sorry operatic lingua
franca _ define Blanche's dedication to art and culture.
</P>
<P>
   At times this device is clumsily used, as in the wailing tenor
saxophone that follows the mention of the seedy Hotel Flamingo (the
site of Blanche's secret descent into nymphomania) or the similar
riff that greets Stanley's testosterone-driven entrance in lurid
red pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   More often, though, it helps clarify the rift between Blanche
and Stanley, with Stella caught poignantly between the two. The
opera's most deeply eloquent moments, in fact, are Stella's,
beginning with the Act 1 aria in which she tries to explain to
Blanche the hold that her undeniably ``common'' husband has on her.
This short, resplendent ballad (``I can hardly stand it when he's
away for a night'') displays the gentility of Stella's upbringing,
but the aching triads underneath are redolent of pure erotic
longing.
</P>
<P>
   Better still _ probably the opera's most magical moment _ is the
duet for the two sisters that ends Act 1. This is the morning after
Stella has confounded Blanche by returning to Stanley after he
drunkenly beats her and lets loose with his famous howl of
repentance, and Previn gives her a sinuous, wordless hum that is as
expressive of erotic satiety as any music ever written.
</P>
<P>
   Blanche, meanwhile, twitters around in uncomprehending
counterpoint, her stately, angular melodies showing how little she
understands of her sister's happiness. Previn may not have intended
to use contemporary operatic style to denote cluelessness, but the
rest of Blanche's role often has that effect. One aria after
another rolls out of her mouth, each one pretty and forgettable;
nothing could spell more clearly the effeteness and decay of the
Old South.
</P>
<P>
   The one major character without an aria, interestingly, is
Stanley. The omission must certainly have been deliberate _
Stanley, after all, would not go in for such highfalutin stuff _
but the problem is that it robs him of some spark of humanity. Much
more than in the original, this Stanley is a heavy _ brutal and
brooding, with none of the dangerous wit that should also be there.
</P>
<P>
   Littell's role as librettist has mostly been editorial _ almost
everything here is taken directly from Williams. And the two major
interpolations are both excruciatingly bad. One is Mitch's Act 2
aria, a stretch of Hallmark Card banality (``You know when it's the
right thing/ You just know it!/ And you do it ... That's all there
is to love.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The other is an odd expansion of the part of the Mexican woman
who appears at the end of the play selling flowers for the dead.
Williams' introduction of that figure in Blanche's darkest hour
(delectably parodied by Edward Albee in ``Who's Afraid of Virginia
Woolf?'') may have been a little coy, but certainly no one missed
its import, or required this weirdly demonic outburst.
</P>
<P>
   Even the production, directed by veteran Colin Graham, seems
largely concerned with being faithful to the source material.
Michael Yeargan's set, with its spare two-room flat and large,
circling outer staircase, conjures up the classic 1951 film, as
does Thomas J. Munn's film noir-ish lighting.
</P>
<P>
   In a wonderfully strong cast, the weakest link, unfortunately,
is Renee Fleming's Blanche. She attacks this grueling role with
commitment and insight, and she is capable of arresting bursts of
lyrical splendor. But her light soprano tends to fade out at
untoward moments, and her dramatic characterization is similarly
flickery _ now sharply focused, now vague and impassive.
</P>
<P>
   As Stanley, Rodney Gilfry embodies the part decisively _ he
looks phenomenally good with his shirt off (take that, Samuel
Ramey!), and he can sing and chew gum at the same time. He makes
the role's barking, petulant outbursts sound so musical, in fact,
that it's a shame Previn and Littell couldn't find an occasion for
him to stretch out into some kind of lyricism.
</P>
<P>
   But the most exciting performances came in the secondary roles,
particularly soprano Elizabeth Futral's magnificent company debut
as Stella. This is a singer who has it all _ a bright, superbly
beautiful tone, flawless technical control, dramatic intelligence
and sheer sex appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Dean Griffey brought a sweet, limpid tenor to the part
of Mitch, bringing out the character's touching blend of insecurity
and moralism. Josepha Gayer sang the Mexican Woman with dark gusto,
and Jeffrey Lentz made an alluring company debut as the young
paperboy. Previn's conducting was a little stiff but forceful.
</P>
<P>
   Could this project have turned out otherwise? It's impossible to
say. An opera based on ``Streetcar'' has been a cherished dream of
general director Lotfi Mansouri for some 20 years now, and I at
least have never understood why.
</P>
<P>
   The balance of evidence from nearly four centuries of opera,
after all, makes it perfectly clear that the greatest plays are
(set ital)not(end ital) the ones that become great operas. They're
too strong, and they simply overpower all but the mightiest
composers. On one side of the ledger in this argument is Verdi's
``Otello''; on the other side, everything else.
</P>
<P>
   What ``Streetcar'' calls to mind, in fact, is not so much
``Otello'' as Ambroise Thomas' ``Hamlet,'' in which the famous
soliloquy frightened the composer so much that he scarcely did
anything with it at all. Previn seems to have been similarly cowed
in the face of Williams' genius. Like Thomas, he was probably right
to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
