u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURDER-ALVAREZ-COX     09-20 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDER-ALVAREZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murder probe forces man into spotlight
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg and Monika Gonzalez
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLE GLADE, Fla. _ Jose Antonio Alvarez has become a reluctant
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Cuban immigrant, just four years in America, is
part of a murder investigation stretching from upper-crust
Manhattan to a neighborhood flush against the sugar fields of
western Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   New York police are convinced the itinerant handyman,
construction worker, fast-food worker and truck driver played no
role in the disappearance and feared murder of socialite Irene
Silverman. But that hasn't stopped New York and Florida reporters
from calling him or descending on the two mobile homes at the
Alvarez family lot.
</P>
<P>
   The family isn't handling its renown well: Jose Alvarez
terminated a fleeting interview by chasing two reporters and a
photographer away from his Belle Glade home with a camping hatchet.
</P>
<P>
   Blame a family named Kimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was working for them and that was the extent of the whole
thing,'' New York police Detective Dan Rodriguez said. ``The guy's
a victim. They used him like they use a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Sante Kimes, 61, and her son, Kenneth Kimes Jr., 23, are in
jail. ``All information we're gathering right now is pointing'' to
the idea that the pair murdered Silverman, an 82-year-old heiress
and former Radio City Music Hall ballerina who rented them a
$6,000-a-month apartment in her upper East Side mansion, Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   When New York police picked up the Kimeses, they found a gym bag
stuffed with items belonging to Silverman as well as a deed giving
the Kimeses her $4 million mansion for $390,000.
</P>
<P>
   But police haven't found Silverman _ and that's why they went
looking for Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   When they saw him on a mansion security videotape, they tracked
him to Florida _ they won't say how _ and flew down to talk to him.
And when he said Kenneth Kimes had told him a New Jersey field
``would be a good place to bury something,'' New York police
assaulted the field with Weed Whackers,TM lawnmowers and other
garden tools in search of Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Kimeses are charged with wrangling a credit card in
the name of Palm Beach lawyer Max Schorr (``They knew all about me
_ my date of birth, my mother's name,'' Schorr said last week) and
buying a $14,000 Lincoln with a bum check.
</P>
<P>
   Manalapan police also believe they bought an $84,000 motor home
with two rubber checks they handed over May 30 in the lobby of the
Ritz-Carlton. The dealer's representative believes Alvarez may have
been the third person he saw in the lobby, Manalapan detective Tom
Clark said. He said Alvarez may have been only an unwitting puppet.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess, just from the way the whole scenario went down, is
he was more of a `go-fer' kind of guy,'' Clark said. But he said he
wants to talk to Alvarez before making sure.
</P>
<P>
   Police have described Sante Kimes as a vicious woman who,
despite inheriting millions when her ex-husband died in 1994,
conned and stole from friends, business associates, insurance
companies and strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Silverman case, the Kimeses are also suspected of
foul play in the cases of a Los Angeles businessman shot in the
head, a lawyer for the Kimeses who disappeared with them on a trip
to Costa Rica, and an Arab banker who vanished just after meeting
Sante Kimes in the Bahamas. They were even briefly suspected in the
disappearance of Palm Beach furniture heiress Jacqueline Levitz
from her Mississippi home.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses recruited Alvarez in May in front of the Pollo
Tropical restaurant on Okeechobee Boulevard in West Palm Beach,
where he had worked for only a month, Rodriguez said. He said the
Kimeses hired Alvarez as a handyman at the villa they were renting
in the Palm Beach Polo Club in Wellington, then took him with them
in June to New York. Police either don't know or won't discuss what
else the trio did in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez has told police he left the Kimeses June 23, long before
Silverman disappeared. New York detective Rodriguez said Alvarez
found himself stranded in Manhattan but was able to cash his last
Pollo Tropical paycheck for bus fare home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They treated me fine, but they were kind of strange, so I
left,'' Alvarez told a New York television station.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Manalapan detectives still want to talk to Alvarez. But
New York police say they're done with him _ and still looking for
Irene Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Kleinberg and Monika Gonzalez write for the Palm Beach
Post, West Palm Beach, Fla. Researcher Lynne Palombo contributed to
this report, which was supplemented by Palm Beach Post archives and
wire services.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
