A5090 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHIPWRECK-COINS-COX     09-20 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHIPWRECK-COINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Treasure salvors win battle, bring coins back to U.S.
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, FLA. _ A fortune in silver from a 17th century
shipwreck is headed to Florida, its journey delayed for more than a
year while treasure salvors battled with Ecuador's government over
the booty of coins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are glad it's over, and we are happy the split was finally
honored,'' said Rob McClung of West Palm Beach, the expedition
leader who recovered nearly 6,000 coins from the shipwreck in early
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador will keep half of the coins. The other half is being
transported to a Central Florida lab for cleaning and inventory.
</P>
<P>
   The coins are from the Spanish galleon La Capitana, which sank
off the Ecuador coast in 1654 when the pilot made a navigation
error and ran the 130-foot ship aground. Most of the 216 treasure
chests aboard were salvaged, but McClung found thousands of coins
buried beneath the ocean floor.
</P>
<P>
   The coins had been stored since May 1997 in the Central Bank of
Ecuador in Quayaquil. They were kept there as the salvors fended
off claims from rivals that coins were being smuggled out of
Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   The government exonerated the salvors and granted the expedition
company its 50 percent share on Sept. 9, said German Moro of
Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Moro's Sudamerica Discovery Inc. held the permit for the salvage
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a year-and-a-half of hardball legal maneuvering to
force the government to do the split,'' said Moro.
</P>
<P>
   The salvors stopped digging in April and filed a $25 million
lawsuit against government officials to force a division of the
treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Moro said representatives from the Ecuadorean finance, education
and defense spent five minutes examining the two piles of coins and
chose the one topped with a gold cross and a pair of chart
dividers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could very well be the instrument the pilot used when he
made his mistake,'' Moro said.
</P>
<P>
   The salvor's half, which Moro estimates has a value of more than
$1 million, will be divided among investors in Ecuador and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   McClung's Oceanic International Corp. has a 5 percent share of
the treasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone will get rich, but there will be enough
to make a nice return for the investors,'' Moro said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the coins, McClung's divers brought up silver bars,
bronze cannon balls, candelabra and dinnerware from the treasure
galleon.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's never been the treasure since I was not getting
the lion's share of it'' McClung said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his reward was finding the ship and the vindication of
allegations from rival treasure hunters that he plundered the
wreck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing comes easily, but not everything should be that
hard,'' he said Friday from his home in Lake Clarke Shores.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, McClung vowed never to return to Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Now he said he's thinking of returning because Moro's group was
issued a new permit by the government to continue digging at the
site.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Douthat writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
