<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-REDS-SOSA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA DRAWS THE COLLAR AS CUBS SLIP BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ANDREW BLUTH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ As Sammy Sosa goes, so go the Cubs, and Sunday Sosa
failed for the fourth straight game to hit a home run, going 0 for
5 in a 7-3 loss to the Cincinnati Reds on a day dedicated to
celebrating his season.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a sunny, festive afternoon quickly turned into a
dreary evening for the Cubs at Wrigley Field. After a 64-minute
rain delay, Bret Boone, the Reds' second baseman, drove in six runs
on three home runs, the last of which the umpires in the crowd
believed to be a foul ball. The Cubs fell a game behind the Mets in
the race for the wild-card spot in the National League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sosa fell two behind the St. Louis Cardinals' Mark
McGwire for the season home run lead. McGwire hit his 65th home run
in an 11-6 victory at Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-game celebration here included presentations of a
trophy, a painting and a new car to Sosa. Before appearances by
Commissioner Bud Selig, Juan Marichal, and the Cub legend Ernie
Banks, the emcee, Chip Caray, read a note of congratulations sent
by McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   It said: ``Congratulations on your special day at Wrigley Field.
We have shared an exciting and historic season that will be
remembered for years to come. You have handled yourself with class
and dignity and are to be commended for a fantastic 1998 season.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa addressed the sold-out crowd of 40,117, thanking the fans,
and then concluded with a celebratory lap around the field before
being swarmed by his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the run around the field because I just want to show the
fans how much I love them,'' Sosa said after the Cubs' last
regular-season home game.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa said the intense news media pressure over the last few
weeks was not affecting him, but he conceded that increased
attention this weekend from friends and fans from the Dominican
Republic, his home country, may have caused him to swing for the
fences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably trying to do too much,'' he said. ``But they
also pitched me really well.''
</P>
<P>
   In sweeping the three-game series, Reds pitchers held Sosa to 0
for 13. Sosa struck out twice Sunday, popped up to first base and
second base, and reached on an error by third baseman Aaron Boone
in the third inning. The Cubs were swept in a three-game series at
home for only the second time this season.
</P>
<P>
   On the day post-season tickets went on sale, a rarity in
Chicago, the Mets defeated Florida, 5-0. Both the Mets and the Cubs
have five games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   In the two innings after the rain delay, the Cubs' starter,
Kevin Tapani, who was shooting for his 20th victory of the season,
gave up five runs, including two of the Boone home runs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
