<DOCNO> NYT19980920.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORIDA-VOTERS-ART-2T     09-20 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-VOTERS-ART-2TAKES(1000)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWING VOTERS MAKE THE `OTHER FLORIDA' CRUCIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIPLEY, Fla. _ Wade Jackson, a farmer near this Panhandle city,
remembers traveling to Punta Gorda in the southwestern part of the
state some 15 years ago to visit a nephew. That was as far south as
he has ever gone in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never had the desire to visit,'' Jackson said of South
Florida, which he has heard is crowded (``You have to live jammed
up'') and full of both immigrants from the North (``the Yankees'')
and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 62, is a native Floridian, but his Florida is not the
one of urban sprawl and sun-and-fun tourist spots that most people
know. It is the other Florida, the one that grows peanuts, cotton
and timber and calls itself ``lower Alabama,'' the one of family
generations, Democratic tradition and black-and-white demographics
and the one that holds the votes that can swing elections.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts call it the ``cracker vote,'' that of rural
whites in the Panhandle and central parts of the state who are
registered Democrats out of loyalty but have no trouble voting
Republican out of belief. And in a year when Republicans need
crossover voters to solidify their power in state government with
the governorship, the November election highlights not only the
importance of this ``other Florida'' but the diversity of a state
where campaigns must play as well with Southerners as with
transplanted Yankees, in the Bible Belt as in concrete canyons and
in cracker as in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't think Florida is a Southern state, but it was the
third state to secede from the union,'' said Lance deHaven-Smith,
associate director of the Florida Institute of Government at
Florida State University in Tallahassee and co-author of the
institute's ``Almanac of Florida Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1920s it led the nation in the number of lynchings per
year,'' deHaven-Smith said. ``Until the 1950s, very few people
lived south of Orlando.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, areas like Washington County, just below the Alabama
border, and South Florida counties like Miami-Dade, at the tip of
the Florida peninsula, offer one of the starkest contrasts found in
a state that doubled its population, to 14.7 million from 6.8
million, in the last quarter-century. With most of that growth
concentrated in the southern half of the state, Miami-Dade County
has bulged into the largest county in Florida with two million
residents, nearly half of them foreign-born and 56 percent of
Hispanic heritage.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of Washington County's 20,000 residents, by
contrast, are Florida natives, 83 percent white and 15 percent
black. About a quarter of the county's population lives in Chipley.
</P>
<P>
   Washington County is the kind of place where the word redneck is
not derogatory, and where one of the landmarks is a monument along
Highway 77 to the possum, ``an important aid to human survival in
times of distress and critical need'' and the subject of a festival
and parade every August. Here, they root not for the Florida
Marlins or the Miami Dolphins but for closer teams, the Atlanta
Braves and New Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   While Miami suffers the ills of big population centers _
corruption, drug trafficking and ethnic conflict _ Washington
County's worst law-enforcement problem is domestic violence. The
sale of liquor and beer is prohibited in the county, where churches
wield strong influence and where voters hold public officials to
high moral standards.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Peel, 51, who had been sheriff for 16 years, found this out
in 1992, when he was voted out of office after he divorced his
wife. In 1996, after he married someone else, voters reinstated
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a religious issue for a lot of people,'' Peel said
of divorce. ``Voters here are very intolerant of anything
associated with character flaws.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Corbus, 33, moved here from St. Petersburg five years ago
to escape what she said was increasing development and congestion.
``In Florida, you have to go north to be in the Deep South,'' Ms.
Corbus said.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, ``sometimes it seems like we're kind of out here by
ourselves,'' Ms. Corbus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems anything west of Tallahassee is like it's not part of
Florida,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling of isolation is bolstered by the diminishing power
of areas like the Panhandle as other regions of the state
experienced explosive growth. Washington County has one state
representative and one state senator. Miami-Dade County alone has
20 state representatives and seven state senators.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Panhandle residents say, sometimes they are
subjected to laws, from management of growth to gun control, that
make more sense in the south than in the north of Florida. And the
region, they complain, is often shortchanged when money is doled
out by the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a liberal-conservative rift that while tenuous _
conservatives dominate among both Democrats and Republicans in the
state Legislature _ surfaces every now and then. For instance, a
Democratic senator representing several counties near the Georgia
border blamed ``South Florida Jewish senators who do not believe in
Jesus'' for defeating a 1994 school prayer bill.
</P>
<P>
   Broward and Palm Beach counties, north of Miami and the second
and third most populous areas in the state with more than one
million residents each, are the state's liberal Democratic
strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   But demographers say the population movement has been shifting
to the north over the last decade, and areas like Washington County
are growing with refugees from South and Central Florida looking
for more room and a more relaxed lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   But growth is not universally welcomed here. Many residents fear
harm to what they regard as the area's pluses _ low crime rates,
good schools, plentiful and reasonably priced land, friendly people
_ and also worry about new demands on services and public works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like our small-town flavor,'' said Jan Morris, editor of
The Washington County News. ``We're experiencing a massive influx
from South Florida right now. The problem is they come here but
they want infrastructure, like paved roads. They locate here and
suddenly they want all the amenities.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While small as a percentage of the electorate, cracker voters
are crucial in statewide and national elections in which
Republicans and liberal Democrats balance each other out, said
deHaven-Smith. What determines the outcome in these elections, he
said, is the bloc of conservative Democrats that sometimes votes
Republican and sometimes Democratic, depending on factors like
familiarity with the candidate and conservative views on issues
like taxes and crime.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Lawton Chiles, a Democrat who is a native of Central
Florida, understood the need to appeal to rural whites when, in the
last televised debate before the 1994 election, he warned his
Republican opponent, Jeb Bush, ``The old he-coon walks just before
the light of day.'' The cracker saying was crystal clear here but
indecipherable to Bush, who moved to Miami in 1980, as well as to
thousands watching the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers like The Miami Herald had to run articles explaining
what he had meant, quoting in one a Hispanic man who said he had
learned ``how people feel when we speak Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   He-coon, it turned out, means the smart raccoon that waits until
just before dawn to come out of hiding, when hunting dogs have
tired of chasing younger, less-smart raccoons. ``He-coon was a
cracker saying I knew crackers would identify with,'' Chiles, 68,
said in a recent interview. He won re-election by about 64,000
votes out of 4.2 million votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush again running for governor, the Democratic contender,
Lt. Gov. Kenneth MacKay, may need more than cracker sayings. While
Democrats lead Republicans in registered voters in Florida, 45
percent to 40 percent, Republican gains reached a watershed in 1996
when voters installed a Republican majority in the state
Legislature for the first time this century.
</P>
<P>
   Around North Florida, the ability to vote in the Democratic
primary in races like sheriff and county commissioner keeps many
from switching party registration. But already Republicans have
taken over local posts in some counties. Chiles and other Democrats
blame an influx of Republicans into the state and redistricting for
their party's losses, but in the Panhandle, Republicans who are
former Democrats say the party has lost its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're against prayer in school and for abortion, it's
clear-cut,'' Durell Peaden Jr., a doctor who represents four
Panhandle counties in the state House of Representatives, said to
explain why he switched to the Republican side last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't change and leave the party,'' Peaden said. ``The
party changed and left us. The Democratic Party became a lot more
liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a Democratic majority among registered voters in
Washington County, Bush carried the county over Chiles in the last
election and many voters remain firmly behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here by and large all hold down jobs and are
entrepreneurial,'' said Allen Clark, 41, an insurance and real
estate businessman who is among the Democrats here who support
Bush. ``Jeb Bush is a big entrepreneurial person. People don't want
a handout, just opportunity, and that's more Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats like Jackson, the farmer, plan to vote for MacKay out
of tradition, but Jackson said he would not be distressed if Bush
won.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics don't worry me,'' Jackson said. ``You can put a
Democrat and a Republican in a burlap bag and shake them up and
they'd fall out at the same time. There's no difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
