<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TV NETWORKS ARE HEADING FOR TOUGHEST FALL FIGHT YET
</P>
<P>
   The new fall television season officially opens Monday night,
and executives of the six broadcast networks are expecting their
bloodiest battle yet for ratings as they squeeze 36 new shows into
an already crowded prime time. Indeed, there is a sense of
desperation in the industry, because the risks are so great and the
stakes so high.
</P>
<P>
   That desperation is reflected in deals like the $13 million an
episode that NBC will pay for ``ER,'' TV's biggest hit. And the
networks are anxiously shuffling their schedules to seek an edge on
specific nights; Fox, for example, is moving its animated series
``King of the Hill'' to Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   WEB SURFING VS. CHANNEL SURFING
</P>
<P>
   Are Web surfers spending less time watching television? Several
surveys have said yes. But a new survey for the Discovery Channel
indicates that even though teen-agers watch less television as
households begin to use the Internet, everyone else watches more.
</P>
<P>
   A WATERGATE SOURCE UNMASKED?
</P>
<P>
   The man known as Deep Throat is credited with being the source
of explosive articles written by Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein as
they unraveled the Nixon administration's abuses of power. Now, a
new book contends that Deep Throat was not just one man, but a
composite and a plot device in the book and the film version of
``All the President's Men.''
</P>
<P>
   CHASING THE ONLINE MUSIC MARKET
</P>
<P>
   Lured by an online music market that the research firm Jupiter
Communications predicts will reach $2.8 billion a year by 2002, the
record industry has struggled with finding a way to use Internet
technologies to realize better margins. But like everything on the
Internet, there is no road map to profits from online music.
</P>
<P>
   BEARS UNNERVE SOME ENTREPRENEURS
</P>
<P>
   For entrepreneurs, going public is the ultimate payoff for their
work. Many founders of start-ups set their sights on taking their
companies public before they even file their incorporation papers.
But the turmoil in the stock market and fears of a bear market have
created a quandary for new-media entrepreneurs and others: should
they try to sell stock now or wait?
</P>
<P>
   LAWYERS OPPOSE YEAR 2000 PLAN
</P>
<P>
   A compromise effort by Congress and the Clinton administration
to promote candid information about Year 2000 problems in the
nation's computers is being assailed by trial lawyers because a
cornerstone of the plan would grant computer and chip makers
immunity from liability suits.
</P>
<P>
   MULTICULTURAL MARKETING EXPANDS
</P>
<P>
   rue North Communications, the giant ad agency company, is
stepping up its efforts in multicultural marketing, forming a unit
devoted to encouraging advertisers to keep pace with the changing
face of consumers by increasing sales pitches aimed at ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   STEAMY REPORT FOR A STAID PUBLISHER
</P>
<P>
   The literature of choice at the year-old Public Affairs
publishing house is intelligent and reflective _ serious nonfiction
that would normally not be a best seller. But the leading title on
its debut list this fall is a steamy one, otherwise known as ``The
Starr Report.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
