</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY SHUT OUT BY SAN JOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ This isn't how the Los Angeles Galaxy wanted
to get ready for the playoffs _ unable to find the net against what
was, until Sunday, Major League Soccer's worst club.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the Galaxy stands just 10 days before its
postseason opener, its storied attack shut out for the second time
in five days by the lowly San Jose Clash, this one a meaningless
1-0 defeat played out before 11,123 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Think the Galaxy is concerned?
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding?'' replied defender Robin Fraser. ``This team?
No chance. I'm not concerned at all. We've got more guns than any
team in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   That they do, with an MLS-record 84 goals through its first 29
matches and at least two players, Cobi Jones and Welton, battling
for the scoring title. But with the Clash willing to defend with
numbers _ a tactic the Galaxy (23-8, 65 points) can expect from
Dallas in the first-round series beginning Oct. 1 _ L.A. could
create only so many decent opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   And so it's been 182 minutes since the team has scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally and tactically we were not disciplined,'' Galaxy
coach Octavio Zambrano said. ``That's certainly a reason to be
concerned. I expect more. I expect more discipline in those two
aspects; they are crucial to aspire to win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the Galaxy's goal, and neither Wednesday's 1-0 shootout
win in San Jose nor Sunday's loss had any impact on its chances.
But if L.A. can't finish in a couple of weeks, its quest will end
prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy had its chances Sunday, the two best by Jones and
Welton in a three-minute span late in the first half. Jones, who
trails Columbus' Stern John by a point in the MLS scoring race, hit
the underside of the crossbar in the 36th minute, and Welton
whiffed on a nifty feed from Mauricio Cienfuegos in the 39th.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, Ronald Cerritos netted the Clash's goal,
curling a 21-yard free kick over a three-man wall and inside the
near post. Goalkeeper Matt Reis, getting a start in place of Kevin
Hartman, got a late jump on the ball. He said he looked away for a
split second just as Cerritos hit it and couldn't make the stop
despite getting his fingertips on it.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose (12-19, 30) managed little else against the Galaxy
defense, but after midfielder Clint Mathis was ejected for a
retaliatory kick at Martin Vasquez in the 66th minute, L.A.
couldn't do much, either.
</P>
<P>
   That kept Jones from adding to his scoring total, although he
nearly bagged an assist after setting up Cienfuegos with five
minutes to go; the shot ripped into Clash defender Eddie Lewis and
bounced away.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the scoring crown would only mean so much, Jones says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the last couple years, Roy Lassiter and Preki
won the scoring titles,'' said Jones, who was hobbling after
hitting knees with Vicente Figueroa in the 78th minute. ``But what
everybody remembers most is that D.C. United won the championship
both years.... That's the most important thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
