<HEADER>
A5123 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-     09-20 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVADA COMMISSION MADE RIGHT DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nevada State Athletic Commission made the appropriate
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson agreed at a hearing on Saturday to be evaluated by a
psychiatrist whom he doesn't know and return with the findings on
Oct 3. If that doctor says he's stable, then his chances of
regaining his license to box in that state look good.
</P>
<P>
   No, there's no way to know how he'll react if he's faced with
another stressful situation in the ring. However, a green light by
a qualified, independent therapist not being paid by Tyson is about
as close as you can get.
</P>
<P>
   And the fighter repeatedly has shown great remorse after biting
off a portion of Evander Holyfield's ear last year, and he seems to
understand the damage _ to both himself and others _ he has caused.
</P>
<P>
   An incident last month in a Washington D.C. suburb in which
Tyson was accused of punching one man and kicking another is a
legitimate concern and ultimately could kill his chances of
regaining his license.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, if he is guilty of committing these violent acts it
demonstrates that he still cannot control his temper and has no
business in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   However, the commissioners are in a tough position.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson must be presumed innocent until he's proven guilty even
though no one will be surprised if it turns out Tyson !ital!did
commit these acts.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there appears to be a way out: The commission
can simply revoke his license again if he's convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is that the case might not be resolved before
his return to the ring, which could come as early as November.
Thus, there's a chance he might fight and then be convicted of the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Given the circumstances, it's a reasonable risk, one which the
commissioners are likely to take if Tyson receives a positive
mental evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Magic touch?: Former Lakers star Magic Johnson was at the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   He has applied for his promoter's license in Nevada _ he already
has one in California _ and hopes to promote Tyson's fights when
and if he comes back.
</P>
<P>
   Also present on Saturday was Dan Goossen of America Presents,
who also hopes to play a role in Tyson's career.
</P>
<P>
   Sad day: Julio Cesar Chavez can be excused for quitting against
Oscar De La Hoya on Friday, although even that is difficult to
accept.
</P>
<P>
   He had taken scores of punches from one of the best fighters in
the world Friday night in Las Vegas, he was bleeding from a deep
cut in his mouth and, at 36, he was dead tired.
</P>
<P>
   Some fighters, fighters with bigger hearts, would've kept
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Ring doctor Flip Homansky looked at the cut and said Chavez
could continue. That he didn't was disappointing, but it can be
defended. Perhaps, he simply had nothing left.
</P>
<P>
   The fact he lied about it _ saying his cornermen stopped the
bout _ cannot be excused.
</P>
<P>
   He can be seen in replays shaking his head as he sat on his
stool after the eighth round, which seems to indicate that he had
had enough. And De La Hoya said afterward that Chavez told him as
much.
</P>
<P>
   However, at the post-fight news conference, he denied it was his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise, really: There's a precedent. He also quit when
he was cut on the forehead in the second Frankie Randall fight, in
1994, even though the ring doctor said he could go on.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez will go down in history as one of the sport's great
champions. The fact he doesn't behave like one is disheartening.
</P>
<P>
   A real champ: De La Hoya didn't beat a surprisingly tough Chavez
as easily as almost everyone expected. However, it was a great
night in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Had he stayed on the outside, he could've won every round. But
he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   He risked a great deal _ his perfect record and perhaps a lot of
money, to be specific _ by fighting Chavez's fight simply to make a
point. He said he was trying to give his fans a good fight.
</P>
<P>
   He should be commended for his uncommon courage.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, De La Hoya became a great champion on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Gabriel Ruelas and James Leija have agreed to
fight Oct. 24 in Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas, who grew up in Arleta, easily outpointed Leija to win
the WBC super featherweight championship in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more confident because of the way I beat him the last
time,'' Ruelas said. ``It's nowhere near to say, `Oh man, I beat
him. All I have to do is train and I'll beat him again.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to train real hard for this fight. We're both a lot
more experienced now.''...
</P>
<P>
   Two other L.A.-area fighters are in action soon.
</P>
<P>
   IBF lightweight champ Shane Mosley of Pomona defends his title
against Eduardo Morales on Tuesday in New York on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   And on Oct. 3 at the Las Vegas Hilton, Genaro Hernandez of L.A.
defends his WBC super featherweight title against Olympian Floyd
Mayweather....
</P>
<P>
   The second almost-anonymous heavyweight title bout in two weeks
is set for Saturday, when Lennox Lewis defends his WBC heavyweight
crown against Zelijko Mavrovic in Uncasville, Conn. On paper, it's
a better matchup than Evander Holyfield's successful title defense
against Vaughn Bean on Saturday....
</P>
<P>
   The next card at the Country Club in Reseda is set for Oct. 22,
when former world champion Orlando Canizales will be the featured
fighter. His opponent has yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Also, former NFL running back Alonzo Highsmith will face
7-foot-2, 425-pound Carl Chancellor in a six-round heavyweight
bout. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
