<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5126 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RIPKEN-ART-630&AMP;AD     09-20 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RIPKEN-ART-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES' RIPKEN ENDS STREAK AT 2,632 GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Cal Ripken when he broke the consecutive-game
record in 1995 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Cal Ripken, the Baltimore Orioles third baseman who
had not missed a game since 1982, removed himself from the starting
lineup here Sunday night after playing in 2,632 consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken, 38, walked into the office of Orioles manager Ray Miller
about half an hour before Sunday night's game and said, ``I think
the time is right.''
</P>
<P>
   His staggering feat of endurance is credited with helping major
league baseball regain the loyalty of its fans three summers ago,
when he broke Lou Gehrig's longstanding record of 2,130 consecutive
games played. While it was possible that Ripken would enter later
in the game, it appeared likely that his own streak would end
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The late change in the Orioles' lineup was not reflected until
just minutes before the start of the game. When the name of Ryan
Minor was inserted in Ripken's place at third base on the
scoreboard, only a few fans at Camden Yards reacted, pointing at
the change.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the Baltimore starters ran onto the field to begin
the game with the Yankees, Ripken wrestled playfully with a
teammate in the Orioles' dugout. When Minor jogged to Ripken's
position, fans still did not seem sure of what was taking place.
But after New York's Chuck Knoblauch, the game's first batter,
grounded out to shortstop, the entire Yankees team emerged from the
visiting dugout and tipped their caps across the field, to Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles fans, who stood and cheered Ripken for more than 22
minutes when he broke Gehrig's record on Sept. 6, 1995, stood at
8:11 p.m. to salute him once again.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken burst from the Orioles' dugout, playfully waving for the
fans to sit, but they would not stop cheering and the Yankees would
not stop clapping. Ripken returned to the Orioles' dugout and the
standing ovation continued. Derek Jeter, on deck, stood out of the
batter's box, and the Orioles' pitcher, Doug Johns, waited, having
no intention of interfering with the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken emerged once again, raising both hands, intermittently
turning to face all corners of Camden Yards and acknowledging the
three minutes of cheers before motioning to Johns to throw his next
pitch. Johns obliged him, and for the first time since May 29,
1982, an Orioles' game was being played without Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Ripken tied and broke Gehrig's record, baseball was
coming back from labor strife that had led to the cancellation of
the 1994 World Series. The national respect and adulation for
Ripken at that time was seen as extremely important to the recovery
of baseball; the celebration of the game on the nights of Sept. 5
and Sept. 6 was comparable to how the country has reacted this
summer to Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa as they broke Roger Maris'
single-season record for home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken's production has gradually diminished as he has aged,
though the Orioles' coaching staff values him because of his
intensity and his reliability. Ripken, the Orioles' shortstop since
the first year of the streak, was moved to third base permanently
after the 1996 season, and in 1997, Ripken suffered a lower back
problem so painful that he said he nearly walked off the field.
</P>
<P>
   There had been growing sentiment within the Baltimore
organization since 1995 that Ripken's streak should be ended, that
he would benefit from additional rest and that other players would
be helped by getting additional playing time in his place. Ripken
had said all along that the decision to end his consecutive-game
streak lay solely in the hands of his manager, but each manager
disagreed, understanding the magnitude of Ripken's accomplishment
and its significance in the history of the sport. Davey Johnson,
Ripken's manager in 1995 and 1996, once said that only God or
Ripken himself could end the streak.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Orioles officials had discussed the possibility of ending
Ripken's streak this summer. One executive had said in May that the
streak could end by July, and for several years club executives
have felt that Ripken's autonomy _ a status created by the streak _
was damaging to the spirit of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Otanez, a third baseman who hit 30 home runs for Class
AAA Rochester this season, was called up last month, and because of
Ripken's streak, Otanez played out of position, in right field, and
broke his wrist awkwardly attempting a diving catch. Ripken
continued to play, with his run production the worst among American
League third basemen, and criticism of the streak had grown.
</P>
<P>
   According to John Maroon, the club's spokesman, Ripken and
Miller had privately discussed the possibility of ending the streak
for several weeks. Ripken felt the timing was right: The Orioles
played their final home game here Sunday night; the club is on the
verge of elimination from the playoff race, and the team has
several young infielders available who are seen as part of the
team's future, including Minor, who will go down in history as the
man who replaced a legend.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 minutes before Sunday night's game, Maroon received an
urgent call from Miller, and Maroon hustled to the manager's
office, where Ripken sat in full uniform. ``Hey, man, I'm not
starting,'' Ripken said to Maroon, his tone even.
</P>
<P>
   Gehrig ended his streak in 1939, going to Yankees manager Joe
McCarthy frustrated and confused by his lack of production. Gehrig
did not know at the time that he was dying of a disease that now
takes his name.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken was born and raised in Maryland, the son of an Orioles
minor league manager, seemingly fated to play for Baltimore.
Drafted by the Orioles in 1978, Ripken was 6 feet 4 inches and 220
pounds, by conventional standards too big to play shortstop. But
Earl Weaver, then the Orioles' manager, shifted Ripken from third
base to shortstop in 1982 because of his exceptional hands, his
ability to anticipate and his instinctive understanding of the
game. Ripken won the American League most valuable player award in
1983 and again in 1991, and he holds numerous offensive and
defensive records for shortstops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
