<DOCNO> NYT19980920.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-ART-     09-20 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-ART-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO STOPPING OLERUD AS METS GRAB THE LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos of John Olerud, Al Leiter and Turk Wendell are
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What John Olerud is going through right now is, as he
put it, ``kind of like the chicken and the egg thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The question could have come from straight from Clint Eastwood.
``Are you hot or are you lucky?'' Olerud was asked Sunday after his
two-run home run helped the Mets to a 5-0 victory over Florida and
gave them the National League wild-card lead, where they hope to
stay for five more games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say more hot,'' Olerud, who is 9 for his last 9 and
has reached base in 14 consecutive plate appearances, one short of
the NL record and two off the major-league mark. ``But definitely,
there's a lot of luck involved, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud raised his average to .354 by going 2-for-2 Sunday and
reaching base all four times he came to the plate in the victory,
which gave the Mets (88-69) a one-game lead over Chicago in the
wild-card race. The Cubs lost, 7-3, to the Cincinnati Reds and
former Met right-hander Pete Harnisch Sunday at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   With five games to go, the Mets _ who are trying to qualify for
the postseason for the first time in a decade _ have not only
matched their victory total of last season, but also have pulled 19
games over .500 for the first time since 1990. And they now have
the upper hand on the Cubs again, thanks to three Bret Boone home
runs in Chicago and eight shutout innings from Al Leiter (17-5)
before a sellout crowd of 52,767 at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud's two-run third-inning home run off the Florida
right-hander Brian Meadows (10-13) provided Leiter _ who allowed
just five hits and one walk, while striking out nine _ with all the
runs he would need as he set a career high for victories with 17.
Meanwhile, by homering, doubling and walking twice, Olerud pulled
closer to Colorado's Larry Walker, the NL's leading hitter at .356.
</P>
<P>
   Just how hot is the Mets' pensive first baseman?
</P>
<P>
   Olerud, would join Ed Delahanty (1899 and 1902), at present the
only players to win batting titles in both leagues, should he
overtake Walker down the stretch. He did not make one single out in
the three-game series the Mets just completed with the Marlins. The
last pitcher to retire Olerud was the left-hander Mike Hampton in
Houston on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   With two hits Sunday, Olerud has 192 on the season, second most
in club history to Lance Johnson's 227 in 1996 _ and one more than
Felix Millan's 191 in 1975. His nine consecutive hits ties the
franchise record established by Jose Vizcaino in 1996. Olerud is
one off the NL record of 10 (set nine times) and three off the
major-league mark of 12 (held by Boston's Pinky Higgins in 1938 and
Detroit's Walt Dropo in 1952).
</P>
<P>
   Most impressive of all is the company Olerud will surpass if he
reaches base safely in his next three plate appearances. Barry
Bonds established the NL record by reaching base 15 straight times
this season. Ted Williams, considered by many the greatest hitter
ever, holds the major-league record of 16, which he set in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   To his brush with greatness, Olerud reacts with a variation of
``aw, shucks.'' Luckily for the Mets, Olerud _ whom his Toronto
teammates used to jokingly call Gabby _ speaks volumes with his
bat.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the moment, one would assume that the baseball looks as big
as a blimp to Olerud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that it looks bigger,'' Olerud said. ``I just
think I'm seeing it better. If anything, it seems like the ball
slows down.''
</P>
<P>
   Which explains why someone with 20/18 vision keeps hitting it so
hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of the last time I've had a streak like this,''
said Olerud, who flirted with .400 in 1993 before winning the
American League batting title with a .363 average.
</P>
<P>
   That was the only one of Olerud's first eight full seasons in
the majors in which he hit .300 or better. This year, Olerud _ a
career .293 hitter when the season began _ is a virtual lock to hit
.300 for the second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he's not going to get on base every time up from now
to the end of the season,'' Tom Robson, the Mets' hitting coach,
said. ``But he's got a chance. And he's been absolutely perfect
lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud walked in his first at-bat against Meadows, one of
Florida's many rookies, then belted a changeup the other way for a
two-out opposite-field homer in the third after Tony Phillips had
walked.
</P>
<P>
   In this third plate appearance, Olerud doubled hard over first
base to lead off the sixth and later scored on Lenny Harris'
two-out single to right. (The slow-footed Olerud somehow beat Mark
Kotsay's online throw, sliding under Randy Knorr's tag for a 3-0
lead.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after the Mets had added a fourth run on Phillips'
run-scoring double in the seventh, Olerud drew another walk (this
time against Antonio Alfonseca) to reach base for the 14th
consecutive time, shortly before he took his 10-day-old son,
Garrett John, on his first tour of the Met clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young Garrett John had never seen him hit,'' Manager Bobby
Valentine said. ``He wanted to show him his best. I've never seen a
guy on base as frequently as he. He's just seeing the ball really
well and a couple of balls he hit he placed really well. He really
placed that changeup well over the left-center-field fence. He's a
pretty good hitter, folks. But that's not a scoop.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell, who is becoming something of a folk hero at Shea
Stadium, pitched the ninth inning to tie a franchise record by
appearing in seven straight games. Jesse Orosco had set the Mets'
record in 1986. On Sunday, the Mets' seventh sellout crowd of the
season cheered madly every time Wendell slammed the rosin bag
behind the pitcher's mound. ``I wanted him to get the appreciation
for the job he's done,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said, in
explaining why he used his right-handed setup man in a 5-0 game.
``He wasn't going to throw more than 15 pitches, and he didn't.''
Wendell threw 13. As for his arm? ``They can rebuild it,'' Wendell
said, echoing an old television show. ``It won't fall off.'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
