<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5132 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-L     09-20 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
R-E-S ... CAN YOU SPELL IT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Son, let's talk about the word (begin
ital)respect(end ital) for a moment here.
</P>
<P>
   Definition 1: It's what baseball supposedly failed to give El
Cube' slugger Sammy Sosa after he belatedly hit post-McGwire taters
numbered 61 and 62 around a birthday greeting to some 117-year-old
fan in Withering Heights, Ill., who claims to remember the last
Cubbie title.
</P>
<P>
   So, a week after it happened, the team tried to amend. It flew
in the touring Maris kids (who sang the seventh-inning stretch
ritual), guilted the commish to miss the Brewers' home game against
the Cards (where McAndro muscled out No. 65 and half of No. 66),
taped up a ``Sammy: You're The Man'' banner over the left-field
bleachers to block out some freeloaders across Waveland, gave him
the obligatory convertible on a day when there was a third-inning
downpour, made sure to show out-of-work MJ in attendance on the WGN
telecast, paid someone to warble through the Dominican Republic's
national anthem and had one of those jet-formation fly-bys
(unfortunately, just as Kevin Tapani was about to pitch to the
second batter in the Reds lineup) during a full-on ``Celebratin'
Sammy'' spectacular before the Wrigleys' final home game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bret Boone launches two of his own, the umps give him
another, Sosa pops out to Boone to end it and the Cubs lose to wrap
up a three-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   This, from a team that has been paying respect to the memory of
a man who has a son named Skip and a grandson named Chip by wearing
a cartoon patch on their right sleeves all year....
</P>
<P>
   Definition 2: It's what Oscar De La Hoya claims he wanted but
never got the first time from Julio Cesar Chavez. That's why on
Friday, they each respectfully agreed to pocket a buncha more cash
_ again _ so that it could be more clearly articulated. Apparently,
there was nothing lost in the translation this time....
</P>
<P>
   Definition 3: It's what Rap Master Blaster Shaq Daddy O'Neal has
titled his new hip-hop CD.
</P>
<P>
   One of the singles is ``Blaq Supaman.'' Kids, that's apparently
how it's spelled. No clownin'.
</P>
<P>
   So what did sports teach us here?
</P>
<P>
   Respect can come belated.
</P>
<P>
   Respect can be purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Respect can be lyrically requested (it even rhymes with
``expect.'')
</P>
<P>
   But the stern lesson someone's gotta learn is that until it's
earned, stop yearning....
</P>
<P>
   The difference in priorities these days at Fox and Disney: One
wants ``King of the Hill'' and ``Ally McBeal'' to start strong, the
other wants Ken Hill and Jack McDowell to finish strong....
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West can put the L.A. sports-legend spin on Michael
Ovitz's NFL stadium plan in Carson _ apparently Magic Johnson
wasn't enough _ but Mr. Clutch might double clutch when he moves
into that Staples Center cubicle. Make sure your key fits. The city
politicians who thought you and the Lakers were down with the
revitalized downtown area now know where your priorities lie....
</P>
<P>
   NBA commish David Stern has volunteered to have his pay held
during the lockout, you know, to take one for the team of
financially strapped owners who stand to lose some gate receipts
this year. And sometime this week, they'll probably announce the
start of training camps won't happen in early October as planned.
When will this nightmare end?...
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson should have to apply for a learner's permit before
he's issued a new license....
</P>
<P>
   Reports are that Roger Taylor of the band Queen (are they still
around?) has put up $16 Grand to help organize a buncha blokes to
keep King Rupert Murdoch from buying Manchester United. Why not
just build a moat around the stadium?...
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch's next quest: bid $2.2 bil for a six-year pay-TV
contract for Italian soccer, according to the Financial Times.
What, American soccer isn't good enough?...
</P>
<P>
   And with the soon-to-be bachelor putting his Beverly Hills
fixer-upper on the market for a mere $19.5 million, enough money
will soon be scraped together for that rebuilt Dodger Stadium....
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC's Keith Olbermann ``has quickly established himself as
perhaps the most thoughtful of the cable guys chewing over'' the
Clinton-Lewinsky affair, claims resected Washington Post TV critic
Howard Kurtz. Olbermann takes the lead over fellow ex-
``SportsCenter'' cohort and soon-to-be ex-``Daily Show'' host Craig
Kilborn....
</P>
<P>
   Al Pacino has been hanging around NFL games and practices to
soak up belligerent behavior for his role as a coach in the
upcoming Ollie Stone expose ``On Any Given Sunday,'' which the
league whole-heartedly unendorses....
</P>
<P>
   The final bill for the damage: McGwire 70, Sosa 68 and the MVP,
Griffey 60, and Ramirez wishin' there was a month left. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
