and Jake Sloane, the start-up's founder, in San Francisco. The
company, created last spring as a platform for unknown bands to
distribute their music, has recently shifted into recording and
artist management. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- ONLINE-MUSIC-1, 9-20 --
Larry Rosen, N2K's chief in New York. Unlike most start-ups in the
Internet world, N2K is headed not by youngsters with more vision
than experience but by respected longtime players in the music
industry. ``It's about dealing with more and more artists,'' Rosen
says. ``Recently, we signed Wynton Marsalis, exclusively for the
Internet, for his performances online.'' (Carrie Boretz/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LONDON -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- BRITAIN-LIBRARY-3, 9-20 --
Perusing the Lindisfarne Gospels on-line at the new British Library
in London. Nearly everyone has been impressed by the imagination
and attention to detail within the building. (Jonathan Player/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LONDON -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- BRITAIN-LIBRARY-2, 9-20 --
The atrium at the new British Library in London. ``The library is,
quite simply, awesome; a great public building that graces its
surroundings, provides us with a unique resource and even offers a
new rendezvous for lovers in London,'' writes the usually skeptical
author Will Self in The Times of London in May. He says it made him
feel young again.(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LONDON -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- BRITAIN-LIBRARY-1, 9-20 --
The main reading room at the new British Library in London. During
the 36 years and $843 million this project took, from conception to
completion, the building often seemed it would become one of the
biggest white elephants London had ever seen. But since the library
opened to glorious reviews, public opinion has changed. (Jonathan
Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
