<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 9/20/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BALTIMORE -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- BBA-RIPKEN, 9-20 --
Baltimore Orioles third baseman Cal Ripken Jr. immediately
following the September 6, 1995 game in which he broke Lou Gehrig's
record of 2,130 consecutive games played. Ripken, the who had not
missed a game since 1982, removed himself from the starting lineup
here Sunday night after completing 2,632 consecutive games. Before
Sunday's game Ripken, 38, told Orioles Manager Ray Miller, ``I
think the time is right.'' (Barton Silverman/1995 New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- BBN-METS-MARLINS-2, 9-20
-- In his biggest victory of the season, Al Leiter dominates the
Marlins on Sunday during a 5-0 victory, putting the Mets a game
ahead of the Cubs with five to go. Leiter (17-5) pitched eight
shutout innings before a sell-out crowd of 52,767 at Shea Stadium.
(Mary DiBiase Blaich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- BBN-METS-MARLINS, 9-20 --
John Olerud (9 for his last 9) and pitcher Turk Wendell following
the Mets' 5-0 victory Sunday at Shea. ``Are you hot or are you
lucky?'' Olerud was asked after his two-run home run had just
helped put the Mets back in the National League wild card lead, a
place they hope to stay for five more games. ``I would say more
hot,'' he says. ``But definitely, there's a lot of luck involved,
too.'' (Mary DiBiase Blaich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) TOMS RIVER, N.J. -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- CANCER-CLUSTERS,
9-20 -- Linda Gillick with her son Michael, 19, and Star. After her
son was stricken with cancer, Mrs. Gillick organized a residents'
movement that successfully lobbied for an environmental study of
her community. Michael says he realizes that all the research may
never tell him why he, or any other cancer victim, is sick. ``It's
too late for me,'' he says. ``It's my wish that this not happen to
others.'' (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- JEWISH-NEWYEAR-FLOATER,
9-20 -- In anticipation of Rosh ha-Shanah, the Jewish New Year,
families make their own shofars at a workshop in Manhattan Sunday.
The ram's horn is blown at the arrival of Rosh ha-Shanah, which
began Sunday evening. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UMATILLA RESERVATION, Ore. -- Sept. 20, 1998 --
AMERINDIAN-TOURISM, 9-20 -- Marjorie Deen, left, talks with a youth
guide, Randall Melton, at the Tamastslikt Cultural Center on the
Umatilla Reservation in Oregon. The center is drawing visitors from
around the world. (Jeff Green/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LOS ANGELES -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- TATTOO-CONVENTION-2,
9-20 -- Jack Armstrong, 79, perhaps the oldest known tattoo artist,
at the Inkslingers Ball in Los Angeles. ``I've been doing it longer
than anyone in the history of tattooing,'' says Armstrong, who was
born in Seattle in the back of his mother's tattoo parlor. ``I have
ink running through my veins.'' (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LOS ANGELES -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- TATTOO-CONVENTION-1,
9-20 -- Lucy Souisa of the Netherlands shows her tattoos of Marilyn
Monroe to judges at the Inkslingers Ball. The gathering is one of
the country's biggest conventions of tattoo artists, also known as
ink slingers. And for the last seven years, ink slingers from
around the world, most from the West Coast, have gathered in
Hollywood for three days of tattoo contests, tattoo tips and
tattooing. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BALTIMORE -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- MEDSCHOOL-ELDERLY-2, 9-20
-- Dr. Michael Westerman, center, a resident in geriatrics at the
Johns Hopkins Bayview Medical Center, and Tim Loo, a fellow in
geriatrics there, treating and chatting with John Foltz at his
Baltimore apartment recently. Westerman says he found his
experience at Hopkins so satisfying that he plans to go into
geriatrics. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BALTIMORE -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- MEDSCHOOL-ELDERLY-1, 9-20
-- Beatrice Seamans listening to doctors discussing her case at
Hopkins Bayview, where reading the complex needs of patients is
critical. The geriatrics training program here, along with a
handful of similar ones at other medical schools around the United
States, is part of a growing effort to meet what experts say is an
urgent need for doctors properly trained in the problems and the
process of aging. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNITED NATIONS -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- OBIT-LALL-B&AMP;W, 9-20
-- Arthur Lall at the United Nations in 1962. He had a crucial
behind-the-scenes role in moderating the abrasive K.P. Khrishna
Menon. Lall died Sept. 13 in New York. He was 87. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- ONLINE-PRIVACY, 9-20 -- A
Federal Trade Commission lawyer, Dean Forbes, 31, searching for Web
site privacy abuses. ``Generally we get ideas from reading the
trade press,'' he says, as well as from ``looking at who is linking
up with list brokers; we get tips from interest groups, usenet news
group postings - and complaints.'' (Carol T. Powers/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SAN FRANCISCO -- Sept. 20, 1998 -- ONLINE-MUSIC-2, 9-20
-- Braden Merrick, in black shirt, a vice president of Red Button,
and Jake Sloane, the start-up's founder, in San Francisco. The
company, created last spring as a platform for unknown bands to
distribute their music, has recently shifted into recording and
artist management. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
