<HEADLINE>
JOHN PAUL JR. WINS LONE STAR 500K
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For the majority of its up-and-coming
drivers, the Pep Boys Indy Racing League is about starting a
career.
</P>
<P>
   For veteran John Paul Jr., the IRL is about a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   Paul's once-promising future in Indy-cars and prototype sports
cars was shelved in the late 1980s after he pleaded guilty to a
charge of racketeering in a drug case that also involved his
father, endurance racing champion John Paul Sr.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Jr., who served a 28-month term in a federal prison, was
labeled as tainted goods upon his return to racing in 1989. He was
relegated to a succession of either one-time or low-budget rides.
But Paul joined Jonathan Byrd's well-stocked IRL team for the True
Value 500K at Texas Motor Speedway in June, and began repaying his
car owner's faith yesterday with a victory in the inaugural Lone
Star 500-kilometer race.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those things (personal problems) are in the past,'' Paul
said after scoring his first IRL victory and first in an Indy-car
since the Championship Auto Racing Teams' Michigan 500 in 1983.
``It's been a long 15 years. I'm looking forward to today and to
the future. With Jonathan's support we're looking for many more
wins down the line. I appreciate everyone waiting for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He was speaking then to the media, but earlier in Victory Lane
Paul thanked God, his wife and his children for standing by him.
</P>
<P>
   Paul's breakthrough victory before an estimated 81,000 fans came
at the expense of IRL rookie Robby Unser, who finished second by
1.577 seconds. Track temperatures were reported between 130-137
degrees led to a rash of blistered Goodyear tires, spins/crashes
and debris that led to more cut tires.
</P>
<P>
   Only the cars of Paul, Unser, Jeff Ward and Roberto Guerrero
were on the lead lap at the conclusion of the 208-lap event. And
only half of the 28-car field was running at the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very relieved to win my first IRL race,'' said Paul, a
38-year-old resident of West Palm Beach, Fla., who became the
league's sixth different winner of 1998. ``I'm very proud to be
associated with the series. To come on board after Indy this year,
we've been competitive from the start. They all know we've got a
car capable of winning a race, and today we showed it. It's a very
special moment for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul, who led four times for 31 laps, took the point for the
final time on lap 192 when former motorcycle champion Ward and 1996
Indy 500 champion Buddy Lazier pitted for fuel and tires. Paul, who
had made his last pit stop on lap 164, was told by Byrd he had
enough fuel to go the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Title contender Davey Hamilton brought out the race's eighth and
final caution on lap 197, when a right rear tire on his car failed
down the front straight of the 1.5-mile trioval and sent him
spinning through the infield grass. That bunched up the field for a
restart, although only Paul and Unser were running on the lead lap.
</P>
<P>
   When the race went green on lap 203, Ward and then Guerrero _
who had brought the crowd to its feet by racing side-by-side for
the point on laps 183 and 184 _ passed Paul to get back on the lead
lap. Those moves basically were uncontested by Paul, who managed to
keep Unser in the one mirror remaining on his car to the finish
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were flat-out every lap, other than restarts,'' said Paul,
whose No. 10 VisionAire-Bryant Heating &AMP; Cooling G Force/Aurora was
shod with Firestone Firehawk tires. ``The last 20 laps, I was
flat-out every lap, then that last yellow occurred. I was a little
nervous and let two guys get by me, but I didn't want to make a
mistake at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul, who won the International Motor Sports Association GT
championship in 1982, pleaded guilty in August 1985 to a charge of
racketeering, involving the unloading of a boat containing
marijuana and helping in preparing to use the boat to haul
marijuana from Colombia to Louisiana. Paul spent 28 months in a
federal prison from 1986-88.
</P>
<P>
   His father still is serving a 25-year term for drug trafficking
and attempted murder of a witness in a federal drug case.
</P>
<P>
   With that background for his driver, Byrd said this victory _
his second in the 3-year-old IRL _ was ``more special.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This one we had to overcome so much adversity,'' Byrd said.
``John Paul is a pleasure to work with. The crew did a wonderful
job. The Firestone tires were fantastic _ we never blistered a
thing. We were having to slow him down a bit because we had such a
good pit strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we didn't have to make another pit stop and knew the
guys in front of us had to. To be able to tell the driver, `You've
got everybody covered and it's going to come to you' ... it was a
pleasure to watch a professional out there at work.''
</P>
<P>
   The race saw 10 drivers lead, with reigning series champion Tony
Stewart pacing a race-high 51 laps before exiting with an engine
problem in his No. 1 Glidden-Menards Dallara/Aurora. He finished
20th in the 28-car field.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Brack, who had won the three previous races but finished
fifth yesterday, began the day with a 23-point lead in the driver's
championship over Hamilton and Stewart. Brack exited Texas with a
31-point lead over Hamilton and a 43-point pad over Stewart heading
into the season ender at Las Vegas Motor Speedway on Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Brack can lock up his first championship and the Pep Boys
Million by finishing seventh or better, even if Hamilton wins the
pole and race and leads the most laps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
