<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FOOD-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SAFER DIETS FOR COWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Sept. 21:
</P>
<P>
   Microbiologists at Cornell University have found that what
cattle eat can affect the safety of hamburgers, opening a whole new
path to controlling food-borne illnesses. Strains of E. coli
bacteria have caused illness and death in humans who have eaten
undercooked ground beef, lettuce and unpasteurized fruit juice.
Thus far most efforts to control the spread of E. coli have focused
on improving safety in slaughtering and food-handling practices.
But the new research shows that the E. coli problem can also be
managed by changing the diet of cattle.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that cattle fed mostly grain are more likely to
harbor harmful E. coli bacteria than cattle fed hay or grass.
Grain-fed cattle develop more acid in their colons, which promotes
acid-resistant bacteria in their digestive tracts. Such bacteria
are more likely to survive in the human stomach, causing illness.
Switching the cattle to hay or grass for even five days can reduce
acid and virtually eliminate acid-resistant E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   The data should prompt the cattle industry to adjust its feed
practices. There is little chance that U.S. cattle will be fed hay
alone because grain feeding is efficient and economical. But widely
publicized incidents in recent years of E. coli contamination in
beef have been highly costly for the industry. Making the change to
hay for the few days prior to slaughter would likely involve only
minimal expense. It is unclear whether the Department of
Agriculture can require such a change. But meat-packing plants,
armed with the new research, may find it in their financial
interest to insist that producers certify that their animals meet
these dietary standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980920.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-20 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5253 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-LEITER-ART-3     09-20 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-LEITER-ART-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'LL BEND YOUR EAR, HE'LL BEND YOUR BATS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos of John Olerud and Al Leiter are being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036. 
(nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Leiter slipped into the chauffeured car on the
Upper East Side Sunday with a cup of coffee and a bagel and
immediately bombarded John Olerud, his Met teammate and fellow
passenger, with his game plan for pitching against the awful
Marlins. Leiter, who is as effusive as a radio talk-show host,
discussed strategy while Olerud, who is as taciturn as a mannequin,
simply listened.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-minute ride from Manhattan to Shea Stadium involved a lot
of chewing by Leiter, both on the bagel and on Olerud's ear. Leiter
explained his feelings about attacking Mark Kotsay and Todd
Dunwoody. Who? There is no doubt that Leiter was the only person in
New York who was dissecting Dunwoody's swing at 10:30 in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   But that is typical of Leiter, who lets the baseball fan inside
him speak almost as much as the pitcher does. Leiter reminded
Olerud how critical Sunday's game was, then he reminded himself a
few dozen times and then he reminded the Marlins how important it
was to him and to the Mets by dominating Florida in a 5-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted this game badly,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine
said. ``He pitched like he wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter wanted it, the Mets got it. After Turk Wendell, the human
pitching machine, relieved Leiter and notched three outs in a noisy
ninth, the remaining fans from the crowd of 52,767 howled because
the Mets had nudged ahead of the Chicago Cubs for the National
League wild-card lead by one-half game. When the Cubs later
stumbled to the Cincinnati Reds, 7-3, the Mets danced in front by
one full game with five games remaining. Leiter orchestrated
Sunday's snazzy waltz.
</P>
<P>
   The public-address system blared ``Wild Boys'' by Duran Duran as
Wendell led the Mets through some chest-bumps and high-fives. The
focus might have shifted temporarily to the hyperactive Wendell,
but it really belonged on Leiter. He overcame an interesting hurdle
in the first inning and coasted through eight solid innings with
nine strikeouts, while permitting five hits and one walk. No wonder
Leiter sounded more like a fan than a pitcher after his biggest
triumph of a still-percolating season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fun day,'' Leiter said. ``It was one of those days
where everything was working.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Almost everything. Jim Leyland, who managed Leiter when the
Marlins won the World Series last season, played Strat-O-Matic and
tossed the first curveball of the afternoon by loading his lineup
with five left-handed batters, including four straight, against the
left-handed Leiter. Leiter kept pointing at the lineup card as he
discussed the hitters with catcher Mike Piazza, looking like a
tourist who had lost at three-card monte. Leyland threw the curve
because right-handed hitters entered the day batting .203 in 516
at-bats against Leiter and left-handed-hitters were at .298 over
104 at-bats against him. Besides, the Class AAA Marlins had nothing
to lose by experimenting.
</P>
<P>
   After Luis Castillo grounded out to open the game, the
procession of lefties started with Dunwoody and Kotsay each
singling. Sensing that Leiter was frazzled, Valentine made a rare
first-inning jaunt to the mound. Leiter had thrown only 10 pitches,
but Valentine had a stern message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to let Al know that he was a great pitcher,''
Valentine said. ``It didn't matter who was in there or if they were
standing on their head. Just stay aggressive. I didn't want to
regret not saying anything.''
</P>
<P>
   When Leiter spotted Valentine, he was surprised. But he looked
the manager in the eye, listened intently and nodded when Valentine
retreated. Although Valentine has been criticized for overmanaging,
counseling Leiter was the shrewdest decision he made all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to give me the old rah-rah thing, get my behind
in gear,'' Leiter said. ``I appreciated it. It worked. Obviously,
whatever he said worked. I did step it up a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter pumped two strikes on his next three pitches to the
cleanup hitter, Cliff Floyd. He was not deterred when Floyd
followed by fouling off three straight pitches and got him to chase
a nasty slider for the strikeout. Ryan Jackson was an easier victim
as Leiter dispatched him on four pitches, whiffing him with a sweet
curveball.
</P>
<P>
   But Leiter's mastery over Leyland's lefties extended beyond the
first inning and beyond Valentine's timely lecture. Leiter wound up
holding left-handed hitters without a hit in the 15 at-bats after
Valentine visited him, which is why he won his career-best 17th
game and why the giddy Mets were hollering in their clubhouse as
the Reds went ahead of the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   A determined Leiter helped position the Mets one precious game
ahead for the wild-card playoff spot, which is surely what he
wanted to discuss on the ride home last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing that I did my job to help keep this team in the race
and possibly go into the postseason is the way everyone has to look
at it,'' Leiter said. ``Today, I did my job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
