<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENNESSEE-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE USES DEFENSE TO SHAKE THINGS UP IN THE POLLS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The scoreboard displayed: Tennessee 20,
Florida 17. And thousands in the school-record crowd of 107,653
were rolling onto the field at Neyland Stadium to pound on the goal
posts. In the middle of them, Al Wilson stood his ground as he had
for four quarters and a thrilling overtime finish against the
Gators.
</P>
<P>
   Three and one-half hours earlier on Florida's opening drive,
Wilson, the Tennessee middle linebacker, set a punishing tone when
he separated the ball from Florida running back Terry Jackson at
the goal line. It was the first of three fumbles that Wilson caused
_ a school record _ and that his teammates recovered.
</P>
<P>
   It began an eight-tackle, one-sack performance that did not come
close to measuring the trouble he gave Florida quarterbacks Jess
Palmer and Doug Johnson, who were often flattened by Wilson after
hurrying their throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense sells tickets,'' said Wilson, an ebullient senior.
``The defense wins championships.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no titles to hand out this early in the season, but
smothering defenses in games across the country on Saturday
revealed the contenders for the national title. Ohio State kept The
Associated Press' No. 1 ranking by holding determined Missouri to
66 second-half yards and turning a 14-13 first-half deficit into a
35-14 victory.
</P>
<P>
   No. 5 Kansas State limited Heisman Trophy candidate Ricky
Williams to 43 yards rushing, forced four turnovers and crushed
Texas, 48-7. Louisiana State returned one interception for a
touchdown and scored off two others to beat Auburn, 31-19, and move
up to No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Tennessee defense that most affected the title
picture: The Volunteers moved up two slots to No. 4 and the Gators
dropped six to No 8.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee turned to big plays to end a five-game losing streak
to Florida. The Volunteers picked up four fumbles, snagged an
interception, had five sacks and limited Florida to three points on
two possessions inside their 5-yard line. They also kept Jackson,
who had been averaging 9 yards a carry, to 26 yards on 19 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't run worth a dog,'' said Florida Coach Steve
Spurrier, whose team fell to 2-1. ``Our running game was
nonexistent. We messed up a whole bunch of protection assignments.
We made enough mistakes to lose the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Gators had a chance to win in overtime. Florida won
the coin toss and decided to defend first, which Spurrier conceded
was a message to Tennessee that his highly vaunted defense could
hold the Volunteers to a field-goal attempt. They did most of the
night, limiting Tennessee to only three points off the five
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Lewis, a Tennessee sophomore, carried 21 times for 82
yards, but the Florida defense frustrated quarterback Tee Martin.
He was 7-for-20 passing for 64 yards and an interception, though he
found Peerless Price for a 29-yard touchdown toss.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran a little bit on us,'' Spurrier said. ``And the
touchdown pass was a jump-ball situation. But I thought our defense
played very hard. A touchdown I thought would win it.''
</P>
<P>
   It looked like the overtime gamble would pay off when Tennessee
began its possession on the Florida 25 and Martin promptly threw
two incomplete passes. On third-and-10, he kept the ball but was
thrown for a loss, which was compounded by a holding penalty.
Suddenly, Tennessee was on Florida's 37-yard line facing
third-and-23.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin, who is a combined 16-for-46 in his two starts,
turned what looked like a sack into a 14-yard scramble that put the
game on kicker Jeff Hall's foot for the second straight week. Hall
drilled a 41-yarder through the center of the posts.
</P>
<P>
   It took Florida only two plays to get a first down on
Tennessee's 15. On first down, Travis Taylor had a half step on
Steve Johnson on the left side of the end zone, but the pass was
high and he got only one hand on it. The next play, Wilson broke
through the line and batted down Palmer's pass. Then on third down,
Florida's Johnson threw wide to Taylor in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   So it was up to Collins Cooper to boot a 32-yarder to keep
overtime alive. The Florida kicker had not attempted a field goal
this year, and it showed. The ball began to drift left as soon as
he hit it. Asked what he told Cooper, Spurrier said he told him to
keep his head up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `It wasn't all your fault. You had one of the many
bad plays we had in the game,''' Spurrier said.
</P>
<P>
   And Wilson and the Volunteers' defense forced most of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
