<HEADLINE>
FOR THIRD TIME, FANS GET GOOD SHOW FROM IRL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ They show up. They sign autographs. They
drive 220 mph.
</P>
<P>
   They don't complain.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well, occasionally A.J. Foyt slaps the winner upside the
head, but that's racing.
</P>
<P>
   Three times now the Indy Racing League has gone to the starting
line at Texas Motor Speedway, and three times the IRL gang has put
on an engaging, entertaining show.
</P>
<P>
   High speeds. Large, though not Woodstock-sized, crowds. And
wimp-free racing.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul Jr.'s victory yesterday in the inaugural Lone Star
500K also stands as vivid testimony of IRL's claim as a haven of
opportunity. Paul's trip to the finish line took 13 years and one
lamentable detour through a federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   The runner-up, Robby Unser, is another IRL opportunist. As the
sixth _ or 60th, I've lost count _ member of the racing Unser
family, 30-year-old Robby finished 1.577 seconds behind the winner
and strengthened his case for being named the circuit's rookie of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Unser's 36-year-old cousin is two-time Indy 500 winner Al Unser
Jr., who would have been here except some wise Solomon split the
Indy-car baby two years ago. The Andrettis, Rahals and European
millionaires went one way; the non-marquee cousins went the other.
</P>
<P>
   Al Jr. rides on the Championship Auto Racing Teams (CART)
circuit, but the speedway at Indy is IRL territory now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's got to be eating him up,'' Robby said. ``Not only
can't he run at Indy, but he can't run against his cousin.''
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry is a friendly one. ``But we're Unsers,'' Robby said.
``We're racers. All we do is compete.''
</P>
<P>
   When Indy Motor Speedway president Tony George founded the IRL,
young, under-financed drivers like Robby were probably what he had
in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for talent here,'' said the younger Unser
cousin. ``The other circuit is full of Europeans with money. There
just wasn't room for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Eddie Cheever Jr.'s Team Cheever, Robby found both a
ride and a league of his own.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not a half-bad league, now that it has broken its ties
to the U.S. Auto Club. The first Indy-car race at TMS was
submarined by timing mishaps, protests and Foyt's memorable
head-slap of Arie Luyendyk in the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like miles ago. At TMS yesterday, there was no
Armageddon traffic snarl. There were no hourlong waits for the
restrooms. The crowd was announced as 81,000 _ modest numbers by
NASCAR Winston Cup standards, but not bad for a warm September
Sunday in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had three great races with the IRL,'' Speedway general
manager Eddie Gossage said. ``On Saturday, they stood out here in
the heat and signed literally thousands of autographs. These guys
do such a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage admits that TMS went through its growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like an expansion team,'' he said. ``And now we're
getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Speedway and the IRL, therefore, have always seemed to be
cousins, of sorts, themselves. New guys on the block, just trying
to wind through the traffic and find a niche.
</P>
<P>
   And the best part _ the loudest sounds yesterday came from the
car engines, not from drivers bleating about an alleged unfair race
track.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for the third time in three races here, the IRL event
was spiced by a brief side-by-side joust at 220 mph. Jeff Ward and
Roberto Guerrero's fates were eventually dashed by a final pit
stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``But guys were out there running two wide, just an inch off the
guy,'' Unser noted. ``You just don't see that everywhere. We're
going to do well, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   As he worked his way back to his trailer late yesterday
afternoon, Unser kept stopping to sign autographs and pose for
pictures. Admittedly, he has a tough act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Besides cousin Al Jr.'s two Indy wins, uncle Al Sr. won the Indy
500 four times. Robby's dad, Bobby, was a three-time Indy winner.
</P>
<P>
   But Unsers, Robby said, support Unsers no matter which path the
race track may take them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a great series going,'' he said. ``This is where I
want my name to be _ my first name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be here. I have no doubt that Tony George's dream
is going to become a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to argue here. The two IRL races at the Speedway this
year have gone off with some flying tire rubber, maybe, not
otherwise nary a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   Wimp-free racing, if I may borrow an expression. I think we
could get used to it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
