<HEADLINE>
FREDERICK KORTH, 89, FORMER SECRETARY OF NAVY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (lb) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frederick Korth, a Texas banker who served for two years as
secretary of the Navy in the Kennedy administration, died on Sept.
14 at his home in El Paso, Texas. He was 89, and had retired from
his practice at a Washington law firm in December.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said his son, Fritz-Alan, of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Korth, who was named secretary of the Navy in 1961, succeeded
John Connally, who resigned to run for governor of Texas. But Korth
resigned after two stormy years as the Navy's civilian chief.
</P>
<P>
   He was criticized for having a conflict of interest in awarding
a multibillion-dollar aircraft contract to General Dynamics Corp.
of Fort Worth, Texas, and of using Navy stationery for matters
pertaining to a Fort Worth bank with which he was associated. A
congressional committee investigating the accusations concluded
that they were groundless.
</P>
<P>
   Korth also clashed with Defense Secretary Robert McNamara over a
proposal to build the nation's first nuclear-powered aircraft
carrier and over a shift of responsibility for the Middle East and
India from the Navy to the Army.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Texas banker and rancher, Korth grew up on the
family ranch in Karnes County, in central Texas. He graduated from
the University of Texas and received a law degree from George
Washington University, where he met his future wife, Vera Sansom
Connell, a fellow Texan who was attending a Washington finishing
school.
</P>
<P>
   After returning to Fort Worth to practice law, he joined the Air
Transport Command of the Army Air Forces in World War II. After the
war, he became president of Continental National Bank, a post he
left for two years to serve as an assistant secretary of the Army
in the Truman administration.
</P>
<P>
   Korth was a member of the Southwestern Texas Cattle Raisers
Association and served on the board of Meridian International in
Washington, a private foundation whose focus is international
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his son, Korth, whose first marriage ended in divorce,
is survived by his wife, Charlotte, of El Paso; a daughter, Nina
Maria Cole of Fort Worth; six grandchildren, and four
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
