<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. KERRY URGES CLINTON TO TESTIFY BEFORE JUDICIARY PANEL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton sought solace in church Sunday in
the final hours before a fresh torrent of lurid evidence, including
a potentially explosive videotape, is made public today by a House
panel investigating his sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton listened to a minister draw on a biblical passage
that begins, ``Judge not, lest ye be judged,'' much of the nation
prepared to view the unedited, four-hour videotape of his grand
jury testimony and receive many other details of his affair with
Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In the turbulent buildup to the latest disclosures, Senator John
F. Kerry, Democrat of Massachusetts, called on Clinton to volunteer
immediately to testify before the House Judiciary Committee to
spare the country a protracted impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the panel, which is reviewing 11 possibly
impeachable allegations against Clinton, endorsed the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the president would be well served to explain
exactly what he did, exactly what he was thinking, do it to the
Judiciary Committee, and let's vote and let's move on one way or
the other,'' said Kerry, a Clinton ally who has sharply criticized
his conduct in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufbite &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Unsupervised children are apt to view the testimony. B3.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation is being ill served by this political water torture
that is taking place in a highly calculated, highly partisan way,''
Kerry said on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Los Angeles Times, White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart said that Kerry's proposal is ``certainly worth
considering'' and that the administration does ``not rule out'' the
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials were occupied Sunday with putting a
positive spin on the videotape, which will be televised nationally,
providing the first images of an American president being
questioned under oath as a target of a criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Alternately enraged, evasive, embarrassed, and apologetic,
Clinton repeatedly loses the polish and poise of his public
persona, according to lawmakers who have seen the videotape. At
times, they said, it effectively presents a portrait of a cornered
suspect squirming amid a devastating interrogation.
</P>
<P>
   The session began with Clinton acknowledging engaging in
``inappropriate intimate contact'' and ``inappropriate sexual
banter'' in telephone conversations with Lewinsky, according to a
text of his opening statement released by his lawyers Sunday. The
text was published Sunday in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Under withering questioning by prosecutors for the independent
counsel, Kenneth W. Starr, Clinton painstakingly refused time and
gain to discuss details of the illicit affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of privacy considerations affecting my family, myself,
and others, and in an effort to preserve the dignity of the office
I hold, this is all I will say about the specifics of these
particular matters,'' he said in his opening statement.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, in a 445-page report to Congress, said he was compelled
to lay out the sexually explicit narrative of Clinton's affair with
Lewinsky because it was crucial to his claim that Clinton committed
perjury during a deposition in the Paula Corbin Jones sexual
harassment lawsuit in January. Clinton denied in the deposition
that he had had sex with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stood by the denial before the grand jury, saying he and
Lewinsky had never had sexual intercourse, which he understood to
be the definition of sex that was issued by the judge in the Jones
case.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's tortured effort to sustain the denial may cause
him particular embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't pull it off well,'' said Representative Lindsey O.
Graham, a South Carolina Republican who serves on the Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   At times, Clinton is ``dancing on the head of a pin to try to
describe what sexual relations are, and it gets to be humorous,''
Graham said. ``But it's not going to be a knockout blow.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who have seen the videotape agree about its potential
impact, including Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell
Democrat, who also serves on the judiciary panel. ``I don't think
it will have a great positive or negative effect,'' Meehan said on
ABC's ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Some segments of Clinton's testimony are expected to strike a
chord with much of the public, particularly those in which he
excoriates Starr for waging a four-year investigation of him and
building a criminal case out of private sexual contact between
consenting adults.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials also accused House Republicans of
unnecessarily releasing the videotape and reams of other explicit
details about Clinton's affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ripped away the veneer of bipartisanship and fairness,''
said Rahm Emanuel, a White House adviser. ``At the core is a
political goal to embarrass this president.''
</P>
<P>
   John Podesta, a White House deputy chief of staff, said Starr's
allegations are ``simply an attempt to drag all this sexual
material into the record for the purpose of humiliating the
president, and I think with the hopes of forcing him from office.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most damaging material to be released today will be
contained in 2,800 pages of documents, including the transcript of
Lewinsky's grand jury testimony and 20 FBI interviews with her. The
material includes many more details of sexual encounters and
sexually explicit phone conversations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
