A5277 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAN-OF-HONOR-LADN     09-20 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAN-OF-HONOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERO WHO FOUND SUSPECT DECLINES OFFERS TO TELL STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fascinated by Cesar Quintero's incredible story,
tabloid magazines, a TV show and movie producers alike have offered
him thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   They've told him that he's a hero because he was a murder
suspect for a slaying he didn't commit _ and then exonerated
himself by finding the man whom police say is the real killer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Quintero has refused the offers, even though the money would
nicely supplement the salary from his job changing oil at an auto
shop. The 20-year-old Reseda man said he simply can't fathom
benefiting financially from the sorrow of the victim's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want them to think I'm taking advantage of what
happened to their son,'' Quintero said.
</P>
<P>
   For this, the mother of the victim said she is grateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly appreciate that,'' said Lorraine Redden, grieving for
her son, Steve, 20, who was stabbed to death on Mother's Day.
``It's a tough thing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Redden said she hasn't met Quintero, but ``now I really have to
see him to thank him.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that she, too, has been offered movie deals through
friends in the entertainment industry, but like Quintero, she
refused. ``Hey, excuse me,'' she said she told them, ``I lost a
20-year-old son. Sorry, I'm not interested.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not worth it. I'll stay poor, because nothing is going to
bring my son back,'' Redden said.
</P>
<P>
   Quintero realizes why his story is so captivating. But he also
can't forget the trauma he and his family endured while police
investigated them until he found the man police say committed the
slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to deal with it anymore. It really scares me even
thinking about it _ spending the rest of my life in jail,'' he said
from his home in suburban Reseda recently.
</P>
<P>
   The National Enquirer has offered him $3,000 if the tabloid
could interview him and use his picture, Quintero said. The
television news magazine show ``Extra'' also offered him a deal, as
well as various talk shows, Quintero said.
</P>
<P>
   But he turned them all down.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police Detective Ron Vega, the main investigator on
the case, said movie and TV producers have contacted him for rights
to the story. But Vega said it's Quintero's prerogative to turn
down offers, and he will honor it as well and not take the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to deal with it. It's his way of dealing with it,''
Vega said. ``You want both, the right and left arm. If he's not
going to go for it, then I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   Vega said the fact that Quintero exonerated himself by finding
the man who ended up charged with murder is no less than ``divine
intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Vega and detectives believed Quintero was
responsible for the slaying. They said he fit eyewitness
descriptions of the man who killed Redden in North Hollywood
northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Quintero became the focus of a grueling investigation that
included his cousin, Rogelio Galindo. Detectives searched
Quintero's home and put him at the top of their suspect list in
mid-June but couldn't muster enough evidence to arrest him, let
alone seek charges.
</P>
<P>
   One day in June, Quintero was working at an oil-change shop when
in drove a red Fiero _ just like the one identified at the scene of
the stabbing and nearly identical to Quintero's. And then he saw
the driver, a man Quintero said resembled him so much that he could
have been his brother.
</P>
<P>
   It was Edgar Adolfo Barrientos, 20. Quintero alerted the police,
and now Barrientos is charged with murder. Barrientos has pleaded
not guilty to the slaying and is due to appear in Superior Court on
Friday for a pretrial hearing.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much money producers and editors offer Quintero,
he cannot help thinking of the families affected by the deadly
ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand their sorrow,'' Quintero said. ``I don't
really care for that money. I don't think it's worth it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said he'll take the $25,000 police reward that will
likely be offered to him for turning in the real suspect. It is
more than he earns in a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider it compensation for what I went through,'' said
Quintero, adding that he plans to use the reward as tuition for an
automotive engineering degree.
</P>
<P>
   Vega has sent in an application recommending Quintero for the
reward, which must be formally approved by the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   And Quintero did grant an interview to ``LAPD Life on the
Beat,'' a TV program that documents the workdays of officers on
patrol. But he will not be paid for the interview, which is
scheduled to air within the next few weeks, he said. Quintero said
he agreed to the interview as a public service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
