<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 UNDATED: problem women.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They include his mother (Linda Lavin), his overbearing sister
(Ever Carradine, daughter of Robert Carradine) and his best friend
(Lauren Graham). Steve Landesberg (``Barney Miller'') is also in
the cast, as a burned-out colleague of Conrad's.
</P>
<P>
   NBC overshot its natural limit of ``chickcoms'' _ they're
female, they're single, they're in the city, and they have lousy
love lives _ and ``Conrad Bloom'' tries to resuscitate the formula
with a male lead.
</P>
<P>
   The guess here is that Feuerstein doesn't have the comedic heft
to carry a show, despite capable help from Lavin and a few other
supporting players. It's just too forgettable.
</P>
<P>
   WB's ``Hyperion Bay'' seems too turgid for the network's
youthful audience.
</P>
<P>
   Mark-Paul Gosselaar stars as a twenty-something computer whiz
who ``drove out of this town in a Civic and turned it into a new
Mercedes.'' This town is a fictional fish-wrap of a place on the
central California coast. Gosselaar is going to save his hometown
by locating a software plant there.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan Neal plays the older brother who once eclipsed Gosselaar.
Raymond J. Barry is their father. Sydney Penny is Gosselaar's sleek
girlfriend, and Cassidy Rae is the townie who's coming on to him
now.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while a dense soaper like this catches on and becomes
a ``Beverly Hills, 90210.'' Usually it just finds its way down the
drain.
</P>
