<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HEALTHPLANS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE INTERNET COULD CHANGE PATIENT CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
The Internet someday could revolutionize the way consumers relate
to their health plans and their doctors.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But _ with one big exception _ you wouldn't ever guess that from
the Web pages produced by health plans today.
</P>
<P>
   All of California's largest health plans now have Web pages
aimed at their members and potential members. But most plans simply
use their Web pages as electronic brochures _ listing benefits they
offer or reprinting information that's already been published in
paper form.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is Kaiser Permanente, which is boldly
experimenting with interactive services like online-advice nurses
and appointment-making and electronic discussion groups for
patients suffering from a common ailment.
</P>
<P>
   ``My general impression is that most health plans are doing
marketing online, and Kaiser is the exception that is doing
something substantial,'' said Tom Ferguson, a University of Texas
professor who edits a newsletter about online health information.
</P>
<P>
   How COULD the Internet someday change the relationship between
health plans and their members?
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a time when your medical records are available in a
private electronic file that you can view over the Internet.
Certain words in the file will link you to other Web resources: If
your doctor types in ``asthma,'' for instance, you might see links
to a half-dozen asthma support groups across the country or to a
bibliography of the latest asthma research.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a time when you routinely exchange e-mail with your
doctor or pharmacist. Or when you can consult with specialists in
New York by e-mail _ and show them your medical chart over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a time when the claims process is entirely visible over
the Web so that you can see whether your health plan has processed
a particular bill. Or when you can file a complaint by e-mail and
get a response in just a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think the action in health on the Web will be in
providing information, but where it really will be is in
interaction and people-to-people connections,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, such innovative electronic services remain a distant
vision.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what almost all health insurers now provide on their Web
sites:
</P>
<P>
   _ Descriptions of the plans they offer but not the prices for
each plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lists of doctors affiliated with their plan. Most health plan
Web sites let you type in your address and get names of nearby
doctors. Some sites give you more information than others _ such as
which hospitals each doctor works with, or whether doctors are
accepting new patients.
</P>
<P>
   _ Basic preventive health information, such as articles on
low-fat cooking, or timetables for when children should get
immunizations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some but not all sites provide the health plan's
formulary _ the list of drugs covered by the plan. A few offer
links to other health-related sites, such as the American Cancer
Society's Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Some health plan Web pages feature information that looks
colorful but has little relevance to anyone's health.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross of California, for instance, has a site that might be
mistaken for a travel agency. It includes listings of where to rent
hot-air balloons in the Napa Valley or how much it costs to rent a
houseboat on Lake Shasta. (Visit the Web site at
www.bluecrossca.com.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What a state! You can surf Malibu one day and ski the Sierra
the next,'' Blue Cross says in the welcome to its site.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of plans provide in-depth health information that can
be extremely useful.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna's site includes a health encyclopedia that it developed
with Johns Hopkins University, where visitors can search for
detailed information on everything from arthritis to vertigo. (Go
to www.aetnaushc.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Kaiser offers a 20,000-page online health
encyclopedia _ much more information than can be found in the
150-page printed health handbook typically given to Kaiser members.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser's health encyclopedia is part of an experimental
interactive Web site that it's gradually rolling out to members in
Northern California, Washington, D.C., and Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   The members-only site is at www.kponline.org, which is different
from Kaiser's general corporate Web site. It is expected to be
available to all Northern California Kaiser members by the end of
this year. (Non-members can tour the site at
www.kaiserpermanente.org /membersonly/overview.htm.)
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser's members-only site offers:
</P>
<P>
   _ Online health assessments that identify your biggest health
risk and provide links to follow-up information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Online access to advice nurses and pharmacists, who will
respond by e-mail within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   _ Online appointment making.
</P>
<P>
   _ Online discussion groups on topics ranging from HIV to
parenting. Some are moderated by doctors and nurses, while others
are led by rank-and-file Kaiser members who have received special
training.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser officials say they envision a ``virtual medical center''
that will someday meet as wide a range of patient needs as today's
brick-and-mortar medical centers do.
</P>
<P>
   Such a goal may be easier to achieve for Kaiser than for other
health plans, which don't have their own doctors, pharmacies and
hospitals all under one corporate roof.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser's current lead in Web services is due partly to this
centralization: Kaiser doesn't have to cajole dozens of different
doctors' groups into linking their appointment books with its
computer.
</P>
<P>
   It's also due to some forethought. Kaiser started looking at how
interactive technology could help its members as early as 1992.
That's given the HMO time to work out issues like how to protect
patient confidentiality, while allowing online interactions.
</P>
<P>
   But other health plans are likely to follow Kaiser down this
path as quickly as they can. Health Net and Blue Cross, for
instance, say they're almost ready to let members check the status
of claims online.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how far down the road you look, the Web doesn't
replace in-person care or telephone access,'' said Tim Kieschnik,
who is overseeing Kaiser's Internet strategy. ``Medicine will
always have a hands-on component. However, a lot of pieces of
medicine can be greatly enhanced by using the Web. We just need to
use it to connect the patient with the physician, rather than to
keep patients and physicians apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-20-98 2345EDT &QL; 
