r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHR     09-20 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO DO ABOUT A BULLY IN THE WORKPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 Q:  I have a small but irritating problem with a co-worker. Every
time he sees me, he insists on calling me by a nickname,
``Stretch.'' (I am a tall woman.) I've asked him repeatedly to stop
it, but like a schoolyard bully, he apparently takes great pleasure
from the fact that it annoys me. I don't want to bring something
this trivial to the attention of management, though I sometimes
have wondered whether it verges on sexual harassment, given its
unwelcome nature. How should I handle this?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; You're smart not to take this issue to management. The last
thing a supervisor wants is to be dragged into the role of
playground monitor in personal spats. And this doesn't fit the
definition of sexual harassment because there's nothing sexual or
gender-based about it.
</P>
<P>
   I posed your question to Ronna Lichtenberg, author of the book
``Work Would Be Great If It Weren't for the People: Ronna and Her
Evil Twin's Guide to Making Office Politics Work for You.''
</P>
<P>
   Lichtenberg happens to be short, and she has had to deal with
co-workers who insisted on calling her ``Little Missy.'' She tried
everything from being ``super-aggressive'' to calling them
nicknames in turn, and nothing ever stopped them.
</P>
<P>
   Her advice? Ignore him and don't let the nickname bug you. In
fact, think of it as a compliment. He may come from a family where
people show affection for each other by nice and not-so-nice
nicknames. Or he may be jealous of your abilities and is looking
for a way to bring you down a notch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should just let go of this,'' Lichtenberg advises. ``As
soon as you get to the point where you enjoy it and think it's
funny, he'll stop doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's probably a good idea to sit down and reflect a bit about
why his name-calling gets under your skin so much.
</P>
<P>
   Plan a response to help you keep your cool: Remind yourself
before work each morning that if he passes you in the hallway and
says, ``Hey, Stretch,'' you'll just smile, nod and keep walking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I'm a midlevel manager. When I'm applying for a job, how do
I know if the number of stock options I'm being offered is
competitive?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; This is a simple question with no simple answer.
</P>
<P>
   Stock options are an increasingly common employment perk _ the
right to buy a certain number of shares of the company's stock at a
certain price.
</P>
<P>
   There are some general rules about how options are distributed.
Generally, high-ranking executives in a company get more options
than people at middle and low levels.
</P>
<P>
   And startup firms are likely to offer more options than big
established firms _ because startups use options as a way to make
up for salaries that are lower and jobs that are less secure than
at bigger companies.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond such general guidelines, things get cloudy. Unlike
salaries, there are no public surveys of how many options are
granted in different industries or professions.
</P>
<P>
   Some compensation experts have developed their own formulas to
determine the size and value of options packages. Matt Ward, CEO of
WestWard Pay Strategies in San Francisco, tells his corporate
clients that the median options package for a high-tech executive
earning $112,500 a year amounts to 36.1 percent of his or her base
salary, or $40,569. The median options package for someone in high
tech earning $62,500 a year is 23 percent of base salary, or
$14,390.
</P>
<P>
   But other compensation experts say it's impossible to come up
with a one-size-fits-all formula. And even if you do settle on a
figure like 23 percent of base salary, there's a lot of guesswork
involved in determining the potential dollar-value of the options.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you're offered the option to buy stock at $5 a share in
a company that hasn't gone public yet. It's anybody's guess whether
the company will go public at $6 or $13, or whether it will flop
before it ever gets on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Given the uncertainty, there are still a few useful questions
you can ask. Try to find out if there's a standard options package
for current employees at your level _ and whether what you're being
offered is comparable.
</P>
<P>
   Also ask how many shares of stock the company has issued. That
partly will determine the value of the options you're being
offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have one client company with just 1,200 shares of stock
outstanding, so every single option is worth a lot,'' said Bill
Metzger, a compensation analyst with Assets Unlimited in Campbell.
``I have another client company with 250 million share outstanding.
Obviously, one option there is not worth as much.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I've worked as a bank teller for nine years, which often
involves lifting heavy boxes of coins. Last March, I started
feeling severe back pain and went out on short-term disability
leave. My doctor initially wrote that the problem came about from
my doing housework, rather than from my job. But last month, I had
further tests that found a lot of damage to my spine and a
herniated disk. The doctor now says the injury is the bank's fault
and that I should apply for workers' compensation. Can I do this
even though he initially diagnosed it as unrelated to work?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Yes, you still can receive workers' comp even if your
doctor initially misdiagnosed the cause of your injury _ as long as
your injury truly is work-related.
</P>
<P>
   You can apply for workers' comp benefits anytime within a year
of when you found out that your injury was work related, according
to Julius Young, a workers' comp attorney with Boxer &AMP; Gerson in
Oakland. In your case, that would give you until August 1999 to
file your application.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure your doctor writes a report that clearly explains why
he or she changed the diagnosis and explains how these new tests
showed that your injury was related to work.
</P>
<P>
   The workers' comp insurance company may send you to a doctor of
their own choice for a second opinion. If the insurance company
denies your claim, you have the choice of seeking a third medical
opinion to back up your own doctor or hiring a lawyer to fight the
denial.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it may be worth hiring an attorney even before your
claim is denied _ if the insurance company wants to take a legal
statement from you. ``Is this a person who can legally fend for
herself? Or is there a risk that the insurer's lawyer might put
words in her mouth?'' said Young. ``If that's the case, she should
get her own lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   To find a good lawyer, talk to friends who have filed successful
workers' comp claims. Look in the Yellow Pages for a lawyer who is
a certified workers' comp specialist. Or call the California
Applicant Attorneys Association at (916) 444-5155.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Correction: Last week, we gave an incorrect Web address for
JobSmart, a terrific Internet site that includes more than 200
salary surveys for different professions and industries. The
correct address is www.jobsmart.org.
</P>
<P>
   Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways,
San Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco, Calif.
94103. Or send e-mail to workways &LR; sfgate.com. Or call (415)
764-2815. We can't respond to each query, but we will answer as
many in print as we can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
