<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NIIZUMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORU NIIZUMA, 67, SCULPTOR AND EDUCATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Japan, N.Y.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Minoru Niizuma, a sculptor and educator who taught at
the Brooklyn Museum of Art and Columbia University, died on Sept. 5
at the University Hospital and Medical Center of Stony Brook on
Long Island. He was 67 and lived in East Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   He died of a stroke, a family member said.
</P>
<P>
   Niizuma was born in Tokyo in 1930 and graduated from the
National Tokyo University of Fine Arts in 1955. He moved to New
York in 1959 and had his first solo show in New York at the Howard
Wise Gallery in 1966. He was subsequently represented by the Gimpel
&AMP; Weitzenhoffer Gallery in New York and Zurich, Switzerland. He had
retrospectives at the Seibu Museum of Art in Tokyo in 1976 and at
the Gulbenkian Museum in Lisbon, Portugal, in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Niizuma taught at the Brooklyn Museum Art School from 1964 to
1970, and then taught sculpture at Columbia University for 12
years.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Niizuma worked predominantly in stone,
especially marble, and was known for his sensitive use of its
textures and veins. His designs ranged from the geometric to the
organic and sometimes used patterns reminiscent of folk art,
fabrics and ritual vessels.
</P>
<P>
   His work is represented in public collections in the United
States, Europe and Japan, including the Museum of Modern Art, the
Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, the Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture
Garden in Washington, the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art and
the National Museum of Modern Art in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Niizuma is survived by his wife, Yuko; three sons, Ta Andre, of
Tokyo, and Ko Christopher and Arata Peter, of New York, and one
grandchild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
