A5283 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARECOUNSEL-ADVOCACY-     09-20 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARECOUNSEL-ADVOCACY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FIRM CAN HELP RESOLVE PROBLEMS WITH HEALTH INSURER  
 BY ILANA DEBARE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Frustrated because your health insurer won't pay for the drugs you
need? Fed up because you can't get a referral to a specialist? Or
simply stumped about how to choose a health plan?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Care Counsel is a new San Rafael company that helps people
resolve such health insurance dilemmas _ as part of their employee
benefits package.
</P>
<P>
   Care Counsel contracts with employers who pay a fixed monthly
sum of approximately $1 to $1.50 per worker. Those workers then can
call up Care Counsel any time they need help navigating the complex
world of health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers have long been able to hire lawyers or other advocates
to represent them on an individual basis in health care disputes.
But Care Counsel is the first firm in California to sell
patient-advocacy services as an employee benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say it hasn't arrived a moment too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get more bang for our buck with Care Counsel than with any
other benefit we provide,'' said Lon Records, CEO of Target
Specialty Products, a Los Angeles County distributor of specialty
agricultural chemicals that signed up with Care Counsel last
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first wrote up this idea several years ago, people gave
me blank stares,'' said Care Counsel CEO Lawrence Gelb. ``Now, I
tell people what we do and everyone says, `That's a great idea.' ''
Care Counsel is still small. Founded last year, it now covers about
10,000 workers and family members at three companies, including San
Francisco's Fritz Cos. It hasn't yet turned a profit.
</P>
<P>
   But Gelb hopes to expand the firm's client base to 100,000
workers and family members by the end of 1999 _ well past his
estimated breakeven of 20,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Gelb came up with the idea for Care Counsel after years spent
working for employee-assistance programs, advising workers with
mental health or substance abuse problems on how to get help from
their health plans. In 1992, the program he worked for was bought
by a large health maintenance organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working inside (the HMO) really reinforced my belief in the
need for a third force to help consumers work through these
cumbersome bureaucracies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts predict that demand for Care Counsel's kind of
service will be limited to small or midsize firms. They say most
big firms can field basic health coverage questions through their
own personnel departments and should have enough clout with health
plans to demand good service for their employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most large employers, this should be unnecessary,'' said
Jeffrey Klonoff, manager of the employee-benefits consulting group
at Hewitt Associates in San Francisco. ``If you need a third party
to continuously advocate for your employees, there's a problem with
the employer/health plan relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Target Specialty Products, top executives started
looking for some kind of outside patient-advocacy service long
before they'd ever heard of Care Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Several employees of the 110-person firm had faced major
problems in getting the care they needed from their health plan.
</P>
<P>
   Records, the CEO, had to call up the plan himself to make sure
that one employee who needed heart surgery was able to get it. He
lobbied personally on behalf of another employee who was being
denied access to a cancer specialist at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the time to do that for every employee,'' Records
said. ``Care Counsel fills a big, big gap in the health care chain
that really needed filling. It's given me a great deal of peace of
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the employee calls that Care Counsel gets are far less
dramatic than the life-or-death disputes that Records fielded.
</P>
<P>
   The most common ones, Gelb said, are from people who are
perplexed about choosing a health plan.
</P>
<P>
   One recent call was from Nancy Voorhees, a Bay Area sales
representative for Target Specialty who lives in Half Moon Bay.
Voorhees' 6-year-old daughter, Kirsten, had broken her leg while
skiing last spring. Voorhees took Kirsten by ambulance to a Truckee
hospital where she had surgery and stayed overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Ten weeks later, her daughter's cast was off. But her health
plan still hadn't paid the $6,000 in medical bills. Voorhees was
getting threatening notices from the hospital but couldn't reach a
live person at her insurer. She was missing important phone calls
at work because she was spending 15-minute blocks of time listening
to &UR;  &LR; Muzak on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Care Counsel and faxed them the bills I was
getting,'' Voorhees said. ``They followed up. Every single day,
they'd call and tell me what they'd managed to find out. It was a
total relief, especially because they kept calling me to tell me
when things were resolved. I could just wash my hands of the whole
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
