<HEADER>
A5284 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTHPLAN-RATINGS-SF     09-20 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHPLAN-RATINGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO LOOK FOR WHEN PICKING A HEALTH CARE PROVIDER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Autumn is here, along with the shopping season that fills many
consumers with dread.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not holiday shopping _ health plan shopping.
</P>
<P>
   September marks the start of open enrollment, the month or two
each year when most companies let their employees change health
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about how to make the best choice so your plan leaves
you healthier and happier, rather than raising your blood pressure
with red tape and runarounds?
</P>
<P>
   Relax. Things are getting easier, thanks to tried-and-true
guidelines and a growing number of independent ratings you can use
to compare plans.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the California Cooperative Healthcare Reporting
Initiative _ a coalition of health care purchasers, plans and
providers _ released its annual report card on health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern California health plans that scored the best in
member satisfaction were Kaiser Permanente and Health Plan of the
Redwoods. The ones that scored the best in preventive care were
Kaiser and Lifeguard. (See charts on pages B3 and B4.)
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Business Group on Health released a similar report
card last week, rating HMOs and hospitals. (See the PBGH Web site
at www.healthscope.org or call (888) 244-2124 for a copy.)
</P>
<P>
   NEW SERVICES
</P>
<P>
   Health plans are touting a number of new services this year. If
these interest you, ask if they're offered by any of the plans
you're considering:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Advice lines. &LR;  More plans now offer 24-hour health advice
lines staffed by nurses _ a useful service when it's 3 a.m. and
your child is running a 103-degree fever. Kaiser has gone a step
further, offering access to nurses over the Internet. (See story on
Page B3.)
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Doctor ratings. &LR;  Last year, the Pacific Business Group on
Health drew up a report card on doctors groups around the state,
and it plans to issue an updated version this winter.
</P>
<P>
   This year, two HMOs _ PacifiCare and Health Net _ decided to
issue their own report cards on doctors in their networks, too.
</P>
<P>
   Such ratings can help you choose a doctors' group. The ratings
are also an incentive for doctors to improve, so in the long run
they may raise the overall quality of health care within a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate that the (doctors') groups with the best
practices will accrue the most members,'' said Dr. Sam Ho, vice
president of PacifiCare. ``We want to use the marketplace to
improve the quality of care by our providers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Third-party review. &LR;  Health Net launched a new program this
year that lets members appeal medical decisions to an outside body
and get an answer within 30 days _ the first such program offered
by a California HMO. So if your request to see a specialist outside
the Health Net system is denied, there's a quick way to challenge
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very positive development and an important step in
reinforcing the trust people have in their health plan,'' said
Margaret Stanley, health benefits administrator for the California
Public Employees Retirement System, a major purchaser of health
insurance for state workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Speedy referrals. &LR;  HMOs used to require members to get a
referral from their primary care doctor every time they wanted to
see a specialist. But now some plans will let you go directly to
certain specialists like allergists or gynecologists, without
having to get a referral from your primary care doctor.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Health support programs.  &LR; Most health plans now offer programs
aimed at fostering good health _ everything from parenting classes
to health club discounts.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Alternative medicine.  &LR; Most health plans are continuing to
expand their coverage of alternative medicine, such as acupuncture
and chiropractic treatments. Blue Cross of California, for
instance, started offering a rider to its standard policies this
year that will pay for herbal medicines.
</P>
<P>
   SAGE ADVICE
</P>
<P>
   With all these new bells and whistles, health care experts say
you still shouldn't neglect some old guidelines when choosing a
health plan:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Start by choosing a doctor and/or medical group.  &LR; When HMO
members choose a primary care doctor, they're automatically
choosing that doctor's medical group.
</P>
<P>
   Your selection of a medical group may prove to be even more
important than your choice of a health plan. Medical groups set
many of the rules for treatment and referrals. They determine which
hospital you'll be admitted to and which specialists you'll be able
to see.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Make sure the doctor you've chosen is accepting new &LR; 
 &UR; patients.  &LR; Sometimes doctors listed as part of an HMO's network
have stopped taking new patients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Consider your personal medical needs.  &LR; If someone in your
family has mental health problems, which plan will pay for the most
counseling sessions? If you're having trouble getting pregnant,
which plan will cover fertility treatments? Some plans cover things
like hospice care or orthopedic shoes, while others don't.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ If there's a particular medication you need, ask to see &LR; 
 &UR; each plan's formulary _ the list of drugs that it covers. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Compare out-of-pocket costs.  &LR; These might include monthly
premiums and co-payments for doctor visits, drugs and other
services.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs are the least expensive kind of plan, but usually limit you
to a list of doctors affiliated with the plan. Preferred provider
organizations (PPOs) give you more choice in doctors, but will end
up costing you more in premiums and co-payments.
</P>
<P>
   Want more information on the different kinds of health plans and
how to choose among them?
</P>
<P>
   Consumers Union offers a three-page tip sheet on choosing a
health plan that you can get by calling (415) 431-6747 or going to
www.consunion.org on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Action, a nonprofit group based in San Francisco, also
offers a brochure on choosing an HMO. Send a self-addressed
envelope with 55 cents in postage to Consumer Action/HMO, 717
Market St. 310, San Francisco, Calif. 94103. Or visit its Web site
at www.consumer-action.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
