A5285 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FALL-2TAKES-SFCHRO     09-20 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WILL &AMP; GRACE' HAS THE RIGHT STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The TV season is official right now, today, Monday, Year of Our
Tube 50 or so, but who's counting when we're having this much fun?
</P>
<P>
   Synchronize those watches. Secure snacks, sit down, await
further instructions.
</P>
<P>
   And what a night this is, with six new network series (first
instruction: gasp excitedly) premiering in one heart-pounding
evening.
</P>
<P>
   You even have critical dispensation to watch two of them _
``Will &AMP; Grace'' on NBC and ``L.A. Doctors'' on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace'' is keenly anticipated because it is the first
post-``Ellen'' sign of gay topicality on big-time TV. It's also a
slick, relatively sophisticated comedy. But that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   Will (Eric McCormack) and Grace (Debra Messing) are best friends
in New York who will, sometime after Monday night's premiere,
become roommates.
</P>
<P>
   She's straight, he's gay. The show's co-creator, Max Mutchnick,
is also gay. And, just to get this over with, Grace has a sex life.
Will, having conveniently just broken up with someone or other,
won't have a sex life anytime soon. Mutchnick _ well, we don't know
about Mutchnick.
</P>
<P>
   So there it is. After ``Ellen,'' gay romance may be so slow that
you don't even see it happening. The word from NBC is that ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' is simply a series about a male-female relationship
unencumbered by sex. Sometimes they call this marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's pilot begins with a tease. Will and Grace are in
separate beds, exchanging pillow talk over the phone, until at last
it's clear that they'll always play in separate stadiums. Then the
show thickens into Will advising Grace not to marry her boyfriend,
Grace taking offense, and finally a reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Boy gets girl, boy loses girl, boy gets girl, but with a whole
new slant to the ancient ritual.
</P>
<P>
   The two leads work nicely together _ Messing, a beauty with a
comic flair, has been in search of the right vehicle ever since
Fox's ``Ned and Stacey'' _ James Burrows' direction is as sharp as
usual, the writing is above average and the supporting cast is an
asset.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Mullally is a wealthy flake amusing herself as Karen, the
secretary for Grace's interior-design business. Sean Hayes is
Will's flamer friend, Jack, who insists that most people assume
he's straight. ``Jack,'' says Will, ``blind and deaf people know
you're gay. Dead people know you're gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Jack protests, Grace didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   Grace: ``My (set ital)dog(end ital) knew.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS' ``L.A. Doctors'' bears more than a comfortable resemblance
to ``L.A. Law,'' raising prospects for an entire ``L.A.'' franchise
down the road. ``L.A. Accountants,'' ``L.A. Bankers'' and, perhaps
suitable for late night, ``L.A. Talent Agents.''
</P>
<P>
   But if one TV show is going to resemble another, at least ``L.A.
Law'' is a respectable model.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cattan (Ken Olin), Tim Lonner (Matt Craven) and Evan
Newman (Rick Roberts) are three doctors who open their own clinic
and, Monday night, recruit another physician, Sarah Church (Sheryl
Lee), to join them.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to see the characterizations take shape _
Cattan as the materialistic Arnie Becker type, Lonner as the
earnest practitioner and family man, Newman as an idealistic
divorced doctor who'll probably become the show's top romantic gun
and Church as the distaff altruist.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. Doctors'' is CBS' best shot in two seasons at a fall
keeper, and the show appears to be carefully refined for the
network. Its look and attitude suggest an NBC demographic _ younger
Baby Boomers _ but the storytelling is cautious and linear, to
include the older CBS crowd. Clever, really.
</P>
<P>
   I'd rather still be watching Olin wend his way through the
corrupt netherworld of ``EZ Streets,'' but maybe ``L.A. Doctors''
is the commercial hit he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   If you caught an ABC show called ``That's Life'' last season,
you've essentially seen CBS' ``The King of Queens.'' You wouldn't
brag about watching either show. Still, as blue-collar comedies go,
not horrible. But ``That's Life'' is gone and forgotten, which
might not bode well for ``The King of Queens.''
</P>
<P>
   It's about a delivery guy in Queens, N.Y. (Kevin James), who's
happily married (Leah Remini plays his wife) and doubly delighted
to have a new TV set that's roughly the size of an aircraft
carrier. Then he ends up having to share his little house with his
crude father-in-law (Jerry Stiller) and sister-in-law (Lisa
Rieffel).
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, more noise than humor ensues. There's something kind
of sweet and sad about James, though. He reminds me of Jackie
Gleason's old ``Poor Soul'' character.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' ``The Brian Benben Show'' finds the star of HBO's ``Dream
On'' (and husband of film actress Madeleine Stowe) playing a TV
newsman in his first network sitcom. Fired from his job as a news
anchorman at an L.A. television station, he's hired back as a fluff
feature reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The show has an irksome isn't-this-hilarious smirk when, matter
of fact, it isn't even mildly amusing. It's all about shoveling
gags, rather than developing characters. Bad mistake.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ``Conrad Bloom'' features Mark Feuerstein (he was in
``Fired Up'' and ``Caroline in the City'' last season) as a single
New York ad executive with too many women problems, or problem
women.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
