u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-425&AMP;ADD-N     09-20 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEMON DROP KID MUDDIES JUVENILE PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ The leading 2-year-old colt in the country, Yes
It's True, the winner in six of his seven starts, tripped over a
bump on the long road to the Kentucky Derby Sunday when he was run
down in the homestretch of the Belmont Futurity and beaten by a
neck by his foremost rival, Lemon Drop Kid.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second victory in four starts for Lemon Drop Kid, a
son of Kingmambo and grandson of Seattle Slew. But it was the
second of the day for Jeanne Vance, his owner, and Scotty
Schulhofer, his trainer, who also won the fifth race with a
3-year-old filly named Sequence, with John Velazquez riding both.
</P>
<P>
   Yes It's True seemed to have a lot of high cards in his hand
entering the race. He is trained by D. Wayne Lukas, a master at
developing juvenile horses, and he already had won four stakes. But
he lent credence to some suspicions about his range when he led his
four rivals into the homestretch after some slow fractions, led the
hard-closing Lemon Drop Kid by two lengths as they neared the
finish, then yielded.
</P>
<P>
   At the close, Lemon Drop Kid had half a length on the beaten
favorite, who had nine lengths on Medievil Hero. The winner ran the
mile in 1:37 2/5 on a dull track, paid $14.80 for a $2 bet to win
and earned $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of figured there'd be a slow pace,'' Schulhofer said.
``But at the end, he really dug in.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas agreed that the pace had been slow and said: ``It's a
learning process. But we might have gotten ourselves a little bit
too relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the twin stakes for fillies, the 12-1 long shot Oh What a
Windfall outran the three top choices in the Matron when she
outlasted Arrested Dreams by a nose after a rousing duel down the
homestretch. She also outran the next two favorites, Marley Vale,
who finished third, and Confessional, fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Confessional, a daughter of Holy Bull, ran up front for nearly
three-quarters of a mile, then was collared by Arrested Dreams, who
was nailed in the deep stretch by Oh What a Windfall. The winner,
sired by Seeking the Gold and trained by Shug McGaughey for Ogden
Phipps, ran the mile in 1:39 1/5 under Shane Sellers, paid $27 for
$2 and earned $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   She lost her debut in July by 20 lengths, won her second start,
and then lost the Spinaway by 11 lengths. She is a sister to
Heavenly Prize, one of the former stars of the Phipps barn.
Sellers, riding her for the first time in place of the injured Mike
Smith, said: ``When I saw her in the paddock, she looked like a
typical Phipps horse _ big, long and good-looking. You know,
they're all bred to run.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Backstage at Belmont, where Skip Away was holding court, the
king was declared fit after his resounding victory in the Woodward
on Saturday, and Sonny Hine reported: ``He acts like he wants to go
again. He'll walk for a couple of days, then go back to training.''
</P>
<P>
   Next for Skip Away, who has won nine straight stakes and $9.5
million: the Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont Park on Oct. 10, which
he has won the last two years. The purse is $1 million, the
winner's share $600,000, which would vault Skip Away past Cigar
into the $10 million bracket, where no race horse has trod before.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen, who ran second in the Woodward, was said to be
leaning toward the $200,000 Kelso Handicap at one mile on the turf
at Belmont Park on Oct. 17, then the Breeders' Cup Mile on the
grass. But Dick Mandella, his trainer, said the Jockey Club Gold
Cup was still a possibility. Running Stag, the horse from Europe
who finished third at 43-1, will stay at Belmont and run in the
Gold Cup. Free House, who ran a disappointing fourth, did not have
a future plan in place.
</P>
<P>
   As for Coronado's Quest, the 3-year-old star who led Skip Away
for nearly half a mile before tiring and finishing fifth and last,
he was also a mystery. But McGaughey, his trainer, said the colt
had come out of the race well, and added: ``Just draw a line
through that race and cross it out. He didn't fire at all. We tried
to do things a little too quickly with this horse by running him.
Nobody was going to beat Skip Away, anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
