<HEADLINE>
HEALTH-PLAN'S CLINICS ELIMINATING LANGUAGE BARRIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE BROWN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
SAN FRANCISCO _ Kaiser Permanente had a serious problem with its
Chinese members three years ago: They were leaving the health plan
faster than any other ethnic group.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Kaiser's San Francisco Medical Center
established a specialized clinic to deal with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The move paid off. With the help of the clinic, the HMO actually
saw its market share of Chinese-speaking patients grow by 1,600
members last year, exceeding its original target of 1,200 members.
</P>
<P>
   The move underscores the importance that the HMO attaches to
accommodating the needs of a growing number of patients who speak
English as a second language.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, patient surveys in 1995 by Kaiser Permanente pointed out
that language was considered the biggest barrier for patients
during medical visits.
</P>
<P>
   The HMO not only has a specialized clinic or ``module'' at its
medical center to serve Chinese-speaking patients, it also has a
clinic for Spanish-speaking ones.
</P>
<P>
   These clinics have separate offices and facilities as well as a
shared waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to doctors, the support staff _ including clerical
staff, medical assistants and nursing staff _ is bilingual and
bicultural.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic modules offer a range of related services, including
interpreting (face-to-face) services and written translation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our system is hard enough for English-speaking people to
maneuver, let alone non-English speaking clients,'' said Gayle
Tang, director of cultural competence for Northern California at
Kaiser Permanente. ``The major focus of these (ethnic) clinics is
to provide language-appropriate, culturally relevant health care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our first step in addressing a very multicultural
population,'' adds Dennis Lum, a Kaiser Permanente official.
</P>
<P>
   The costs of setting up the clinics have been nominal. Lum said
the major cost has gone to marketing research ($30,000), with the
remainder achieved through organizational restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Forty languages now are spoken at the medical center. ``We know
we can't do every ethnic community at once,'' Tang says. ``So the
initial focus was on the largest groups in the San Francisco area,
the Chinese and Latino communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the San Francisco Medical Center's 160,000 members,
one-sixth are Chinese _ that is, more than 27,000 patients, 80
percent of whom do not speak English as their native language.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser officials said they have been able to monitor the
movement of Chinese-speaking patients through their system by
tracking their surnames. That isn't possible, however, with the
Latino patient population.
</P>
<P>
   Tang, a registered nurse and medical anthropologist, says Kaiser
recently added language-preference data to the computer information
for each patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come in to receive health care, the position we're
taking is `What language do you PREFER to speak in?' and `Which is
your preferred written language?' Many patients prefer to receive
material in their own language.''
</P>
<P>
   With this in mind, Kaiser has developed a bilingual
Chinese-language newsletter that is distributed to more than 14,000
members. It also has a special phone hotline for Chinese patients,
and it publishes patient handbooks for Spanish- and
Chinese-speaking members.
</P>
<P>
   In the modules, at least three certified medical interpreters
who speak Chinese and other Asian languages are available every
day. There also are at least two Spanish-speaking interpreters on
hand in the Latino module.
</P>
<P>
   Other Bay Area HMOs, including Blue Cross, HealthNet and
CaliforniaCare, are making inroads in outreach to ethnic patient
populations. All provide translated patient information materials,
offer multicultural patient-appreciation days and open houses, and
provide interpreter services.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaiser Permanente, with its bilingual modules, is the most
proactive Bay Area HMO in this regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language issue as it relates to health care is very
personal _ it's kind of like food,'' Tang says. ``When people are
sick, they tend to go back to what makes them most comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, if you had asked me which language I would
prefer to get my health care in, I would have said English,'' says
Tang, who has lived in the United States since age 10. ``But now, I
would say Cantonese. When I became seriously ill two years ago, I
found myself wishing for a Chinese-speaking doctor. It really hit
home _ this is how our patients must feel.''
</P>
<P>
   All eight doctors in Kaiser's Bilingual Chinese Module speak
both Chinese and English. Apart from Cantonese, four are fluent in
Mandarin and four in Toishanese.
</P>
<P>
   The Western approach to health concerns can be foreign to people
from other cultures, Tang says.
</P>
<P>
   ``So in the Chinese module, our physicians must be competent as
far as the culture goes,'' Tang says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the model is still (the) Western biochemical model,
our doctors need to understand and accept alternative medicine,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese- and Spanish-speaking patients are not forced into the
ethnic modules, Tang stresses. ``We ask them for their preferences.
Sometimes, they say, `No, I'd rather use an interpreter and see a
white doctor.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The outcome on patient health is direct,'' she says. As a
nurse who worked in ob-gyn, Tang says she saw too many women coming
in with end-stage cancer, when intervention could have happened if
they were comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese patients would postpone consultation because they feared
making appointments by phone and feared seeing a doctor and being
unable to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``These patients can be labeled as `difficult' or
`nonresponsive,' '' Tang says, ``when it may be that we are not
doing our job in communicating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
