<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-TIRES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIRE TROUBLES LEAVE DRIVERS FLAT AT TMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ As far back as anyone can remember, Goodyear
has made a tire Indy-car drivers and owners swear by.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday at Texas Motor Speedway, Goodyear brought a tire that
car owner A.J. Foyt was swearing at.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt, the notoriously short-fused owner of cars driven by Kenny
Brack and Billy Boat, let loose a profanity-laced tirade after a
shredded right rear tire, his second puncture of the day, caused
Boat's car to crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodyear brought the hard-compound tire,'' said Foyt, who
spent part of his day in the pits, personally inspecting his cars'
tires. ``I told them not to bring it. They did anyway, and now
we're paying for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt's drivers weren't the only ones. In all, nine drivers in
yesterday's Lone Star 500K lost ground as a result of cut or
blistered tires _ seven of them on Goodyears. Boat and Scott Sharp
each had two blowouts, the second of which ran them into the wall.
Boat was able to return to the track, but his chance for a second
consecutive victory at TMS was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Contenders Jeff Ward and Davey Hamilton both had problems with
their Goodyears late in the race, while Brack, the Indy Racing
League points leader, said his tires forced him to run
conservatively rather than making a run at victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was a race of survival,'' Brack said, ``and that's
not how I like to race.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear officials weren't thrilled with it, either. Lead
engineer Todd Carpenter fell short of ``mea culpa,'' but did say
the company, which has provided tires for the winners of seven of
the 10 IRL races this year, was ``disappointed with our tire
performance today.''
</P>
<P>
   One Goodyear official apologized to the drivers for the tires,
admitting they were unable to hold up in the heat generated on the
track. When the race began at 2 p.m., Goodyear engineers measured
the track temperature at 140 degrees. The heat caused the tire
pressure to increase, making the tires more susceptible to damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodyear is a great company, but they had a bad day,'' Boat
said. ``I don't think anyone there expected to see these kinds of
tire temperatures. To win this race, you had to baby your tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless, that is, you were riding on Firestones, which proved to
be far more durable. Winner John Paul Jr. ran as many as 87 laps on
a single set of tires and had no problems all day. The only
punctures for Firestone drivers came from running over debris on
the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our tires have consistently held up better in the heat,''
Firestone spokesman Mark Robinson said. ``That's one of the
trademarks of our tires.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
